(1379, '2022/02/11', '3:28 p.m.', '1', '1', 'Annika Spedding', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms (with purpose)', 'Oral Phonogram Review (OPR) - Various Phonograms (see notes)', 'Heather Excell', 'Achieved', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>OPR/WPR:</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>wor, oo, er, ou, ear, ow, ir, ee, ur</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p>Spelling Dictation:</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>on, a, it, is, she, can</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p>NOTES:</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Annika has retained quite a lot of her phonogram sounds. We did 1-43 phonograms, and she only needed prompting once we approached the double letter phonograms. Annika was able to recall her sounds after heaing the first few sounds.<br><br>Annika and I played a game of \'jump on the sound\' where we lay phonogram cards on the ground, give each other a sound and jump on the correct card', NULL, '2022-02-11 15:28:32', '2022-02-11 17:48:10'),
(1380, '2022/02/11', '3:33 p.m.', '1', '1', 'Connor Thompson', 'English', 'Writing - Parts of Speech & Vocabulary', 'Adjectives - describe nouns', 'See Notes', 'Neve Mitchell', 'Not Yet', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Goal setting task. Ask Connor what he wants to achieve in tutoring/this year in general. Break these goals into smaller tasks. Establish how we are going to achieve these tasks.&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Spoke to Connor about school. His goals are to: finish school (get Bs &amp; As in every subject, focusing on English and Maths), destroy me in a game of Words at Work, and to destroy something.</td></tr><tr><td>We broke Goal 1 into smaller, more manageable tasks, including: bring school work to tutoring every week, go over the week\'s content at tutoring, bring in homework and we\'ll figure out a schedule/plan to help him manage his time.</td></tr><tr><', NULL, '2022-02-11 15:33:06', '2022-02-17 15:00:34'),
(1381, '2022/02/11', '4:25 p.m.', '1', '1', 'Nate Betros', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms', 'Oral Phonogram Review (OPR) with Stated Purpose - Various Phonograms (see notes)', 'Neve Mitchell', 'Achieved', 'Achieved', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR: 27-70</td></tr><tr><td>WPR: ci sh ow ough ou ew ui wr ng au aw ear</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Rule review: 4 29 28</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD:begun-born</td></tr><tr><td>Read R&amp;S</td></tr><tr><td>Explain/discuss the markings and meanings of analysed words.</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Rule Intro: NA</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Sentence Structure: Use Ayres words in compound and complex sentences. Had to remind and coach NB using the SBB to refresh his memory after the break.&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figu', NULL, '2022-02-11 16:25:17', '2022-02-17 15:05:34'),
(1382, '2022/02/11', '4:32 p.m.', '1', '1', 'Joshua Zeeman', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms (with purpose)', 'Oral Phonogram Review (OPR) - Various Phonograms (see notes)', 'Heather Excell', 'Achieved', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>OPR/WPR:</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>ea, ee, ie, er, ar, or, oe, t, ti</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p>Rules:</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>4, 6, 9, 14, 19</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p>Spelling Dictation:</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>reveal, sleeve, soldier, summary, sum, sword, tomatoes, tomato</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p>WRITING:</p><ul><li>Modelling thought process off ethical frameworks, write a persuasive speech to say that “Lying is not bad depending on how it\'s done”&nbsp;<ul><li>Josh = Natural Law Ethics</li><li>Heather = Situational Ethics</li></ul></li></ul><p>NOTES:</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbod', NULL, '2022-02-11 16:32:50', '2022-02-11 17:51:21'),
(1383, '2022/02/11', '5:28 p.m.', '1', '1', 'Archie Seelig', 'Mathematics', 'Number & Place Value', 'BODMAS', 'TEXT BOOK - EXERCISES, QUESTIONS, ACTIVITIES', 'Ivan Botero', 'Not Yet', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', '<p>Archie and I were working today in BODMAS and did a review on long divisions and multiplications with 2 and 3 digits numbers. 432x24 and 123x321&nbsp;</p><p>In terms of BODMAS, Archie is capable to solve foundation to some above-average problems. The problems which the student finds more challenging are those related to sign the law. If he has to solve problems like --4+(3+-7) sometimes he forgets to apply this principle to solve these problems.&nbsp;</p><p>At the end of the lesson to relax a little bit, we were solving long divisions and multiplications. Archie was able to solve them quickly and without mistakes.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, NULL, '2022-02-11 17:28:29', '2022-03-06 19:30:44'),
(1384, '2022/02/15', '7:45 a.m.', '1', '1', 'Tiki Salt', 'English', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Campbell Jepson', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>worked well throuhg kilpatrick with a few hesitations on a couple. Was very confident with OPR and WPR. Hesitated on a couple of words with dictaion such as beauty.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-02-15 07:45:53', '2022-03-01 10:06:16'),
(1385, '2022/02/15', '2:37 p.m.', '1', '1', 'Stella Lorkin', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms', 'Oral Phonogram Review (OPR) with Stated Purpose - Various Phonograms (see notes)', 'Juno Galang', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>OPR: 1-30</p><ul><li>Stella could recite most first sounds but struggled with /b/, /d/, and /g/. She also did not recognise 2-letter phonograms.</li></ul><p>WPR:</p><ul><li>a, h, b, m, g</li><li>Stella wrote /b/ in uppercase, showing uncertainty about lowercase direction.</li></ul><p>Morphology: Donah 21</p><p>Stella was great at the Donah activity!</p><p>Rule: 4</p><ul><li>We did a very preliminary introduction to Rule 4, and Stella was able to answer revision questions with some scaffolding</li></ul><p>SD: A-G List 1</p><ul><li>Used only for reading &amp; marking. Next week, we will start on the 2-letter words.</li></ul><p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-02-15 14:37:36', '2022-03-07 09:31:19'),
(1386, '2022/02/15', '2:43 p.m.', '1', '2', 'Max Shapiro', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms', 'Oral Phonogram Review (OPR) with Stated Purpose - Various Phonograms (see notes)', 'Neve Mitchell', 'Not Yet', 'N/A', 'Attended Tardy', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'Introductory', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>PA: Kilpatrick</td></tr><tr><td>MS could succesfully delete the sound, but also deleted the second syllable.</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Challenge: out</td></tr><tr><td>Connected with picture: 3 stick people, 2 of whom say the same sound at the same time.</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>DBG -- run as fun, b/d mix ups (30% self-corrected), MS sounded out all words!!</td></tr><tr><td>OPR: 27-44 or ck</td></tr><tr><td>WPR: sh ow ou ay or</td></tr><tr><td>MS became very disheartened when he got the phonograms back to front. He lost interest immediately, and commented \"I\'m going to mess it up every time.\" We spoke about neural path', NULL, '2022-02-15 14:43:21', '2022-02-15 18:12:17'),
(1387, '2022/02/15', '3:11 p.m.', '1', '2', 'Jett Knighton', 'Mathematics', 'Patterns & Algebra', 'Simplify algebraic expressions involving the four operations', 'Text book - Exercises, Questions, Activities', 'Ivan Botero', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', '<p>Today we continued our work on algebraic operations.</p><p>Even though Jett and I were working on this at the end of 2021, his algebraic skills were out of practice.&nbsp;</p><p>We reviewed the four operations, index law, expansion, factorization, and BIDMAS.&nbsp;</p><p>Overall, Jett did a good job. However, I am confident he can make it better.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, NULL, '2022-02-15 15:11:45', '2022-02-22 10:54:28'),
(1388, '2022/02/15', '3:29 p.m.', '1', '2', 'Banjo Mills', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Delete syllable from two syllable word - Kilpatrick Level D', 'Laree Thorsby', 'Achieved', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p><strong>PA&nbsp;</strong>DK D1 D6 syllable deletion&nbsp;</p><p>B able to easily syllabify compound words.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>OPR&nbsp;</strong>a e I o u y + c b d s g qu f + th sh ee&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>WPR&nbsp;</strong>clockface focus&nbsp;a e I o u&nbsp; f c g d qu ee</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>H/W&nbsp;</strong>2 oclock. Placed clock on table nw focus on e</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Rule Review</strong></p><p>review of vowels v consonants. Practised sorting</p><p>Review of 1st/2nd sounds. Intro to 3rd sounds.&nbsp;</p><p>Rule 4 intro using counters and flashcards</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Spelling Dictation</strong></p><p>Me go so no he she we be&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-02-15 15:29:17', '2022-02-15 17:53:36'),
(1389, '2022/02/15', '3:29 p.m.', '1', '1', 'Stella Bowerman', 'Mathematics', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Campbell Jepson', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>ran through modules 22 and 21. she struggled with both of them which is concerning because she was able to do most of it before the summer break. she had no idea about the first two questions on module 22 even after I explained it for about 10 mins each. dropped down to module 21 and saw similar but better results.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-02-15 15:29:37', '2022-03-01 10:04:32'),
(1390, '2022/02/15', '3:30 p.m.', '1', '1', 'Tyler Van Nimwegen', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Manipulate (delete or substitute) initial phoneme in initial blend - Kilpatrick Level H', 'Juno Galang', 'Achieved', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-02-15 15:30:41', '2022-02-21 09:49:21'),
(1391, '2022/02/15', '3:31 p.m.', '1', '2', 'Sophie Mirowski', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms', 'Oral Phonogram Review (OPR) with Stated Purpose - Various Phonograms (see notes)', 'Neve Mitchell', 'Achieved', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR: 45-62</td></tr><tr><td>WPR: ui ew ed ea igh kn ough au</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>PROMPT CARDS ON BOARD</td></tr><tr><td>Read R&amp;S: Current Ayres Column</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Rule review: 11&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD: few-pitch</td></tr><tr><td>Read R&amp;S</td></tr><tr><td>Explain/discuss the markings and meanings of analysed words.</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Rule Intro: NA</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>LOTS of discussion about words. Discussed homophones.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Vo', NULL, '2022-02-15 15:31:48', '2022-02-15 18:17:20'),
(1392, '2022/02/15', '4:04 p.m.', '1', '2', 'Esther McIver', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms', 'Oral Phonogram Review (OPR) with Stated Purpose - Various Phonograms (see notes)', 'Heather Excell', 'Achieved', 'N/A', 'Cancelled - No Show', 'N/A', 'Cancelled', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-02-15 16:05:30', '2022-02-15 16:06:09'),
(1393, '2022/02/15', '4:22 p.m.', '1', '2', 'Lachlan Prior', 'English', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Campbell Jepson', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Worked well through OPR, had a few new ones in there for him. Struggled with \'ou\' even after a few goes at it. Ran through the mistakes he made last week with dictaion and explained some of the rules with him but will really focus on them next week with an activity. &nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-02-15 16:22:13', '2022-03-01 09:58:41'),
(1394, '2022/02/15', '4:28 p.m.', '1', '2', 'Luca Mignanelli', 'Mathematics', 'Number & Place Value', 'Mental Computation', 'MAD MINUTE MATHS FACTS TO 50', 'Heather Excell', 'Achieved', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Luca was quite excited to complete his multiplication work today. He finished his entire grid in over 8 minutes.<br><br>After being quizzed on his tables by Ivan, Luca and I had a round of WAFF to begin the mental math tasks<br><br>Luca and I looked at converting fractions, decimals and percentages again. Luca seems to struggle with his place value as this is what is constantly holding him back each week. To pre-empt this struggle, we spent some time looking at the place value of a handful of numbers. Luca did this with ease, and was able to articulate why we convert decimals, fractions and percentages the way we do.<br><br>We were constantly refer', NULL, '2022-02-15 16:28:13', '2022-02-15 17:38:30'),
(1395, '2022/02/15', '4:34 p.m.', '1', '2', 'Shay Douglas', 'Mathematics', 'Patterns & Algebra', 'Factorise algebraic expressions by identifying numerical factors', 'Text book - Exercises, Questions, Activities', 'Neve Mitchell', 'Achieved', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Subject: Year 10 Maths</td></tr><tr><td>Focus: Reviewing assumed knowledge -- factorisation of quadratic equations, simplifying equations by factorising and cancelling,&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Activity: Number and Algebra Module 33 -- Factorisation AMSI Exercises</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Shay did well with these activities. He found puzzling out the factorisation solution somewhat tedious -- he needs practice to make this a quick skill he can employ in a variety of more difficult problems.</td></tr><tr><td>He also made a few errors in regard to positive and negative numbers, and when he went too fast. We had a', NULL, '2022-02-15 16:34:43', '2022-02-22 17:39:24'),
(1396, '2022/02/15', '4:41 p.m.', '1', '2', 'Andrew Allan', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Language Rules (Pronunciation/Spelling/Grammar)', 'Rule 4: vowels a, e, o, u say their second (long) sound at the end of a syllable', 'See Notes', 'Laree Thorsby', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'Attended Tardy', 'Not Returned', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', NULL, '<p><strong>T1W2–Tardy by 10 minutes lead to a disrupted start. &nbsp;</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>PA&nbsp;</strong>DK 1 final phoneme deletion Level 2 NW</p><p>&nbsp;<strong>OPR</strong><br>All consonants + a e I o u y er ir ur wor ear ed&nbsp; ng ee&nbsp;ea&nbsp; wh&nbsp; &nbsp;wr&nbsp; oo oa oe or ar j dge ck ch tch ey kn&nbsp;</p><p><br><strong>WPR</strong> kn tch dge ea ey qu ck th ch &nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>HW focus&nbsp; -lines start at top. Andrew formed all his WPR letters correctly except ‘d’</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Rule Review</strong></p><p>Rule 4 flashcards and counters&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Spelling Dictation</strong> Ayres – mother three cold hot plus A.s choice – fa', NULL, '2022-02-15 16:41:56', '2022-02-15 17:50:20'),
(1397, '2022/02/15', '5:25 p.m.', '1', '2', 'Callum Coulson', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Purpose for learning phonograms - To connect speech sounds to their written symbol which helps with reading, writing and spelling', 'See notes', 'Yina Peng', 'Achieved', 'Achieved', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<ol><li>Spelling assessment.</li><li>Speil folder.</li><li>As Callum\'s mother said, he did not learn much about sounds and phonemes at school. Callum does not have a strong sense of individual sounds. We will need to work on the basic concept more: sounds, symbols, letters, words, and syllables.</li><li>Callum shows a &nbsp;good interest in reading and he likes to do reading activities.&nbsp;</li></ol>', NULL, '2022-02-15 17:25:34', '2022-02-15 19:02:24'),
(1398, '2022/02/15', '6:42 p.m.', '1', '2', 'Isaac Ellis', 'Mathematics', 'Linear & Non-Linear Relationships', 'Linear & Non-linear equations', 'Text book - Exercises, Questions, Activities', 'Ivan Botero', 'Not Yet', 'Not Yet', 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Isaac and I were doing a revision on algebraic operations with algebraic expressions, this included expansion, and factorisation.</p><p>I could notice that the student was forgetting some key concepts such as index law, sign law, and BODMAS. All of those are very important to correctly perform operations with algebraic expressions.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-02-15 18:42:05', '2022-02-22 14:33:36'),
(1399, '2022/02/16', '8:48 a.m.', '1', '2', 'Brock Smith', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Delete onset or rime - Kilpatrick Level F', 'Yina Peng', 'Achieved', 'Achieved', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<ol><li>Kilpatrick F</li><li>Assessment</li><li>OPR: 1-70. Brock struggles with the last ten phonograms.</li><li>WPR: 1-70.He is not very familiar with phonograms from 50 to 70.</li><li>Spelling: South Australia Test. He is 9 years and 2 months old, and his spelling age is between 8 years and 4 months and 9 years and 2 months, which is a great result.&nbsp;</li><li>Reading: Waddington. His reading age is 8 years and 5 to 9 months.&nbsp;</li></ol>', NULL, '2022-02-16 08:49:11', '2022-03-22 09:14:45'),
(1400, '2022/02/16', '1:47 p.m.', '1', '2', 'Angel King', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Language Rules (Pronunciation/Spelling/Grammar)', 'Rule 4: vowels a, e, o, u say their second (long) sound at the end of a syllable', 'See Notes', 'Laree Thorsby', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Angel was unsettled and emotional but she did engage when asked to.&nbsp;</p><p>Today we reviewed phgs1-45, completed a short WPR and wrote some words using first vowel sounds.</p><p>REviewed prior knowledge of rule 4 by playing the flashcard version of spin a star.&nbsp;</p><p>Oral Fluency Fitzroy book 11</p><p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-02-16 13:47:07', '2022-02-24 12:42:06'),
(1401, '2022/02/16', '3:25 p.m.', '1', '2', 'Max Brookfield', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms', 'Oral Phonogram Review (OPR) with Stated Purpose - Various Phonograms (see notes)', 'Neve Mitchell', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>PA: Kilpatrick</td></tr><tr><td>MB struggled with this. He always got the last syllable but often cut off the syllable in the middle.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR: a o + 27-38</td></tr><tr><td>Got stuck on a, ay/ai, oy/oi</td></tr><tr><td>WPR: ch ow ou a&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Review: Open &amp; Closed Syllables</td></tr><tr><td>Sort open/closed syllables and underline vowels at the end of an open syllable.</td></tr><tr><td>Explain that a vowel says its second sound (its name) at the end of an open syllable. Read through syllables for s', NULL, '2022-02-16 15:25:10', '2022-02-16 16:25:29'),
(1402, '2022/02/16', '3:31 p.m.', '1', '2', 'Lilly Oettle', 'English Assessment', 'Reading Comprehension', 'Application of mental actions, composition and text type knowledge', 'Practicing and Assessing comprehension passage - Spalding Level 3', 'Laree Thorsby', 'Achieved', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>OPR – vowels + ai ay oi oy ea oa ou ow ti</p><p>WPr as above</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Rule review – 4&nbsp;</p><p>Spelling – restrain aboard afraid elect election&nbsp;</p><p>Intro to marking&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>OF – 1 min Fitzroy 41&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>HW 1 min Fitzroy</p><p>Spalding RC grade 3 no2.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-02-16 15:31:25', '2022-02-17 11:45:40'),
(1403, '2022/02/16', '3:32 p.m.', '1', '2', 'Phoebe Webb', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics & Morphology - The Vocabulary of Word Structure', 'Vowels - the voiced sounds of the letters a, e, i (y), o, u that are made by an unobstructed flow of air', 'Articulate/Explain the meaning of vowel', 'Yina Peng', 'Achieved', 'Achieved', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<ol><li>assessment&nbsp;</li><li>spelling. Phoebe is not aware of multi letter phonograms. For example, she would write wich for which. She is confused by a and e, a and u,&nbsp;</li><li>reading. Phoebe does not like reading and her reading age is below 5 years old. &nbsp;It shows that she is struggling with single sounds in words. &nbsp;</li><li>Speil part one. It is quite hard to get Phoebe into the work, but I do find that if I integrate work with games, she is interested in. We worked on the basic concepts Sounds&gt;symbol&gt;word&gt;syllable&gt;sentence&gt;paragraph&gt;extended text</li></ol>', NULL, '2022-02-16 15:32:16', '2022-02-16 16:59:28');
INSERT INTO `attens` (`id`, `date_created`, `time`, `term`, `lesson`, `student_name`, `subject_name`, `concept_name`, `conceptDetail`, `learningActivity`, `tutor_name`, `tutor_evaluation`, `student_self`, `student_attendance`, `homework_completed`, `weekly_lesson`, `homework_assignment`, `email_school`, `comment`, `commentPrivate`, `notesAttendance`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(1404, '2022/02/16', '3:33 p.m.', '1', '2', 'Toby Webb', 'English', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Campbell Jepson', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Worked well through the speil pack. Seemed to understand most concepts quite quickly. Went through one of the reading tests together. I would read out the question and he would read the multiple-choice answers. He seems just to be looking at the first few letters and just guessing from then on. when he sounds out the words he seems to get them close but is unable to use more than one sound when sounding out the words.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-02-16 15:33:04', '2022-03-01 10:08:28'),
(1405, '2022/02/16', '3:33 p.m.', '1', '2', 'Connor McLaren', 'Mathematics', 'Number & Place Value', 'Compare, order, add and subtract integers', 'TEXT BOOK - EXERCISES, QUESTIONS, ACTIVITIES', 'Ivan Botero', 'Not Yet', 'Not Yet', 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', '<p>Today we continued working with integers.&nbsp;<br>We were placing numbers on the number line, completely looked at the sign law and the practical aspects of it.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, NULL, '2022-02-16 15:33:26', '2022-02-22 14:45:02'),
(1406, '2022/02/16', '4:28 p.m.', '1', '1', 'Adelaide Brown', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Manipulate (delete or substitute) initial phoneme in initial blend - Kilpatrick Level H', 'Juno Galang', 'Achieved', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Kilpatrick<br>H1<br>Notes<br>Perfect</p><p>OPR<br>ay<br>ea<br>ch<br>oo<br>ng<br>a<br>c<br>e<br>g<br>Adelaide struggled slightly with /ch/, /ay/ as these phonos were new for her.</p><p>WPR<br>ae<br>ea<br>ch<br>oo<br>ng</p><p>Donah 21 \"box\"</p><p>SD: H</p><p>Oral Fluency<br>423<br>s.c – “mild”, “swordfish”, “uses”</p><p>Writing Program Section<br>Paragraph<br>4 – Sentence Stories<br>Adelaide is so good at sitting and writing long paragraphs! Such a pleasure to teach. We went through spelling errors after</p>', NULL, '2022-02-16 16:28:07', '2022-03-07 10:37:25'),
(1407, '2022/02/16', '4:31 p.m.', '1', '2', 'Luke Gomer', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms', 'Oral Phonogram Review (OPR) with Stated Purpose - Various Phonograms (see notes)', 'Heather Excell', 'Achieved', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>OPR/WPR:</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>ay, ou, e, ur, ea, c</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p>Rule Review:</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>4, 18, 19</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p>Spelling Dictation:</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>delay, pound, behind, around, burn, camp, bear, bare, clear, clean</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p>WRITING:</p><ul><li>Up-levelling sentence worksheets - adding adjectives into sentences</li></ul><p>NOTES:</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Luke had a bit of a slow start this lesson. He resisted to putting a sentence together about his day, and instead provided one word answers \'tired\' and', NULL, '2022-02-16 16:31:54', '2022-02-16 17:26:50'),
(1408, '2022/02/16', '4:32 p.m.', '1', '2', 'Jacob Tipping', 'Mathematics', 'Number & Place Value', 'Recognise and represent multiplication as repeated addition, groups and arrays', 'TEXT BOOK - EXERCISES, QUESTIONS, ACTIVITIES', 'Ivan Botero', 'Not Yet', 'Not Yet', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', '<p>Jacob and I were working with counting in groups. We did this by using different counting strategies including counters, pictures on the board, mental computation, and when it possible marshmallows.&nbsp;</p><p>Jacob swiftly grasped the concept, hence we moved to multiplications and divisions. I used, “find how many groups of” to explain divisions. Next week will be working using the symbols and if possible, get ready to start with long multiplications and divisions.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, NULL, '2022-02-16 16:32:39', '2022-02-22 15:08:37'),
(1410, '2022/02/16', '5:52 p.m.', '1', '2', 'Angus Zeeman', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms', 'Oral Phonogram Review (OPR) with Stated Purpose - Various Phonograms (see notes)', 'Neve Mitchell', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, 'OPR: 43-70\nWPR: kn gn oe wr ie dge  ei au si ea \n\nReview errors from Morrisson McCall.\n-- Giving AZ a reason/connection between spelling and the word\'s context (like for minute/minute) was a good tool for helping him retain memory of the spelling\n-- Adding 4 marks for words he didn\'t need instruction to fix.\n\nVocab: Use word from spelling in oral vocab development task to show meaning of the word.\n\nGame: Waff', NULL, '2022-02-16 17:54:25', '2022-02-16 18:01:53'),
(1411, '2021/12/16', '7:49 a.m.', '1', '2', 'Chester Vincent', 'English', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Campbell Jepson', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Still stumped on \"ou\" so going to continue with the same phonos as next week. Not much change as last week worked well during phonos and dictation.</p>', NULL, '2022-02-17 07:49:22', '2022-03-01 09:43:26'),
(1412, '2022/02/17', '8:08 a.m.', '1', '2', 'Tyler Van Nimwegen', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Manipulate (delete or substitute) initial phoneme in initial blend - Kilpatrick Level H', 'Juno Galang', 'Achieved', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-02-17 08:08:55', '2022-02-21 09:53:44'),
(1413, '2022/02/17', '8:50 a.m.', '1', '2', 'James Levings', 'Mathematics', 'Decimals', 'Operations with decimals', 'Discussion & Practise (on board/in book)', 'Ivan Botero', 'Not Yet', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Today we were working with multiplications and divisions with decimals by 10, 100, and 1000.&nbsp;<br>It was very useful for James to use the aid which we have in Educate Tutoring. I run a small quiz on the board and James had 9/12 correct answers.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-02-17 08:50:47', '2022-02-27 17:43:33'),
(1414, '2022/02/17', '2:15 p.m.', '1', '2', 'Mia Harvey', 'Mathematics', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Campbell Jepson', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>started off playing the Uno game but just using addition. She answered all questions very quickly even when I hid the numbers very quickly. We worked through module 10 very slowly question by question and she seemed to be very confident on most of the questions. she seemed embarrassed to use her fingers to count though so i assured her i still do it.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-02-17 14:15:50', '2022-03-01 09:33:08'),
(1415, '2022/02/17', '3:26 p.m.', '1', '2', 'Sofia Creek', 'Mathematics', 'Fractions', 'Operations with fractions', 'Discussion & Practise (on board/in book)', 'Ivan Botero', 'Not Yet', 'Not Yet', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', '<p>We started to work with fractions.&nbsp;</p><p>We worked on:</p><ul><li>What is a fraction</li><li>Numerator/Denominator.</li><li>Representing fractions.</li><li>Comparing fractions.&nbsp;</li></ul><p>Overall, Sofia did a good job. However, as she had an injury on her lip, we just did foundation to easy problems.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, NULL, '2022-02-17 15:26:58', '2022-03-03 10:26:22'),
