(1627, '2022/03/07', '8:48 a.m.', '1', '2', 'Flynn Ascencio-Lane', 'English', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Campbell Jepson', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Went through the phonos pretty well but was too focused on trying to convince me to play a game on my laptop. I settled for playing wordle so we\'re able to actually do something. Got through some words and tried dictation but didn\'t seem interested.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-03-07 08:48:18', '2022-03-16 08:54:17'),
(1628, '2022/03/07', '9:41 a.m.', '1', '4', 'Tyler Van Nimwegen', 'English', 'Writing - Paragraph & Composition Construction', 'Essay Structure - Body Paragraphs', 'Compose TEEL paragraphs: topic, evidence, explanation, link/transition', 'Juno Galang', 'Achieved', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', NULL, '<p><strong>Coaching: Autobiography</strong></p><p>Continuing with his autobio assignment, Tyler and I used the Writing Process to brainstorm his academic strengths. He listed his strengths in order and was encouraged to think deeply and be able to arrange items in a way that reflected order:</p><ol><li>VET</li><li>Cooking</li><li>Photography</li><li>History</li><li>English</li><li>Work Studies</li><li>Sport</li><li>Religion</li><li>Health&nbsp;</li><li>Math</li><li>Science</li></ol><p>We were also able to further elaborate and add explanation to why these were his strengths and weaknesses. We then assessed his weak points in Math and English:</p><ul><li>Math: Line graphs, arithmetic</li><li>', NULL, '2022-03-07 09:43:04', '2022-03-07 09:46:42'),
(1629, '2022/03/07', '10:16 a.m.', '1', '3', 'Hunter McNees', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Manipulate (delete or substitute) initial phoneme in initial blend - Kilpatrick Level H', 'Juno Galang', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Kilpatrick<br>H1<br>Notes<br>Hunter struggles a lot with initial consonant blends. We have had to scaffold every word to find the second sound.</p><p>OPR/WPR: 31-38</p><p>Donah 21</p><p>Rule<br>8<br>Multi-letter phonos<br>Hunter is improving with using multi-letter phonos in his spelling! Today he struggled with /ur/ and /ai/ but will revisit on Saturday.</p><p>Ayres Section<br>A - G<br>fur<br>green<br>oil<br>paint<br>pool<br>tooth<br>teeth<br>worm</p><p>Oral Fluency<br>115 – Amazing Prosody!<br>Hunter has improved dramatically and can now progress</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-03-07 10:17:21', '2022-03-07 10:27:19'),
(1630, '2022/03/07', '10:21 a.m.', '1', '4', 'Hunter McNees', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Manipulate (delete or substitute) initial phoneme in initial blend - Kilpatrick Level H', 'Juno Galang', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Kilpatrick H1</p><ul><li>This is something that continues to be difficult for Hunter and requires breaking down.</li></ul><p>OPR/WPR</p><ul><li>ea</li><li>wor</li><li>ng</li><li>ear</li><li>ir</li><li>ur</li><li>er</li></ul><p>Errors: /ea/ /ur/</p><p>SD</p><ul><li>fur</li><li>paint (pait)&nbsp;</li><li>feed</li><li>it</li><li>eat</li><li>eaten</li><li>plate (plaet)</li><li>ate (aet)</li><li>gate (gane)</li><li>late&nbsp;</li></ul><p><i>I truly think Hunter had difficulty with my mask on, as well as having trouble distinguishing between /n/ and /t/. We also need to work on his SFE rules once more!</i></p><p>Sentences:</p><ul><li>Errors: with (wiv) because (beecayse)</li></ul><p><i>Hunter d', NULL, '2022-03-07 10:22:22', '2022-03-09 09:19:29'),
(1631, '2022/03/07', '10:50 a.m.', '1', '4', 'Darcy Callaghan', 'English', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Campbell Jepson', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>ZOOM. Was a bit difficult to go through zoom, didn’t have a pen or paper so just had to go through the phonos which he did well at. Got stumped on \'ie\' and \'ei\'. Spent most of the time trying to find a book that we both had and found matilda. Spent the rest of the lesson reading and went well but he seemed to be guessing the words a lot. Is good most of the time but i think he\'s too focused on trying to read fast rather than use all the pauses.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-03-07 10:50:57', '2022-03-16 08:52:39'),
(1632, '2022/03/07', '12:01 p.m.', '1', '4', 'Nina Gust', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Manipulate (delete or substitute) initial phoneme in initial blend - Kilpatrick Level H', 'Juno Galang', 'Achieved', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Kilpatrick<br>H1<br>For Nina, this took a minute to register for the first word, but was able to successfully complete the rest.</p><p>OPR/WPR<br>p<br>ow<br>th<br>ee<br>sh<br>y<br>u<br>Nina struggled between /f/ and /th/ (mask did not help!). She also needs work on /y/.</p><p>Handwriting focus<br>/d/</p><p>Rule Jobs 1 &amp; 2</p><p>SD: A-G<br>time<br>have<br>blue<br>ago<br>old<br>bad<br>This list was hard for Nina, especially “ago”, “old” and “bad”</p><p>Oral Fluency<br>100<br>Errors:&nbsp;<br>“got”<br>“college”<br>“just”<br>“plate”<br>Nina has improved so much in fluency, especially compared to Week 1! Her progress has been amazing.</p><p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-03-07 12:04:12', '2022-03-07 12:04:56'),
