(1911, '2022/03/31', '3:04 p.m.', '1', '7', 'Cara Lashmar', 'English', 'Writing - Paragraph & Composition Construction', 'The Writing Process - Plan, Compose, Revise, Edit, Publish (by reading, speaking, media presentation)', 'Use the writing process to compose informative paragraph', 'Laree Thorsby', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Focus on the writing process plan, compose, revise , edit publish a piece of informative writing.</p><p>1.Revised, &nbsp;edited and published &nbsp;last week\'s writing - Should recess be longer - Informative/persuasive writing.</p><p>2. How to Ride a bike.</p><p>Planned via dot points - detailed on white board</p><p>Composed a draft by identifying the main points and expanding. A combination of paragraph format with bullet points.</p><p>Revised paragraph to ensure correct information and sentences made sense</p><p>NW: Edit and Publish.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-03-31 15:06:19', '2022-03-31 15:13:29'),
(1912, '2022/03/31', '3:27 p.m.', '1', '7', 'Sofia Creek', 'Mathematics', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Ivan Botero', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, '<p>Lesson No 7 was re-scheduled to Monday 28.03.2022. However, the student didn\'t show up, when I called Shaye, she said she forgot the lesson.&nbsp;</p>', '2022-03-31 15:27:00', '2022-07-02 19:45:50'),
(1913, '2022/03/31', '3:34 p.m.', '1', '5', 'Seth Vanderlaan', 'English', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Campbell Jepson', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Started off with the phonograms after a while of him refusing to do work, just wanted to play games for a bit. Went through the usual phonos and added in \'ay\' \'ar\' and \'er\' so we could write some words with them. Was very reluctant to figure out any words until i started writing my own he said that he wanted to do it. got him to say a sentence for me and he copied it down on the whiteboard. finished off with playing the phono dice game with the vowels which he cheated at pretty much every go in order to win but still had to use his literacy skills so i was happy.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-03-31 15:34:40', '2022-04-06 14:52:46'),
(1914, '2022/03/31', '3:53 p.m.', '1', '8', 'Lucy Fairbrother', 'Mathematics', 'Number & Place Value', 'solve problems involving all four operations with whole numbers', 'TEXT BOOK - EXERCISES, QUESTIONS, ACTIVITIES', 'Naomi Wright', 'Achieved', 'Achieved', 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'Followup', '<p>Today we worked on solving a multi-layered word problem on page 55 NSPM Level 3A. &nbsp;Lucy was prompted to use pictures to help unpack the question. &nbsp;This helped immeasurably. &nbsp;Lucy was able to solve the problem accurately with minimal input.</p><p>Additionally, when asked how she may check her answer at the end, she was able to reverse the scenario and by default reverse the equation solving it visually only using the sums already recorded to create a reverse operation problem. &nbsp;This relied on working memory and confident mental arithmetic. &nbsp;</p><p>Lucy later said, “I can do that,” when I asked if she might be able to have a go at as simple algebraic equation at hom', NULL, NULL, '2022-03-31 15:54:39', '2022-03-31 17:57:12'),
(1915, '2022/03/31', '4:06 p.m.', '1', '8', 'Tyler Van Nimwegen', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Juno Galang', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Today, Tyler and I began work on his Religion assignment. It is a comparative essay (no word count) regarding similarities/differences between Christianity and Islam. Tyler and I began the writing process in terms of planning an essay. Tyler was shown how to construct a comparative table for planning, and how to find quotes and sources to start filling out the table. Although Tyler has some trouble skimming for information due to reading and processing difficulties, he has greatly improved in comprehension. His task for today was to find sources for Christian rituals, narratives, and beliefs. He was able to fill out his side of the table, with some explanation and scaffolding! Next week, ', NULL, '2022-03-31 16:07:07', '2022-03-31 16:09:47'),
(1916, '2022/03/31', '4:09 p.m.', '1', '8', 'Reuben Shelverton', 'English', 'Reading - Fluency & Prosody', 'Components - read accurately, recognise words automatically, read without hesitation, read with expression', 'Articulate/explain the meaning of fluency and list components', 'Juno Galang', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'Cancelled - No Show', 'N/A', 'Cancelled', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Reuben did not show up. I tried to ring his mum, Claire, but the call could not go through, so an email was sent.</p>', NULL, '2022-03-31 16:10:24', '2022-03-31 16:11:31'),
(1917, '2022/03/31', '4:29 p.m.', '1', '6', 'Samuel Lamont', 'English', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Campbell Jepson', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Started off with a game of chess which I won. Moved onto the phonos which went through nicely with no problems. Did well on WPR but needs to work on his handwriting, no care in it, and is very messy. For dictation I could barely read his writing, went well with dictation got him to write 5 of them into sentences but needs to work on his sentence structure, not every requirement was in there and I got him to rewrite one because it was so messy</p>', NULL, '2022-03-31 16:29:20', '2022-04-06 14:55:26'),
(1918, '2022/03/31', '4:33 p.m.', '1', '8', 'Finlay Tueno', 'Mathematics', 'General Mathematics – Foundation', 'Consumer arithmetic', 'Please see the notes', 'Ivan Botero', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', '<ul><li>calculate weekly or monthly wage from a salary and from an hourly rate, including situations involving overtime and other allowances, and earnings based on commission or piecework. = In progress</li><li>calculate payments based on government allowances and pensions = Achieved</li></ul>', NULL, NULL, '2022-03-31 16:33:05', '2022-07-02 18:30:52'),
(1919, '2022/03/31', '4:53 p.m.', '1', '8', 'Callisto Pratten', 'Mathematics', 'Money & Financial Maths', 'Connect the compound interest formula to repeated applications of simple interest', 'Text book - Exercises, Questions, Activities', 'Rosemary Beswick', 'Achieved', 'Achieved', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Callisto\'s class has finished the Finance Unit and so we spent time working on examples that she had missed in class. This included ‘Annuities in Arrears’ examples, using the graphics calculator. Callisto completed this work fairly independently after we had done some work on discovering where she had gone wrong in her calculations. She needs to take care with the calculation of the number of interest-bearing periods. Callisto will have a test coming up soon and so I emailed her a copy of a past exam so that she can do some practice. The printer didn\'t work here and so Stephen will print it for her.</p>', NULL, '2022-03-31 16:53:54', '2022-03-31 18:28:50'),
(1920, '2022/03/31', '5:29 p.m.', '1', '8', 'Nicholas Geeves', 'Mathematics', 'Data Representation and Interpretation', 'Graphs, tables & charts', 'Discussion & Practise (on board/in book)', 'Ivan Botero', 'In Progress', 'In Progress', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', '<p>We continued our work on data analysis and representation.&nbsp;</p><p>Today we looked at two-step experiments and tree diagrams. We used those to find the change/likelihood of a subsequent event to happen after one major even controls the situation.&nbsp;</p><p>Nicholas was slightly confused with the first experiments. I provided a very detailed explanation and he was happy with this. Once we went into the practice round, he did a great job and hit almost all correct answers.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, NULL, '2022-03-31 17:29:47', '2022-07-02 16:19:17'),
(1921, '2022/03/31', '5:53 p.m.', '1', '7', 'Lucy Fairbrother', 'Mathematics', 'Number & Place Value', 'Mental Computation', 'MAD MINUTE MATHS FACTS TO 30', 'Naomi Wright', 'In Progress', NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'Not Returned', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', '<p>These notes are for the lesson conducted Thursday 24th March:</p><p>Focus on subtraction of fractions, decimals, borrowing across columns.</p><p>All fraction work includes simplifying final answers, and also converting to common denominators in order to subtract.</p><p>Lucy was easily guided through these tasks and completed the equations successfully. &nbsp;Ongoing practice and review will be incorporated to ensure retention.</p>', NULL, NULL, '2022-03-31 17:56:03', '2022-03-31 19:43:05'),
(1922, '2022/03/31', '7:27 p.m.', '1', '7', 'Archie Lester', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Substitute onset & rime - Kilpatrick Level G', 'Naomi Wright', 'Achieved', NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', '<p>These notes are for Friday 25th March 2022.</p><p>PA – Kilpatrick – G2, Sets 3 and 4</p><p>OPR – ei, ie, e, ey, th, wh, o,er</p><p>WPR – midpoint focus</p><p>Word decoding – for spelling: &nbsp;Homophones (there, they\'re, their, your, you\'re, here, hear, where, wear, were, to, two, too</p><p>Spelling dictation – (you), your, you’re</p><p>Sentence dictations :</p><ul><li>Put your clean underpants in your bag.</li><li>If you don’t change your underpants, you’re gross! Not! &nbsp;Review complex structure and add comma.</li><li>Where was their dog?</li><li>Their dog came over here when we were eating tea.</li></ul><p>Explore the connections between here, there, where – this spot, that spot, w', NULL, NULL, '2022-03-31 19:31:41', '2022-03-31 19:36:48'),
(1923, '2022/03/31', '7:39 p.m.', '1', '7', 'Lottie Young', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Naomi Wright', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', '<p>These notes are for the lesson held on Friday 25th March 2022:</p><p>Read Chapters 3 and 4 in Billie B Brown, ‘The Birthday Mix-up’.&nbsp; Used a green overlay which seems to provide a valuable support to Lottie.</p><p>Analysed the first two pages of Chapter four – markings for multi-letter phonograms. &nbsp;Lottie was engaged with this task and was interested by the number of phonograms she was able to find.</p><p>Dictate x2 sentences from Chapter Four &nbsp;text:</p><ol><li>What time is it now, Jack?&nbsp;&nbsp;</li><li>He looks down at his watch.</li></ol><p>Contractions – what is &gt; what’s, it is &gt; it’s, can not &gt; can’t (The apostrophe tells the reader that a space and a lette', NULL, NULL, '2022-03-31 19:39:47', '2022-03-31 19:42:11'),
(1924, '2022/04/01', '7:30 a.m.', '1', '8', 'Charlotte Kratz', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms', 'Oral Phonogram Review (OPR) - Various Phonograms (see notes)', 'Heather Excell', 'Achieved', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p><strong>SPELLING</strong>:</p><p>opr/wpr:</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>ough, ou, ar, ir, ei, gu, y</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p><strong>WRITING</strong>:</p><p>Key into inference - level 2 set S3</p><p><strong>NOTES</strong>:</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Charlotte and I had a slower start to tutoring this week, as we were both feeling the effects of an early start and a dark morning.<br><br>We started off with an OPR/WPR, but decided to work on inferences instead of spelling this week. Charlotte did well with common inferences (explaining that the boy was dirty if he hadn\'t been in contact with soap/water etc.), but struggled with \'the spade mad</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-04-01 07:33:55', '2022-04-08 17:34:07'),
(1925, '2022/04/01', '10:16 a.m.', '1', '8', 'Archie Lester', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Naomi Wright', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-04-01 10:17:22', '2022-04-01 10:17:22'),
(1926, '2022/04/01', '10:18 a.m.', '1', '8', 'Lottie Young', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms', 'Oral Phonogram Review (OPR) - Various Phonograms (see notes)', 'Naomi Wright', 'Achieved', NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', '<p>Review Lesson:</p><p>Read phonogram card packs in folder – all vowel sounds, SFe a-e, e-e, i-e, o-e, u-e,. &nbsp;Paste in book.</p><p>Read word decoding card packs – Sfe job 1, CVC, ow, ui, oo words (see pack in folder)</p><p>Read word decoding cards – Section A-G previously difficult – child, mace, book, tooth, earth, worm, six, late, paint, play, chance, must, sea, come.&nbsp; Oral analysis of markings and purpose for same &gt; multiletter phonograms, jobs of SFe, 2/3/4 sounds etc. &nbsp;Lottie is increasingly fluent with this level of analysis.</p><p>Mark pages 36 and 37 from Billie B Brown\'s \'The Birthday Mixup\". &nbsp;Some support needed to refine thees, but Lottie recognised majorit', NULL, NULL, '2022-04-01 10:19:25', '2022-04-01 10:35:54'),
(1928, '2022/04/04', '04:24 pm', '1', '8', 'Tiki Salt', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - High Frequency Vocabulary', 'Accurate use of analysed words', 'Compose oral sentences', 'Campbell Jepson', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Worked well through most of the phonos today got confused with\'ou\' but got there after a few seconds, was a little hesitant with the \'ie\' and \'ei\' because he didn\'t want to get them wrong. Had no idea what &nbsp;\'augh\' was. Moved onto WPR and no problems with any of them. When we moved onto dictation we focused on the \'augh\' ones for a while rather than just brushing over them. had trouble remembering to put the words into each syllable. put the words into sentences and asked him to put at least 2 adjectives in them but after his first try didn\'t put any in so i think we\'ll need to work on using them in writing a bit more.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-04-04 16:25:36', '2022-04-05 18:53:22'),
(1929, '2022/04/04', '04:25 pm', '1', '8', 'Max Shapiro', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Campbell Jepson', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-04-04 16:26:17', '2022-04-04 16:26:17'),
(1930, '2022/04/04', '04:26 pm', '1', '8', 'Stella Bowerman', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Campbell Jepson', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-04-04 16:26:45', '2022-04-04 16:26:45'),
(1931, '2022/04/04', '04:26 pm', '1', '8', 'Lachlan Prior', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Campbell Jepson', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Started with a quick game. Moved through the phonos pretty quickly, with no problems but is always looking for the poster when it comes to the \'er\' sounds. WPR was fine and got them all right. For dictation, we went through the words he got incorrect on the first page and made corrections to the draft. Was better at just adding the suffixes to the end rather than writing every sound he hears. Played a quick game of wordle before continuing with his story which brought us to the end of the lesson.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-04-04 16:27:18', '2022-04-05 18:57:25'),
(1932, '2022/04/04', '04:27 pm', '1', '8', 'Toby Webb', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Campbell Jepson', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Started off with a quick Kilpatrick which he nailed. Moved on to a game of wordle which seemed like it took forever because almost refused to try. We worked together on it and went through the jobs of the silent final e for a bit because of it. Seemed to understand but also seemed to just be good at repeating what i was saying to make it seem like he knew. Will make sure to go over it next week. WPR and OPR were both good and no problems involved apart from \'ow\' and \'ou\' so went over the sounds and words involved.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-04-04 16:28:28', '2022-04-05 19:00:30'),
(1933, '2022/04/04', '04:28 pm', '1', '8', 'Chester Vincent', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Campbell Jepson', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Started off playing hide and seek with the bouncy ball for the first 5-8 minutes. When we moved to OPR he decided they were too easy so I threw \'igh\' in there again to challenge him and see if he still remembered it. Other than that he got them all right even \'ou\' which he had problems with up until now. for WPR he got them all right apart from \'ay\' and \'ar\' so we went over them and found words that involved those two. we finished off with some reading which he did really well at sounding out all the words but didn\'t register the multi-letter phonograms in the words.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-04-04 16:29:08', '2022-04-05 19:04:39'),
(1934, '2022/04/04', '04:29 pm', '1', '8', 'Seth Vanderlaan', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Campbell Jepson', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>took a while for Seth to want to sit down and work but when he did he was very engaged. We ran through the phonos 20-30 which he got the first sound for pretty much all of them but the ones he didn\'t get straight away we put up on the board. We found words that had \'ay\' \'oy\' \'ch\' . &nbsp;We then turned those into two sentences which he wrote out on his whiteboard pretty accurately but went silly on a few letters. We then played phonodice with the vowels which he was very good at and didn\'t even cheat this time. we had about 7 minutes left so played \'cats\' with the ball.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-04-04 16:29:53', '2022-04-06 14:53:21'),
(1935, '2022/04/04', '04:29 pm', '1', '8', 'Samuel Lamont', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Campbell Jepson', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Start off with a game of chess and wordle. Wordle seemed to take a while but he\'s getting a lot better at actually coming up with words with the letters in them rather than just words that h thinks may fit. We moved to OPR and got confused at \'ou\' and couldn\'t remember all the sounds for \'ch\' we did all 35-43 for WPR and got them all right but got him to rewrite a few because they were too messy. Instead of the ayres words, i wanted him to think of words that had the phonos and got him to spell them by sounding them out with my segmenting help. he then put them into sentences which took us to the end of the lesson.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-04-04 16:30:18', '2022-04-06 14:55:56'),
(1936, '2022/04/04', '04:30 pm', '1', '9', 'Darcy Callaghan', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms', 'Oral Phongram Review (OPR) - Cards 46 > 54', 'Campbell Jepson', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Started off with a wordle which was quite difficult so we broke it down and really thought about it to get his brain working. We moved onto OPR which he got them all right but the cue in words were wrong on some of them so we went over them in further detail. in WPR he got \'kn\' and \'gn\' the wrong way around so we spent a short amount of time going over the cue in words for both and if there is a cue in needed. we then moved to create words out of a few of the phonos which he was easily able to do for most. We ran out of time for sentences so just played a game.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-04-04 16:31:24', '2022-04-05 18:49:24'),
(1937, '2022/04/04', '04:38 pm', '1', '9', 'Thomas Johnson', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms', 'Oral Phongram Review (OPR) - Cards 1 > 30', 'Yina Peng', 'Achieved', 'Achieved', 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Thomas has been more comfortable around and being quite active in class. Even if sometimes it is handful to handke him being overactive, it is still manageble for a decent learning session. He loves ball and hands on activities. We did tiwster for OPR today, he can say at least one sound on his own for the first 26 phonograms, yet he is still quite struggling to say 3 sounds for u at once. WPR: Thomas tend to write letters quite big and we have focused on line letters tody. Thomas still need help with vowels and consonants occassionally. We have been working on CVCC words today, he needed a bit reminder over vowels.<br>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-04-04 16:39:28', '2022-04-05 12:54:06'),
