(2002, '2022/04/13', '03:35 pm', '1', '10', 'Luca Mignanelli', 'Mathematics', 'Number & Place Value', 'Mental Computation', 'MAD MINUTE MATHS FACTS TO 50', 'Heather Excell', 'Achieved', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Luca started with his multiplication grid again this week. He managed to completely solve the grid in 12 min 3 sec.&nbsp;<br><br>Luca and I started looking at the division of decimals today. He seemed to understand this content to a degree, but was resistant to listening to explanations. We managed to go over a few examples together before Luca successfully completed a number of worksheets on his own. Despite this, constant revision next term would still be of benefit in this area.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-04-13 15:35:37', '2022-04-13 16:06:43'),
(2003, '2022/04/13', '03:59 pm', '1', '10', 'Max Brookfield', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Delete onset or rime - Kilpatrick Level F', 'Neve Mitchell', 'Achieved', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>PA: F1</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR: 1-8 , 27-38</td></tr><tr><td>WPR: a c s ee ou ay ch oi&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>SD: Morrison &amp; SA&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Sentence Structure: Write sentences&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>SCORE 1.4</td></tr><tr><td>Game: CVC spelling, medial sound</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Bit tricky as I hadn’t seen Max for two weeks. Needed help with 1-8 in OPR. Keep those in in future. Max on ritalin and very subdued, I kept asking if he needed a break from SA (As he looked a bit glazed over) but Max said he was fine. He improved on his SA but not enough to rank a score, Na suggested Waddington spelling. Some trouble for Max in identifying vowel sounds.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-04-13 16:00:29', '2022-04-13 18:12:21'),
(2004, '2022/04/13', '04:36 pm', '1', '10', 'Luke Gomer', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms', 'Oral Phonogram Review (OPR) - Various Phonograms (see notes)', 'Heather Excell', 'Achieved', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>SPELLING:</p><p>opr/wpr:</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>tch, er, u, ck, ar, th, ng, e</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p>Rule review:</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>5, 11, 29</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p>Spelling Dictation:</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>sometimes, engage, final, terrible, surprise</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p>WRITING:</p><p>Sentence structure:</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Sentence Structure Assignment - follow up on 3 weeks ago</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p>NOTES:</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Luke was a little tired this week post-covid, so we made sure to take the lesson nice and slowly.<br><br>First week with updated spelling list - Luke did well, but stumbled over a few of the sounds. Prompted to give sounds in syllables, and he did well.<br><br>Luke insisted on still doing his sentence assessment despite the brain fog. He completed this with only minor prompting (interrogative vs imperative) and did well to otherwise remember all his sentences/punctuation. It will still be good to further review his sentence structure (compound + complex) over the next term.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-04-13 16:36:22', '2022-04-13 17:09:52'),
