(2028, '2022/05/05', '04:24 pm', '2', '1', 'Lucy Fairbrother', 'Mathematics', 'Number & Place Value', 'Mental Computation', 'Mad Minute Maths - Facts to 100', 'Naomi Wright', 'In Progress', NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'Followup', '<p>Lucy needed a considerable amount of time and support working through the calculations to solve 96/12, using the 9 times tables, checking with the 4 times tables and then checking as a multiplication. &nbsp;Once she had grasped these connections. Lucy then used them tentatively to support the checking of long division equations in the NSPM workbook.</p><p>It was really pleasing to see Lucy refer to long division problems solved with support to help her work through further problems independently.</p>', NULL, NULL, '2022-05-05 16:24:43', '2022-05-05 18:16:53'),
(2029, '2022/05/05', '04:55 pm', '2', '1', 'Callisto Pratten', 'Mathematics', 'Pythagoras and Trigonometry', 'Pythagoras theorem', 'TEXT BOOK - EXERCISES, QUESTIONS, ACTIVITIES', 'Rosemary Beswick', 'In Progress', 'In Progress', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', '<p>Callisto has an assignment for Maths which is due on Monday. It involves Pythagoras\' Theorem and basic right-angle Trig. She had forgotten lots about these aspects of Maths and needed reminders about how to proceed with the problems. We did not finish the last question.</p>', NULL, NULL, '2022-05-05 16:57:18', '2022-05-05 18:10:42'),
(2030, '2022/05/05', '05:06 pm', '2', '1', 'James Coleman', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Delete onset or rime - Kilpatrick Level F', 'Ellie Connor', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week One</td></tr><tr><td>Thursday, 5 May 2022</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>PA: Kilpatrick</td></tr><tr><td>MA: Donah</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR/WPR: oa ew a ar er o ou ur ea th ti</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Rule Review: 17, 29, 4</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD: Sec. L - soap, news, new, small, smaller, smallest, war, summer, above</td></tr><tr><td>Read S&amp;R</td></tr><tr><td>Talk about comparative and superlative, use in sentences to show meaning. Talk about context helping us understand words</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>ORF x1</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Homework: Prefix practice page</td></tr><tr><td>Good with PA and MA (some prompting), prompting with ti but otherwise fine on phonos. No cues for rules, JC was all over it and could tell me what was happening in each word. He drew a picture of things that were small, smaller and smallest, then we read for a bit.&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-05-05 17:06:33', '2022-05-06 20:10:56'),
(2031, '2022/05/05', '05:06 pm', '2', '1', 'Chelsea Cooper', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Delete onset or rime - Kilpatrick Level F', 'Ellie Connor', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week One</td></tr><tr><td>Thursday, 5 May 2022</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>PA: Kilpatrick Multisyllabic F1</td></tr><tr><td>MA: Donah #11</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR/WPR: oa ew a ar er o ou ur ea th ti</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Rule Review: 4, 19</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD: behind, around, burn, camp, bear, bare, clear, clean</td></tr><tr><td>Read S&amp;R</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>ORF x3</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Needed prompting with PA, pretty good with MA. Some prompting with initial sounds of phonos, but CC was able to finish them independently. Really good with SD. CC tends to struggle when reading for S is different to reading for R</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-05-05 17:08:08', '2022-05-06 20:15:16'),
(2033, '2022/05/06', '10:49 am', '2', '1', 'Archie Seelig', 'Mathematics', 'Patterns & Algebra', 'Expand binomial products and factorise monic quadratic expressions using a variety of strategies', 'Text book - Exercises, Questions, Activities', 'Ivan Botero', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-05-06 10:50:03', '2022-05-06 10:51:40'),
(2034, '2022/05/06', '03:09 pm', '2', '1', 'Luna Shapiro', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Delete onset or rime - Kilpatrick Level F', 'Neve Mitchell', 'Achieved', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>PA: Kilpatrick F1</td></tr><tr><td>With physical modelling Luna did very well at separating onset and rime</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Recap voiced/unvoiced sounds. LS remembered from last time!</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>How do we talk to one another? By making sound? When we write, we\'re trying to put our words on paper. We use letters for this. Each letter matches up with a sound! Letter match with first sounds in pictures.</td></tr><tr><td>OPR: 1-8 -- teach first sounds. X2</td></tr><tr><td>WPR: 1-8</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>These letters are special because they all have the same starting point when they are written. Show the racecar tracks, tracing pages. They all have a circle!&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Trace on the tracing pages, then 2x2 boxes for: a d g s o</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>We can hear these sounds in words.</td></tr><tr><td>Segment, count, blend:&nbsp; ad, god, sad,&nbsp; dad, dog</td></tr><tr><td>Use stickers to \'write\' god, dog, sad&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>We are going to use these letters to write words. Dictate above words.</td></tr><tr><td>Read for spelling/reading</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p>Notes</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>School language: digraph. Luna only connected this to the idea of sound/letter, not the 2 letters making one sound.</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Luna is still a tricky customer but today went better than last time. She\'s quick to try and procure a bribe (if I do this can I have a lolly? Etc). Finding physical ways to do the activities was helpful, although I was thinking on my feet. E.g. segment, count, blend I made her get up and jump to different points on the floor for the segment/blend.&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Her a formation was great for the most part and I am so proud of her for that. She also remembered a significant amount of work from last time. I think we can get clockface letters down so long as I present it in a very physical task. Maybe drawing giant letters on the floor? Or getting a giant clock that she can walk/trace letters around... maybe the hula hoop???</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-05-06 15:10:08', '2022-05-10 16:08:32'),
(2035, '2022/05/06', '03:10 pm', '2', '1', 'Elsa Clennett', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms', 'Oral Phonogram Review (OPR) - Various Phonograms (see notes)', 'Neve Mitchell', 'Achieved', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR: 27-70</td></tr><tr><td>WPR: ew ui gu ey gn kn ie dge ough</td></tr><tr><td>EC shaky in WPR after the break</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Read R&amp;S: Current Ayres Column</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Rule review: 29 6 24</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD: course-carry</td></tr><tr><td>Read R&amp;S</td></tr><tr><td>Explain/discuss the markings and meanings of analysed words.</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Rule Intro: NA</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Use Ayres words in sentences for carriage/marriage.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>WP: 100 word story. Plan the beginning/middle/end.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Elsa is so attached to her ideas of structure in terms of story telling -- I really want her to branch out and get creative with what she\'s doing! I think she would like it once she sees it in action. I also think it\'s holding her back a little… want to share Roald Dahl story with her so we can talk about short story structure and building up suspense in other ways.</td></tr><tr><td>Elsa was so tired today. It was really difficult and slow, her words got muddled and she would continuously be like \"oh, you know what I mean.\" I\'ve started making her explain herself and not just brush it aside like that, and she usually can, but it seems like such a taxing effort for her. Hard to keep spirits up.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-05-06 15:10:27', '2022-05-10 16:17:01'),
(2036, '2022/05/06', '03:11 pm', '2', '1', 'Arki Young', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms', 'Oral Phonogram Review (OPR) - Various Phonograms (see notes)', 'Neve Mitchell', 'Achieved', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR: 50-70</td></tr><tr><td>WPR: oe ough ey ie dge ei eigh&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>PROMPT CARDS ON BOARD</td></tr><tr><td>Read R&amp;S: Current Ayres Column</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Rule review: 4 6 14 18</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD:</td></tr><tr><td>Read R&amp;S</td></tr><tr><td>Explain/discuss the markings and meanings of analysed words.</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Rule Intro: NA</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Use Ayres words in oral/written sentences in various sentence types.</td></tr><tr><td>WP: Review broken down paragraph from last lesson &amp; the topic sentences. Create paragraph from this scaffold.&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>WP: Explain the importance of topic sentences in providing structure/maintaining a clear argument. Goals of a topic sentence: state main idea of section. A paragraph will have one main idea, but maybe three or four \'mini\' ideas as well.</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;Create a new plan for topic of Arki\'s choice and then turn into a paragraph.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Great lesson with Arki as usual. He\'s still struggling a little with the concept of topic sentences -- or, maybe more accurately, paring back his topic sentences to JUST be topic sentences. I\'m thinking ahead here to essay writing where he won\'t be including his argument/evidence in the first sentence. It\'s easier to do this with short paragraph tasks.</td></tr><tr><td>I modelled the creation of topic sentences but Arki still tended to include his key words in the topic sentence. Maybe we could ramp up to writing essays? I\'m viewing this paragraph task as more like a short essay… maybe Arki and I need to chat about that. Alternatively, a paragraph task where there\'s just ONE argument supported by supporting sentences, not supporting sentences introducing new ideas.</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Arki\'s goals:</td></tr><tr><td>Grade 8 curriculumn --&gt; compressing a year, jump to grade 9. Grade 8 content.</td></tr><tr><td>Being able to write bigger pieces of writing.</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-05-06 15:11:28', '2022-05-16 17:53:06'),
(2037, '2022/05/06', '03:11 pm', '2', '1', 'Sophie Mirowski', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Manipulate (delete or substitute) initial phoneme in initial blend - Kilpatrick Level H', 'Neve Mitchell', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>PA: Kilpatrick H1</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR: 39-55</td></tr><tr><td>WPR: or ew ui ng gu ea ed&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Read R&amp;S: Current Ayres Column</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Rule review: 24 5 6 (28 12)</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD: thunder-vein</td></tr><tr><td>Read R&amp;S</td></tr><tr><td>Explain/discuss the markings and meanings of analysed words.</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Rule Intro: NA</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Sentence Structure: Use Ayres words in sentences. Focus has been just getting Sophie to use her words in context since we so often run out of time, but I really want to try and push for type/structure to be involved…&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p>Notes:</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Really slow lesson with Sophie. Kilpatrick H1 is a good level to spend some time on. Had to scaffold for every task, and even then she would sometimes miss off the second letter of the consonant blend. I had to correct her often and I think she got disheartened by that.</td></tr><tr><td>We also had difficulty with sounding spelling words and applying rule 24, which was a combination of Soph getting muddled between whether she was sounding out tried or tries, and then not understanding my verbal instructions for applying rule 24. When I showed her on the board and modelled it with a visual element she was fine.&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-05-06 15:11:46', '2022-05-17 17:02:40'),
(2038, '2022/05/06', '03:11 pm', '2', '1', 'Shay Douglas', 'Mathematics', 'Linear & Non-Linear Relationships', 'Linear & Non-linear equations', 'Text book - Exercises, Questions, Activities', 'Neve Mitchell', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'Attended Tardy', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Maths</td></tr><tr><td>Completing the square.</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Cambridge textbook exercises for completing the square. Introduced Shay to the concept pre-emptively so he\'ll be familiar with it when it arises at school.&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Easy enough for Shay to pick up. Shay also has an English assignment to start working on but it\'s still very early days so he did not want to spend time on it today.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-05-06 15:12:02', '2022-05-17 16:50:21'),
