(2137, '2022/05/13', '08:55 am', '2', '1', 'Archie Lester', 'English', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Naomi Wright', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-05-13 08:55:41', '2022-05-13 08:55:41'),
(2138, '2022/05/13', '09:48 am', '2', '2', 'Gus  Pettit', 'Mathematics', 'Fractions', 'Operations with fractions', 'Discussion & Practise (on board/in book)', 'Ivan Botero', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', '<p>Kindly Gus asked me to work on fractions as he\'s struggling with those at school.&nbsp;</p><p>We were looking at the relationship between fractions and divisions, operations with fractions, and simplifying fractions and equivalent fractions.&nbsp;</p><p>Overall, the student did a great job. After I gave him explicit instruction on how to do operations with fractions, he was able to solve all the problems in round practice almost without a problem.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, NULL, '2022-05-13 09:48:53', '2022-07-02 14:21:15'),
(2139, '2022/05/13', '02:30 pm', '2', '2', 'Molly Jackson', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Manipulate (delete or substitute) second phoneme in initial blend - Kilpatrick Level K', 'Neve Mitchell', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>PA: Kilpatrick K1</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Challenge: south</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR: 56-70</td></tr><tr><td>WPR:&nbsp; ew ui oa gu ph ey + they, key, money, people</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Read R&amp;S: Current Ayres Column</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Rule review: 4 13</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD: next-cause</td></tr><tr><td>Read R&amp;S</td></tr><tr><td>Explain/discuss the markings and meanings of analysed words.</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Rule Intro: NA</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Sentence Types: Create oral sentences for 4x sentence types.</td></tr><tr><td>Sentence Structure: Recap simple and compound structure. Introduce/review \'independent clause\' word, talk about meaning of independent,&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Molly looking at prefixes at school</td></tr><tr><td>Good lesson with Molly, she got a bit goofy towards the middle but giving her a physical game to play (karate chop) and also some breathign exercises calmed her down successfully for spelling. She was great with her sentence types and structures. Note for me -- house images for structure/type discussion.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-05-13 14:31:44', '2022-05-13 17:41:20'),
(2140, '2022/05/13', '03:31 pm', '2', '2', 'Harlow Booy', 'Mathematics', 'Number & Place Value', 'Explore the connection between addition and subtraction', 'TEXT BOOK - EXERCISES, QUESTIONS, ACTIVITIES', 'Ivan Botero', 'Not Yet', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', '<p>Harlow\'s maths teacher, Bronwyn Hofman, sent me an email about the work they\'re doing at school.&nbsp;</p><p>The information is a screenshot of Harlow\'s profile in the software Essential Assessments.&nbsp;</p><p>Her recommendations are to cover the areas the student has some gaps, we started with exploring the connection between additions and subtractions.&nbsp;</p><p>Recognise and represent multiplication as repeated additions, groups and arrays.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, NULL, '2022-05-13 15:31:58', '2022-07-02 11:51:27'),
(2141, '2022/05/13', '03:39 pm', '2', '1', 'Connor Thompson', 'Essay Writing', 'Elements', 'Referencing & Bibliography', 'See Notes', 'Neve Mitchell', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Connor had not completed the homework worksheet I made up for him last week, so we completed that in class. I really went through what referencing is, why we do it, what plagiarism is, even involving some base word discussion about what it means to \'refer\'. Connor\'s attitude was typical. I think this discussion was helpful -- he didn\'t know what plagiarism meant, other than \"to do something wrong.\" It\'s just hard to persevere in these lessons because Connor\'s attitude is so dismissive/unengaged. I\'m really losing patience for it.</td></tr><tr><td>I even asked Connor how he imagines I feel to come in here week after week and essentially do all the talking, and sometimes here \"mm, mhmm, mm.\" But Connor did not engage with this at all, just dismissed it. It\'s fine, but I told him I don\'t know what he expects me to do if he won\'t meet me halfway, but of course Connor\'s response was \"mmhmm.\"</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-05-13 15:39:46', '2022-05-13 17:40:15'),
(2142, '2022/05/13', '04:33 pm', '2', '2', 'Mason Turner', 'Mathematics', 'Patterns & Algebra', 'Find unknown quantities in number sentences involving the four operations', 'Text book - Exercises, Questions, Activities', 'Ivan Botero', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Mason and I were working in both sessions on simple equations. The student struggles with the algebraic operations of simple terms.&nbsp;<br>We did equations like 3X+4=10 during the whole 2 sessions.&nbsp;</p>', '<p>Friday 06.05.22 Mason came twice in the morning and afternoon</p>', '2022-05-13 16:33:45', '2022-07-02 10:06:07'),
(2143, '2022/05/13', '04:34 pm', '2', '2', 'Nate Betros', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms', 'Oral Phonogram Review (OPR) - Various Phonograms (see notes)', 'Neve Mitchell', 'Achieved', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Discussion about Nate\'s coin collection -- shillings/pence, etc</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR: 44-71</td></tr><tr><td>WPR: NA</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Read R&amp;S: Current Ayres Column</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Rule review: 21 4 29</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD: charge-office</td></tr><tr><td>Read R&amp;S</td></tr><tr><td>Explain/discuss the markings and meanings of analysed words.</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Rule Intro: NA</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Writing Process: Paragraph ID elements and colour code activity</td></tr><tr><td>Writing Process: Create plan for persuasive paragraph using firstly, secondly, thirdly.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Nate apprehensive about writing a paragraph, didn\'t feel he was up to it. I went through his book and showed him how he had mastered simple, compound, complex sentences and using these in paragraphs was the next step. I may still have to pare back a little --&gt; three sentences about single topic rather than a \"paragraph\"? He was doing well initially but it disintergrated when he lost sight of his topic (although he was, as typical, adamant that he knew better than me and I was wrong to say he was getting off topic!)</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-05-13 16:34:31', '2022-05-13 17:45:07'),
(2144, '2022/05/16', '08:40 am', '2', '1', 'Darcy Callaghan', 'English', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Campbell Jepson', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-05-16 08:40:06', '2022-05-16 08:40:06'),
(2145, '2022/05/16', '08:46 am', '2', '3', 'Lewis Prevost', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Delete syllable from two syllable word - Kilpatrick Level D', 'Ellie Connor', 'Achieved', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week Three</td></tr><tr><td>Monday, 16 May 2022</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>PA: Kilpatrick D1 supplemental</td></tr><tr><td>MA: Donah #13</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>OPR/WPR: gu igh ey oo ch wr wh</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>SD: us, am, good, little</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Pip and Tim 4+ \"The Little Vet\"</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>CVC game</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Homework: us, am, good, little, ago, old, bad, red</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>I was so impressed with Lewis today. A little quiet and reserved when he came in (was apparently grumpy with Alysia), but he quickly snapped out of it. Some prompting with MA, but fine with PA (other than being a little distracted). Really good with his phonos, gets confused with cues but is fine with sounds. Some initial prompting with gu, ey, oo (order). I was super impressed with LP\'s SD. He wrote super neatly and didn\'t have to rewrite anything for the whole lesson. He was also able to ID markings for good and little. Read Pip and Tim 4+ \"The Little Vet\" - a level up from what he\'s currently been doing. Lewis wasn\'t fluent, but was able to decode everything almost independently (some prompting with b/d/p), and got through the whole book on his own. I was amazed with his focus and stamina. Finished with a CVC game. Alysia told me that they\'ve got a speech path report, but she\'s been really frustrated with the whole process, feeling like she\'s being told to do things she\'s already done/doing.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-05-16 08:46:00', '2022-05-16 10:03:59'),
(2146, '2022/05/16', '03:31 pm', '2', '3', 'Thomas Johnson', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms', 'Oral Phongram Review (OPR) - Cards 31 > 45', 'Yina Peng', 'Achieved', 'Achieved', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>1. challenge word: na vy. Thomas could recall rule 4 and articulate. Mia was able to repeat.</p><p>2. OPR: 27-38-try not to moo game in which Mia could pay attention more about what she says and she won the game which meant that she could accurately say the sounds for most of the phonograms. &nbsp;Thomas is a competitive kid and he could concentrate very well to say multi sounds for all phonograms. Mia was great at them too yet she needed help with ai. &nbsp;They both could say first 3 sounds of ou, first 2 sounds of ch, and both needed help for phonogram ow.&nbsp;</p><p>3. WPR: 27-38. Handwriting focus was line letter b. Mia needed help with ay, ai, oi, and oy. Thomas wrote sh backwards.&nbsp;</p><p>4. Rule 4 and rule 7 review. Thomas could explain these two rules and MIa was able to articulate after being told, but she will need recap.&nbsp;<br>5. SD and new rule: rule 8. rule 8 cutting and sorting game which kept them engaged. Mia needed help with longer words to find five er.&nbsp;</p><p>6. Sentence writing. Please refer to folder. her first nurse works early.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-05-16 15:31:46', '2022-05-17 14:15:10'),
