(2235, '2022/05/23', '05:48 pm', '2', '2', 'Connor McLaren', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Manipulate (delete or substitute) initial phoneme in initial blend - Kilpatrick Level H', 'Ellie Connor', 'In Progress', 'In Progress', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week Two</td></tr><tr><td>Monday, 9 May 2022</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>PA: Kilpatrick H2 S4</td></tr><tr><td>MA: Donah #8</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR/WPR: gi ow sh er ea th ng ch ee</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Rule Review: 26, 4, 11, 22</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD: Sec. N - October, reason, fifth, baking, bake, bowl, cheap, cheerful</td></tr><tr><td>Read S&amp;R</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Challenge word: CM: nation (may need prompt with r. 14),&nbsp; LS: driving (may need prompt with base/suffix)</td></tr><tr><td>VD: both to give verbal sentences using each other\'s words (i.e. CM: driving, LS: nation)</td></tr><tr><td>Use WP to start a piece of persuasive writing (relate back to the science of persuasion principles)</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>ORF x3</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Uno, words at work or darts</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Half hour extra to catch up W1. Boys good with PA and MA, intro of \'gi\', both fine with it. Needed prompting to sound as they wrote. No issues with SD, both able to ID markings. Framed the challenge word as a competition</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', '<p>Extra half hour from Week 1 as catch up.</p>', '2022-05-23 17:49:34', '2022-05-23 17:53:07'),
(2236, '2022/05/23', '05:49 pm', '2', '2', 'Lachlan  Smith', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Manipulate (delete or substitute) initial phoneme in initial blend - Kilpatrick Level H', 'Ellie Connor', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week Three</td></tr><tr><td>Monday, 16 May 2022</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>PA: Kilpatrick H2 S5</td></tr><tr><td>MA: Donah #9</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR/WPR: er ti ch ck ng oe ai kn ea th</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Rule Review: 25, 11, 4, 6, 25,&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD: Sec. N - chicken, driving, drive, echoes, echo, fairy, knock, leather, linen</td></tr><tr><td>Read S&amp;R</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Challenge word: declared (CM)&nbsp; vacation (LS)</td></tr><tr><td>VD: both to give verbal sentences using each other\'s words</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Darts</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Half hour extra to catch up W1. Boys were a bit rowdy esp during SD, but quickly settled once I had a little growl at them. Fine with PA, MA and phonos (some prompting to say them in unison). Boys were distracted and a bit too silly in SD, so I had to tell them to calm down and do as I asked. They did a challenge word on the board, and I was impressed with their efforts. We analysed a couple of government election campaigns and talked through why they were/weren\'t effective. LS worked quite well on his persuasive task, CM took a really long time to settle, and I had to tell him off a couple of times for distracting Lachlan. We eventually got through it and played darts to finish.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', '<p>Half hour to catch up W1</p>', '2022-05-23 17:50:25', '2022-05-23 18:12:26'),
(2238, '2022/05/23', '06:12 pm', '2', '3', 'James  Coleman', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Substitute onset & rime - Kilpatrick Level G', 'Ellie Connor', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week Three</td></tr><tr><td>Thursday, 19 May 2022</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>PA: Kilpatrick</td></tr><tr><td>MA: Donah #15</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR/WPR: igh ti ar ch ci ir th ee ai si</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Rule Review: 26</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD: Sec.&nbsp; L - right, write, wrote, date, road, rode, ride, March, march, next</td></tr><tr><td>Read S&amp;R</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Use homophones/related words in sentences together to show meaning.</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Start recap of sentence structure</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>ORF x3</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Homework: Two sentences using words from last week (uncompleted)</td></tr><tr><td>Really good with MA, PA, phonos and SD. Some prompting to make connections between si and th (unvoiced and voiced sounds), otherwise able to give sounds easily. Just need to work on making connections unprompted. Good convo about homophones and similar or related words. James wrote three sentences, each one using a \'group\' of related words from our spelling list. I thought he\'d find this really hard, but his spelling has improved so much. He was able to do this task almost unprompted (I gave a bit of help with using \'road\'), and provided some good sentences. Finished with ORF x3</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-05-23 18:13:46', '2022-05-23 18:16:07'),
(2239, '2022/05/24', '07:43 am', '2', '4', 'Henry  Badock', 'Mathematics', 'Number & Place Value', 'Explore the connection between addition and subtraction', 'Game', 'Laree Thorsby', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>T2W4</p><p>Focus: Mental computation</p><p>Timed activities: to/from 20</p><p>Focus: Addition retaining place value. Henry tends to add from right to left. Complete the addition to 100 worksheet</p><p>Use number line to count up with addition to check answers</p><p>Dice Game/Pirate Pete</p><p>Roll the 20 dice and record the number. Roll the 12 dice and make a addition problem. Record and answer using the number line to count on.</p><p>Highest number stabs Pete.</p><p>Repeat with subtraction. Lowest number stabs Pete</p><p>Focus: Explore the relationship between Addition and Subtraction</p><p>Check every answer by using the opposite function.&nbsp;</p><p>NW: demo counting up as a strategy for subtraction.&nbsp;</p><p><br>Focus: Explore the relationship between Addition and multiplication</p><p>Worksheet with boxes – x2&nbsp;</p><p>Last week Henry was able to represent the following, however he struggled to recognise the reverse was true. He recorded each initially as addition and eventually was able to model 4x5 after extensive coaching and use of the manipulatives.&nbsp;</p><p>5x3 = 3+3+3+3+3=15</p><p>5x2 =2+2+2+2+2+2=10</p><p>5x4 =4+4+4+4+4=20</p><p>This week we used a worksheet and Henry completed and articulated each step. He has not grasped the concept that repeated addition is the same as multiplication.</p><p>Bucket Toss</p><p>1 round of subtraction from 50, recording on the number line.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-05-24 07:43:46', '2022-05-24 09:14:47'),
(2240, '2022/05/24', '08:48 am', '2', '5', 'Max Shapiro', 'English', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Campbell Jepson', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-05-24 08:48:03', '2022-05-24 08:48:03'),
(2241, '2022/05/24', '02:34 pm', '2', '4', 'Stella Lorkin', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms', 'Oral Phongram Review (OPR) - Cards 31 > 45', 'Yina Peng', 'Achieved', 'Achieved', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Stella is still quite playful during our lesson yet she can concentratet on better than before. She has short term concentration so we needed to keep her moving and engaged the whole time&nbsp;</p><ol><li>OPR/WPR v, w, x, sh, ee, th, ow, ou. multi sound game for ou. Suprisingly, she can say most of them and just needed help with sh, ee, ow. She is still very struggling at written phonograms review for ou, ow, th and sh.&nbsp;</li><li>Handwriting focus: line letter w. Stella can form most of the letters above in the right way when she is reminded. She tends to write them in her best way because she knows I will take a photo of them and put them in her notebook.</li><li>Morphology: activity 13. She is quite good yet she needed color code to represent words in a compound word.&nbsp;</li><li>SD: ice, gem. Stella is not ready for these.&nbsp;</li><li>Oral sentence: she usually makes great complete sentence orally with SD words.<br>&nbsp;</li></ol>', NULL, '2022-05-24 14:34:50', '2022-05-25 11:04:43'),
(2242, '2022/05/24', '03:28 pm', '2', '3', 'Stella Bowerman', 'Mathematics', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Campbell Jepson', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-05-24 15:28:16', '2022-05-24 15:28:16'),
(2243, '2022/05/24', '03:31 pm', '2', '4', 'Brock Smith', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Language Rules (Pronunciation/Spelling/Grammar)', 'Rule 28: Read ed as /ed/ if the base word ends in d or t, as /d after a voiced consonant, /t/ after an unvoiced consonant', 'See Notes', 'Yina Peng', 'Achieved', 'Achieved', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<ol><li>Kilpatrick H1.&nbsp;</li><li>OPR/WPR or, ou, ee, ea, th, er, ed. Brock needed help to recall the fourth sound of ou, and 3 sounds of ea.&nbsp;</li><li>SD: rule review : 6, 8, 9, 28. &nbsp;vocabulary: world-trip.&nbsp;</li><li>Sentence: Brock used body and meat made a complex sentence. He is shaky on making logical sentence as he does not like writing but he likes reading.&nbsp;</li><li>Parts of speech: he knows nouns and verbs, we recapped adjectives, pronouns and adverbs. &nbsp;</li><li>&nbsp;</li><li>Brock shows no interest in writing and he love math.&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;</li></ol>', NULL, '2022-05-24 15:31:06', '2022-05-25 08:56:32'),
(2244, '2022/05/24', '03:32 pm', '2', '4', 'Sophie Mirowski', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Manipulate (delete or substitute) initial phoneme in initial blend - Kilpatrick Level H', 'Neve Mitchell', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>PA: Kilpatrick H3</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR: 35-54</td></tr><tr><td>WPR: ay ai oy oi er ur ear ed ew ui</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Read R&amp;S: Current Ayres Column</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Rule Review: 2 9 26 6</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD: centre-learn</td></tr><tr><td>Read R&amp;S</td></tr><tr><td>Explain/discuss the markings and meanings of analysed words.</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Rule Intro: NA</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Sentence Structure: Use Ayres words in sentences to show meaning.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>A typical lesson for Sophie. I\'m trying so hard to keep her on track (asking her to leave her stories until the end, cutting her off (politely), prompting her back on task) but she loses focus so often and on such whims. E.g., writing a simple sentence usually presents at least 3 moments where she will put her pen down, head up, and start talking. And once she starts talking she talks at a mile a minute and she won\'t stop/refocus until she gets it all out of her system. Otherwise whatever she wants to say is just circling around in her head and preventing her from doing what she\'s meant to be.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-05-24 15:32:45', '2022-05-24 16:32:42'),
(2245, '2022/05/24', '04:17 pm', '2', '3', 'Lachlan Prior', 'English', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Campbell Jepson', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-05-24 16:17:04', '2022-05-24 16:17:04'),
(2246, '2022/05/24', '04:33 pm', '2', '4', 'Callum Coulson', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Language Rules (Pronunciation/Spelling/Grammar)', 'Rule 19: i may say /I/ and o may say /O/ when followed by two consonants', 'See Notes', 'Yina Peng', 'Achieved', 'Achieved', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<ol><li>Kilpatrick F.</li><li><strong>OPR/WPR: oo. s, i, x, ed, or, o. Callum was a little bit shaky on oo and ed, but in general he is so much beter at recognizing each sound of each phonograms. He occasionally still say s with a rolling tongue.&nbsp;</strong></li><li><strong>New phonogram: oe,&nbsp;</strong></li><li><strong>Rule review rule 20 extra , 4, even 17, small. He does not remember the rules but he understands them when we read the rules.&nbsp;</strong></li><li><strong>New rules rule 28, 19.&nbsp;</strong></li><li><strong>SD: section M stood-drill.</strong></li><li><strong>SD words making a sentence. He made a compound sentence. Callum\'s sentence makes sense yet he usually struggles of coming up an idea for his sentences.&nbsp;</strong></li><li><strong>Morphology: we introduced parts of speech---noun, verb, adjectives, adverb. He knows these in general and just needs help with finding a specific type of words.&nbsp;</strong><br><br>&nbsp;</li></ol>', NULL, '2022-05-24 16:33:53', '2022-05-25 09:06:49'),
(2247, '2022/05/24', '04:37 pm', '2', '1', 'Shay Douglas', 'Academic Coaching', 'Independent Study', 'School Assigned Worksheet or Assignment', 'See Notes', 'Neve Mitchell', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Subject: Maths/English</td></tr><tr><td>Focus: Compound interest / Creating logical structure/order to argument.</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Asked Shay if there were some general areas of his essay writing skills he thought could use improvement (thinking back to his past essays). In his latest essay, he identified that: due to various reasons, he didn\'t have the exact question when he began writing the essay, so had some elements written that then didn\'t fit, some pactice ordering his thoughts and structuring his argument better.</td></tr><tr><td>We created an essay plan for an essay we\'ll never write, so it had to be immensely detailed. I also gave Shay a 3000w word count to fill. We had to really put our heads together and think outside the box to get enough content to fill the essay. We talked about structuing an argument.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-05-24 16:37:44', '2022-05-24 17:12:48'),
(2248, '2022/05/24', '05:31 pm', '2', '3', 'Isaac Ellis', 'Mathematics', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Ivan Botero', NULL, NULL, 'Rescheduled', 'N/A', 'To Be Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, '<p>Isaac\'s 3rd lesson was re-scheduled; new date 15/07/2022</p>', '2022-05-24 17:31:03', '2022-06-13 09:58:41'),
(2249, '2022/05/24', '05:32 pm', '2', '4', 'Andrew Allan', 'English', 'Writing - Parts of Speech & Vocabulary', 'Adjectives - describe nouns', 'See Notes', 'Laree Thorsby', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'Not Returned', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>T2W4</p><p>Andrew was fidgety and ODD. He did eventually agree to attempt each task but it took a lot of prompting and calming techniques to get him to focus.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>OPR ow ou au aw or ar ng&nbsp;dge tch g gu&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>WPR ow ou au aw or ar ng&nbsp;dge tch g gu&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Rules&nbsp;</p><p>hive</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>SD</p><p>Stand stands yard bring &nbsp;five&nbsp;</p><p>next week rule 17 words&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Writing</p><p>&nbsp;</p><ol><li><strong>Complete the sentence using the words from this list.&nbsp;</strong></li></ol><p>&nbsp;</p><p>yard&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; stands&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; ball&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; yells&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; bring</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Dad _____________ in the ___________ and__________, “__________&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>the _________ to me.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Add <i>adjectives</i> to the <i>nouns</i> <strong>yard</strong> and <strong>ball</strong> to make the sentence more interesting.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Dad stands in the ___________ yard and yells,&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“Bring the _________ ball to me.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><ol><li><strong>Complete the sentence using words from this list.</strong></li></ol><p>&nbsp;</p><p>belong&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; bears&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; tell &nbsp; &nbsp; five&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>__________ me, do the _________ soft _________ __________ to you?&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Find the &nbsp;2 <i>adjectives</i> describing the bears and write them below.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>___________&nbsp; ___________ bears.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Reading Fitzroy 40 shawn and the go-kart read fluently, sounding out unfamiliar words.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-05-24 17:32:22', '2022-05-24 17:41:25'),
(2250, '2022/05/24', '05:41 pm', '2', '4', 'Esther Mclver', 'English', 'Writing - Sentence Construction & Vocabulary', 'Elements of a compound sentence > Capital letter, two independent clauses joined by a coordinating conjunction (FANBOYS), ending punctuation', 'Recognise/Analyse/Model/Compose compound sentences that include subject nouns/pronouns and coordinating conjunctions for, and, nor, but, or, yet, so (FANBOYS)', 'Laree Thorsby', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>T2W4</p><p>OPR a e I o u y x ie ei wr wh kn gn ough gu ew ui ea ey qu ng ay ee th ti si ci&nbsp; &nbsp;</p><p>WPR wr wh kn gn ng gu ay ee th ti si ci&nbsp; &nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Rule Teaching:&nbsp;</p><p>29 col lar&nbsp;</p><p>Job 1 gave&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Sect N woman – eve ning</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Writing:</p><p>Dictate I will pay the bus fare so we can ride to the fun fair.&nbsp;</p><p>Compose the following-</p><p>Compound sentence:</p><p>Young woman&nbsp;</p><p>Complex sentence using&nbsp;</p><p>Even though the woman was running, …………………………….</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Of 111</p><p>Timed read 3 errors&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Hw sheet given&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-05-24 17:42:15', '2022-05-24 17:44:58'),
(2251, '2022/05/25', '08:11 am', '2', '3', 'Darcy Callaghan', 'English', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Campbell Jepson', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-05-25 08:11:45', '2022-05-25 08:11:45'),
(2252, '2022/05/25', '09:08 am', '2', '4', 'Luke  Vandenberg', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Language Rules (Pronunciation/Spelling/Grammar)', 'Rule 27: Write z to say /z/ at the beginning of words (write s to say /z/ in the middle or end of a word)', 'See Notes', 'Yina Peng', 'Achieved', 'Achieved', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Luke has shown lot of impatience today and all he wanted to do was to play the ball. It was hard to keep him concentrate on tasks. I will have to talk to Juno about how to keep him concentrated. He did not want to work on sentences and writing.&nbsp;</p><ol><li>Kilpatrick I</li><li>Challenge: He was given<strong> &nbsp;a complex sentence and explain parts of speech. He seems like not recall anything about the sentence structure elements when it comes to application. He could not find the right parts of speech I was asking and needed help with analyzing the sentence.</strong></li><li><strong>OPR/WPR: oo, ch, ui, ew, o, e, ck, z. He perfectly killed these.&nbsp;</strong></li><li><strong>Handwriting: cursive j</strong></li><li><strong>Rule review 17, 25. full. check. He could not recall anything yet he seems like he understands them.&nbsp;</strong></li><li><strong>SD: doll, egg, fruit, looks, pick, rich, zoo, zip zero. With zero, he needed help with syllibilification and could not recall rule 4 and 27.&nbsp;</strong></li><li><strong>Morphology: he perectly added suffix ed to pick and made a new word.&nbsp;</strong></li><li><strong>Letter to Callan. His sentence can be very oral sometimes and he did not use punctuation at all.&nbsp;</strong><br><br><br><br>&nbsp;</li></ol>', NULL, '2022-05-25 09:09:15', '2022-05-25 09:20:28'),
(2253, '2022/05/25', '01:45 pm', '2', '4', 'Eleanor  Stam', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Language Rules (Pronunciation/Spelling/Grammar)', 'Rule 10: In words with two syllables where the accent is on the second syllable which also has one vowel followed by one consonant, double the consonant before adding a vowel ending/suffix', 'Sorting activity (WVC, ET flashcards)', 'Laree Thorsby', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>T2W3</p><p>Rule 9 sorting</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>PA</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>OPR/WPR</p><p>ng ed ck tch ch ew ui aw au wr wh kn gn gu&nbsp; y a e I o u&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>SD</p><p>Begin (ing)</p><p>Reset(ing)</p><p>Forgot(en)</p><p>Upset(ing)</p><p>Repot(ed)</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Writing</p><p>Compound exclamatory sentence using a upset.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Underline the subject noun and the verb (and object noun).</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Reading</p><p>Silent practice</p><p>Timed read.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>HW</p><p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-05-25 13:45:10', '2022-05-25 15:05:49'),
(2254, '2022/05/25', '01:46 pm', '2', '4', 'Angel King', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Language Rules (Pronunciation/Spelling/Grammar)', 'Rule 10: In words with two syllables where the accent is on the second syllable which also has one vowel followed by one consonant, double the consonant before adding a vowel ending/suffix', 'Sorting activity (WVC, ET flashcards)', 'Laree Thorsby', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>T2W3</p><p>Rule 9 sorting</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>PA</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>OPR/WPR</p><p>ng ed ck tch ch ew ui aw au wr wh kn gn gu&nbsp; y a e I o u&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>SD</p><p>Begin (ing)</p><p>Reset(ing)</p><p>Forgot(en)</p><p>Upset(ing)</p><p>Repot(ed)</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Writing</p><p>Compound exclamatory sentence using a upset.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Underline the subject noun and the verb (and object noun).</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Reading</p><p>Silent practice</p><p>Timed read.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>HW</p><p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-05-25 13:46:46', '2022-05-25 15:02:49'),
(2255, '2022/05/25', '03:31 pm', '2', '4', 'Luke Gomer', 'English', 'Writing - Sentence Construction & Vocabulary', 'Elements of a complex sentence > Capital letter, one independent clause, one dependent clause containing a subordinate conjunction, ending punctuation', 'Recognise/Analyse/Model/Compose compound sentences that include subject nouns/pronouns and subordinating conjunctions if, after, when, than, unless, because, however', 'Laree Thorsby', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>T2W4</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>OPR/WPR</p><p>Ea ey ie ei ee ng ed sh ch ck dge&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>SD Rule Page&nbsp;</p><p>Rules 9 and 10</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Worksheets – adding vowel suffix to 1 and 2 syllable words.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Writing</p><p>Review first 2 complex sentence structures</p><p>Compose a complex sentence using the dependant clause chosen from the card and a rule 9 or 10 word from our worksheets.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Reading OF 510 &nbsp;x2&nbsp;</p><ol><li>102 words 4 errors</li><li>85 words 0 errors.&nbsp;</li></ol><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Luke reads the initial and end sound of longer unfamiliar words and “makes up the middle bits” Quote!! Elaborated became elated, ecstatic became elastic.</p>', NULL, '2022-05-25 15:31:16', '2022-05-25 17:12:45'),
(2256, '2022/05/25', '03:32 pm', '2', '4', 'Toby Webb', 'English', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Campbell Jepson', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-05-25 15:32:05', '2022-05-25 15:32:05'),
(2257, '2022/05/25', '03:33 pm', '2', '4', 'Phoebe Webb', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms', 'Oral Phongram Review (OPR) - Cards 1 > 30', 'Yina Peng', 'Achieved', 'Achieved', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Phoebe was hard to manage today at the beginning of the lesson, so I had to be firm to her and it got much better. She is smart &nbsp;can has lots of potential, but sometimes she is just very reststant to learning.&nbsp;</p><ol><li>Kilpatrick F</li><li>OPR: a, e, i, o, u, b, d, g, sh, c, s, ee,th, ow. Phoebe needed help with multi sounds for phonograms e and ee. She is quite unfamiliar with three sounds of u.&nbsp;</li><li>WPR: a, e, i, o, u, b, d, g, sh, c, s, ee,th, ow. She did not know how to write ow and ee.&nbsp;</li><li>handwriting focus: clockface d. Her formation of d got corrected today.&nbsp;</li><li>Rule review and SD activity: rule 4. We focused on rule 4 and its marking today again. We used colored code to help with the activity. She did very well with this and is getting better at understanding rule 4. She does betetr when we do one thing step by step.&nbsp;</li><li>Using SD words to make a written sentence: I went to the prk with har(her). we will need to recap five er next week.&nbsp;<br><br><br><br>&nbsp;</li></ol>', NULL, '2022-05-25 15:33:29', '2022-05-25 17:39:03'),
(2258, '2022/05/25', '04:29 pm', '2', '3', 'Angus Zeeman', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms', 'Oral Phonogram Review (OPR) - Various Phonograms (see notes)', 'Neve Mitchell', 'Achieved', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR: 39-70</td></tr><tr><td>WPR: aw ir ur ea au ie eigh&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Spelling words: excite flew flies hurrying giant gigantic guide</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Rule review: 25 23</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD: knowledge-pickle</td></tr><tr><td>Read R&amp;S</td></tr><tr><td>Explain/discuss the markings and meanings of analysed words.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Vocab: Use words in sentences to show meaning. Create 3 related sentences following a beginning/middle/end structure.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Writing Challenge: Play a round or two of Taboo. Write a short (5 sentences max) narrative story about one of the Taboo topics, omitting any of the words on the card. This is an inference task, but rather than the student making the inference from a text, they are implying meaning themselves. Explain this to them.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Angus totally got the Taboo task, and I demonstrated how he was implying meaning that his reader could infer from.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-05-25 16:29:58', '2022-05-25 17:59:36'),
(2259, '2022/05/25', '04:33 pm', '2', '2', 'Jacob Tipping', 'Mathematics', 'Number & Place Value', 'Develop confidence with number sequences to and from 100 by ones from any starting point', 'TEXT BOOK - EXERCISES, QUESTIONS, ACTIVITIES', 'Ivan Botero', 'Not Yet', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', '<p>Before continuing our work with decimals, Jacob and I did a revision on making multiplications and divisions by 10, 100 and 1000. Also, we were working on converting between mm, cm, m and km.&nbsp;</p><p>Jacob was having some difficulties remembering how to do multiplications; we had to do a revision on the board about counting in groups forwards and backwards.&nbsp;</p><p>Once we finish with this, we were doing multiplications and divisions by 10, 100 and 1000; we used the “decimal table” moving numbers to the left or right depending on the operation we might need to do.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '<p>Jacob is missing lesson 2 (11.05.22) Tracy still has COVID, and lesson 3 (18.05.22) I was on sick leave.&nbsp;</p>', '2022-05-25 16:33:29', '2022-07-01 22:01:02'),
(2260, '2022/05/25', '04:34 pm', '2', '4', 'Xavier Schmidt', 'English', 'Writing - Paragraph & Composition Construction', 'The Writing Process - Plan, Compose, Revise, Edit, Publish (by reading, speaking, media presentation)', 'Use the writing process to compose first-person narrative paragraph', 'Laree Thorsby', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Xavier had an english assessment task to complete on suspenseful writing.&nbsp;</p><p>We followed the writing process plan for composing a narrative.</p><p>Theme - suspense</p><p>Setting - Forest</p><p>Plot -lost nd trying to find a way out. Must include a big reveal/ahahhaaa moment&nbsp;</p><p>Voice - 1st person</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Xavier wrote solidly for 45 mins. He was involved with the story and stepped up to the challenging of writing more than the minimum words. He used a variety of descriptive language and phrases.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>We also discussed the Science assessment he has been asked to resubmit. I strongly suggested he read it aloud and reorganise his thoughts and information into concise sentences, with correct punctuation. Editing for spelling - use the online dictionary for technical words or text book or class notes.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-05-25 16:34:43', '2022-05-25 17:25:10'),
(2261, '2022/05/25', '05:26 pm', '2', '4', 'Max Brookfield', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms', 'Oral Phonogram Review (OPR) - Various Phonograms (see notes)', 'Neve Mitchell', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Max didn\'t want to be here today! He was really resistant and upset upon arriving at tutoring, hiding behind Mum/in the garden. Had a quick chat to Melissa about how he\'s going, she mentioned his confidence levels dropping at school re: work and friends. Enticed Max up to tutoring with the CVC spelling game and we played a round with Melissa.</td></tr><tr><td>After Melissa left Max immediately curled up in a ball, he really didn\'t want Mum to go. He was silent. He went under the desk and, when I told him I was going to join him sitting on the floor (but that we didn\'t have to talk/do anything), he curled up facing away from me under a chair. Poor guy. He\'s never shown this type of behaviour before. I talked to him a little and told him we could just sit quietly for a bit, or I could leave the room, or he could pick something to do. We sat for about 10 minutes in silence.</td></tr><tr><td>When I felt like it was the right time, I got our chapter book out and told Max I was going to read it aloud to myself, but he could come and listen if he wanted. Started reading and it worked like a charm! We read some chapters, got the beanbag so he was nice and comfy, and finished the book. I also showed Max the Stones cards but he couldn\'t find any that looked how he felt. He was really interested in them though and liked looking at the pictures. He liked the \'bravery\' card best. Eventually he told me he was feeling upset earlier, happy and sad at the same time, and picked the \'hollow/drained\' card. He also said I could tell Mum he was feeling that way.</td></tr><tr><td>Didn\'t do any jobs, but at least he went home feeling much better :-)</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-05-25 17:26:38', '2022-05-25 18:06:17'),
(2262, '2022/05/25', '05:32 pm', '2', '4', 'Kaiden Reynolds', 'English', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Campbell Jepson', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-05-25 17:32:14', '2022-05-25 17:32:14'),
(2263, '2022/05/25', '05:33 pm', '2', '3', 'Luca Mignanelli', 'Mathematics', 'Number & Place Value', 'Solve problems involving division by a one digit number including those that result in a remainder', 'TEXT BOOK - EXERCISES, QUESTIONS, ACTIVITIES', 'Ivan Botero', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', '<p>Using Singapore Education textbooks No 3 and 4 and made-up problems, Luca and I were working on:</p><ul><li>Long additions without carrying.</li><li>Long additions with carrying.</li><li>Long subtractions without borrowing.</li><li>Long subtractions with borrowing.</li><li>Long multiplications by one-digit numbers.</li><li>Long multiplications by 2-digit numbers.</li><li>Long divisions with 1 digit with and without reminder.</li></ul>', NULL, '<p>Lessons No 2 and 3 were delivered on 25.05.22.&nbsp;<br>This was because of sickness and an injured finger, I couldn\'t be at work.&nbsp;</p>', '2022-05-25 17:33:28', '2022-06-13 13:40:52'),
(2264, '2022/05/26', '07:33 am', '2', '2', 'Nate Betros', 'Mathematics', 'Number & Place Value', 'Solve problems involving division by a one digit number including those that result in a remainder', 'TEXT BOOK - EXERCISES, QUESTIONS, ACTIVITIES', 'Ivan Botero', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', '<p>In this lesson, Nate and I were revisiting long divisions.&nbsp;</p><p>It was necessary to look at all parts of a division, Dividend, Divisor and Quotient.&nbsp;</p><p>Then we moved to the “bus” strategy, at the meantime, we quickly check the time\'s tables.&nbsp;</p><p>Then I was asking Nate, how many times 2 fits into 4. At first, this was a tricky concept for him, so I used the idea of sharing: <i>If you want to share 4 objects between 2 people, how many objects does each person get?</i></p><p>Once Nate came up with the correct answer, put 2 above 4. Then, I asked to repeat the step with the second digit in the dividend.</p><p>I used these simple equations to reinforce place value too.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '<p>Lesson No 2 was delivered on 12.05.2022</p>', '2022-05-26 07:33:15', '2022-07-03 11:01:19'),
(2265, '2022/05/26', '08:49 am', '2', '2', 'James Levings', 'Mathematics', 'Measurement', 'Find perimeters and areas of parallelograms, trapeziums, rhombuses and kites', 'Text book - Exercises, Questions, Activities', 'Ivan Botero', 'Not Yet', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', '<p>James and I were working with floor plans.</p><p>We designed our own patio using assorted shapes including, parallelograms, kites and rectangles. James found this activity very useful.&nbsp;</p><p>I gave him homework to complete about measurement using decimals and fractions.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, NULL, '2022-05-26 08:49:55', '2022-05-26 11:45:27'),
(2266, '2022/05/26', '02:19 pm', '2', '4', 'Mia Harvey', 'Mathematics', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Campbell Jepson', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-05-26 14:19:26', '2022-05-26 14:19:26'),
(2267, '2022/05/26', '02:35 pm', '2', '3', 'Nell  Brooks', 'Mathematics', 'Number & Place Value', 'Solve problems involving all four operations with whole numbers', 'Text Book - Exercises, Questions and Activities', 'Ivan Botero', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', '<p>Today, we worked on:</p><ul><li>Multiplications by 10, 100 and 1000 base numbers.</li><li>Long multiplications.</li><li>We did the Zombie Riddle activity (Ted Talks)</li></ul><p>Homework was to solve sudokus.&nbsp;</p><p>Nell understood well how to make multiplication with the 10 &nbsp;base numbers; however, I could see that Nell is not practising the multiplication/counting strategies I gave her at home. &nbsp;</p>', NULL, NULL, '2022-05-26 14:35:04', '2022-07-02 22:49:55'),
(2268, '2022/05/26', '03:27 pm', '2', '3', 'James  Coleman', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Delete syllable from three syllable word - Kilpatrick Advanced Syllable Level', 'Ellie Connor', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week Four</td></tr><tr><td>Thursday, 26 May 2022</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>PA: Kilpatrick</td></tr><tr><td>MA: Donah #16</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR/WPR: ee our er sh au s igh ng ea</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Rule Review: 13, 4, 8,&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD: Sec. L - indeed, four, herself, power, wish, because, cause, world,&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Read S&amp;R</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Recap sentence structures using blocks and prompt page</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>JC a little shy with WH in the room. MA tricky but fine with PA. Some prompting for \'our\' but otherwise okay with phonos. SD good, pretty good with sentence structures but definitely needed a lot of prompting. Finished with JC using some SD words in sentences in the workbook.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-05-26 15:27:21', '2022-05-30 09:53:19'),
(2269, '2022/05/26', '03:29 pm', '2', '3', 'Reuben Shelverton', 'English', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Juno Galang', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-05-26 15:29:47', '2022-05-26 15:29:47');
INSERT INTO `attens` (`id`, `date_created`, `time`, `term`, `lesson`, `student_name`, `subject_name`, `concept_name`, `conceptDetail`, `learningActivity`, `tutor_name`, `tutor_evaluation`, `student_self`, `student_attendance`, `homework_completed`, `weekly_lesson`, `homework_assignment`, `email_school`, `comment`, `commentPrivate`, `notesAttendance`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(2270, '2022/05/26', '03:30 pm', '2', '4', 'Sofia Creek', 'Mathematics', 'Number & Place Value', 'Solve problems involving all four operations with whole numbers', 'Text Book - Exercises, Questions and Activities', 'Ivan Botero', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', '<p>This lesson was on multiplying by 10, 100 and 1000 base numbers.&nbsp;</p><p>Sofia followed my indications thoroughly and this helps to grasp the concept in just one lesson. Hopefully, she will remember this method and will be beneficial for her. &nbsp;</p>', NULL, NULL, '2022-05-26 15:30:59', '2022-07-02 20:28:47'),
(2271, '2022/05/26', '03:33 pm', '2', '2', 'Seth Vanderlaan', 'English', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Campbell Jepson', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-05-26 15:33:16', '2022-05-26 15:33:16'),
(2272, '2022/05/26', '03:39 pm', '2', '4', 'Lucy Fairbrother', 'Mathematics', 'Number & Place Value', 'Mental Computation', 'Mad Minute Maths - Facts to 100', 'Naomi Wright', 'In Progress', NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', '<p>Today, Lucy worked on long division and problem solving with modelling from the Level Three NSPM. &nbsp;SHe was able to solved long division equations without input with regards to the process, however, she is being held back by her lack of immediate recall of number facts involving the 8 and 9 times tables especially. &nbsp;I encouraged Lucy to record the skip-counted answers down the side of the page to use as a reference - she was able to come back and add to these when solving equations needing these tables further down the page.</p><p>When working on worded problems, although Lucy needed a prompt to look back through her book for strategy ideas, once she identified the need to model, she completed a textbook perfect model with workings and labels.</p><p>Key Maths Algebra, Concept Cluster 6, Lesson 3, Independent Practice 2 and 3.</p><p>Key Maths Algebra, Concept Cluster 7, Lesson 2, Guided Practice - Lucy was able to make connections with these foundation algebra task and prior learning when she was able to produce models for 2 of the 3 expressions she solved on this page.&nbsp;</p><p>HW: &nbsp;Practice answering questions involving the 8 and 9 times tables - include multiplication, division, subtraction from table answers using table number. &nbsp;Eg: &nbsp;72 - 8 (9x8=72, so 8x8) = 64</p>', NULL, NULL, '2022-05-26 15:39:27', '2022-05-26 17:00:09'),
(2273, '2022/05/26', '03:52 pm', '2', '4', 'Cara Lashmar', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Laree Thorsby', NULL, NULL, 'Cancelled - No Show', 'N/A', 'Cancelled', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>cara absent due to illness.</p>', '<p>ill</p>', '2022-05-26 15:53:07', '2022-06-17 09:45:16'),
(2274, '2022/05/26', '04:22 pm', '2', '4', 'Finn Mackey', 'English', 'Writing - Paragraph & Composition Construction', 'The Writing Process - Plan, Compose, Revise, Edit, Publish (by reading, speaking, media presentation)', 'Use the writing process to compose first-person informative-narrative paragraph', 'Laree Thorsby', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Focus The writing Process</p><p>First person Informative Narrative&nbsp;</p><p>Plan/Compose Draft</p><p>Embedded in this session was the appropriate use of punctuation for speech.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-05-26 16:22:00', '2022-05-26 17:45:17'),
(2275, '2022/05/26', '04:25 pm', '2', '3', 'Nicholas Geeves', 'Mathematics', 'Patterns & Algebra', 'Factorise algebraic expressions by identifying numerical factors', 'Text book - Exercises, Questions, Activities', 'Ivan Botero', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', '<p>After the comprehensive revision of the index law from the last lesson. Considering the 2 hours timeframe, we were working on a totally new topic, Factorization.&nbsp;</p><p>Nicholas and I solved a significant number of problems on the whiteboard, we had a refresh on distributive and commutative laws.&nbsp;</p><p>In the first hour, Nicholas was a bit confused about how to follow the process to factorise by using common factors and groups. &nbsp;However, during the second hour, Nicholas\' answers were more accurate and not very far from the ideal algebraic expression.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '<p>Today we had lessons 3 and 4. We started at 4:30 pm and finished at 6:30 pm. We had a 6 minutes break.&nbsp;</p>', '2022-05-26 16:25:04', '2022-07-02 17:14:52'),
(2276, '2022/05/26', '04:30 pm', '2', '3', 'Samuel Lamont', 'English', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Campbell Jepson', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-05-26 16:30:54', '2022-05-26 16:30:54'),
(2277, '2022/05/26', '04:38 pm', '2', '4', 'Chelsea Cooper', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Delete onset or rime - Kilpatrick Level F', 'Ellie Connor', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week Four</td></tr><tr><td>Thursday, 26 May 2022</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>PA: Kilpatrick</td></tr><tr><td>MA: Donah #14</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR/WPR: ee our er sh au s igh ng ea</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Rule Review: 11, 17, 13, 6</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD: Sec. K (leave two lines) stamp, light, coming, come, night, pass, shut, easy, ease</td></tr><tr><td>Read S&amp;R</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Recap sentence structures using blocks and prompt page</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>ORF x2</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>CC was very chill with WH observing. Fine with PA, MA, OPR/WPR, SD. Need to move up a level in Ayres list. Started sentence structure recap worksheet, talked about morphology of \'independent\' in relation to clauses. 2x ORF. Assessments next week!</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-05-26 16:38:39', '2022-05-30 09:49:38'),
(2278, '2022/05/26', '04:49 pm', '2', '4', 'Callisto Pratten', 'Mathematics', 'Trigonometry', 'Cosine Rule', 'Text book - Exercises, Questions, Activities', 'Rosemary Beswick', 'Achieved', 'Achieved', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Callisto has not been to Maths since we last met and so no progress has been made through the course. Therefore, we spent time on the next part of the course that she has not yet covered which is the cosine rule. She mastered these calculations and is quite confident. The only point of difficulty is the drawing of correct diagrams to inform solutions.</p>', NULL, '2022-05-26 16:49:31', '2022-05-26 18:18:57'),
(2279, '2022/05/27', '07:33 am', '2', '3', 'Gus  Pettit', 'Mathematics', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Ivan Botero', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'Followup', NULL, NULL, '<p>Nat let us know Gus couldn\'t come to Tutoring on the 20th of May. To organise the catch-up lesson, we decided to start the lesson at 7:30 am and finish it at 9:00 am for two weeks. In that way, the tutoring hour will be covered.&nbsp;</p>', '2022-05-27 07:33:45', '2022-06-03 08:32:59'),
(2280, '2022/05/27', '07:49 am', '2', '5', 'Archie Lester', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Manipulate (delete or substitute) initial phoneme in initial blend - Kilpatrick Level H', 'Naomi Wright', 'Achieved', NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', '<p>Archie began the lesson with analysis of the word ‘windows’. &nbsp;Prompting was needed to recognise and mark the second sound of ‘s’. &nbsp;The discussion included the following check for understanding questions:</p><ul><li>Where does the syllable break go?</li><li>What markings do we do?</li><li>What do the markings tell us?</li><li>What is a morpheme?</li><li>How many morphemes are in this word?</li><li>How many phonemes?</li><li>How many letters?</li></ul><p>During the sentence writing lesson, Archie was asked to identify all the nouns and verbs on today\'s spelling list. &nbsp;He made a number of errors during this task, so he was then asked to use each of the labelled words in simple sentence. &nbsp;The sentences were then analysed for subject nouns and verbs which helped Archie to recognise the function of each word thereby correcting the label he had assigned. &nbsp;The sentences he created were: &nbsp;The tree is bare.&nbsp; The bucket is full.&nbsp; Naomi failed the test.&nbsp; Your garden is big. You harvest wheat.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>He was then asked to use the word ‘window’ as an object noun in a compound sentence. &nbsp;He composed the following: The window is the size of an ant.&nbsp; The ant is the size of the window.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>We settled on: Archie cleans the very dirty windows.</p><p>Archie was then asked to compose a simple sentence for the word ‘garden\' that included an adjectival phrase. &nbsp;‘Your old tropical garden is magnificent.’ Archie modelled the three layers of sentence structure (parts of speech, clause and sentence) &nbsp;using sentence builder blocks, identifying the parts of speech for each word – adjectives (your old tropical), noun (garden) linking verb (is) adjective (magnificent) .&nbsp; Three layers – what two words make up the independent clause. &nbsp;Answer check for understanding questions about parts of speech that = a clause, a clause needing punctuation to = a sentence.</p>', NULL, '<p>Archie\'s lesson was observed by a new tutor, Will Hughes, this morning. &nbsp;</p>', '2022-05-27 07:49:34', '2022-05-27 15:39:45'),
(2281, '2022/05/27', '09:02 am', '2', '5', 'Mason Turner', 'Mathematics', 'Patterns & Algebra', 'Simplify algebraic products and quotients using index laws', 'Text book - Exercises, Questions, Activities', 'Ivan Botero', 'Not Yet', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Today we moved into index laws and how to expand and simplify algebraic expressions.&nbsp;</p><p>We did problems like:</p><p>2X(XYZ + 2X)&nbsp;</p><p>X ( 2X-2Y)&nbsp;</p><p>(3X-4Y)(6X^3 - XY)&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-05-27 09:02:17', '2022-07-02 10:20:03'),
(2282, '2022/05/27', '10:10 am', '2', '1', 'Matthew Heard', 'Mathematics', 'Patterns & Algebra', 'Simplify algebraic products and quotients using index laws', 'Text book - Exercises, Questions, Activities', 'Ivan Botero', 'Not Yet', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'Introductory', '<ul><li>Index law.</li><li>Sign law.</li><li>4 operations with positive and negative numbers.&nbsp;</li><li>Operations with fractions.</li><li>Operations with Algebraic expressions.&nbsp;</li></ul><p>We used Matt\'s school assignments and Essential Mathematics Year 10.&nbsp;</p><p>Matt and I were working on foundation-level problems and progressed to a much higher level during the lesson.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '<p>Matt 1st lesson was on 02/05/22.&nbsp;<br>He wasn\'t on the DB.&nbsp;</p>', '2022-05-27 10:11:17', '2022-06-11 17:10:32'),
(2283, '2022/05/27', '10:11 am', '2', '2', 'Matthew Heard', 'Mathematics', 'Geometric Reasoning (Y3 onwards)', 'Angles-Identifying & naming', 'Text book - Exercises, Questions, Activities', 'Ivan Botero', 'Not Yet', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'Followup', '<ul><li>Congruency and similar triangles.</li><li>Parallel and perpendicular lines.</li><li>Angles.&nbsp;</li></ul><p>Work done as per teacher\'s recommendations.&nbsp;</p><p><i>We are starting with Geometry and Measurement this week: Similarity and congruent proofs and then also going back to ensure they have a good understanding of Geometric Reasoning with angles, lines and shapes.</i></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '<p>Matt 2nd lesson was on 09/05/22</p>', '2022-05-27 10:21:37', '2022-06-11 17:17:22'),
(2284, '2022/05/27', '10:21 am', '2', '3', 'Matthew Heard', 'Mathematics', 'Geometric Reasoning (Y3 onwards)', 'Formulae Proofs', 'School-assigned worksheet/task', 'Ivan Botero', 'Not Yet', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'Followup', '<ul><li>Formulate proofs involving congruent triangles and angle properties.</li><li>Apply logical reasoning, including the use of congruence and similarity, to proofs and numerical exercises involving plane shape.</li></ul>', NULL, '<p>Matt 3rd lesson was on 16/05/22.<br>He wasn\'t on the DB.&nbsp;</p>', '2022-05-27 10:22:06', '2022-06-11 17:21:41'),
(2285, '2022/05/27', '10:22 am', '2', '4', 'Matthew Heard', 'Mathematics', 'Patterns & Algebra', 'Find unknown quantities in number sentences involving multiplication and division', 'Text book - Exercises, Questions, Activities', 'Ivan Botero', 'Not Yet', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', '<ul><li>Solve problems involving linear equations, including those derived from a formula.</li><li>Extend and apply the index laws to variables, using positive integer indices and the zero index.</li><li>Apply the distributive law to the expansion of algebraic expressions, including binomials, and collect like terms where appropriate.</li></ul><p>Overall, Matt is starting to improve not only with his maths work but also in confidence.&nbsp;</p><p>The student is taking less time to perform algebraic operations and follows the procedure to solve equations without mixing the terms.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '<p>Matt 4th lesson was on 23/05/22</p>', '2022-05-27 10:24:24', '2022-06-11 17:26:38'),
(2286, '2022/05/27', '02:25 pm', '2', '4', 'Molly  Jackson', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms', 'Oral Phonogram Review (OPR) - Various Phonograms (see notes)', 'Neve Mitchell', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>PA: Kilpatrick K</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR: 49-70</td></tr><tr><td>WPR: ough ck ew oa gu ey igh kn wr ie dge ei eigh&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Sentence structure: Provide student with independent and dependent clauses. Sort into DC and IC. In DCs, circle subbies. Compose 3x IC and DCs (NM model first), using the list of SUBBIES for DCs.</td></tr><tr><td>Sentence Structure: Explain and model that complex sentences can also follow a DC;IC structure. Explain that this structure requires a comma to give the reader a moment to think (model the act of placing the comma block on the SBBs). Introduce the ice-cream analogy (a waiter brings a bowl of sprinkles to the table, the diner is confused, but when a bowl of ice-cream arrives next, they are no longer confused. Compare to if the waiter brings ice-cream followed by sprinkles. The diner doesn\'t need a moment to ask themselves \"wait, what\'s going on?\").&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Sentence Structure: Compose DC;IC complex sentences and coach as needed. Ask student to begin their sentence with a SUBBIE, and the complex sentence structure will naturally follow. Colour code and model on SBB.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Molly really silly today -- I suspect the hot chocolate is the culprit! She exhausted me very quickly. We had to forego spelling when she couldn\'t keep it together and write neatly or recall her rules. She kept up with complex sentences easily and was able to put them into practice.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-05-27 14:25:33', '2022-05-27 17:06:47'),
(2287, '2022/05/27', '03:30 pm', '2', '3', 'Harlow Booy', 'Mathematics', 'Number & Place Value', 'Represent and solve simple addition and subtraction problems using a range of strategies', 'TEXT BOOK - EXERCISES, QUESTIONS, ACTIVITIES', 'Ivan Botero', 'Not Yet', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', '<p>Today we were working on long additions and subtractions.&nbsp;</p><p>We did all our work on the whiteboard, the problems were with and without carrying and borrowing. I tried to create the connection among carry with Carly and for borrowing, I passed the following tip to Harlow. If there\'s more on the floor go and borrow from next door.&nbsp;</p><p>After this, I took the Syllabus 2A textbook to solve some word problems with Harlow on these operations.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, NULL, '2022-05-27 15:30:30', '2022-07-02 12:01:53'),
(2288, '2022/05/27', '03:36 pm', '2', '4', 'Connor Thompson ', 'Academic Coaching', 'Independent Study', 'School Assigned Worksheet or Assignment', 'See Notes', 'Neve Mitchell', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'Attended Tardy', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-05-27 15:36:15', '2022-05-27 17:08:26'),
(2289, '2022/05/27', '03:39 pm', '2', '4', 'Reuben Shelverton', 'English', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Juno Galang', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-05-27 15:39:50', '2022-05-27 15:39:50'),
(2290, '2022/05/27', '03:59 pm', '2', '2', 'Josh Zeeman', 'Academic Coaching', 'Independent Study', 'School Assigned Worksheet or Assignment', 'See Notes', 'Will Hughes', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Explored Judaism and Buddhism this afternoon with Josh. Josh was able to recite the information from the video back to me with little to no prompt, and continued with his google doc for his cards. Josh was focussed for the full lesson, asking good questions and listening attentively, as well as taking good notes.</p>', NULL, '2022-05-27 15:59:50', '2022-05-27 16:51:07'),
(2291, '2022/05/27', '04:08 pm', '2', '5', 'Lottie Young', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Substitute onset & rime - Kilpatrick Level G', 'Naomi Wright', 'In Progress', NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', '<p>Lottie had notable difficulty processing sounds in the phonological awareness lesson. &nbsp;My observations are that Lottie has fluent and not-so-fluent episodes with this task.</p><p>During our lesson today, we reviewed single letter phonograms and partner phononograms (ai/ay, oi/oy, ou/ow, au/aw, ew/ui).</p><p>Lottie has found it difficult to recall these phonograms over time in spite of repeated reviews. &nbsp;Today, after completing the initial WPR, I re-presented the same phonograms in a different order anticipating that Lottie would make connections with those she had already written and corrected. &nbsp;Lottie did not do this. &nbsp;I subsequently switched the focus of the lesson to making connections, assisting Lottie to reference previously written phonograms as she continue to record given phonograms. &nbsp;</p><p>Lottie made a conscious and visible effort to engage in this learning making a very deliberate and effortful attempt to complete the task.&nbsp;</p><p>Additionally, when recording these same phonograms as part of a word, Lottie benefited from frequent prompts to sound aloud as when she did so, the level of accuracy increased significantly. &nbsp;When she is attempting to record words from memory and without using sounds as a prompt, the level of spelling accuracy drops. &nbsp;Lottie was able to read for spelling and reading without error.</p><p>Dictated words: paw, Paul, cloud, blow, stray, blew, flew, suit, fruit, joy</p>', NULL, NULL, '2022-05-27 16:10:06', '2022-06-07 15:28:08'),
(2292, '2022/05/27', '04:36 pm', '2', '4', 'Mason Turner', 'Mathematics', 'Patterns & Algebra', 'Find unknown quantities in number sentences involving the four operations', 'Text book - Exercises, Questions, Activities', 'Ivan Botero', 'Not Yet', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Mason is showing some progress. Now 1 and 2-step equations aren\'t that hard for him. Now we are working with equations using fractions and hopefully this won\'t be as hard as the other ones.&nbsp;</p>', '<p>Mason came twice on 03.06.2022</p>', '2022-05-27 16:36:18', '2022-07-02 10:14:50'),
(2293, '2022/05/30', '07:28 am', '2', '3', 'Nate Betros', 'Mathematics', 'Number & Place Value', 'Recognise and represent multiplication as repeated addition, groups and arrays', 'TEXT BOOK - EXERCISES, QUESTIONS, ACTIVITIES', 'Ivan Botero', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', '<p>In this lesson, we focused on long multiplications.</p><p>Using the area strategy, Nate and I solved more than 10 problems. Also, in the end, I gave 3 more problems to Nate to solve by using this strategy.</p><p>The problems were three-digit numbers X one and two digits numbers.&nbsp;</p><p>Nate told me that he finds this very useful and he will try his best to do it at school.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '<p>Lesson 3 was delivered on 26.05.2022</p>', '2022-05-30 07:28:52', '2022-07-03 11:28:00'),
(2294, '2022/05/30', '07:34 am', '2', '4', 'Darcy Callaghan', 'English', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Campbell Jepson', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-05-30 07:34:14', '2022-05-30 07:34:14'),
(2295, '2022/05/30', '08:44 am', '2', '5', 'Lewis Prevost', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Delete syllable from two syllable word - Kilpatrick Level D', 'Ellie Connor', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week Five</td></tr><tr><td>Monday, 30 May 2022</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>PA: Kilpatrick D1 supplemental</td></tr><tr><td>MA: Donah #14</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>OPR/WPR: gu igh ey oo ch wr wh</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Discuss \'consonant blends\' (back to phonograms etc)</td></tr><tr><td>Sound some SB smash words</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Pip &amp; Tim \"The Little Vet\"</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Drawing time (5 min)</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Homework: consonant blend words (ID blend)</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Mo: LP struggled with \'ago\', \'toe\', \'blue\', \'charge\' in homework. Awesome with PA and MA (enjoyed MA!). Really good with OPR (not cues). Not super neat with WPR, but mostly correct (noticed a lot of reversals though i.e. writing the last letter first). Focus on consonant blends - LP unable to articulate what a consonant is, so went right back to what a phonogram is, spiel with sound/symbol etc. Finally able to tell me difference between vowels and consonants (prompted), and discussed what a \'consonant blend\' could be. Sounded some SB smash words, LP lost patience (a little all over the place today) quickly so didn\'t play a game or write any down. LP gave me sentences using two nonsense words, then we read a Pip and Tim.&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-05-30 08:44:32', '2022-05-30 09:47:23'),
