(2306, '2022/05/30', '04:33 pm', '2', '5', 'Zac Pharaoh ', 'Mathematics', 'OTHER', 'OTHER', 'Please read comments', 'Ivan Botero', 'In Progress', 'In Progress', 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', '<ul><li>Investigate and calculate percentage discounts of 10%, 25% and 50% on sale items, with and without digital technologies.</li><li>Create simple financial plans.</li><li>Find percentages of quantities and express one quantity as a percentage of another, with and without digital technologies.</li><li>Review, multiplications and divisions with decimals by 10, 100 and 1000 base numbers.&nbsp;</li></ul>', NULL, NULL, '2022-05-30 16:33:36', '2022-06-11 19:28:40'),
(2307, '2022/05/30', '04:57 pm', '2', '5', 'Arlo Clark', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Delete onset or rime - Kilpatrick Level F', 'Yina Peng', 'Achieved', 'Achieved', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>We did kilpatrick assessment and Arlo performed very well in secotion F. He can recognize that words are made of individual sounds, able to delete the initial sounds of a word.</p><p>Speil secotion 1-3<br>English sounds:</p><p>vowels and consonants<br>voiced and unvoiced sounds<br>&nbsp;</p><p>phonological awareness: He learned what activities we can do within a word for phonological awareness. We also learned how to segment, count and blend sounds.&nbsp;</p><p>Modeling word: mist.</p><p>Scaffolding word: can&nbsp;</p><p>Arlo has a strong awareness of individual sounds and different sounds such as vowels and consonants. He needed help understand voiced and unvoiced sounds.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-05-30 16:57:42', '2022-05-31 16:18:02'),
(2308, '2022/05/31', '10:21 am', '2', '5', 'Henry  Badock', 'Mathematics', 'Number & Place Value', 'Recognise and represent multiplication as repeated addition, groups and arrays', 'TEXT BOOK - EXERCISES, QUESTIONS, ACTIVITIES', 'Laree Thorsby', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>T2W5</p><p>Focus: Mental computation</p><p>Timed activities: to/from 20</p><p>Written and verbal</p><p>Focus: Addition retaining place value. Henry tends to add from right to left. Complete the addition to 100 worksheet&nbsp;</p><p>Use number line to count up with addition to check answers</p><p>Focus: Addition with regrouping</p><p>Henry likes to work from right to left when adding. Explained this isn’t possible if the numbers in each column add up to more than 9. We went through many examples, however Henry still insisted on moving right to left, even when he could see the answers were incorrect. This was more an oppositional issue than understanding as he did attempt regrouping (in reverse!)&nbsp;</p><p>Dice Game/Pirate Pete</p><p>Focus: Subtracting from 20: &nbsp;Roll the 12 dice and write down the subtraction problem. Record and answer using the number line to count on. Highest number stabs Pete.</p><p>Henry was able to do most of these mentally. He demonstrated different strategies for solving these.</p><p>Eg 20-7 H. articulated 20-4 =16 and 16-3 = 13</p><p>Repeat with multiplication. highest number stabs Pete</p><p>Focus: Explore the relationship between Addition and Subtraction; add/multn.</p><p>Check every answer from the Pirate game by using addition&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Focus: Multiplication is a short cut to addition</p><p>We began with multiples of 2:</p><p>Roll the dice for the number of times (jumps). Eg 6 H counted and marked the NL in 2s 6 times. He then wrote 2+2+2+2+2+2 =12 and then 6 x 2 = 12</p><p>Repeated several times, changing multiple to 5 and 10.&nbsp;</p><p><br>Bucket Toss</p><p>Multiplication: Assign each counter the same number. Toss counters in bucket and count how many in. Use number line to JUMP the required amount&nbsp;</p><p>Round 1 =2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 9x2=18 (9 jumps of 2)</p><p>Round 2=5&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 9x5=45 (9 jumps of 5)</p><p>Round 3=10&nbsp;&nbsp; 9x10=90 (Henry did this without any help. X10 is automatic)</p>', NULL, '2022-05-31 10:22:11', '2022-05-31 10:43:51'),
(2309, '2022/05/31', '02:22 pm', '2', '3', 'Gabriel Bohm', 'English', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Campbell Jepson', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-05-31 14:22:59', '2022-05-31 14:22:59'),
(2310, '2022/05/31', '02:48 pm', '2', '5', 'Brock Smith', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Yina Peng', NULL, NULL, 'Cancelled - No Show', 'N/A', 'Cancelled', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-05-31 14:48:56', '2022-05-31 14:48:56'),
(2311, '2022/05/31', '03:02 pm', '2', '5', 'Stella Lorkin', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Language Rules (Pronunciation/Spelling/Grammar)', 'Rule 4: vowels a, e, o, u say their second (long) sound at the end of a syllable', 'See Notes', 'Yina Peng', 'Achieved', 'Achieved', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Stella can concentrate more nowadays and less playful mood.&nbsp;</p><p>We tried to assess for Kilpattrick F today but she is not ready for section F.&nbsp;</p><p>OPR a, e, o, u, ou, ow. She is very familiar with o. She is a bit confused with multi sounds for a and u, and she needed help for 2 sounds of e. She can say a few sounds for ow and ou.<br>WPR a, e, o, ow, ou. Stella does not recognize a and u. She cannot write ow and ou.&nbsp;</p><p>handwriting focus: clockface a and o. &nbsp;We focused on the right formation of a and o for both lower and upper cases.</p><p><br>SD: rule 4 activity . pink book page 1--color code vowels, vowels at the end of a syllabke, and vowels that are at the end of a syllable and also say their names---rule 4. Stella graspped this rule thouroughly now.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-05-31 15:02:17', '2022-05-31 16:10:48'),
(2312, '2022/05/31', '03:22 pm', '2', '3', 'Connor McLaren', 'Mathematics', 'Fractions, Decimals & Percentages', 'Fractions, decimals & percentages with operations', 'Text book - Exercises, Questions, Activities', 'Ivan Botero', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', '<p>Using the Singapore education textbook No 4 and 5, made-up problems and mathisfun.com, Connor and I were working on:&nbsp;</p><ul><li>Compare, order and represent decimals.</li><li>Add and subtract decimals, with and without digital technologies, and use estimation and rounding to check the reasonableness of answers.</li><li>Multiply decimals by whole numbers and perform divisions by non-zero whole numbers where the results are terminating decimals, with and without digital technologies.</li><li>Multiply and divide decimals by powers of 10.</li></ul>', NULL, '<p>Lesson No 3 was delivered on 25.05.2022</p>', '2022-05-31 15:22:20', '2022-06-13 11:54:04'),
(2313, '2022/05/31', '03:23 pm', '2', '1', 'Sebastian Bowerman', 'Mathematics', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Campbell Jepson', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-05-31 15:23:50', '2022-05-31 15:23:50'),
(2314, '2022/05/31', '03:32 pm', '2', '5', 'Sophie Mirowski', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Manipulate (delete or substitute) initial phoneme in initial blend - Kilpatrick Level H', 'Neve Mitchell', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>PA: Kilpatrick H1</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR: 49-70</td></tr><tr><td>WPR: wh ed oa ey wr ie&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Read R&amp;S: Current Ayres Column</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Rule review: 25</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD: chain-pare</td></tr><tr><td>Read R&amp;S</td></tr><tr><td>Explain/discuss the markings and meanings of analysed words.</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Rule Intro: NA</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Sentence Structure: Use Ayres words in sentences to show meaning.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>A good lesson with Sophie! Kilpatrick took about 20 minutes because it was a) really tricky for her and b) she kept interuppting with her stories from school. However, this paid off in the long run because she didn\'t have tangents to go off during her spelling lesson. We had more time to spare for sentences at the end than usual. I also just felt it worked better to let her get it all out at the start.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-05-31 15:32:40', '2022-05-31 16:29:30'),
(2315, '2022/05/31', '03:33 pm', '2', '5', 'Esther Mclver', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Language Rules (Pronunciation/Spelling/Grammar)', 'Rule 32:  r may change the sound of \'a\' to /e/ and \'o\' to /or/', 'See Notes', 'Laree Thorsby', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>T2W5</p><p>OPR ar ea or y ch er ough th ee ow ou s</p><p>WPR ar ea or y ch er ough th ee ow ou s</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Rule Review:&nbsp;</p><p>29 /6 hurry&nbsp;</p><p>17 smell</p><p>26 May</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Sect N Plan- God</p><p>Identify POS.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>New Rule: 32 R changes sound of a to e</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Pare pair fare fair hair share stare&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Writing:</p><p>Don’t stare at my fair hair!</p><p>I paid the fare, so you can share with me. &nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Compose the following-</p><p>Compound sentence:</p><p>Sure sugar</p><p>Simple sentence using&nbsp;</p><p>A Proper Noun and share.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Of 111</p><p>Timed read 90 zero errors&nbsp;</p><p>Next 112</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Hw sheet given + 112</p>', NULL, '2022-05-31 15:33:35', '2022-05-31 17:35:10'),
(2316, '2022/05/31', '04:29 pm', '2', '4', 'Lachlan Prior', 'English', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Campbell Jepson', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-05-31 16:29:54', '2022-05-31 16:29:54'),
(2317, '2022/05/31', '04:32 pm', '2', '5', 'Andrew Allan', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms (include purpose - to connect speech sounds to their written symbol which helps with reading, writing and spelling)', 'Oral Phongram Review (OPR) - Cards 55 > 70', 'Laree Thorsby', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>T2W4</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>OPR ow ou au aw or ar ng&nbsp;dge tch g gu&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>WPR ow ou au aw or ar ng&nbsp;dge tch g gu&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Rules&nbsp;</p><p>hive</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>SD</p><p>Stand stands yard bring&nbsp;five&nbsp;</p><p>next week rule 17 words&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Writing</p><p>&nbsp;</p><ol><li><strong>Complete the sentence using the words from this list.&nbsp;</strong></li></ol><p>&nbsp;</p><p>yard&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; stands&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; ball&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; yells&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; bring</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Dad _____________ in the ___________ and__________, “__________&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>the _________ to me.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Add <i>adjectives</i> to the <i>nouns</i> <strong>yard</strong> and <strong>ball</strong> to make the sentence more interesting.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Dad stands in the ___________ yard and yells,&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“Bring the _________ ball to me.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><ol><li><strong>Complete the sentence using words from this list.</strong></li></ol><p>&nbsp;</p><p>belong&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; bears&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; tell &nbsp; &nbsp; five&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>__________ me, do the _________ soft _________ __________ to you?&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Find the&nbsp; 2 <i>adjectives</i> describing the bears and write them below.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>___________&nbsp; ___________ bears.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Reading Fitzroy 40 shawn and the go-kart read fluently, sounding out unfamiliar words.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-05-31 16:32:27', '2022-06-07 10:08:24'),
(2318, '2022/05/31', '04:34 pm', '2', '1', 'Shay Douglas', 'English', 'Writing - Paragraph & Composition Construction', 'Essay Structure', 'See Notes', 'Neve Mitchell', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Subject: English</td></tr><tr><td>Focus: Structuring Essays</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Continued essay structure work and essay map from last week. Shay found it a little difficult to translate his arguments in the structure. Will make up a clearer reference page, I think. We talked about the strategy of framing our point as \"what does my reader need to know here?\". Maybe a practical example with a plan I make up?</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-05-31 16:34:09', '2022-05-31 18:55:17'),
