(2499, '2022/06/14', '04:38 pm', '2', '7', 'Shay Douglas', 'Essay Writing', 'Elements', 'Essay Structure', 'See Notes', 'Neve Mitchell', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Subject: English</td></tr><tr><td>Focus: Structuring Essays</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Create a broad and more specific essay structure (containing evidence). Begin by outlining stages of argument. Model for Shay what this entails. Create own on laptop. Model how to go more in-depth for Essay Structure. Create own on laptop.</td></tr><tr><td>We also talked about strengthening our arguments by finding/identifying links between them.</td></tr><tr><td>Discussion: Not including \"how\" in your plan &amp; why not (more work for yourself when writing!)</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-06-14 16:38:50', '2022-06-14 17:30:46'),
(2500, '2022/06/14', '04:40 pm', '2', '7', 'Callum Coulson', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms (include purpose - to connect speech sounds to their written symbol which helps with reading, writing and spelling)', 'Oral Phongram Review (OPR) - Cards 46 > 54', 'Yina Peng', 'Achieved', 'Achieved', 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>kilpatrick F1</p><p><br>challenge: &nbsp;write a simple sentence and articulate parts of speech. Callum needs help to clarify what a noun, verb, and adjective is. We will need to recap this.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>OPR:46-57. Callum cannot physically say certain sounds together even if he knows the sounds, such as the first 2 sounds for ough. He needs help with the sounds for ew, ui, aw, au, wh,gu(2nd sound).&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;</p><p>WPR: 46-57. Callum needs more practice for phonograms ew,ui, au, aw in words. &nbsp;<br><br><br>new phonogram: oe, ey, igh. He learns things slowly and here he needs time to get the three sounds for ey.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Sentence structures. Reviewed simple sentence.&nbsp;</p><p>Learned the structure of compound sentence.</p><p>We will need to recap sentence structures again.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&n