(2516, '2022/06/15', '04:10 pm', '2', '7', 'Max Brookfield', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms (include purpose - to connect speech sounds to their written symbol which helps with reading, writing and spelling)', 'Oral Phonogram Review (OPR) - Various Phonograms (see notes)', 'Neve Mitchell', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'Attended Tardy', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR: 39-58 + 59-64</td></tr><tr><td>WPR: ow ea ck ed ou gu er ph</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Rule review: SFe1</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD: out-today</td></tr><tr><td>Read R&amp;S</td></tr><tr><td>Explain/discuss the markings and meanings of analysed words.</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Rule Intro: NA</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Sentence Structure: Use words in sentences.&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>A delayed lesson because Max did not come into tutoring -- he stood outside for 10/15 minutes where I couldn\'t see him and I had to ring Michelle, who told me he\'d been dropped off. By the time I got back down to check, he had come inside. He was in a sulk again so I got him up to the room and we read a Dr Suess book.&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-06-15 16:10:40', '2022-06-15 17:06:12'),
(2517, '2022/06/15', '04:28 pm', '2', '5', 'Jacob Tipping', 'Mathematics', 'Number & Place Value', 'Solve problems involving all four operations with whole numbers', 'Text Book - Exercises, Questions and Activities', 'Ivan Botero', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'Not Returned', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Revision on long additions and subtraction with/without carrying and borrowing.</p><p>Introduction to a fraction.&nbsp;</p><ul><li>What is a fraction?</li><li>What are the parts of a fraction?<br>A fraction has three parts. They are…</li><li>What is a unit fraction?</li><li>Using objects to visualise fractions.&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;</li></ul>', NULL, '2022-06-15 16:28:35', '2022-07-03 12:24:35'),
(2518, '2022/06/15', '04:28 pm', '2', '5', 'Angus Zeeman', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - High Frequency Vocabulary', 'Analysis of word structure and application of learned concepts (sounds, phonograms, rules)', 'Spelling Dictation - Precisely say, write and read words in Section R', 'Neve Mitchell', 'In Progress', 'In Progress', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Quiz!&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Spelling Words: improvement&nbsp; often century resign piano community communities</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Rule review: NA</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD: total-affair</td></tr><tr><td>Read R&amp;S</td></tr><tr><td>Explain/discuss the markings and meanings of analysed words.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Vocab development: create a crossword, including clues, using Ayres words from today → needs further work/instruction; Angus\' hints not clear enough!</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-06-15 16:28:49', '2022-06-15 18:48:23'),
(2519, '2022/06/15', '04:30 pm', '2', '7', 'Xavier Schmidt', 'English', 'Writing - Paragraph & Composition Construction', 'Paragraphs - Two or more sentences about a topic presented in a logical order of ideas with appropriate indentations and margins', 'Think aloud when identifying the topic in two or more given sentences and whether they are related', 'Laree Thorsby', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Xavier brought his BAttle of Hastings task to complete. He spent 15 minutes researching and completing paragraph two. We used this task to discuss the importance of Proper Nouns and the need to give them capital letters. Xave then altered each Proper Noun in his writing, checked for spelling of names and places, and read aloud each sentence to ensure it made sense. Words were often missing which made this difficult. More focus is needed on sentence structure.&nbsp;</p><p>Xave used spell check to assist with troublesome words. We also used the syllabification process we practiced last week to assist in words that spell check did not identify.&nbsp;</p><p>Xave to complete this process at homeby checking:</p><p>Proper nouns</p><p>Sentences make sense when read aloud.</p><p>Punctuation is used correctly.</p><p>Spell check on words which are not picked up. Chunk and sound.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-06-15 16:30:46', '2022-06-15 17:48:18'),
(2520, '2022/06/15', '05:36 pm', '2', '7', 'Luca Mignanelli', 'Mathematics', 'Number & Place Value', 'Solve problems involving all four operations with whole numbers', 'Text Book - Exercises, Questions and Activities', 'Ivan Botero', 'Achieved', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', '<p>Today\'s lesson was about reinforcing strategies and procedures to solve word problems with more than 2 operations.&nbsp;</p><p>Luca\'s problem-solving skills are amazing; with little guidance, Luca is able to solve high-standard-level questions.&nbsp;</p><p>The only minor setback would be rushing and/or guessing. Luca wants to solve the questions in less than 5 minutes. I said to him that is okay, time management is important. However, considering that we are working with a high level of difficulty, taking the time to check the operations is sometimes necessary.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, NULL, '2022-06-15 17:36:03', '2022-07-03 18:07:34'),
(2521, '2022/06/15', '05:42 pm', '2', '3', 'Finn McKenzie', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms (include purpose - to connect speech sounds to their written symbol which helps with reading, writing and spelling)', 'Oral Phonogram Review (OPR) - Various Phonograms (see notes)', 'Neve Mitchell', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR: 1-8, 27-38 + igh, ed, oe</td></tr><tr><td>WPR: a c g o th ow ou ch ed igh&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Read R&amp;S: Current Ayres Column</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Rule intro: SFe1 + 2nd/3rd sound marking</td></tr><tr><td>Section M</td></tr><tr><td>SD: file-go</td></tr><tr><td>Read R&amp;S</td></tr><tr><td>Explain/discuss the markings and meanings of analysed words.</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Rule Intro: NA</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Sentence Structure: Show SBB &amp; recap compound structure. Use Ayres words in compound sentences. Had to discuss independent clauses &amp; noun/verb \"pairs\", + when using for as FANBOYS it means \"because\"</td></tr><tr><td>Sight used instead of site.&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Oral Fluency: 501</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Finn was pretty quiet and subdued today, very nonchalant in everything we undertook. He\'s got a great knowledge basis for us to be working with &amp; hopefully improving his phonogram knowledge will boost him up a bit.&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Going to really have to properly/explicitly teach the rules -- maybe make them the lesson\'s focus?&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-06-15 17:42:56', '2022-06-15 18:46:50'),
(2522, '2022/06/15', '06:20 pm', '2', '2', 'Callan Bartlett', 'Mathematics', 'Decimals', 'Operations with decimals', 'Discussion & Practise (on board/in book)', 'Kieran Oates', 'In Progress', NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'Assigned', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, '<p>Callan was very attentive but a little energetic so we played darts to finish off the lesson</p><p>&nbsp;</p>', '2022-06-15 18:20:55', '2022-06-15 18:42:12'),
(2523, '2022/06/16', '07:28 am', '2', '7', 'Nate Betros', 'Mathematics', 'Number & Place Value', 'Solve problems involving all four operations with whole numbers', 'Text Book - Exercises, Questions and Activities', 'Ivan Botero', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'Followup', '<p>In this lesson we worked on:</p><ul><li>Long additions with/without carrying.</li><li>Long subtractions with/without borrowing.</li><li>Times tables.</li><li>Division facts.</li><li>Word problems with two operations with/without a calculator. &nbsp;</li></ul><p>Overall, Nate did a great job. Even though he got confused sometimes with the operation he had to do. He managed to look for the answer.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, NULL, '2022-06-16 07:28:19', '2022-07-03 11:58:30'),
(2524, '2022/06/16', '08:48 am', '2', '3', 'Hunter McNees', 'English', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Juno Galang', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-06-16 08:48:02', '2022-06-16 08:48:02'),
(2525, '2022/06/16', '08:50 am', '2', '5', 'James Levings', 'Mathematics', 'Ratios', 'Using Ratios to Find Amounts', 'Textbooks, practice papers, school work', 'Ivan Botero', 'Not Yet', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>By passing a ball to each other, James and I practised the times\' tables. 2, 4, 5 and 6.&nbsp;</p><p>Then we were talking about cryptocurrency and how this changed throughout time.&nbsp;</p><p>Using that concept allowed us to look at ratios and slightly introduce James to cross-multiplication.&nbsp;</p><p>Then we were doing problems like, if 2 apples are $3, how much do I need to buy 6?&nbsp;</p><p>James\' behaviour was much better than in other weeks, even the jokes are back and the communication went really good.&nbsp;</p>', '<p>Lesson No 5 was delivered on 09.06.2022</p>', '2022-06-16 08:50:04', '2022-07-03 09:06:03'),
(2526, '2022/06/16', '03:27 pm', '2', '6', 'Sofia Creek', 'Mathematics', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Ivan Botero', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, '<p>The family got COVID and when I called the parent she apologised because she forgot to let ET know about this.&nbsp;</p>', '2022-06-16 15:27:50', '2022-07-02 20:38:26'),
(2527, '2022/06/16', '03:30 pm', '2', '5', 'James  Coleman', 'English', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Ellie Connor', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-06-16 15:30:13', '2022-06-16 15:30:13'),
(2529, '2022/06/16', '03:30 pm', '2', '7', 'Cara Lashmar', 'English', 'Writing - Paragraph & Composition Construction', 'Essay Structure - Introductory Paragraph', 'Map introductory summary using body paragraph topic sentences', 'Laree Thorsby', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Focus: The Writing Process</p><p>Introductory Paragraphs</p><p>Today\'s focus was on writing an introductory paragraph under the guise of summarising a movie - Writing a review.&nbsp;</p><ol><li>Worksheet reviewed and discussed.&nbsp;</li><li>identified the key points to summarise by highlighting them in the example given. Title, characters, setting, plot, ending</li><li>Watched a short Lego movie on youtube with no dialogue. Notes were taken for each identified point.</li><li>Write a summary of a recent movie/book/show. Cara chose Chicago Med, a popular tv series, to use as her practice piece.&nbsp;</li></ol><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-06-16 15:30:32', '2022-06-17 09:24:57'),
(2530, '2022/06/16', '03:36 pm', '2', '7', 'Lucy Fairbrother', 'Mathematics', 'Number & Place Value', 'Solve worded problems using four basic operations + modelling', 'Text Book  - Exercises, Questions, Activities', 'Naomi Wright', 'In Progress', NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', '<p>Focus on corrections in Workbook 3A NSPM today. &nbsp;Lucy was much slower to process these word problems and equations than what I anticipated she would be.&nbsp;</p><p>Lucy had some difficulty solving division problems using given information in the worded problem, and instead used her knowledge of the multiplication tables. &nbsp;Whilst this is a strategy to be acknowledged and encouraged, it became a hindrance for Lucy when she was unable to translate the figures she was manipulating from memory and those presented in the problem that produced a ‘left-over’ value. &nbsp;Lucy was encouraged to use reverse operation to check her answer, but she was unable to do so without some guidance. &nbsp;Eg &nbsp;$30 to spend. &nbsp;$4 per item. &nbsp;How many items can be purchased? &nbsp;Lucy said 7x4 is 28 so “28 items can be purchased”. &nbsp;The reverse operation, 30/4=7 &gt; $30 divided by $4 = 7 items, led to some confusion. &nbsp;We\'ll work more on these equations going forward.</p><p>It was really great to see that Lucy initially chose to use long division during one practice task, in spite of being invited to use short division if she would prefer. &nbsp;However, after a couple of equations, she chose to use short division which is an indication that she understands both strategies and is now making a choice about which one works best for her in a given moment.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, NULL, '2022-06-16 15:36:19', '2022-06-16 17:17:27'),
(2531, '2022/06/16', '03:42 pm', '2', '7', 'Arki Young', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms (include purpose - to connect speech sounds to their written symbol which helps with reading, writing and spelling)', 'Oral Phonogram Review (OPR) - Various Phonograms (see notes)', 'Neve Mitchell', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, '<p>No lesson due to public holiday.</p>', '2022-06-16 15:43:39', '2022-06-16 15:50:20'),
(2532, '2022/06/16', '04:23 pm', '2', '7', 'Finn Mackey', 'English', 'Writing - Paragraph & Composition Construction', 'Essay Structure - Introductory Paragraph', 'See Notes', 'Laree Thorsby', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Focus: The Writing Process</p><p>Introductory Paragraphs</p><p>Today\'s focus was on writing an introductory paragraph under the guise of summarising a movie - Writing a review.&nbsp;</p><ol><li>Worksheet reviewed and discussed.</li><li>identified the key points to summarise by highlighting them in the example given. Title, characters, setting, plot, ending</li><li>Watched a short Lego movie on youtube with no dialogue. Notes were taken for each identified point, written on the board</li><li>Finn then dictated his summary in the form of a speech to L. Initially his focus was on very specific details rather then the 5 categories given. L halted the process after a few sentences and reviewed the 5 categories, identifying which Finn had covered. Finn then gave a broader review of the second half of the movie, without focusing on every minute detail. Further practice is needed.</li></ol><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Focus: Speech in Text task - soccer commentary.</p><p>Revised and edited his homework. Finn is still very motivated by this form of writing and is very involved in the piece. We will publish it when complete.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-06-16 16:23:32', '2022-06-17 09:37:46'),
(2533, '2022/06/16', '04:26 pm', '2', '7', 'Chelsea Cooper', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Substitute onset & rime - Kilpatrick Level G', 'Ellie Connor', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week Seven</td></tr><tr><td>Thursday, 16 June 2022</td></tr><tr><td>WH Relief</td></tr><tr><td>PA: Kilpatrick</td></tr><tr><td>MA: Donah #19</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Challenge word: another</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR/WPR: er ur ir ti sh ough ou ck (back of phonogram box)</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Rule Review: 9, 4</td></tr><tr><td>9. If a word has 1 syllable, 1 vowel followed by 1 consonant. (I .e. swim) double consonant before adding a vowel ending (swimming).</td></tr><tr><td>SD: Sec. k - country, cloud, before, trip, tripped, hop, hopping, church</td></tr><tr><td>Read S&amp;R</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Use challenge word, plus two others from SD in a sentence</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Break up sentences and identify verbs, adjectives etc. Subordinate conjunction start&nbsp; with Unless/because</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>CC: 317-I (in folder)</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', '<p>EC on leave - WH relief&nbsp;</p>', '2022-06-16 16:26:17', '2022-07-08 15:45:48'),
(2534, '2022/06/16', '04:51 pm', '2', '7', 'Callisto Pratten', 'Mathematics', 'Patterns & Algebra', 'Describe, continue, and create number patterns resulting from performing addition or subtraction', 'Text book - Exercises, Questions, Activities', 'Rosemary Beswick', 'Achieved', 'Achieved', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Callisto completed her Trig test in class last Friday and so is now onto a new unit of work on Sequences and Series. We worked through examples from the textbook as described in the check sheet from school, using the teacher PowerPoint to clarify any points of confusion. The questions we dealt with concerned algebraic sequences and involved finding expressions to describe sequences.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-06-16 16:51:40', '2022-06-16 17:29:14'),
(2535, '2022/06/16', '05:18 pm', '2', '6', 'Nicholas Geeves', 'Mathematics', 'Patterns & Algebra', 'Quadratics', 'Expand binomial products and factorise monic quadratic expressions using a variety of strategies', 'Ivan Botero', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', '<p>Today we focused on factorising by grouping, for example, 1 + a + ac + a^2c</p><p>In the first 20 minutes, I did the explanation and then for the rest 40 min, Nicholas was solving problems with my help.&nbsp;</p><p>Nicholas has been improving on his factorisation skills, there is work to be done.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, NULL, '2022-06-16 17:18:37', '2022-07-02 17:48:44'),
(2536, '2022/06/17', '09:18 am', '2', '7', 'Phoebe Webb', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms (include purpose - to connect speech sounds to their written symbol which helps with reading, writing and spelling)', 'Oral Phonogram Review (OPR) - Various Phonograms (see notes)', 'Will Hughes', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>First lesson with Phoebe after handover from Yina, Wednesday 15/06/2022. Completed Yina\'s lesson plan, Phoebe was trying to work out what she can get away with with me, worked on 5 ers. Phoebe very good with 5 ers and new phonograms ea and ng. Had to turn things into a competition in order for her to be motivated to do it.</p>', NULL, '2022-06-17 09:18:51', '2022-06-17 09:23:12'),
(2537, '2022/06/17', '09:57 am', '2', '1', 'Ajay Sekar', 'Mathematics', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Campbell Jepson', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-06-17 09:57:50', '2022-06-17 09:57:50'),
(2538, '2022/06/17', '10:32 am', '2', '3', 'Amelia Sekar', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Manipulate (delete or substitute) initial phoneme in initial blend - Kilpatrick Level H', 'Ellie Connor', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td><ul><li>Donah and Kilpatrick</li></ul></td></tr><tr><td><ul><li>OPR recap s c g qu, intro a e o u</li></ul></td></tr><tr><td><ul><li>WPR s a c e g x o qu u</li><li>vowels in rule page 1</li></ul></td></tr><tr><td><ul><li>Intro rule 2 and 3<ul><li>Sorting activities</li></ul></li><li>Segment/count/blend c&amp;g words, write down 6x, use in sentence<ul><li>fancy, cent, cycle, city, pencil</li><li>gem, giant, genie, gym, magic</li></ul></li></ul><p><strong>BREAK</strong></p><p>Cyclops and Giants</p></td></tr><tr><td>Use SD words in sentences (EC write, AS dictate and draw pictures)</td></tr><tr><td>ORF assessments&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Read a story together&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Amelia did well today. Really good with PA, able to remember a few of cons subsequent sounds. Good with introduced vowels, but needed prompting particularly with o and u. Did really well with WPR process, although could focus more on handwriting. AS tends to go quickly and rush her work, so most times prompting her to slow down will prevent errors. Intro of rule 2 and 3 took no time at all, Amelia picked it up and was able to articulate it super quickly. No problems with the sorting activities, and was fine with SD words. Some prompting needed i.e. using /g/ /j/ to make the sound /j/. Five minute snack break and free time on the iPad, then we restarted the lesson with a game of Cyclops and Giants. Again, Amelia was fine with the rules when she stopped and thought about it, and enjoyed the game. Used SD words in sentences. AS wrote one, then dictated the other five. Drew a picture to accompany. Tried to do ORF assessments, but it was hard to mark because Amelia would run her words together and mumble when she wasn’t sure, and this would snowball. As soon as she started mumbling/skimming over words, she’d lose her focus and wasn’t able to regain it without prompting. Need to do a lot of work here in her reading accuracy before fluency can be addressed. Read a Billie B Brown together and played another C&amp;G game to finish.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', '<p>Week 7</p>', '2022-06-17 10:33:35', '2022-06-17 12:20:19'),
(2539, '2022/06/17', '11:43 am', '2', '7', 'Lottie Young', 'English', 'Reading - Fluency & Prosody', 'Read words aloud - accurately, automatically, with expression (connected text)', 'See given text in notes', 'Naomi Wright', 'In Progress', NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'Introductory', '<p>As Lottie rubbed off the board, she decoded the sentences:</p><p>His serves were small. &nbsp;The two serves were place in a bowl. &nbsp;The serves were quite large. &nbsp;The serve\'s sprinkles were brightly coloured.</p><p>Phonemic awareness, phonogram reviews and spelling dictation lessons centred partner phonograms: ai/ay, oi/oy, ou/ow, au/aw, ui/ew.</p><p>OPR x2 with check for understanding questions as well as several rounds of stepping out phonograms around the room making articulate and explicit connections between partners and cue words in order to support recall of the phonogram sounds.</p><p>WPR x2 with stepping out activity in between.</p><p>Spelling dictation x2 - one with analyses and one as a spell check. play, joy, Paul, cloud, boil, bow, fruit, new, drain law. &nbsp;Read for spelling and reading then read partner phonogram only in each word. Eg: &nbsp;j…oy…joy. &nbsp;p…l…ay…play. b…oi…l…boil. Then oy, ay, oi.</p><p>Lottie was able to see that her score improved from 4/10 to 7/10 on her WPR and from 4/10 to 8/10 on her spell check. &nbsp;We had a conversation about how she was able to take her score from one to the other. &nbsp;She mentioned “stepping out”. &nbsp;When asked what she was doing when stepping out, she said, “saying the sounds.” &nbsp;I also guided the conversation bringing attention to the fact that she deliberately made connections between partner phonograms and cue words which could be seen as “exercising her brain”. &nbsp;This highlights the need for Lottie to be an engaged and active participant in learning opportunities presented to her. &nbsp;This deliberate attempt to ‘remember’ information and then use it was a fruitful conversation that we can build on going forward.</p>', NULL, '<p>Lottie was absent with Covid last Friday, 10/06/2022 and the Friday previous, 3/06/2022 when Claire was in hospital.</p>', '2022-06-17 11:45:34', '2022-06-17 12:12:58'),
(2540, '2022/06/17', '01:52 pm', '2', '7', 'Archie Lester', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Segment, count and blend sounds in given words', 'Naomi Wright', 'In Progress', NULL, 'Attended Tardy', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', '<p>Challenge word - because &gt; what be the cause of… &nbsp;Syllables, markings, rule</p><p>Phonograms for OPR and WPR &gt; ir, oa, oe, ear, ng, gn, wr, si, ea, ci, oo, ow, wh, ou - Archie was a little slow to respond to some phonograms today, likely a result of a break in the program.</p><p>Word decoding (spelling notebook) and spell check words previously spelled incorrectly and later analysed and used in sentence writing &gt; poor, across, bare, full, fail, garden, wheat, window</p><p>Morphology - review affix (prefix and suffix), base (base word and word root) and record the following, discussing the meaning of each morpheme and how they change the meaning of the whole word - authored, worms, reworming, rewormed, serves. &nbsp;Discuss the three meanings of the suffix ‘s’ &gt; more than one, ownership and third person.</p><p>Analyse the meaning of the suffix in the following sentences:</p><ul><li>His serves were small. &nbsp;(More than one)</li><li>The two serves were placed in a bowl. (More than one)</li><li>The serves were quite large. &nbsp;(More than one)</li><li>The serve\'s sprinkles were brightly coloured. (Ownership - the sprinkles belonged to the serve [of icecream])</li></ul><p>Introduced the concept of 1st person verb (singular), 3rd person verb (singluar), 3rd person verb (plural)</p><p>To introduce the pronoun chart next lesson.</p>', NULL, '<p>Naomi was unwell for the lessons dated 3/06/2022 and 10/06/2022. &nbsp;Archie was also unwell earlier in the term with Covid. &nbsp;These lessons will be caught up with a 2 hour lesson on Saturday the 18/06/2022 and an additional hour yet to be scheduled.</p>', '2022-06-17 13:53:09', '2022-06-17 14:30:51'),
(2541, '2022/06/17', '03:25 pm', '2', '6', 'Harlow Booy', 'Mathematics', 'Number & Place Value', 'Investigate number sequences involving multiples of 3, 4, 6, 7, 8, and 9', 'TEXT BOOK - EXERCISES, QUESTIONS, ACTIVITIES', 'Ivan Botero', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', '<p>Today we checked all the times\' tables going forwards and backwards.&nbsp;</p><p>Using counters we implement strategies to use when we need to work out a multiplication sum.&nbsp;</p><p>Also, in the end, Harlow had a tiny quiz about adding and subtracting up to 4 digits numbers with and without carrying and borrowing. She did it very well, however, at home, there is used a method that isn\'t the same as the one used at school and that created a conflict.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, NULL, '2022-06-17 15:25:21', '2022-07-02 12:20:43'),
(2542, '2022/06/17', '04:00 pm', '2', '5', 'Josh Zeeman', 'Academic Coaching', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Will Hughes', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-06-17 16:00:44', '2022-06-17 16:00:44'),
(2543, '2022/06/17', '04:03 pm', '2', '7', 'Connor Thompson ', 'English', 'Reading - Comprehension > Text Type & Mental Actions', 'Mental Actions of Reading', 'Monitor comprehension of words, phrases & sentences', 'Neve Mitchell', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>White Card -- Connor wanted my help with answering the questions. Did some mental actions work &amp; also instruction on how to answer questions (e.g. process of elimination for multiple choice). It was pretty tricky, especially as Connor didn\'t really care about answering the questions, just getting them right. Concerning as this is all about safety procedures! When I could get him to slow down it was okay, although as he hadn\'t read through the course slides I was kind of teaching to the question. Connor\'s strategy before this seemed to have been choosing every single answer until it told him he was correct.</td></tr><tr><td>He was very gung ho, especially about that strategy, and didn’t take the time to double check his initial impulses against the slides before doing a \'literal\' check by hitting the submit button.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-06-17 16:04:02', '2022-06-17 16:29:38'),
(2544, '2022/06/17', '04:23 pm', '2', '7', 'Nate Betros', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms (include purpose - to connect speech sounds to their written symbol which helps with reading, writing and spelling)', 'Oral Phonogram Review (OPR) - Various Phonograms (see notes)', 'Neve Mitchell', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR: 27-52</td></tr><tr><td>WPR: ear ou oo ee ea aiay</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Read R&amp;S: Current Ayres Column</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Rule review:29 6</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD: coffee-fly</td></tr><tr><td>Read R&amp;S</td></tr><tr><td>Explain/discuss the markings and meanings of analysed words.</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Rule Intro: NA</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Sentence Structure: Composing 3 related sentences, easing Nate into paragraph structure/writing stories/longer texts.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Nate was still pretty resistant to paragraph writing, but with coaching he wrote 3 related sentences! Repeated a second time. The second time he was more confident. Still exhibiting the behaviour where he says something different to what he writes down. E.g. went instead of when -- and he knows how to spell when and can recognise the error when he is prompted to look for mistakes. He\'s also writing with lots of capital letters in stories to show feeling, but I\'m picking my battles at the moment.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-06-17 16:23:33', '2022-06-17 17:40:43'),
(2545, '2022/06/18', '10:22 am', '2', '6', 'Archie Lester', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Manipulate (delete or substitute) initial phoneme in initial blend - Kilpatrick Level H', 'Naomi Wright', 'Achieved', NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', '<p>Phonograms as per yesterday\'s lesson.</p><p>Spelling dictation - Rule Page 2: Her &gt; heard (x15 words)</p><p>Morphology - continue with Prefix/Base/Suffix table with the words serves, service and herded and check for understanding questions about bases, affixes, meaning of morphemes, how affixes changed the meaning of given words, parts of speech of given words (with and without morphemes) and spelling rule 11 (remove SFe when adding a vowel suffix).</p><p>Sentence Writing - Dictate given sentences and identify the meaning of the suffix ‘s’ in each - label. &nbsp;(See Wrokbook entry) &nbsp;Discuss ‘nominalisation’ - turning a verb into a noun (serve &gt; service). &nbsp;Archie also wanted me to work out the meaning of the term proprioceptive neuromuscular facilitation (PA Stretching). &nbsp;Using an understanding of morphemes, broke down the possible meaning of this term.</p><p>Introduce the concept of nouns of direct address, appositives (renaming the noun), and speaker tags. &nbsp;Model and dictate example sentences. &nbsp;To compose sentences next lesson using these elements.</p>', NULL, '<p>Saturday 18/06/2022 Double lesson held in lieu of 3/6 and 10/6. &nbsp;</p>', '2022-06-18 10:23:01', '2022-06-18 15:27:47'),
(2546, '2022/06/18', '03:37 pm', '2', '6', 'Lottie Young', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Segment, count and blend sounds in given words', 'Naomi Wright', 'In Progress', NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', '<p>Lottie is being encouraged to segment and blend sounds with her fingers. &nbsp;She was able to identify the sounds much more precisely when this process was slowed down after assigning one finger per sound, deliberately pausing and then blending to make the word. &nbsp;The words segmented were taken from the partner phonogram word list in Lottie\'s folder.</p><p>Partner phonograms were the focus for Lottie again today. &nbsp;She achieved a score of 9/10 and 8/10 respectively on both of her written reviews. &nbsp;Lottie\'s handwriting is notably improving.</p><p>Lottie and I had a conversation about the value of taking time to let her memory recall the information it needs at any time - in this case for phonogram recall. &nbsp;It became very apparent today that when Lottie wasn\'t struggling with the tension of ‘not knowing’ and was given the freedom to pause and think, she produced more consistently accurate responses. When Lottie was seen to start stressing about not remembering, I reminded her that it was okay to take time, her body physically relaxed, she paused, thought and wrote - it was a very deliberate process. &nbsp;It was clear that she was making a most concerted effort to recall the information, at times making connections with other phonograms or words or placement of the cards on the floor in her memory - we spoke about seeing the information in her mind\'s eye.</p><p>I also showed Lottie the picture of the ‘dyslexic brain’ processing from point A to point B with a journey through different parts of the brain as opposed to the non-dyslexic brain that goes in line from one to the other. &nbsp;I spoke about the gift of the longer journey and how it activates different parts of the brain and that, whilst it takes longer, this process develops other skills and strategies the the line version can\'t access. &nbsp;This seemed to resonate with Lottie.</p><p>Going forward, the focus will be on developing Lottie\'s confidence in the accuracy of her responses that she can take from the knowledge of the strategy or connection she has made.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '<p>Saturday 18/06 a one hour catch up for missed lesson on 10/06.</p>', '2022-06-18 15:38:47', '2022-06-18 17:01:01');
INSERT INTO `attens` (`id`, `date_created`, `time`, `term`, `lesson`, `student_name`, `subject_name`, `concept_name`, `conceptDetail`, `learningActivity`, `tutor_name`, `tutor_evaluation`, `student_self`, `student_attendance`, `homework_completed`, `weekly_lesson`, `homework_assignment`, `email_school`, `comment`, `commentPrivate`, `notesAttendance`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(2547, '2022/06/20', '10:49 am', '2', '4', 'Ajay Sekar', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms (include purpose - to connect speech sounds to their written symbol which helps with reading, writing and spelling)', 'Oral Phonogram Review (OPR) - Various Phonograms (see notes)', 'Neve Mitchell', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>OPR – a + 27-43, all first sounds</p><p>OPR – introduce 2nd and 3rd sounds up to 33</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>WPR –&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Spelling Dictation:</p><p>Sheep</p><p>Date</p><p>(had to stop here for a break as Ajay was just too wriggly/excitable/unfocused/adamant about doing a drawing).</p><p>Day</p><p>eat</p><p>School</p><p>chook</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Created a cartoon with Ajay – lots of writing involved, plus segmentation and encoding for “cartoon”.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Use words in sentence.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Quality lit – read a story with Ellie.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Game</p>', NULL, '2022-06-20 10:50:08', '2022-06-20 11:51:14'),
(2548, '2022/06/20', '11:55 am', '2', '4', 'Amelia Sekar', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Manipulate (delete or substitute) initial phoneme in initial blend - Kilpatrick Level H', 'Ellie Connor', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p><i><strong>LESSON FOUR&nbsp;</strong>– Monday 20 June 2022 (T2W8)</i></p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td><ul><li>Donah 10</li><li>Kilpatrick H1 number 3</li></ul></td></tr><tr><td><ul><li>OPR s c g qu a e o u <i>intro i y sh th ee</i></li></ul></td></tr><tr><td><ul><li>WPR s a c e g x o qu u<i> i y sh th ee</i></li><li>i and y in rule page 1</li><li>a c i e g sh u th x y o ee&nbsp;</li></ul></td></tr><tr><td><ul><li>Recap rule 2 and 3<ul><li>Cyclops and giants game</li></ul></li><li>Intro rule 4<ul><li>Rule 4 spin a star</li><li>Cut up rule 4 words activity</li></ul></li></ul><p><strong>BREAK</strong>&nbsp;</p><ul><li>Write a e o u words into rule page 1</li></ul></td></tr><tr><td>Use SD words in sentences (EC write, AS dictate and draw pictures)</td></tr><tr><td>ORF x3 assessments&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td><p>Read a story together&nbsp;</p><ul><li>Talk about narrative elements</li></ul></td></tr><tr><td>AS really enjoys having a plan for the lesson, and likes to know what’s happening (e.g. asking how many more PA questions she has to go). She did really well with phonos. Prompting with subsequent sounds of o, u, qu, but otherwise pretty good for the most part. Picked up new phonos well and able to do WPR easily. Loved playing C&amp;G and was able to articulate her understanding of rules 2 and 3 – some scaffolding needed. Intro to rule 4, AS able to ID syllables (despite some initial confusion about syllables vs sounds) and didn’t take long for her to become more comfortable with splitting words into syllables. AS enjoys cutting and pasting activities, so liked doing the rule 4 snipping work. We had a snack break with Ajay and Neve, then came back and did SD with vowel words in rule page 1. Amelia needed a lot of prompting to stay on track and not chat about irrelevant things, but with stricter guidelines we actually powered through the words quite quickly. Able to ID rule 4 words and words where vowels were saying their second or third sound. We then wrote a letter for Campbell, and Amelia spent some time decorating it for him. I read a story to Ajay and Amelia, then we finished with a game altogether.&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', '<p>Monday week 8</p>', '2022-06-20 11:55:33', '2022-06-20 11:57:30'),
(2549, '2022/06/20', '02:46 pm', '2', '8', 'Luna Shapiro', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Substitute onset & rime - Kilpatrick Level G', 'Neve Mitchell', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>PA: Kilpatrick Level G. Some scaffolding in beginning but Luna soon picked it up.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR: All sounds 1-8 + 27-30</td></tr><tr><td>Handwriting: 2x2 boxes + talking to pencil. Luna was great at talking to her pencil today!</td></tr><tr><td>WPR: She\'s struggling with imagining her own 2 o\'clock on the paper -- but okay with tracing. Going to send home some multi-letter phonogram words for handwriting practice.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Rule 1: q and u stick together like glue!</td></tr><tr><td>Draw a picture/create rule page.</td></tr><tr><td>Mark words.</td></tr><tr><td>SD: queen, quit, quiz, quack (for tomorrow)</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Luna did so well today! She was a little under the weather which, funnily enough, really helped keep her focused because she was much less interested in jumping about. She did well on her OPR and WPR although needed help with second sounds.&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-06-20 14:46:15', '2022-06-20 15:54:41'),
(2550, '2022/06/20', '03:25 pm', '2', '3', 'Jacob Tipping', 'English', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Juno Galang', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-06-20 15:25:37', '2022-06-20 15:25:37'),
(2551, '2022/06/20', '03:27 pm', '2', '8', 'Thomas Johnson', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms (include purpose - to connect speech sounds to their written symbol which helps with reading, writing and spelling)', 'Oral Phongram Review (OPR) - Cards 31 > 45', 'Yina Peng', 'Achieved', 'Achieved', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Kilpattrick F &nbsp;with timer. Mia and Thomas both did a great work on this, They used 30 seconds avaragely for it.</p><p>OPR: five er, ng, ea. ea. They both needed help for ea but Mia remebered this one better.&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;multi sound boucing game for ea.&nbsp;</p><p><br>WPR: &nbsp;five er, ng, ea. &nbsp; &nbsp;<strong>Mia struggles with the formation for ur. ear, and Thomas needs help with ir, ur, ear. They both tend to write ae for ea.&nbsp;</strong></p><p>handwriting focus: line letter u.&nbsp;</p><p>marking system- pink book page 2. They learned how to mark multi letter phonograms and phonograms that do not say its first sound.&nbsp;</p><p><br>SD:five er words, ng, ea words. her, first, nurse, works, early. sea, ring. They were a bit struggling with the words early and nurse.&nbsp;</p><p>compose sentences using SD words. See notebooks.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-06-20 15:27:33', '2022-06-22 09:27:52'),
