(2763, '2022/07/26', '05:23 pm', '3', '1', 'Lucy Crosswell', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Substitute onset & rime - Kilpatrick Level G', 'Neve Mitchell', 'Achieved', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>PA: Level G</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR: 1-8, 27-38</td></tr><tr><td>WPR: a c g ow th ou ch ar ay ai&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>ow ar</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Rule 2 &amp; 3 review. Discussion on whitebaord (revisited a lot of spiel elements). Cut &amp; Paste activity. Cyclops and Giants.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Big chat with Lucy about c and g. She initially told me she was okay after our quick recap, but when I pressed and asked her if she would like me to explain it a little more, she said yes. We completed the c and g activities with a LOT of articulation, more or less for every word. Like last time, once she\'d seen it a couple of times she picked it up.</td></tr><tr><td>In our discussion we talked about trying to figure out which sound a letter is saying, and how we can use our knowledge of the word (e.g. we know the a says A in game because we recognise the word, and therefore know how to sound it out) if it\'s a familiar word, but can find it trickier when the word is unfamiliar. I used made up words to demonstrate this. I then linked this to the spelling rules by explaining that the rules will help tell us what sound to make/give us an instruction (like traffic lights give you an instruction). Lucy seemed like she understood this concept.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-07-26 17:23:11', '2022-07-26 18:38:32'),
(2764, '2022/07/27', '07:47 am', '3', '1', 'Luke  Vandenberg', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - High Frequency Vocabulary', 'Analysis of word structure and application of learned concepts (sounds, phonograms, rules)', 'Spelling Dictation - Precisely say, write and read words in Section P', 'Yina Peng', 'Achieved', 'Achieved', 'Attended Tardy', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<ol><li>PA: Kilpatrick i</li></ol><p>2. SD: assessment. Luke\'s chronological age is 11 and his spelling age is now 9 years and 11 months. His spelling grade is 3.7. He has not gained much in the last term. We will need to focus on his high frequency vocabulary again.&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;</p><p>3. no punctuation sentence activity. He normally ask for confirmation for his answers to each activity.&nbsp;</p><p>4. writing activity: birthday card for children who suffer from poverty worldwide. Luke normally shows anxiety and impatience during our lesson. Hence his spelling usually has more mistakes and he does not want to write essays.&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-07-27 07:47:41', '2022-07-28 13:02:17'),
