(2782, '2022/07/28', '03:29 pm', '3', '1', 'James  Coleman', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Substitute onset & rime - Kilpatrick Level G', 'Ellie Connor', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week One</td></tr><tr><td>Thursday, 28 July 2022</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>PA: Kilpatrick</td></tr><tr><td>MA: Donah #27</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Challenge word: push&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>VD: mark and use affixes to build 11 new words</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR/WPR: ow er th ng ou oa ea ch qu ee gn</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>SD: Sec L - close, close, flower, flour, nothing, ground, lead, led, lead</td></tr><tr><td>Read S&amp;R</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Continue sentence structure booklet (clauses and key terms)</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Homework: simple -&gt; compound sentences and mark clauses</td></tr><tr><td>James was really good today, but did seem to get a little tired and disengaged towards the end. Pretty good with PA and MA, but did need some prompting. Did a good job of word building activities, although I noticed that he was anxious about coming up with real words - encouraged him a few times to play with non-words e.g. we created \'overpushable\'. SD was super easy (NB need to look at MM and bump him up a level?). Convo about the brackets in our word list - homophones and words that had similar meanings. Then continued talking through sentence structure booklet, looking specifically at key terms and then clauses. Nice link to our morphology discussion earlier when we discussed morphology of \'independent\', although I did notice James\' focus fading quickly.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week One</td></tr><tr><td>Thursday, 28 July 2022</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', '2022-07-28 15:29:36', '2022-09-17 12:34:23'),
(2783, '2022/07/28', '03:30 pm', '3', '1', 'Cara Lashmar', 'English', 'Writing - Paragraph & Composition Construction', 'The Writing Process - Plan, Compose, Revise, Edit, Publish (by reading, speaking, media presentation)', 'Use the writing process to compose informative paragraph', 'Laree Thorsby', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Persuasive Writing Task</p><p>Reading the question to ensure comprehension.&nbsp;</p><p>Examples using neg/pos language</p><ol><li>Should school uniforms be compulsory?</li></ol><p>School uniforms should not be compulsory.</p><p>What is the difference? are they asking the same thing?</p><p>Write a list of pros and cons/yes or nos/ positives or negatives for each.</p><p>Order points from most important to least.&nbsp;</p><p>Choose your view</p><p>Write an introductory sentence stating your view giving the main reason why.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>2. Should salmon be kept in pens and farmed in the Derwent River?</p><p>Making connections - What do you know? What does the question tell you?</p><p>Identify key words</p><p>What does it mean?</p><p>How does farming work?</p><p>Why?</p><p>What might the issues be?</p><p>Who/what will it affect?</p><p>Plan - on board writing dot points.</p><p>Write an intro sentence stating your position and why?</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-07-28 15:30:28', '2022-08-02 10:43:23'),
(2785, '2022/07/28', '03:33 pm', '3', '1', 'Mia Harvey', 'Mathematics', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Campbell Jepson', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-07-28 15:33:53', '2022-07-28 15:33:53'),
(2786, '2022/07/28', '03:43 pm', '3', '1', 'Lucy Fairbrother', 'Mathematics', 'Number & Place Value', 'Mental Computation', 'Mixed Equations', 'Naomi Wright', 'In Progress', NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', '<p>Lucy initially worked through a mental maths practice page with a variety of missing values. I noted that Lucy didn\'t show any workings and even reverted to using tally marks for calculating groups of 14 in 51 instead of testing her estimate or using the ‘reverse operation\' approach we have practiced. Lucy will complete the small number of corrections at home.</p><p>Lucy then identified estimated values on a number line according to the placement of the given arrow in relation to the halfway mark between groups of one hundred. &nbsp;We will revisit this task next week so as to give Lucy as review and practice in articulating the reason for her selection.</p><p>The final portion of the lesson was spent identifying the highest/greatest (GCF) common denominator of two given numbers, initially side-by-side on the board and then for the numerator and denominator on given fractions. Lucy benefited from the task of having to articulate the meaning of the term ‘greatest common factor’ and then applying this knowledge to the process of simplifying fractions.</p><p>It was wonderful to hear Lucy say that the algebra unit she is studying at school presently is ‘easy’. &nbsp;After looking through tasks uploaded to Mr Carmel\'s intranet systems, it appears the school are using Cambridge text books, so we will begin preparing Lucy for the upcoming assessment of this unit with this resource.</p>', NULL, NULL, '2022-07-28 15:43:08', '2022-07-28 18:20:24'),
(2787, '2022/07/28', '04:23 pm', '3', '1', 'Chelsea Cooper', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Substitute onset & rime - Kilpatrick Level G', 'Ellie Connor', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week One</td></tr><tr><td>Thursday, 28 July 2022</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>PA: Kilpatrick</td></tr><tr><td>MA: Donah #26</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Challenge word: push</td></tr><tr><td>VD: mark and use affixes to build 11 new words</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR/WPR: ow er th ng qu ou oa ea gn ch ee</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Rule Review: 1, 19</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD: Sec. K - mouth, oak, peach, pole, queen, rope, season, sign, space</td></tr><tr><td>Read S&amp;R</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Start reading Matilda together</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Chelsea really struggled with her PA today - not sure if it\'s just due to the break? She needed a lot of scaffolding to provide the correct answers, and seemed to find that the affix representative magnets were really useful. Overall, she just seemed to be working slower and finding tasks more difficult than she previously has. Struggled a bit with MA, too - needed prompting and heavy coaching. Spent a really long time on the word building activity, despite me letting her know that it was just a quick warm up activity, and that the words didn\'t need to be real ones. Powered through phonos and SD (prompting to sound sfe, with qu), then spent the last 10mins talking through text types and mental actions quickly before reading the first bit of Matilda.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-07-28 16:23:14', '2022-07-28 18:05:30'),
(2788, '2022/07/28', '04:23 pm', '3', '1', 'Finn Mackey', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Language Rules (Pronunciation/Spelling/Grammar)', 'Various rules (see notes)', 'See notes', 'Laree Thorsby', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<ol><li>Spell Check 10 words &nbsp;use of ck/k + rule 9 11 24 unpick, blocked, chat, shopping, funny, happily, wake, spoken, biggest, cried</li><li>Identify POS - adverbs = ly Finn unclear on use.&nbsp;</li><li>Sentence Dictation</li><li>identify sentence structure/type.</li><li>suffixes - ing ed er est ance ant al y es ly&nbsp;</li><li>Rules when adding suffixes 9 10 11 24 via sorting cards. Print more.&nbsp;</li><li>Spell check - rules&nbsp;</li></ol>', NULL, '2022-07-28 16:23:32', '2022-08-02 10:51:09'),
(2789, '2022/07/28', '04:26 pm', '3', '1', 'Samuel Lamont', 'English', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Campbell Jepson', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-07-28 16:26:32', '2022-07-28 16:26:32'),
(2790, '2022/07/28', '04:41 pm', '3', '1', 'Callisto Pratten', 'Mathematics', 'Linear & Non-Linear Relationships', 'Linear & Non-linear equations', 'Text book - Exercises, Questions, Activities', 'Rosemary Beswick', 'Achieved', 'Achieved', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', '<p>Callisto had a very long assignment on sequences and series. She had attempted some questions. We completed most of it with some help from the PowerPoint for that topic.</p>', NULL, NULL, '2022-07-28 16:41:10', '2022-07-28 18:13:37'),
(2791, '2022/07/29', '07:47 am', '3', '1', 'Archie Lester', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - High Frequency Vocabulary', 'Analysis of word structure and application of learned concepts (sounds, phonograms, rules)', 'Challenge Word Analysis - Record and label syllables, markings and rules + discuss morphemes', 'Naomi Wright', 'In Progress', NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', '<p>The challenge word for today was ‘desirable’. &nbsp;This was a longer conversation than anticipated. &nbsp;Archie had some difficulty selecting the accurate placement of syllables which then impacted his ability to segment and pronounce the word. &nbsp;Many questions were asked prompting Archie\'s thinking and application of previously learned knowledge. &nbsp;For example: &nbsp;What do you know about every syllable? &nbsp;What sound is the vowel making in this syllable? &nbsp;Why? &nbsp;What type of syllable is this? Why can\'t we move the syllable break? &nbsp;What will that do to the syllable/vowel sound? What type of ‘e’ is this? &nbsp;What job is it doing? &nbsp;How many morphemes? etc</p><p>Phonograms reviewed today: c, ng, er, wr, ch, e, ed, a, o, ei, ie, gn</p><p>Words for phonemic awareness: come, coming, write writer, change, changed desire, desirable</p><p>Words for spelling dictation: hope, hoping, write, writer, change, changed, serve, service, nerve, nervous, desire, desirable</p><p>During the sentence writing lesson, Archie was asked to identify the comma tips previously studied and to answer check for understanding questions regarding the structure of each. &nbsp;Three sentences were then dictated for Archie to record and punctuate justifying his placement of commas.&nbsp;</p><p>See notes in Archies folder for the detailed lesson plan.</p><p>Next week, all components of this lesson will be revisited strengthening application of knowledge, supporting the movement of information from short to long term memory. &nbsp;Further review of today\'s sentences will include check for understanding questions including identification of sentence type and structure in addition to those outlined today.</p>', NULL, NULL, '2022-07-29 07:47:48', '2022-07-29 11:57:08'),
(2792, '2022/07/29', '09:04 am', '3', '1', 'Lottie Young', 'English Assessment', 'Phonics Knowledge - understand and apply the sound/symbol connection', 'Recall of sounds for given symbols (see the symbol, say the sound)', 'Oral Phonogram Assessment - 70 common phonograms', 'Naomi Wright', 'In Progress', NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', '<p>Three lengthy assessments were conducted today the results of which show that Lottie is making gradual and tangible gains. &nbsp;In spite of difficulties she has experienced in recalling focus phonograms last term (ay/ai, oy/oi, aw/au, ow/ou, ew/ui) she was able to recognise all of these for reading today, and all bar ui for writing. &nbsp;This was most encouraging.</p><p>See Survey of Phonogram Recall on file in Lottie\'s folder.</p><p>Additionally, Lottie was very confident and accurate in all initial sound/symbol connections on the Waddington Reading Test #2 and in decoding all single words given. &nbsp;When reading her selections to me, Lottie recognised and self-corrected the one error.</p><p>Areas of focus going forward include what words follow ‘a’ and ‘an’ as well as decoding words in single sentences &nbsp;by identifying multiletter phonograms, syllables, segmenting and blending. &nbsp;It is apparent that Lottie will guess words to make them fit what she thinks the sentence is saying.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, NULL, '2022-07-29 09:04:18', '2022-07-29 11:32:54'),
(2793, '2022/07/29', '02:27 pm', '3', '1', 'Molly  Jackson', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Manipulate (delete or substitute) second phoneme in initial blend - Kilpatrick Level K', 'Neve Mitchell', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>PA: K1 again</td></tr><tr><td>Counters on table for scaffolding. Molly sometimes looked at them, but mostly didn\'t need them. She said she liked having them on the table just in case. She still needs to sound out the word, sound out with the deleted sound and blend to get the answer</td></tr><tr><td>Also took us a long time - 10 minutes or so.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR: 27-70</td></tr><tr><td>WPR: ed ea igh dge oa ch ow or th ir&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Read R&amp;S: Current Ayres Column</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Rule review: NA</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD: lead-mind</td></tr><tr><td>Read R&amp;S</td></tr><tr><td>Explain/discuss the markings and meanings of analysed words.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Sentence Structure: Use Ayres words in sentences to show meaning. Some discussion around lead/led as this was a little tricky for Molly (as I expected it would be!). She did a great job at composing interesting sentences and was also able to talk about her complex sentence and identify where she needed a comma.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Oral Fluency: 222 &amp; 223. Molly was a bit rushed initially and her words were stringing together/there was little inflection. When I asked her to slow down she said she had only been reading it that way because she was mindful of being timed. She was much better on the second go through.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-07-29 14:27:32', '2022-07-29 16:18:36'),
(2794, '2022/07/29', '03:42 pm', '3', '1', 'Archie Smith', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Will Hughes', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p><strong>Archie Smith 27/7/22</strong></p><p>Kilpatrick K1 no.12 and no.13</p><p>Donah Morphology&nbsp;#22</p><p>Break</p><p>Phonograms OPR: eigh, ti, ed, kn, ai, ch, ay, oa, ie</p><p>Write down phonograms</p><p>Break</p><p>SD (O): eight, election (tall sh), objection (tall sh), aboard (use oa of boat), jail, restrain, chief, station (tall sh), friend, captain, cautious, floated, knee, holiday</p><p>5 Sentences</p><p>Challenge word: Orchestra</p><p>Break</p><p>ORF 511-I</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Archie was in a bit of a grumpy mood today when he arrived for tutoring. After throwing some darts and playing some soccer, he was in a good mood and willing to do the work. He struggled with ‘ie’ and ‘ed’, and got a couple wrong in Kilpatrick. He also missed some lines in his ORF. He got the hang of the rest of the phonograms and did well in spelling, but struggled with cautious and got station mixed up with solution. He was very good with the challenge word and put together some really good sentences incorporating the challenge word, as well as 6 words from SD.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-07-29 15:43:17', '2022-07-29 15:44:28'),
(2795, '2022/07/29', '03:44 pm', '3', '1', 'Cole McGuinness', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Will Hughes', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Cole and I got along really well in his first lesson. We worked on assessments and it shows that Cole is currently behind in both spelling and reading. Cole enjoyed playing hangman for a break, definitely something we can continue to do.</p>', NULL, '2022-07-29 15:45:28', '2022-07-29 15:46:27'),
(2796, '2022/07/29', '03:46 pm', '3', '1', 'Harriet Van Der Laan', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Will Hughes', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>HVDL Lesson 25/07/22</p><p>Kilpattrick Level D1 in Folder</p><p>OPR/WPR: e, o, u, y, c, g, s, qu, b,</p><p>Handwriting: Cc</p><p>Introduce Rule 1: q is always followed by u</p><p>Review Rule 7 Job 1</p><p>SD: last, not, good, live (R.7), ice, we, will, my, old, bad, but, all, quit</p><p>Kindergarten Fluency Book 18, week 17, days 1 and 2 (in folder).</p><p>Donah #1</p><p>Game</p><p>Harriet struggled with ‘qu’, ‘y’ and second sound of ‘c’. She quickly understood Rule 1, and she also remembered Rule 7 Job 1. Harriet tends to forget things quite quickly. Harriet is confident with the reading sheet that we have been working on for the last few weeks, and we will move onto the next challenge next lesson. She is also understanding her morphology.</p>', NULL, '2022-07-29 15:47:04', '2022-07-29 15:47:42'),
(2797, '2022/07/29', '03:48 pm', '3', '1', 'James Oettle', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Will Hughes', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>James and I were getting along, but he started missing his mum. It was a very difficult lesson based on James\' age and the fact I did not know what to expect. I have devised a lesson plan that will hopefully suit James\' needs going into next week.</p>', NULL, '2022-07-29 15:48:47', '2022-07-29 15:50:01'),
(2798, '2022/07/29', '04:15 pm', '3', '1', 'Nicholas Geeves', 'Mathematics', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Ivan Botero', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-07-29 16:15:20', '2022-07-29 16:15:20'),
(2799, '2022/07/29', '04:25 pm', '3', '1', 'Nate Betros', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms (include purpose - to connect speech sounds to their written symbol which helps with reading, writing and spelling)', 'Oral Phonogram Review (OPR) - Various Phonograms (see notes)', 'Neve Mitchell', 'Achieved', 'Not Yet', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR: 27-70</td></tr><tr><td>WPR: ew ow ea th er ie ed ei au dge&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Rule review: 4 24 28 5 6 12</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD:&nbsp; sew-vein</td></tr><tr><td>Read R&amp;S</td></tr><tr><td>Explain/discuss the markings and meanings of analysed words.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Use Ayres words in sentences.</td></tr><tr><td>Not Completed:</td></tr><tr><td>Writing Process: Plan a narrative. ID beginning, middle, end, and the conflict/problem that needs to be resolved.</td></tr><tr><td>Writing Process: Write first draft of narrative.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Nate was in a very silly mood today. We had lots of trouble with Spelling Dictation and Nate\'s handwriting and general accuracy and care with handwriting and markings. I made him erase his work multiple times. Nate didn\'t like this but even when I told him that the solution was to do it properly/with care on the first try he continued to deliberately antagonise me.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-07-29 16:25:28', '2022-07-29 17:42:14'),
(2800, '2022/08/01', '07:32 am', '3', '2', 'Darcy Callaghan', 'English', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Campbell Jepson', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-08-01 07:32:40', '2022-08-01 07:32:40'),
(2801, '2022/08/01', '08:44 am', '3', '1', 'James Oettle', 'English', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Will Hughes', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Second lesson with James. Much better. The new lesson plan works well <strong>James Oettle 1/8/22</strong></p><p>Spaulding Mindset</p><p>10-15 minute attention span: plan lessons in 15 minute blocks.&nbsp;</p><p>One minute Kilpatrick activities. Heggerty – wider range of phonics.&nbsp;</p><p>Work through spiel in a slow way.&nbsp;</p><p>Road signs, toy cars.&nbsp;</p><p>Counters and cups – counters represent each sound in a word, put a counter in a cup for each sound.&nbsp;</p><p>Oral/Written Phonogram Review.</p><p>Lesson focus: Bb</p><p>Big, bag, beg, bog, bug</p><p>Name and sound, handwriting and reading.&nbsp;</p><p>Drawing</p><p>Colouring</p><p>Games involving Bb</p><p>Splash Learn&nbsp;</p><p>Chalk on driveway?</p><p>We are working through the alphabet and focusing heavily on James\' handwriting. His reading is very good, and his knowledge of letters and sounds is also fantastic for someone so young. Mum sat in for the whole lesson, but James did not get distracted too much.</p>', NULL, '2022-08-01 08:44:00', '2022-08-08 10:18:00'),
(2802, '2022/08/01', '08:45 am', '3', '2', 'Liam Wells', 'English', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Campbell Jepson', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-08-01 08:45:10', '2022-08-01 08:45:10'),
(2803, '2022/08/01', '03:20 pm', '3', '1', 'Gabriel Bohm', 'English', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Campbell Jepson', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-08-01 15:20:57', '2022-08-01 15:20:57'),
(2804, '2022/08/01', '03:26 pm', '3', '1', 'Jacob Tipping', 'English', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Juno Galang', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-08-01 15:26:12', '2022-08-01 15:26:12'),
(2805, '2022/08/01', '03:27 pm', '3', '2', 'Thomas Johnson', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms (include purpose - to connect speech sounds to their written symbol which helps with reading, writing and spelling)', 'Oral Phongram Review (OPR) - Cards 31 > 45', 'Yina Peng', 'Achieved', 'Achieved', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>I set up a competition for Mia and Thomas today. They had to concentrate for all questions and rules to earn love heart shape and the student who won the most would get to pick a chocolate at the end of the lesson. They were very competitive and concentrated very well. They have mastered rule 4 and had a great grasp of rule 6 and rule 17!</p><p>Kilpattrick F &nbsp;with timer. They both are ready to move up.&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;</p><p>OPR o, e, y, ou, w, i, l, u, a, s. &nbsp; Mia is a bit shaky at the mutiple sounds of e, ou, a, and s. Thomas needed help with ou and u<br><br>WPR: o, e, y, ou, w, i, l, u, a, s. They both did an excelent job.&nbsp;</p><p><br>rule review: rule 4. new rule r. 17, 5, 6 with activities. Mia and Thomas grasped the new rules very fast as they concentrated very well.&nbsp;</p><p><br>SD: top, he, you, will, we, my, up, last</p><p><br>compose sentences using SD words.</p><p><br>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-08-01 15:27:11', '2022-08-01 18:03:18'),
(2806, '2022/08/01', '03:29 pm', '3', '2', 'Mia Harvey', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms (include purpose - to connect speech sounds to their written symbol which helps with reading, writing and spelling)', 'Oral Phongram Review (OPR) - Cards 31 > 45', 'Yina Peng', 'Achieved', 'Achieved', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>I set up a competition for Mia and Thomas today. They had to concentrate for all questions and rules to earn love heart shape and the student who won the most would get to pick a chocolate at the end of the lesson. They were very competitive and concentrated very well. They have mastered rule 4 and had a great grasp of rule 6 and rule 17!</p><p>Kilpattrick F &nbsp;with timer. They both are ready to move up.&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;</p><p>OPR o, e, y, ou, w, i, l, u, a, s. &nbsp; Mia is a bit shaky at the mutiple sounds of e, ou, a, and s. Thomas needed help with ou and u<br><br>WPR: o, e, y, ou, w, i, l, u, a, s. They both did an excelent job.&nbsp;</p><p><br>rule review: rule 4. new rule r. 17, 5, 6 with activities. Mia and Thomas grasped the new rules very fast as they concentrated very well.&nbsp;</p><p><br>SD: top, he, you, will, we, my, up, last</p><p><br>compose sentences using SD words.</p><p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-08-01 15:29:07', '2022-08-01 18:01:29'),
