(2854, '2022/08/04', '04:31 pm', '3', '6', 'Samuel Lamont', 'English', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Campbell Jepson', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-08-04 16:31:37', '2022-08-04 16:31:37'),
(2855, '2022/08/04', '04:32 pm', '3', '2', 'Cara Lashmar', 'English', 'Reading - Comprehension > Text Type & Mental Actions', 'Mental Actions of Reading', 'Monitor comprehension of words, phrases & sentences', 'Laree Thorsby', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Tardy', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'Followup', NULL, '<p>Cara is studying MAcbeth this term at school. Her teacher emailed to request we work on looking at this, plus figurative language, and sentence structure.&nbsp;</p><p>Today\'s focus was understanding a Lady Macbeth monolgue appliying the Mental Actions of Reading. Once Cara had identified the unknown words in the highlighted sentence she used her knowledge of parts of speech and morphology to gain a fairly literal word for word translation. Next ,she looked at the inferred meaning by reading back and ahead - we used a translated version of the text for this.&nbsp;</p><p>Cara was bale to grasp the meaning of the entire monolgue using this method and was able to summarise it in her own words.&nbsp;</p><p>HW - 2 short passages to complete at home.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-08-04 16:32:27', '2022-08-05 09:34:29'),
(2856, '2022/08/04', '05:00 pm', '3', '2', 'Callisto Pratten', 'Mathematics', 'Patterns & Algebra', 'Create algebraic expressions and evaluate them by substituting a given value for each variable', 'Text book - Exercises, Questions, Activities', 'Rosemary Beswick', 'Achieved', 'Achieved', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', '<p>Callisto worked on some questions on ‘Growth and Decay’ last time she was in class. We completed this section from the textbook, according to her list of work to do. We then spent a short amount of time working on ‘Difference Equations’, learning how to do these for both arithmetic and geometric sequences. We also worked out how to do them on the calculator.</p>', NULL, NULL, '2022-08-04 17:00:38', '2022-08-04 18:12:16'),
(2857, '2022/08/05', '08:23 am', '3', '2', 'Archie Lester', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - High Frequency Vocabulary', 'Analysis of word structure and application of learned concepts (sounds, phonograms, rules)', 'Challenge Word Analysis - Record and label syllables, markings and rules + discuss morphemes', 'Naomi Wright', 'Achieved', NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', '<p>Challenge word - reviewed ‘desirable’ again and then analysed admirable through making connections with desirable. &nbsp;Discussed check for understanding questions including morphology (morphemes as smallest unit of meaning, the number of syllables in each morpheme and the meaning of each morpheme).</p><p>Archie found generating ideas for sentence writing a bit difficult this morning, so some prompting needed here. &nbsp;His understanding and application of the structure was accurate, however, it will be beneficial to spend some time focusing on the subject noun and verb when written as phrases. &nbsp;Eg, “Naomi\'s desire for Archie to write the word ‘desirable’ (noun phrase) is (linking verb)…”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Played ‘Crazy Sounds’ card game - match vowel sounds of multi-letter phonograms.</p>', NULL, NULL, '2022-08-05 08:23:04', '2022-08-05 10:38:08'),
(2858, '2022/08/05', '08:44 am', '3', '0', 'Henry  Badock', 'Mathematics', 'Number & Place Value', 'Recognise and represent multiplication as repeated addition, groups and arrays', 'TEXT BOOK - EXERCISES, QUESTIONS, ACTIVITIES', 'Laree Thorsby', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'Not Returned', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Today\'s session was a catchup lesson from term 2. week 8.&nbsp;</p><p>We continued on with our focus on multiplication. Focus was 10 x and 2 x table. Presented Henry with various manipulatives, ten frames, and activities to get started but he was very oppositional. Probably not helped by the change in room.&nbsp;</p><p>There is a real block around the language of multiplication. H is still to grasp the concept of groups of, lots of , piles of, cups of…. equalling a number eg in 6 x 2 he can count 2 objects into a pile, he can then replicate this 6 times when pushed. when asked to articulate how many groups/piles/bundles he says 6. when asked how many objects are in each bundle he will say 6. we check and recount and he agrees on 2 in each group, and agrees there are 6 groups, and by this stage has worked out there are 12 objects in total (addition or counting in twos) but does not grasp the concept that the 6 groups of 2 equals 12 objects in total. he still continues to say 6. He is equating each group as 1 whole object every time. Henry then becomes oppositional as he is not experiencing immediate success, and states \"it\'s too easy. If given 7 x 6 -a problem he cannot work out in his head, he refuses to engage. The aim is for henry to &nbsp;grasp the concept and the language, verbal and written. HE currently refuses to engage in the language as he is not sure of the meaning. Henry can and has memorised the ten x table although he will not say three times ten equals 30. If asked to read a problem he has yet to demonstrate that he grasps the relationship between the words and the symbols. He can do this with plus and minus. This shows he does not understand the concept of multiplication as yet.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-08-05 08:45:08', '2022-08-05 09:11:25'),
(2859, '2022/08/05', '02:31 pm', '3', '2', 'Molly  Jackson', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Manipulate (delete or substitute) second phoneme in initial blend - Kilpatrick Level K', 'Neve Mitchell', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>PA: K1 (counters on table)</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR: 50-70</td></tr><tr><td>WPR: ed ew ui oa gu ough oe igh sh th ir oi</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Rule review: 13 4 17</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD: shall-body</td></tr><tr><td>Read R&amp;S</td></tr><tr><td>Explain/discuss the markings and meanings of analysed words.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Sentence Structure: Use Ayres words in sentences.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>After sounding out alone -- \"I\'m alone a lot.\" NM: Oh, how come? MJ: \"I get bullied sometimes… no I don\'t, I\'m kidding.\"</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Tried to have a conversation with Molly today about the sound/symbol connection. It arose primarily with the word point. I had Molly sound it out, then she wrote down \"ponit\" while sounding out point. I asked her to read back through/sound out and she sounded out point. I took us out of spelling and said I wanted to have a chat about sounds and symbols. English is like a code, we have to crack the code, we crack the code by making sure the letters match up with sounds. It was a really difficult conversation because Molly was jumping about all over the place/couldn\'t sit still/kept trying out other spellings of point (pontie, pornit, etc) without taking the time to listen to me or understand what I was telling her about the model. I put a scaffold on the board for the single/2 letter phonograms ( . __ . .) to match up with the sounds but again Molly couldn\'t encode. We had some discussion about how our brains work and get muddled.</td></tr><tr><td>We talked about how Molly\'s brain wanted to spell the word point, and was going through the \"word memory\" box in her head. But the word memory box is tricky sometimes because it only remembers the letters and not the order they were in. So then we (our \'outside\' brains) have to go back through and check if the letters are in the right order by seeing if it sounds out to make the word. But often Molly\'s brain is SO SURE that it got the word right that it can trick us when we\'re sounding out to make us think we\'re correct. It\'s easier if we send our brain through the phonics box.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-08-05 14:32:12', '2022-08-05 15:43:53'),
(2860, '2022/08/05', '03:31 pm', '3', '2', 'Freya McIver', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics & Morphology - The Vocabulary of Word Structure', 'Morphemes - Words consist of distinct parts each of which have their own meaning > base words/word roots + affixes (prefixes/suffixes) = derived word', 'Compare base words & word roots - articulate/explain the similarities & the differences', 'Ellie Connor', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Lesson Two</td></tr><tr><td>Friday, 5 August 2022</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>If Freya doesn\'t bring work: word building activities using action, act, justice, just, gentleman, gentle - use in sentences. Revisit sentence structures (can fill out doc together)</td></tr><tr><td>Did some PA, then dictated words above. Analysed together like in SD, then talked through their etymology and parts of speech by using them in sentences. Freya looked very bored and like she was falling asleep! Powered through the last bit of this activity, then I coaxed Freya into doing a Morrison, even though she wasn\'t super happy about it. She did pretty well, but has gone slightly backwards. I was impressed by her persistence and focus throughout this test. Finished with a game of Exploding Kittens!</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Lesson Two</td></tr><tr><td>Friday, 5 August 2022</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', '2022-08-05 15:31:42', '2022-09-16 16:11:07'),
(2861, '2022/08/05', '02:32 pm', '3', '2', 'Connor Thompson ', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms (include purpose - to connect speech sounds to their written symbol which helps with reading, writing and spelling)', 'Oral Phonogram Review (OPR) - Various Phonograms (see notes)', 'Neve Mitchell', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'Cancelled - No Show', 'N/A', 'Cancelled', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, '<p>No Connor due to illness, cancelled last minute.</p>', '2022-08-05 15:35:50', '2022-08-19 16:06:58'),
