(2863, '2022/08/05', '03:59 pm', '3', '1', 'Josh Zeeman', 'Academic Coaching', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Will Hughes', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-08-05 15:59:08', '2022-08-05 15:59:08'),
(2864, '2022/08/05', '04:28 pm', '3', '2', 'Nate Betros', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms (include purpose - to connect speech sounds to their written symbol which helps with reading, writing and spelling)', 'Oral Phonogram Review (OPR) - Various Phonograms (see notes)', 'Neve Mitchell', 'Achieved', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-08-05 16:28:09', '2022-08-05 17:00:36'),
(2865, '2022/08/06', '02:48 pm', '3', '2', 'Lottie Young', 'English', 'Reading - Fluency & Prosody', 'Read words aloud - accurately, automatically, with expression (words in isolation)', 'See word list in notes - read for spelling and/or read for reading', 'Naomi Wright', 'Not Yet', 'Not Yet', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'Introductory', '<p>Lottie was observed as being unable to accurately read a series of CVCC and CCVC words making guessing errors, adding sounds, mispronouncing vowel sounds etc. &nbsp;Some errors she self corrected, but many prompts were given for her to re-attempt the reading of these words.</p><p>flap, clam, punk, crank, flop, flam, gunk, prank, flip, flan, grunt, rank, slip, span, grant, tank.</p><p>During Spelling Dictation, Lottie spelled all words accurately as she sounded them out with just one error, a reversal of the letter ‘p’.</p><p>Similarly, there was only one word on the list that Lottie was unable to define (flam - a particular type of drum-beat). &nbsp;We spoke about the extraordinary places one word can take us in our mind when visualising (eg Lottie spoke about a specific type of military tank when I imagined a water tank on a lush green property)</p><p>I asked Lottie to rate her reading our of 10. &nbsp;She gave accuracy 4/10 and comprehension 9/10. &nbsp;She is very intuitive regarding her assessment as I also would have assigned these values.</p><p>A conversation subsequently ensued about the different reading skills (decoding/saying/reading words, fluency/smooth reading, and comprehension/understanding words). &nbsp;We noted the distinct difference between Lottie\'s ability to understand words (among her many other strengths) and her ability to accurately decode words. &nbsp;We again referenced the dyslexia brain image discussed a few weeks ago that shows the longer journey her thoughts take to process and respond to input. &nbsp;It was profound to be able to make this distinction with Lottie understanding that she must be so very cognizant of what she hears and understand vs what she is able to decode from the page. We spoke about this difficulty of this skill being the result of how one particular part of her brain is wired and that together we can work to rewire the neural pathways responsible for this skill. &nbsp;Lottie seemed genuinely invested in this shared project.</p><p>We then reviewed the four types of sentences and highlighted key words.</p><p>For the words ‘gunk’ and ‘slip’, Lottie wrote the sentence, ‘The gunk is slipping down the wall\'s in Arky\'s bedroom.\' &nbsp;Lottie made a connection with a recent contraction lesson held at school and the word he’s being short for ‘he has’. &nbsp;To clarify the distinction between he\'s and wall\'s, we had a lesson on contractions, discussing the meaning of the word ‘contract’ with some examples (Lottie referenced birthing contractions, and I referenced the expansion and contraction of concrete…) Writing words on the board, Lottie crossed out the space and the letters to be removed, and wrote the corresponding contraction with apostrophe representing the missing letters. &nbsp;</p><p>it Is – it’s, can not – can’t, he has – he’s, should not – shouldn’t, would have – would’ve</p><p>Further review + ownership apostrophe to be discussed next lesson.</p><p>Lottie showed me a method she has learned at school for accurate directionality and formation when writing numbers using the left hand thumb.</p><p>Claire and I had quite a long conversation after Lottie\'s lesson about neural pathways (stacked vs branched) and the value of Lottie being spoken to at her intellectual level rather than ‘down to’. &nbsp;Claire notes the school have assessed Lottie as being at grade standard for her reading. &nbsp;She also commented on a lack of evidence based teaching in Lottie\'s classroom observed during her parent teacher interview. &nbsp;She said there was no substitute for the value of the MILA approach to handwriting vs repeated writing of (for example) “k…k…k”.&nbsp;</p><p>Some profound connections were made today. &nbsp;It will be great to continue this work with Lottie perhaps with a new sense of partnership moving toward a shared goal.</p>', NULL, '<p>Extended conversation with Claire (Mo) after lesson regarding discussion held with Lottie during class. &nbsp;</p>', '2022-08-06 14:48:59', '2022-08-06 15:52:33'),
(2866, '2022/08/08', '07:31 am', '3', '3', 'Darcy Callaghan', 'English', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Campbell Jepson', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-08-08 07:31:44', '2022-08-08 07:31:44'),
