(2877, '2022/08/08', '03:35 pm', '3', '3', 'Elsa Clennet', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms (include purpose - to connect speech sounds to their written symbol which helps with reading, writing and spelling)', 'Oral Phonogram Review (OPR) - Various Phonograms (see notes)', 'Neve Mitchell', 'Achieved', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR:&nbsp; 27-38, ea, 67-70</td></tr><tr><td>WPR: or th er ou ea oe o eigh ti&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Rule review: 4 6</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD: northern-potato</td></tr><tr><td>Read R&amp;S</td></tr><tr><td>Explain/discuss the markings and meanings of analysed words.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Use Ayres words in a sentence &amp; (subsequently) talk about alliteration and when we might use that/what sort of effect it gives Elsa\'s sentence in terms of tone.</td></tr><tr><td>Writing Process: Continue composing first draft of informative text.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p>Notes:</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Elsa is having very little difficulty with this informative task. She has a solid grasp of how to use her plan to maximise her writing ability, and her vocabulary lends her work an articulate air.&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Perhaps a stronger emphasis on research? I could prepare her for developing her referencing and bibliography skills. Perhaps some source analysis/using primary evidence in her work would be beneficial? That could also bridge the gap between narrative and informative work (we could write about a theme in LOTR, for example)...</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-08-08 15:35:18', '2022-08-08 16:26:57'),
