(2882, '2022/08/08', '04:35 pm', '3', '3', 'Arlo Clark', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms (include purpose - to connect speech sounds to their written symbol which helps with reading, writing and spelling)', 'Oral Phongram Review (OPR) - Cards 31 > 45', 'Yina Peng', 'Achieved', 'Achieved', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Arlo was a bit fatigue today and as his speech report suggested, we should keep his learning into small breaks. Keep him move around so that he can rest away from his fatigue. He knows at least one sound for each phonogram out of 31 and he retains rule 4 we have learned before.&nbsp;</p><p>Kilpattrick F1</p><p>OPR: 1-31 try not to moo. Arlo got confused with ow, ou, u, and o.&nbsp;we might concentrate on one sound each in the future. &nbsp;<br>WPR:1-31. Arlo is a bit shaky at writing ou and ow. Rule page 1 focus. We leared rule 2 &amp; rule 3, homework related to these has been sent home. We wil need to recap these rules again next week by activities.&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-08-08 16:35:02', '2022-08-09 15:11:58'),
(2886, '2022/08/08', '04:46 pm', '3', '3', 'Arki Young', 'English', 'Writing - Paragraph & Composition Construction', 'Essay Structure', 'See Notes', 'Neve Mitchell', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Academic Coaching -- Arki\'s Geographic Report.</td></tr><tr><td>Use the template to create a scaffold for Arki on a word doc on his laptop. Start by using the \"headers\" from the template.</td></tr><tr><td>Had a go with the dictation function on Arki\'s laptop and also showed Arki a bunch of technological \'tricks\' to make his essay writing easier, including split screen and how to create dot points.</td></tr><tr><td>We used a technique where Arki found relevant information from a website and then copy and pasted it onto his scaffold to create a \"map\" of information in the correct logical order to help when he turns that information into his own words. We also talked about keeping track of websites by keeping the url at the bottom of the document.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-08-08 16:47:20', '2022-08-08 17:38:32'),
(2887, '2022/08/08', '06:22 pm', '3', '3', 'Connor McLaren', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Delete onset or rime - Kilpatrick Level F', 'Ellie Connor', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week Three</td></tr><tr><td>Monday, 8 August 2022</td></tr><tr><td>1.5hr</td></tr><tr><td>PA: Kilpatrick</td></tr><tr><td>MA: Donah #28</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR/WPR: ea th or our ee ti er dge 61-70</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Rule Review: 4, 6, 14</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD: Sec. O - restrain, royal, objection, object, pleasure, measure, treasure, navy</td></tr><tr><td>Read S&amp;R</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>NM inference passage</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>ORF x3</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Today\'s lesson was really tough! Connor was all over the place and wouldn\'t listen to my instructions at all. Somewhat reinforced my thoughts around separating the pair. Even PA, OPR and WPR were challenging to do (boys out of sync, Connor being silly and giggling, Lachlan laughing at Connor and distracted, Connor answering for Lachlan and not giving him a chance to speak etc.). I put the lesson plan on the board, complete with time stamps for games after each half hour, but this didn\'t seem to make a difference to Connor, whose behaviour was distracting for Lachlan. Struggled with SD - CM handwriting was atrocious, and he wasn\'t taking any time with it. LS did really well though, and ended up providing all markings. Took a 5 min break while I printed off a word analysis sheet for the boys with their spelling words, then LS stepped through it with me. At this point, CM was on the floor and was completely disengaged, so I just finished the SD with LS. We played a quick game of Words at Work (I figured it would substitute for sentence work), but Connor was again disengaged and silly, to the point of almost not hearing my instructions. Wrapped this up and then split the boys. CM stayed in the classroom working independently on a mental actions/inference task, as I hoped he would settle a bit with no external stimulus. Alex was watching from the office, and stepped in to chat with him when CM started throwing pencils at the dartboard, and trying to throw all the darts at once. Meanwhile, I did 2x ORF with LS. Swapped the boys over, LS working on inference task while CM did reading with me. CM distracted and silly, e.g. holding the book on his head, punctuating his words by banging on the desk and not responding to any of my instructions.&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', '<p>Extra half hour to catch up W2</p>', '2022-08-08 18:22:41', '2022-08-08 18:23:47'),
(2888, '2022/08/08', '06:24 pm', '3', '2', 'Lachlan  Smith', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Delete final sound in word or final blend - Kilpatrick Level I', 'Ellie Connor', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'Rescheduled', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, '<p>EC unwell - catching up by adding 30 minutes to lessons in Weeks 3 and 4</p>', '2022-08-08 18:25:12', '2022-08-08 18:26:40'),
(2889, '2022/08/08', '06:25 pm', '3', '3', 'Lachlan  Smith', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Substitute onset & rime - Kilpatrick Level G', 'Ellie Connor', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week Three</td></tr><tr><td>Monday, 8 August 2022</td></tr><tr><td>1.5hr</td></tr><tr><td>PA: Kilpatrick</td></tr><tr><td>MA: Donah #28</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR/WPR: ea th or our ee ti er dge 61-70</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Rule Review: 4, 6, 14</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD: Sec. O - restrain, royal, objection, object, pleasure, measure, treasure, navy</td></tr><tr><td>Read S&amp;R</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>NM inference passage</td></tr><tr><td>ORF x3</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Today\'s lesson was really tough! Connor was all over the place and wouldn\'t listen to my instructions at all. Somewhat reinforced my thoughts around separating the pair. Even PA, OPR and WPR were challenging to do (boys out of sync, Connor being silly and giggling, Lachlan laughing at Connor and distracted, Connor answering for Lachlan and not giving him a chance to speak etc.). I put the lesson plan on the board, complete with time stamps for games after each half hour, but this didn\'t seem to make a difference to Connor, whose behaviour was distracting for Lachlan. Struggled with SD - CM handwriting was atrocious, and he wasn\'t taking any time with it. LS did really well though, and ended up providing all markings. Took a 5 min break while I printed off a word analysis sheet for the boys with their spelling words, then LS stepped through it with me. At this point, CM was on the floor and was completely disengaged, so I just finished the SD with LS. We played a quick game of Words at Work (I figured it would substitute for sentence work), but Connor was again disengaged and silly, to the point of almost not hearing my instructions. Wrapped this up and then split the boys. CM stayed in the classroom working independently on a mental actions/inference task, as I hoped he would settle a bit with no external stimulus. Alex was watching from the office, and stepped in to chat with him when CM started throwing pencils at the dartboard, and trying to throw all the darts at once. Meanwhile, I did 2x ORF with LS. Swapped the boys over, LS working on inference task while CM did reading with me. CM distracted and silly, e.g. holding the book on his head, punctuating his words by banging on the desk and not responding to any of my instructions.&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', '<p>Extra half hour to catch up W2</p>', '2022-08-08 18:25:39', '2022-08-08 18:27:46'),
(2890, '2022/08/09', '07:27 am', '3', '3', 'Henry  Badock', 'Mathematics', 'Number & Place Value', 'Recognise and represent multiplication as repeated addition, groups and arrays', 'TEXT BOOK - EXERCISES, QUESTIONS, ACTIVITIES', 'Laree Thorsby', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>T3W3</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Henry immediately engaged with today’s first task as I gave him some blocks to fiddle with, which we used as part of our first activity.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Focus: Multiplication as repeated addition.</p><ol><li>Blocks used to model verbal instructions.</li></ol><p>Blocks joined in a long line. Henry had to break off and place on the table.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Script:</p><p>Show me 2/5/10 blocks +?more +?more+5?more</p><p>How many blocks in total?</p><p>How many groups/stacks/lots of 2/5/10 blocks are on the table.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Henry often volunteered the total number of blocks on the table. Primary method of calculation was counting in 2s/5s/10s. He still does not explicitly use manipulatives/fingers to assist in this. Always encourage him to do so to check his answer. He does not like to be wrong.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><ol><li>Blocks loosely placed in piles of 6x2, 5x3, 3x5, 4x5 with different colours for each group</li></ol><p>I modelled the first 2 with Henry answering the questions&nbsp;</p><p>How many groups? How many blocks in each group? Write as a sum (+). How else could you write this?&nbsp;</p><p>Interestingly H. immediately identified he could write it as 3x5 etc. He completed the final 2 without assistance and even provided the answers for all 4 (not a focus). Sheet in folder.</p><ol><li>Blocks joined together within their groups eg 6 x 2 and Henry then used these to create a sword with a replicating pattern for each problem.&nbsp;</li><li>Worksheet using arrays and groups to represent multiplication. Aside from the usual refusal to actually count 1-1 and making an error, Henry recognised the patterns and could use the language when asked to verbalise the process. Every error required a check. Henry prefers to guess before checking.&nbsp;</li><li>Pirate pete using dice to 10 and blocks in groups of five (joined). Roll dice, model the problem, work out answer, decide who is bigger or smaller.&nbsp;</li><li>Review addition – sheet given for HW. Reminder to set out work using place value and begin from left to right.&nbsp;</li></ol>', NULL, '2022-08-09 07:27:18', '2022-08-09 09:23:28'),
(2891, '2022/08/09', '07:36 am', '3', '3', 'Cole McGuinness', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms (include purpose - to connect speech sounds to their written symbol which helps with reading, writing and spelling)', 'Oral Phongram Review (OPR) - Cards 31 > 45', 'Will Hughes', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'Attended Tardy', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p><strong>Cole McGuinness 8/8/22</strong></p><p>Kilpattrick Level I2 in folder no. 1 and 2</p><p>Introduce rule 6, English words do not end with ‘i’ use ‘y’</p><p>OPR/WPR: th, ow, ou, oo, ch, ar, ay, ai</p><p>hangman</p><p>SD (k): became, brother, rain, keep, start, mail, male, female</p><p>Hangman</p><p>3 sentences, 2 words.&nbsp;</p><p>ORF- 301A in folder</p><p>Donah #1</p><p>Game</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Need to revisit ou, oo and ou next week. Cole being very distracted from the fan, will remove next lesson. Kilpattrick was good, and Cole got a solid understanding of rule 6 and is also very aware of rule 7 job 1. Cole is continuing to enjoy hangman, which is a great way to break up the lesson. Cole also did some good sentences. Cole also did very well on Donah.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-08-09 07:36:34', '2022-08-09 07:37:52'),
(2892, '2022/08/09', '10:28 am', '3', '2', 'Matthew Heard', 'Mathematics', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Ivan Botero', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-08-09 10:28:32', '2022-08-09 10:28:32'),
(2893, '2022/08/09', '03:32 pm', '3', '3', 'Sophie Mirowski', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Manipulate (delete or substitute) initial phoneme in initial blend - Kilpatrick Level H', 'Neve Mitchell', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>PA: Kilpatrick H</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR: 27-44</td></tr><tr><td>WPR: er th or ough ea ch&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Oral Fluency: ORF 411.&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Sophie was absolutely knackered from performing in the musical all day. She was visibly drooping and emotional because of how tired she was. She got through Kilpatrick, OPR and WPR, but started tearing up when spelling came about. She said she couldn\'t help it and wasn\'t even upset, just so tired! I felt so sorry for her! We played Jenga and did some sentence work and reading activities.&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-08-09 15:32:22', '2022-08-09 16:37:16'),
(2894, '2022/08/09', '03:38 pm', '3', '3', 'Brock Smith', 'English', 'Writing - High Frequency Vocabulary + Parts of Speech', 'Verbs - doing, linking, helping', 'See Notes', 'Yina Peng', 'Achieved', 'Achieved', 'Attended Tardy', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Brock showed up a bit late today and not in a good mood. He could do most of the task but it was quite hard to keep him concentrate on writng process.&nbsp;</p><p>Kilpatrick H1<br><br>rule review rule2, 9, 29, new rule 32</p><p>SD of fer, suf fer, cen tre, front, run ning, run<br>read for spelling<br>read for reading&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;</p><p>online verb game -verb tense. Brock hasn\'t totally graspped verb tense yet he can pick the right tense for specific situation correctly.</p><p><br>Writing: Monster writing: revising. We did planning and composing last week and he was very resistent at revising this week. However, he still finished what he needed to do by adding transitioning words to link his 5 sentences into a paragragh. He has some misspelling in his writing.&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-08-09 15:40:51', '2022-08-10 08:53:34'),
(2896, '2022/08/09', '04:21 pm', '3', '3', 'Lachlan Prior', 'English', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Campbell Jepson', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-08-09 16:21:01', '2022-08-09 16:21:01'),
(2897, '2022/08/09', '03:40 pm', '3', '3', 'Callum Coulson', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Language Rules (Pronunciation/Spelling/Grammar)', 'Rule 25: Write ck to say /k/ after a single vowel saying its first (short) sound', 'See Notes', 'Yina Peng', 'Achieved', 'Achieved', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Callum returned from his recovery of illness last week and he seemed a bit disencouraged to his learning today when he gets frustrated with phonograms and spelling.&nbsp;</p><p>kilpatrick F1<br>rule review 29, 4, 11, 25<br>SD: tick et, ac count, driv en, re al, re cov er. He had problem to write recover and real into syllables and next time, we will try to write wrods first before we divide syllables &nbsp;as he is nearly a college student.&nbsp;</p><p><br>affixes activity with SD Callum confuses suffixes with phrases. When asked to add a suffix to real, he would make up phrase like real life.&nbsp;</p><p><br>parts of speech: &nbsp;online noun game. He can function very well at recognizing nouns yet he is still confused about the concept.&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-08-09 16:34:27', '2022-08-10 09:00:53'),
(2899, '2022/08/09', '04:37 pm', '3', '3', 'Shay Douglas', 'Physics', 'Physics', 'Physics', 'Physics', 'Neve Mitchell', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'Attended Tardy', 'N/A', 'To Be Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Activity: Work through Shay\'s physics revision test, with me coaching as needed. Shay was pretty alright with all of this and a lot of formulas/formula application came back to him as he worked through the questions!</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-08-09 16:37:48', '2022-08-09 17:18:59'),
(2900, '2022/08/09', '05:32 pm', '3', '3', 'Lucy Crosswell', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Substitute onset & rime - Kilpatrick Level G', 'Neve Mitchell', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>PA: Kilpatrick G</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR: 1-8, 27-43</td></tr><tr><td>WPR: a c g ee th ow ou ch ar ay</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Revisit sound/symbol connection.</td></tr><tr><td>Rule review: Create a \"rule review\" pack to laminate. Rule 1, 2, and 3. Decorate and discuss the rules. Make sure to include an example and mark accordingly.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>The rule review activity took a lot longer than I thought it would but I think it was really worthwhile. Lucy was still getting muddled at the start with just rule numbers and she found the Spalding explanation really tricky to understand. We re-worded the rules into Lucy\'s own words, with whatever worked for her. We also added pictures that had a connection to the rule.</td></tr><tr><td>I feel pretty good about where Lucy is at at the moment. She is doing really well in OPR and WPRs. I also feel pretty good about Rules 1, 2 and 3 now. I just want to make sure she keeps seeing them throughout the next couple of weeks. Possibly in her homework? Not just using rule 2 and 3 words, but analysing them as well.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-08-09 17:32:43', '2022-08-09 18:27:41'),
(2901, '2022/08/10', '08:09 am', '3', '3', 'Luke  Vandenberg', 'English', 'Writing - High Frequency Vocabulary + Parts of Speech', 'Nouns - name people, places, things, ideas', 'See Notes', 'Yina Peng', 'Achieved', 'Achieved', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>I have combined Luke\'s ball game into our learning today and it seems quite good for Luke\'s learning. We had four tasks as I explicitly told him at the beginning, after each task, each of us could have three licks at the ball game, then we collect the points and write them in his book for next week. He could sit down nicely for our work yet still shows a bit impatience. He ets frustrated when he write a word wrong as he purses perfection sometimes.&nbsp;</p><p>kilpatrick F1<br>OPR/WPR: u, s, ai, au, v, ti, eau, Luke needed help with u, o, ou, au ti for opr, and he is confused with ti for wpr. He could not remember ai for wpr either.&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;</p><p>Rule review: 4, 6, 11,14, 22, 24,</p><p>SD: u su al, com plaint, au to, va ca tion, beau ti ful, beau ty. He wrote orto for auto, which means he is confused with the three or, au, and aw.&nbsp;<br>Read R&amp;S<br>Explain/discuss the markings and meanings of analysed words.</p><p><br>online noun game. He is quite good at this yet he usually need my confirmation for nouns in sentences.&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-08-10 08:10:01', '2022-08-10 09:09:59'),
(2902, '2022/08/10', '01:49 pm', '3', '3', 'Eleanor  Stam', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics & Morphology - The Vocabulary of Word Structure', 'Suffix - letters added to the end of base words or word roots to create new words > they have their own meaning & they change the meaning of the base or root - Suffixes cannot stand/be used alone', 'Spell words with suffixes indicating tense > ed/ing', 'Laree Thorsby', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Week 3</p><p>Writing</p><p>Compound sentence, focus on structure – capital, IC fanboy comma IC full stop.&nbsp;</p><p>Model with blocks.</p><p>Use a word from spelling list&nbsp;</p><p>Write in book.</p><p>Underline the POS</p><p>Wk3 Assess 102&nbsp;</p><p>Game – Endings Connect 4&nbsp;</p><p>HW</p><p>Suffixes no rules worksheet + OF 110 to end.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-08-10 13:49:58', '2022-08-15 21:13:05'),
