(2916, '2022/08/11', '03:24 pm', '3', '2', 'Reuben Shelverton', 'English', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Juno Galang', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-08-11 15:24:40', '2022-08-11 15:24:40'),
(2917, '2022/08/11', '03:28 pm', '3', '3', 'James  Coleman', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Substitute onset & rime - Kilpatrick Level G', 'Ellie Connor', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week Three</td></tr><tr><td>Thursday, 11 August 2022</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>PA: Kilpatrick G2</td></tr><tr><td>MA: Donah #29</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR/WPR: ti ie sh kn si dge ci igh gn wr eigh&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Rule Review: 13 and 14</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD: Rule page 6 - ti words</td></tr><tr><td>Read S&amp;R</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>ORF x2</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Homework template 1 using \'ti\' words</td></tr><tr><td>James seems to find it easier to write sentences/compose work when he has words placed in front of him - i.e. use spelling words in a sentence. Correcting own handwriting in WPR (\"that\'s too big\"). Almost accurate with gn/kn, but needs more practice, prompting with igh in WPR. I was really impressed with James in SD. There were a couple of occasions where I needed to prompt him to sit up straight (he would put his head on the desk and his writing would immediately go wonky) or to stop rocking back in his chair. Otherwise, he was totally fine with the multi-syllabic words, and didn\'t seem to have an issue breaking them into syllables and then decoding each syllable. Able to ID \'ti\' and rule 4 markings in words. Walked James through his homework for the week (no issues), and then he read 2x ORF.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week Three</td></tr><tr><td>Thursday, 11 August 2022</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', '2022-08-11 15:28:49', '2022-09-17 12:38:36'),
(2918, '2022/08/11', '03:34 pm', '3', '3', 'Cara Lashmar', 'English', 'Reading - Comprehension > Text Type & Mental Actions', 'Monitoring Comprehension', 'See Notes', 'Laree Thorsby', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>We are starting to look in to figurative language this coming week, specifically simile, metaphor and personification. We are making the link between how Shakespeare used figurative language to add complexity to the characters and to let the audience know what the characters were thinking and feeling.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>We are going to look at identifying the different types of figurative language within the passages attached. Then dig more in to Lady Macbeth’s use of figurative language throughout the play and what that tells us about her.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>I realise this is not very specific, but hopefully it gives you enough to align to our content a bit better.</p><p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-08-11 15:34:25', '2022-08-25 15:18:17'),
(2919, '2022/08/11', '04:21 pm', '3', '3', 'Finn Mackey', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics & Morphology - The Vocabulary of Word Structure', 'Suffix - letters added to the end of base words or word roots to create new words > they have their own meaning & they change the meaning of the base or root - Suffixes cannot stand/be used alone', 'Spell words with suffixes indicating part of speech > y/er/en/ful/ion/ance/ence (tion)', 'Laree Thorsby', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Spell check with words containing prefixes (re/pre/mis/un/dis) and suffixes (ed/ing/ly/y/es/on/ance/ence</p><p>Writing task - review plan and compose draft. Finn chose to tell his story through dialogue between characters. He made a great start, but has become slightly detail focused. We completed another sentence to add to the end in order to give Finn a goal to work toward.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-08-11 16:21:20', '2022-08-15 21:07:05'),
(2920, '2022/08/11', '04:33 pm', '3', '3', 'Chelsea Cooper', 'Mathematics', 'Number & Place Value', 'Solve problems involving multiplication of large numbers by one- or two-digit numbers', 'TEXT BOOK - EXERCISES, QUESTIONS, ACTIVITIES', 'Ellie Connor', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week Three</td></tr><tr><td>Thursday, 11 August 2022</td></tr><tr><td>Maths work</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Looked at Chelsea\'s homework - she did well, but we need to do more work on ti/ci/si so that she knows which one to use in each place. She had brought along some maths work, so we looked at that together this lesson. Did some place value questions, and Chelsea found it helpful to use the whiteboard so that she could work out the place value of each number. Also talked about how multiplication and division are related i.e. 8x5=40, 40/5=8 etc.&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week Three</td></tr><tr><td>Thursday, 11 August 2022</td></tr><tr><td>Maths work</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', '2022-08-11 16:33:52', '2022-09-17 12:56:52'),
(2921, '2022/08/11', '04:52 pm', '3', '3', 'Callisto Pratten', 'Mathematics', 'Patterns & Algebra', 'Describe, continue, and create number patterns resulting from performing addition or subtraction', 'Text book - Exercises, Questions, Activities', 'Rosemary Beswick', 'Achieved', 'Achieved', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'Followup', '<p>Callisto is up to Set 3 of the Sequences and Series unit in GM3. This set deals with Difference Equations. We started this work briefly last week and so are just continuing the work this time. The initial problems deal with representing sequences using difference equations and also using a difference equation to find the first few terms of a sequence. Callisto was OK with this once she got going but seemed tired at the start and require a few reminders at that point. I sent an email to Callisto\'s teacher to try to find out if there would be a unit test soon and also whether there are any assignments that have been missed</p>', NULL, NULL, '2022-08-11 17:09:46', '2022-08-11 17:54:57'),
(2922, '2022/08/12', '07:48 am', '3', '3', 'Archie Lester', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - High Frequency Vocabulary', 'Analysis of word structure and application of learned concepts (sounds, phonograms, rules)', 'Challenge Word Analysis - Record and label syllables, markings and rules + discuss morphemes', 'Naomi Wright', 'Not Yet', NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', '<p>Archie\'s ‘challenge words’ today were excitable r.20, 2, 5, 4 + Job 1 SFe and noticeable r.4 + Job 3 &amp; 4 of SFe. &nbsp;Archie was not cognitively in the lesson at this point and was making lots of guesses about syllable placement, markings and rules of these words. &nbsp;I spoke with him about the cogs not lining up in his brain to think clearly. &nbsp;I strongly encouraged him to slow down and make connections with work he has done the past two lessons and to make connections between the two words on the board to help him work out the structure of these words. I also asked Archie what a morpheme is and for him to identify and label the morphemes in these words. &nbsp;We then compared the r. 11 in excitable with the need to keep the SFe in the word noticeable. &nbsp;There was a lot to unpack and a lot of very productive conversation during this session.</p><p>Phonograms reviewed today: dge, gn, ear, a, ie, ed, c, o, au, sh, ck, i, w, f, u. &nbsp;Archie was a little unsure with a number of the sounds and their associated cues today. The check-for-understanding question, ‘How can this phonogram represent it’s second sound?\' was challenging &gt; when at the end of a syllable, with a SFe and consonant in between or followed by two consonants (i and o).</p><p>In morphemic awareness segment, completed an oral and a written morpheme review (OMR, WMR) introducing associated rules. &nbsp;Included marking the base-word dash before a suffix:</p><p>-ful r.21, -less r.17, -ed r.28, -s, -ing</p><p>Explained that -ing “means now” but it also means “at that point in time” which may be past or future. &nbsp;Eg: &nbsp;At the time you called me, I was playing the piano. &nbsp;At the time you call me, I will be playing the piano.</p><p>Sandrah Donah #14 (has also completed at home).</p>', NULL, NULL, '2022-08-12 07:48:57', '2022-08-12 11:40:22');
INSERT INTO `attens` (`id`, `date_created`, `time`, `term`, `lesson`, `student_name`, `subject_name`, `concept_name`, `conceptDetail`, `learningActivity`, `tutor_name`, `tutor_evaluation`, `student_self`, `student_attendance`, `homework_completed`, `weekly_lesson`, `homework_assignment`, `email_school`, `comment`, `commentPrivate`, `notesAttendance`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(2923, '2022/08/12', '10:40 am', '3', '3', 'Lottie Young', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms (include purpose - to connect speech sounds to their written symbol which helps with reading, writing and spelling)', 'Oral Phonogram Review (OPR) - Various Phonograms (see notes)', 'Naomi Wright', 'Achieved', NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', '<p>Began today\'s lesson with a review of our discussion last week re the layers of reading skill - decoding &gt; fluency &gt; comprehension. &nbsp;We recalled the rating Lottie gave herself out of 10 for decoding and comprehension. &nbsp;Prompting was needed for Lottie to recall the meaning of these key words and her self-assessment, but it was a good refresher and set the scene for the lesson in terms of the focus on decoding skills given Lottie has strong comprehension of what she reads. &nbsp;I spoke with Lottie about how the Science of Reading tells us that the fastest way for the brain to make the connection between the sound and the symbol (the vital skill needed for decoding). &nbsp;Lottie frequently chooses not to sound as she writes in spite of encouragement for her to do so and an obvious improvement in accuracy when she does.</p><p>Consonant blends were the focus for our phonics lesson today - Lottie segmented and blended the following in both oral and written (selection only) reviews with read for spelling and read for reading at the end:</p><p>gr, gl, pr, sn, br, dr, sc, cl, sl, st, tr, pl, sp, fr, fl, str, cr, sm, bl, sw, tw, squ, all, nd, spl, nt, spr, lt, nk, ast, mp, shr, thr, old, nch, ind, ost, alk&nbsp;</p><p>Blends then encoded in spelling dictation lesson: trip, step, clap, slop, scrunch, drop, bran, snot, prep, glad, grump, plot.</p><p>Reviewed sentence types and composed one of each type of sentence for analysed words. &nbsp;Many check for understanding questions around type and structure: &nbsp;What type of sentence is this? &nbsp;What\'s another name for that type of sentence? &nbsp;What punctuation did you use for that type of sentence? &nbsp;What is missing from an imperative sentence (subject noun)? &nbsp;What structure is this sentence? &nbsp;How do you know? &nbsp;What is the first thought? What is the second thought? &nbsp;How are those thoughts connection? &nbsp;What punctuation did you use? &nbsp;What does it tell the reader?</p><p>Lottie was able to answer most of these questions articulately and accurately by the end of this session.</p><p>SCORE reading of Tests 112, 120, 124 were mostly accurate with developing fluency. Test 129 with introduction of CCVC words was less accurate. &nbsp;Repeat these pages next lesson.</p><p>Provided a pacer/mechanical pencil for Lottie to use today. &nbsp;It had a positive impact on her writing, but she chose not to use it after a while - perhaps because she presses hard and the lead snapped a few times. &nbsp;I will encourage this again next lesson.</p>', NULL, NULL, '2022-08-12 10:40:26', '2022-08-12 11:11:29'),
(2924, '2022/08/12', '02:27 pm', '3', '3', 'Molly  Jackson', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms (include purpose - to connect speech sounds to their written symbol which helps with reading, writing and spelling)', 'Oral Phonogram Review (OPR) - Various Phonograms (see notes)', 'Neve Mitchell', 'Achieved', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-08-12 14:27:01', '2022-08-12 14:56:22'),
(2925, '2022/08/12', '03:43 pm', '2', '10', 'Finn Mackey', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Language Rules (Pronunciation/Spelling/Grammar)', 'Various rules (see notes)', 'See notes', 'Laree Thorsby', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Make up class &nbsp;completed on Aug 12th</p><ol><li>Spell check &nbsp;representing presentation &nbsp;prequalifying &nbsp;spacious &nbsp;disqualification &nbsp;expansion explosion predetermined contentedly dissatisfaction</li><li>Include discussion on meaning and POS</li><li>Continue writing task. Narrative with selected starters for beginning and final sentences.</li></ol>', NULL, '2022-08-12 15:43:05', '2022-08-15 21:00:11'),
(2926, '2022/08/12', '04:24 pm', '3', '3', 'Nate Betros', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms (include purpose - to connect speech sounds to their written symbol which helps with reading, writing and spelling)', 'Oral Phonogram Review (OPR) - Various Phonograms (see notes)', 'Neve Mitchell', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-08-12 16:24:55', '2022-08-12 16:34:31'),
(2927, '2022/08/12', '03:50 pm', '3', '3', 'Connor Thompson ', 'Mathematics', 'Pythagoras and Trigonometry', 'Trig ratios SOH CAH TOA', 'TEXT BOOK - EXERCISES, QUESTIONS, ACTIVITIES', 'Neve Mitchell', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Tardy', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Maths -- Trigonometery Worksheet.</td></tr><tr><td>Pythagoras\' theorum &amp; SOHCAHTOA revision, mostly. Connor did say that he was having trouble because he hadn\'t seen either of them in a while.</td></tr><tr><td>It was a little disheartening as we basically went right back to the start, and had already covered this at one time. Some of Connor\'s worksheet problems were completed correctly, some incorrectly, though it was hard to tell because he didn\'t have his working out. Connor was okay at these problems but struggled when he had to identify how to solve them, or when he had to complete an action/problem BEFORE solving the given problem. E.g. Using Pythag to solve the length of a side before able to use Trig to find angle.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-08-12 16:27:04', '2022-08-19 16:38:46'),
(2928, '2022/08/13', '11:55 am', '3', '3', 'Jacob Tipping', 'Mathematics', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Ivan Botero', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-08-13 11:55:12', '2022-08-13 11:55:12'),
(2929, '2022/08/15', '07:31 am', '3', '4', 'Darcy Callaghan', 'English', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Campbell Jepson', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-08-15 07:31:38', '2022-08-15 07:31:38'),
