(2931, '2022/08/15', '08:50 am', '3', '4', 'Lewis Prevost', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Delete syllable from three syllable word - Kilpatrick Level E', 'Ellie Connor', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week Four, Lesson One</td></tr><tr><td>Monday, 15 August 2022</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Syllables, sounds: ago, old, bad, red, of, be</td></tr><tr><td>PA: continue PAST</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>OPR: a g qu ay ai oy oi er</td></tr><tr><td>WPR: assessment 1-30</td></tr><tr><td>Recap spiel - sounds to communicate, syllables are the beats in a word (used analogy of building blocks)</td></tr><tr><td>Syllable types - open, closed, consonant+le, sfe. ta, nur, bea, treme, now, glean, leve, -ble, ish, -tle, ver, tir, nu, fen, ma, taw, nice, roog, nave, sor, der, nea, mo, pu, -zle, cup, dos, -dle, port, cham</td></tr><tr><td>Sort syllable type magnets</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Home support pack</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Prompting with the difference between syllables and sounds - i.e. physical prompt of holding hand under chin for syllables. Otherwise, LP was really good with initial phonological awareness activity! We did one more PAST box, which he found difficult but did a great job with - some prompting from EC. EC modelled all OPR phonos first, then LP was able to give sounds for them all and provide cues. Did WPR assessment on 1-30 and saw a massive improvement. Lewis was confident, engaged and focused on his work. He got all 30 phonos correct with minimal prompting (I helped with \'v\' and prompted \'k\' i.e. \"tall letter\"), and his handwriting was super accurate and neat. I praised him heaps and we looked at today\'s assessment alongside the ones from 2020 and 2021. Lewis was really happy and felt proud of himself! Finished the lesson by talking about syllables and introducing the 4x syllable types. LP initially struggled to ID the difference between open and closed sounds (esp. with confusion between letter names and sounds), but once he nailed this he was really onto it. Sorted a few syllable types together before we packed up. Will revisit on Thurs. Lewis and Alysia have been doing heaps of work at home with spelling and PA, and it sounds like its going really well for them.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week Four, Lesson One</td></tr><tr><td>Monday, 15 August 2022</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', '2022-08-15 08:50:06', '2022-09-14 16:37:05'),
