(2933, '2022/08/15', '02:47 pm', '3', '4', 'Luna Shapiro', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms (include purpose - to connect speech sounds to their written symbol which helps with reading, writing and spelling)', 'Oral Phonogram Review (OPR) - Various Phonograms (see notes)', 'Neve Mitchell', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>PA: Kilaptrick G2</td></tr><tr><td>\"Fan… or… fanor… fan…or…for!\"</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>DBG -- Sound out words. LS: What way does it start from?</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Intro first sounds: er ck ch ed oo&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>OPR: 1-8, sh th ee ow oo ch er ck ed</td></tr><tr><td>WPR: 1-8</td></tr><tr><td>HF: Introduce to jumping letters!</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Handwriting game/instruction with jumping letters.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p>Notes:</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>B and D reversals/mix ups when sounding and writing today.</td></tr><tr><td>Promised Luna a game if she could prove to me that she knew her 2 o\'clock letters, which she did! Her writing was so beautiful and she even had her letters a respectable size and between the lines.&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-08-15 14:47:07', '2022-08-15 15:44:56'),
(2934, '2022/08/15', '03:26 pm', '3', '3', 'Jacob Tipping', 'English', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Juno Galang', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-08-15 15:26:09', '2022-08-15 15:26:09'),
(2935, '2022/08/15', '03:26 pm', '3', '4', 'Mia Harvey', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms (include purpose - to connect speech sounds to their written symbol which helps with reading, writing and spelling)', 'Oral Phongram Review (OPR) - Cards 1 > 30', 'Yina Peng', 'Achieved', 'Achieved', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Thomas has been a bit overactive during our session lately. He usually can\'t sit properly and make noise and Mia can be a bit distracted by this. They usually share quite well togetehr yet they can be too competitive with each other, which sometimes can tend to be not nice to each other. They both get better when I remind them to be friendly.&nbsp;</p><p>Kilpattrick F with timer</p><p>OPR/WPR i, a, v, l, u, b, ch, c, ar, g. Both of them need more work on the phonogram u.&nbsp;</p><p>rule 7: sfe activity. They can concentrate better now. We introduced all five jobs for silent final e. Thomas usually tends to learn faster yet he does not retain the knowledge very well, and Mia can be slow when understanding new knowledge yet she can remeber them better.&nbsp;</p><p>SD: sfe</p>', NULL, '2022-08-15 15:26:50', '2022-08-17 09:35:35'),
(2936, '2022/08/15', '03:27 pm', '3', '2', 'Archie Seelig', 'Mathematics', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Madeleine Foster', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-08-15 15:27:28', '2022-08-15 15:27:28'),
(2937, '2022/08/15', '03:29 pm', '3', '4', 'Thomas Johnson', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Language Rules (Pronunciation/Spelling/Grammar)', 'Rule 7: There are five jobs for a silent final \'e\'', 'Spelling Notebook - Rule Page 1', 'Yina Peng', 'Achieved', 'Achieved', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Thomas has been a bit overactive during our session lately. He usually can\'t sit properly and make noise and Mia can be a bit distracted by this. They usually share quite well togetehr yet they can be too competitive with each other, which sometimes can tend to be not nice to each other. They both get better when I remind them to be friendly.&nbsp;</p><p>Kilpattrick F with timer</p><p>OPR/WPR i, a, v, l, u, b, ch, c, ar, g. Both of them need more work on the phonogram u.&nbsp;</p><p>rule 7: sfe activity. They can concentrate better now. We introduced all five jobs for silent final e. Thomas usually tends to learn faster yet he does not retain the knowledge very well, and Mia can be slow when understanding new knowledge yet she can remeber them better.&nbsp;</p><p>SD: sfe</p>', NULL, '2022-08-15 15:29:02', '2022-08-17 09:36:16'),
(2938, '2022/08/15', '03:29 pm', '3', '4', 'Connor McLaren', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Substitute onset & rime - Kilpatrick Level G', 'Ellie Connor', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p><strong>Connor &amp; Lachlan (4pm – 4:30pm)&nbsp;</strong></p><p>Connor (3:30pm – 4pm)</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td><strong>Phonological Awareness</strong></td><td><i>restrain (2,7)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;royal (2,4)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;object (2,6)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; pleasure (2,6)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; navy (2,4)</i></td><td>ü</td></tr><tr><td>Phonemic Awareness</td><td>Kilpatrick G2</td><td>ü</td></tr><tr><td>Morphemic Awareness</td><td>Donah #30</td><td>ü</td></tr><tr><td>Challenge Word</td><td>Say, base word, syllables, prefixes/suffixes - objection ject = to throw (eject) something that is thrown against – e.g. in court “objection!”</td><td>ü</td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Phonics:</strong>&nbsp;</p><p>OPR/WPR</p></td><td>Assessments</td><td>ü</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p><strong>Connor:&nbsp;</strong>Did phonological then phonemic awareness, Donah and challenge word. No issues with these activities, Connor needed heavy prompting with challenge word but was able to create meaning from the info I gave him. Completed OPR &amp; WPR assessments (all 70 phonos), and Connor did a great job. Almost all OPR were correct, but WPR was evidently more challenging. We need to work on: ck, j, n/ng/gn/kn, au/aw/or, ui/ew, si, ey, a, oo, ey, our</p><p>Together – Writing &amp; composition, mental actions and reading</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Writing:</strong>&nbsp;</p><p>Sentence Structures</p></td><td>Recap sentence structures (booklet)</td><td>ü</td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Reading:</strong>&nbsp;</p><p>Mental actions &amp; comprehension</p></td><td><p>Recap mental actions &amp; text structures (boys to work together and sort magnets)&nbsp;</p><p>NM inference passage</p><ul><li>Discuss infer vs. imply</li><li>Read passage and work through mental actions<ul><li><strong>Monitor comprehension</strong></li><li><strong>Make connections</strong> – Narnia, playing hide and seek as a kid, fox fur at antique shop</li><li><strong>Predict</strong> – character</li><li><strong>Reformat</strong> – identify key words</li><li><strong>Mentally summarise</strong> – summarise passage in one sentence</li></ul></li></ul></td><td>&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p><strong>Connor &amp; Lachlan:&nbsp;</strong>Looked at the sentence structure workbook with both boys. Took us the whole half hour to get through the first page. Even though I’ve done sentence structure to death with both boys, neither were very confident or automatic with their responses. Lachlan hardly offered any input, and was fiddling with his pencil the whole time, or groaning about how bored he was. Confirmed that my decision to split the boys was the correct one.</p><p>&nbsp;</p>', '<p>Started half hour crossover this week - Connor from 3:30pm, Lachlan from 4pm</p>', '2022-08-15 15:29:39', '2022-09-17 15:53:00'),
(2939, '2022/08/15', '03:31 pm', '3', '2', 'Seth Vanderlaan', 'English', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Campbell Jepson', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-08-15 15:31:49', '2022-08-15 15:31:49'),
(2940, '2022/08/15', '03:35 pm', '3', '4', 'Elsa Clennet', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms (include purpose - to connect speech sounds to their written symbol which helps with reading, writing and spelling)', 'Oral Phonogram Review (OPR) - Various Phonograms (see notes)', 'Neve Mitchell', 'Achieved', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>PA: Kilpatrick Level I</td></tr><tr><td>Although Elsa struggled a little when we did a \'spot check\' last week, these were too easy for her today.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR: 46-70</td></tr><tr><td>WPR: ur ch qu ar au er eigh ci ti</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Rule review: 4 11 28 29 17</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD: pressure-secret</td></tr><tr><td>Read R&amp;S</td></tr><tr><td>Explain/discuss the markings and meanings of analysed words.</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Rule Intro: NA</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Writing Process: Continue composing first draft of informative text.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p>Notes:</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Aimed to finish Elsa\'s informative draft so that we can spend some time revising and editing next week, and then publish! I gave her time to work indepently on this as per her request. For next lesson I may transcribe her work onto my laptop so we can edit/publish a digital copy.</td></tr><tr><td>After this focus has finished, continue with notes from last week (reproduced here):&nbsp; prepare her for developing her referencing and bibliography skills. Perhaps some source analysis/using primary evidence in her work</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-08-15 15:35:53', '2022-08-15 16:25:43'),
(2941, '2022/08/15', '04:26 pm', '3', '4', 'Arki Young', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms (include purpose - to connect speech sounds to their written symbol which helps with reading, writing and spelling)', 'Oral Phonogram Review (OPR) - Various Phonograms (see notes)', 'Neve Mitchell', 'Achieved', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Arki found the phonograms a little tricky when shuffled.&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>OPR: 27-70 shuffled</td></tr><tr><td>WPR: ea ph oi eigh ai th or er&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Rule review: 4 6 11&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD: strange-uncle</td></tr><tr><td>Read R&amp;S</td></tr><tr><td>Explain/discuss the markings and meanings of analysed words.</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Rule Intro: NA</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Compose sentences using Ayres words to demonstrate differences in meaning for homophones ate/eight. Arki initially showed some confusion with ate during SD -- \"I thought it was e/a/t -- no, that\'s eat.\"</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Writing Process: Review Arki\'s plan from W2 for his nuclear power paragraph/short essay. Begin composition. Arki showed some great initiative during the planning stage, including mapping out an essay map after he had numbered his points in a logical order (inserting the introduction and conclusion into the map)</td></tr><tr><td>We discussed how Arki would like to write this short essay -- dictation (through the computer or to me), handwritten, etc -- but Arki asked if he could type it (on my laptop) as a way of practicing his typing skills. Arki had about fifteen minutes to do so, and got about 2 sentences written. He remarked that it was quite hard to word things whilst also typing, but insightfully added that he could refine his work during the editing stage. I\'m unsure what the focus should be here -- I want him to develop his typing skills, but feel like that could happen at home &amp; we could focus more on composition in our lessons. May chat to Na.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Side Note -- Saw and spoke to Claire on Friday morning due to my being at AR when Lottie had her lesson. She was very appreciative and said Arki is loving the \"blend\" of school/explicit literacy that we are working with at the moment: \"He\'s finally seeing and understanding why he\'s been doing tutoring fo rall these years.\" &lt;3</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-08-15 16:26:44', '2022-08-16 15:44:17'),
(2942, '2022/08/15', '04:34 pm', '3', '4', 'Arlo Clark', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Language Rules (Pronunciation/Spelling/Grammar)', 'Rule 4: vowels a, e, o, u say their second (long) sound at the end of a syllable', 'Spelling Notebook - Rule Page 1', 'Yina Peng', 'Achieved', 'Achieved', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Arlo understands and masters rule slowly and he has been struggling with rule 4. We will need to do more activities for this and might not rush into many rules so far.&nbsp;</p><p>He usually needs one small break during the session and another game at the end of the session.&nbsp;</p><p>Kilpattrick F1</p><p>OPR/WPR: h, e, y, ou, w, u, l, a, s . Arlo is a bit shaky at phonograms e and u,</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>morphology activity 2. He is getting the picture of compound words but still needs help with breaking them down.&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>rule review: rule 4. He couldn\'t remember this rule..&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD: he, you, we, up, last,</td></tr><tr><td>SD words sentence. Arlo made a great simple sentence yet his spelling is not very good yet. frend-friend.&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-08-15 16:34:31', '2022-08-17 08:58:42'),
(2943, '2022/08/15', '09:07 pm', '3', '3', 'Andrew Allan', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Laree Thorsby', NULL, NULL, 'Rescheduled', 'N/A', 'To Be Completed', 'To Be Assigned', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Scheduled for 2/9/22 but Andrew did not show. Laree contacted John who advised he forgot to cancel. Andfrew is unwell. Lesson forfeited.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-08-15 21:08:06', '2022-09-02 21:13:26'),
