(2955, '2022/08/17', '08:43 am', '3', '4', 'Luke  Vandenberg', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Language Rules (Pronunciation/Spelling/Grammar)', 'Rule 11: Drop the silent final \'e\' when adding a vowel ending/suffix', 'See Notes', 'Yina Peng', 'Achieved', 'Achieved', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Today is the first day that Callan and Luke having a paired lesson together. They were quiet at first yet after a soccer game together, they have been getting farmiliar with each other more and talk more to get to know each other. Callan is a very polite kid so at first he was quiet with Luke, yet Callan likes to talk to the tutor and he is quite expressive.&nbsp;</p><p>They both are in grade six. Callan is a bit behind compared to Luke. He needs help with phonograms from 35 to 65. Luke tends to be more competitive and Callan is a bit timid today. HOpefully they can get better.&nbsp;</p><p>Callan can usually sits longer yet Luke has to get up every ten minutes. So we had 2 soccer games today during our session and Callan was happy to join.&nbsp;</p><p>PA: Kilpatrick</p></td></tr><tr><td>i</td></tr><tr><td>OPR/WPR: igh, e, a, i, ai, ou, ng. Callan needed help with igh.&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD: flight, trav el, rap id, re pair, tou bling, trou ble. Callan write repar for repair during his sentence writing. It seems that we will need to help him with phonograms more and Luke needs more challenge.&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Read R&amp;S</td></tr><tr><td>Explain/discuss the meanings and word class of analysed words.</td></tr><tr><td><p>write a compound sentence with sd words and find verbs. Callan was quite good at this and he found parts of speech easily. yet Luke was distracted by his soccer and wrote a simple setence.&nbsp;</p><p>online verb game for Callan.&nbsp;</p><p>Writing activity introduction. Callan introduced his character to Luke as well as the writing backgrounds.&nbsp;</p><p>Lastly, I don\'t feel Luke and Callan is a good pair from their levels and interests, but I will have a chat with their parents as well as Juno next week and see if we can try one more week to see how it goes.&nbsp;</p></td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-08-17 08:43:47', '2022-08-17 09:29:54'),
(2956, '2022/08/17', '08:58 am', '3', '4', 'Brock Smith', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Language Rules (Pronunciation/Spelling/Grammar)', 'Rule 30:  w may make an \'a\' say /o/ or an \'o\' say /u/', 'See Notes', 'Yina Peng', 'Achieved', 'Achieved', 'Attended Tardy', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Brock did a hard work today and he got better at learning during the session. He usually shows less interest in things &nbsp;but he follows steps very well for tasks.&nbsp;</p><p>Kilpatrick H1</p><p>OPR/WPR: u, y, ch, ai, ea, th, ear, o, er. He is a bit shaky at the phonogram ea.&nbsp;</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>rule review rule 6, 29, new rule 30</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD: rule car ry, chain, death, learn, won der. nSince we start to read out loud rules for review and then use them in spelling dictation, Brock shows less frustration and does better for word analysis.</td></tr><tr><td>read for spelling</td></tr><tr><td><p>read for reading</p><p>online adj game. He has mastered adjectives and can easily find all adjectives, yet he can sometimes confuse verbs with adjectives.&nbsp;</p><p>Writing: Monster writing: editing and publishing. Brock really liked editing his errors in his writing.&nbsp;</p></td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-08-17 08:59:39', '2022-08-17 09:06:56'),
(2957, '2022/08/17', '09:02 am', '3', '5', 'Archie Smith', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Will Hughes', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Tardy', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p><strong>AS 17/8/22</strong></p><p>Kilpattrick Level K1 Challenge Words no.3 and no.4</p><p>Donah #23</p><p>OPR/WPR: th, ie, ci, gu, ng, ur, ar, ai, ea, wr, ee</p><p>Break</p><p>Introduce Rule 10: Words of 2 syllables in which the second syllable is stressed, if the second syllable has 1 vowel followed by 1 consonant, double the consonant before adding the vowel ending:</p><p>i.e. be gin + ner</p><p>SD(o-p): appreciate, thief, surface, sweeping, waist, waste, waiting, weary, write, writing</p><p>Break</p><p>3 related sentences, each using two words</p><p>Challenge word: familiar&nbsp;</p><p>Base word: family</p><p>(rule 24: when adding an ending to a word that ends with a consonant ‘y’, change the ‘y’ to ‘i’: family)&nbsp;</p><p>1 above first a for first sound</p><p>Open/close syllables</p><p>ORF 512-IN (need to photocopy)</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Archie smashed through donah and the OPR/WPR, struggled a bit on the challenge words. Archie even requested we do phonogram ‘ough’ as he remembered the 6 sounds – he nailed it, after previously struggling with it. Archie understood Rule 10, and also did very well in his spelling. We briefly introduced rule 24, and jobs of silent final ‘e’. We will revisit these later. Archie struggled with reading, which is understandable as we started a new, more difficult one. He is about the level we are doing.</p>', NULL, '2022-08-17 09:02:49', '2022-08-17 09:03:14'),
(2958, '2022/08/17', '09:07 am', '3', '4', 'Callum Coulson', 'English', 'Writing - High Frequency Vocabulary + Sentence Construction', 'Elements of a compound sentence > Capital letter, two independent clauses joined by a coordinating conjunction (FANBOYS), ending punctuation', 'Articulate/Explain the elements of a compound sentence (include use of manipulatives)', 'Yina Peng', 'Achieved', 'Achieved', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>kilpatrick F1. We might have to bring more challenge for callum for this activity.&nbsp;</p><p>OPR/WPR: ou, ai, s, ea, a, igh, o, a, c, l. Callum has been quite good at his phonograms. Compared to the beginning, Callum now can say all sounds in a row at once and he has mastered most of the phonograms.&nbsp;</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>SD: moun tain, speak, past, might, contract, deal. Callum was struggling to spell words with phonograms we have learned. He needs to practice the application of phonograms in specific words and be able to break a word down into parts.&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td><p>read for spelling and reading;</p><p>write a compound sentence with SD words and analyze parts of speech. He did well here.&nbsp;</p></td></tr><tr><td>writing process step 1. I will need to discuss about this with Callum and help him with his school writing.&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-08-17 09:09:13', '2022-08-17 09:17:53'),
(2959, '2022/08/17', '01:50 pm', '3', '4', 'Eleanor  Stam', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Language Rules (Pronunciation/Spelling/Grammar)', 'Rule 5: i and y may say their second (long) sound at the end of a syllable', 'See Notes', 'Laree Thorsby', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Tardy', 'Not Returned', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>T1W4</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Challenge words on board. Find base word and suffix.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Smiling &nbsp;swimmer grated&nbsp; funnily (E)</p><p>Making skipped squeezing happily (A)&nbsp;</p><p>OPR/WPR</p><p>Au aw wr r wh w o ee e ea ei ey ai ay eigh a u igh y I&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Rule review: Rule 4/5/6</p><p>Vowel sounds at end of syllables + y at end of words.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Identify word and sort into a/e/i/y/o/u/</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Formalise Rule 5 Using i/y words from Rule 4/5 box.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Sentences</p><p>Write 2 simple related sentences using rule 5/6 words.</p><p>Join with a fanboys to write a compound sentence.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Write a compound sentence using 2 i/y words</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>OF 111 High Heels practice read.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Game Spin a star.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-08-17 13:50:47', '2022-08-17 14:55:40'),
