(2974, '2022/08/17', '06:33 pm', '3', '4', 'Finn McKenzie', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms (include purpose - to connect speech sounds to their written symbol which helps with reading, writing and spelling)', 'Oral Phonogram Review (OPR) - Various Phonograms (see notes)', 'Neve Mitchell', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'To Be Assigned', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR: 27-63</td></tr><tr><td>WPR: ed aii ck ea ou er igh ough ng th gu</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Rule intro: 19 21</td></tr><tr><td>Rule review: 21 19 17 4</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD: might-of</td></tr><tr><td>Read R&amp;S</td></tr><tr><td>Explain/discuss the markings and meanings of analysed words.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Review: A clause is a group of words. There are two types of clauses. We call them IC and DC. Think about the word Independent, what does it mean? An independent clause makes sense by itself. A dependent clause doesn\'t make sense by itself. We looked at some IC and DCs last week, here they are. We discovered that each of the DCs has a word that makes the clause dependent. This is called a subbie.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Sentence structure: Compose complex sentence following IC;DC structure. Coach as needed.</td></tr><tr><td>Sentence Structure: Compose DC;IC complex sentences and coach as needed. Ask student to begin their sentence with a SUBBIE, and the complex sentence structure will naturally follow. Colour code and model on SBB.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Pretty good lesson with Finn, he\'s fairly quick off the mark. He said he had no trouble with the homework and I have reminded him/his mum to send me a photo of the work he has completed, as I have asked Namidja twice now via email with no response. Finn appeared tired today but was generally okay with most concepts. We have ticked off complex sentences. I would still like to have him regularly writing/articulating compound and complex sentences when using Ayres words, but can hopefully now retreat to a scaffolding role.</td></tr><tr><td>May now be looking at reading comprehension activities, starting with Key Into Inference activities to get a gauge of where he is.</td></tr><tr><td>I also would like to issue some \"rules quizzes\" to see whether I can move him up from introduced to mastered for some. Finn did comment that he has trouble remembering the rule numbers, though I assured him that was okay.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-08-17 18:34:33', '2022-08-17 18:38:02'),
(2975, '2022/08/18', '07:49 am', '3', '3', 'Chester  Vincent', 'English', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Campbell Jepson', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-08-18 07:49:43', '2022-08-18 07:49:43'),
(2976, '2022/08/18', '08:45 am', '3', '4', 'Lewis Prevost', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Delete syllable from three syllable word - Kilpatrick Level E', 'Ellie Connor', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week Four, Lesson Two</td></tr><tr><td>Thursday, 18 August 2022</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>PA: continue PAST</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR: 30-60</td></tr><tr><td>WPR: assessment 30-60</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Review rules 4, 19. Dictate: ago, old, bad</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Home support pack</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>I was really impressed with Lewis\' focus and determination this lesson. He was really excited to tell me about a movie he\'d seen, so it took a while for him to settle into our activities initially. Once we did get into it, though, he worked really hard. Found PAST activity difficult, but persevered and was able to provide all correct responses with minimal prompting (some finger scaffolding provided). Did OPR with phonos 30-60, and while LP did need some help with cues, he was fine with sounds of pretty much all phonos. Really struggled with WPR assessment. LP didn\'t want to make a mistake, and really wanted to write the correct answer, so I helped him with most of the phonos. I noticed that he reversed a lot of letters, and used critical thinking to work out what some phonos were - e.g. if it \"can\'t go\", it must have an \'i\' or \'u\' at the end. I was impressed with his perseverance and rationalisation. He didn\'t get upset once, even though he struggled with pretty much all 30 of the phonos assessed today. This assessment didn\'t match the OPR one we did recently, where he was able to identify sounds for 41 of the 60 introduced phonos. This discrepancy fits with recent dyslexia diagnosis. LP struggles to recall written phonos to match the sounds (and letters in the right order), probably hence why his reading (decoding) is stronger than his spelling (encoding). Will continue to focus on this. Finished the last 10 minutes with a word dictation, and LP was suprisingly enthusiastic about this? He was excited to provide answers about syllables and sounds, and correct handwriting formation. We had a good discussion about rules 4 and 19 before doing our three words. Lewis was concerned about the accuracy and neatness of his writing, and fixed errors without prompting from me (e.g rubbing out an underline made in error). I was so impressed with him, and made sure that he grabbed a choccie at the end of the session. He was like a different kid!</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week Four, Lesson Two</td></tr><tr><td>Thursday, 18 August 2022</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', '2022-08-18 08:45:13', '2022-09-17 16:22:27'),
