(2979, '2022/08/18', '03:29 pm', '3', '4', 'James  Coleman', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Substitute onset & rime - Kilpatrick Level G', 'Ellie Connor', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week Four</td></tr><tr><td>Thursday, 18 August 2022</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>PA: Kilpatrick</td></tr><tr><td>MA: Donah #29</td></tr><tr><td>James did an amazing job with PA &amp; MA today - sped through it!</td></tr><tr><td>Challenge word: discussion</td></tr><tr><td>Base word, suffix, what changes when I add a suffix?</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR/WPR: wr oa ay oe ey gn ie dge ei eigh ti ci si</td></tr><tr><td>Struggled with ey (hesitated to think) but got there independently.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Rule Review: 13 and 14, intro rule 15</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD: rule page 6 - si (1st sound) words</td></tr><tr><td>Read S&amp;R</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Need to work on: wr wor aw au or oa ay oe ey gn ie dge ei eigh</td></tr><tr><td>Rule 14 cut and paste words - syllabication</td></tr><tr><td>JC did a good job today, focusing nicely. No issues with PA or MA, good convo around challenge word, and pretty good with phonos. James was able to recap rules 13 and 14 (with coaching), and picked up rule 15 relatively quickly. We got through all the first sound \'si\' words today, and James was able to ID markings and sounds easily, accurately reading for spelling and reading. He was a bit confused by the base word si words (i.e. using si because base word has an \'s\' where it changes) and needed some help in syllabifying his homework words, but on the whole I was really impressed with how he worked.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week Four</td></tr><tr><td>Thursday, 18 August 2022</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', '2022-08-18 15:29:14', '2022-09-17 12:41:46'),
(2980, '2022/08/18', '03:30 pm', '3', '3', 'Reuben Shelverton', 'English', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Juno Galang', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-08-18 15:30:28', '2022-08-18 15:30:28'),
(2981, '2022/08/18', '03:37 pm', '3', '4', 'Cara Lashmar', 'English', 'Reading - Comprehension > Text Type & Mental Actions', 'Mental Actions of Reading', 'Make connections with prior knowledge, within the text, and with other texts to infer word meanings, topic, cause and effect', 'Laree Thorsby', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>We continued on with our analysis of the language used in Macbeth. We are focussing on the scenes sent by her teacher Peta. See below from the email...&nbsp;</p><p>This week we are starting our work on looking at the imagery in ‘Macbeth’. To begin with we are looking at how select pieces of imagery tell us more about the character Macbeth (file named ‘Macbeth’s Imagery Quotes’).</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Then we are focusing on particular scenes (which I’ve attached), and are breaking them down so that students work in groups to analyse sections of the scenes and don’t have to look at them all. The main focus here is to link the imagery to the character and make connections across scenes to see how the changes in similar imagery indicate a change in the character’s mindset.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Cara has so far been good at identifying examples of figurative language but could use some guidance around identifying the layers of meaning within them.</p><p>&nbsp;This week we watched a video Act 2 scene 5? Read a modern translation and then identified the imagery in both. Cara found this much easier as she understood the language and was readily able to identify and examine the imagery for meaning rather than just seeing it at face value.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-08-18 15:37:46', '2022-08-25 15:23:28'),
(2982, '2022/08/18', '04:21 pm', '3', '4', 'Finn Mackey', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics & Morphology - The Vocabulary of Word Structure', 'Suffix - letters added to the end of base words or word roots to create new words > they have their own meaning & they change the meaning of the base word or root word - Suffixes cannot stand/be used alone', 'Spell words with suffixes indicating part of speech > y/er/en/ful/ion/ance/ence (tion)', 'Laree Thorsby', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Finn had completely rewritten his narrative during the week. He removed dialogue and cemented the storyline.&nbsp;</p><ol><li>Revise sentence structure.</li><li>Edit for spelling.</li><li>Plan for how the story will proceed and for a clear ending.</li></ol><p>Suffixes:</p><ol><li>complete the worksheet where no rules apply</li><li>spell check on these words.</li><li>Spell check on words using tion sion cion&nbsp;</li></ol><p>HW: final chpter of story. Suffixes worksheet.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-08-18 16:21:04', '2022-08-23 15:03:16'),
(2983, '2022/08/18', '04:31 pm', '3', '7', 'Samuel Lamont', 'English', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Campbell Jepson', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-08-18 16:31:14', '2022-08-18 16:31:14'),
(2984, '2022/08/18', '04:32 pm', '3', '4', 'Chelsea Cooper', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Substitute onset & rime - Kilpatrick Level G', 'Ellie Connor', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week Four</td></tr><tr><td>Thursday, 18 August 2022</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>PA: Kilpatrick G2</td></tr><tr><td>MA: Donah #29</td></tr><tr><td>Chels did really well! Persevered with challenging PA, but Donah almost too easy.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR/WPR: wr oa ay oe ey gn ie dge ei eigh ti ci si</td></tr><tr><td>Really struggled. One round with me modelling and Chelsea repeating, then with me coaching, and then scaffolding! CC struggled with cues, and sounds of especially ey ie eigh oe.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Rule Review: 13 and 14</td></tr><tr><td>SD: Rule page 6 - ti words</td></tr><tr><td>Read S&amp;R</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Rabbit thing</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Homework template 1 using \'ti\' words</td></tr><tr><td>This was a really challenging lesson for Chelsea, but I was impressed with how she persevered. Understood rule 13 and 14, good convos about these rules. Fine with SD words but struggled especially with sounding first syllable of \'torrential\' - /t/ /o/ /r/ instead of /t/ /or/. She got a little frustrated here and seemed to start to get upset. After doing the SD on the rule page, we finished with a game.&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week Four</td></tr><tr><td>Thursday, 18 August 2022</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', '2022-08-18 16:32:30', '2022-09-17 12:58:16'),
(2985, '2022/08/18', '04:47 pm', '3', '4', 'Callisto Pratten', 'Mathematics', 'Patterns & Algebra', 'Extend and apply the laws and properties of arithmetic to algebraic terms and expressions', 'Text book - Exercises, Questions, Activities', 'Rosemary Beswick', 'Achieved', 'Achieved', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', '<p>Callisto has a Maths test on Sequences and Series tomorrow and so we spent an extra half an hour today and used past exams to revise for the test. Callisto is reasonably confident with most aspects of this topic. She needed occasional prompts with the formatting of difference equations.</p>', NULL, NULL, '2022-08-18 16:47:10', '2022-08-18 18:25:01'),
(2986, '2022/08/18', '08:42 pm', '3', '3', 'Lucy Fairbrother', 'Mathematics', 'Number & Place Value', 'Mental Computation', 'Mad Minute Maths - Facts to 100', 'Naomi Wright', 'Not Yet', NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', '<p>Lucy was quite confounded during MMM today. &nbsp;She was able only to complete two equations accurately. &nbsp;Worked on a strategy for solving a division by turning it into a multiplication. &nbsp;Eg &nbsp;72/12= &gt; X x 12 = 72. &nbsp;Substitute 12 for 10 to make an initial estimate easier. &nbsp;Process = 7 x 10 = 72 &gt; # too large. &nbsp;6 x 10 = 60. &nbsp;Closer, so let\'s see what happens. &nbsp;6x11=66…getting closer. &nbsp;6 x 12 = 72. &nbsp;Only had to add 6 then add 6 again. &nbsp;Another strategy Lucy can use to make connections between number facts and reverse operations for problem solving.</p><p>One of Lucy\'s tasks today was to justify her answer to two problems she solved for Key Math Measurement, Concept Cluster 6, Lesson 2, Guided Practice. &nbsp;Discussed strategies including draw an image, incorporate each fact in the image, tick off each fact in the worded problem, use symbols (+ and &lt;) to reformat worded information, use image to explain solution. &nbsp;Much critical thinking was required to solve each layer of these problems as Lucy made connections between the information provided and the problem solving strategies.</p><p>Reviewed greatest common factors in context of equivalent fractions by recording a prompt. &nbsp;Eg: ½ x 2/2 = 2/4 or 3/6 divided by 3 = ½. &nbsp;</p><p>Removed scaffold to continue same - simplify and expand given fractions.&nbsp;</p><p>5/10 &gt; ID GCF &gt; Simplify &gt; ½. &nbsp;Leaving out the / prompt in the middle was most challenging for Lucy as she processed the equation mentally and then made a choice about which value she was recording - the divisor or the answer. &nbsp;She needed to think very deliberately throughout this process, but was self correcting some errors in the final portion of the task. &nbsp;Revisit this task next lesson.</p><p>Lucy advised that she achieved a ‘High\' grade in an algebra test she had at school this week. &nbsp;She notes she was just three marks off an ‘Outstanding’. &nbsp;This is such wonderful news.</p>', NULL, '<p>Lucy was absent last week due to illness. &nbsp;Two lessons to be caught up. &nbsp;Aim for one at 4:00 on Tuesday 23/08/2022 at AR Kingston office.</p>', '2022-08-18 20:42:43', '2022-08-18 21:00:58'),
(2987, '2022/08/19', '07:49 am', '3', '4', 'Archie Lester', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - High Frequency Vocabulary', 'Analysis of word structure and application of learned concepts (sounds, phonograms, rules)', 'Challenge Word Analysis - Record and label syllables, markings and rules + discuss morphemes', 'Naomi Wright', 'In Progress', NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', '<p>Today\'s challenge words: &nbsp;excitable and noticeable. &nbsp;Review last week\'s learning. &nbsp;Deep discussion on base words, sounds and rules in each word. &nbsp;Use in an oral sentence.</p><p>Kilpatrick Section J Set 3 and Mixed Level pate 193.</p><p>Morpheme reviews covered: Prefixes - un, re, over, under, up, out. &nbsp;Suffixes - ing, s, ed, ful, less + all associated rules.</p><p>Spelling Dictation Words using Morphemes: unkind, return, overheat, outback, underneath, uphold, speaking, students, landed, joyfulness, hopeless. (Cue-in words: mess r.17, helpful r.22, jumped r.28, beyond r.4, mind r.19, rock r.25 and associated markings.)</p><p>Sentences Dictated: Noun of Direct Address - If you leave the mild in the car on a sunny day, it\'ll overheat.&nbsp;</p><p>Complex - To maintain your integrity in the workplace, you must uphold the standards of your profession.&nbsp;</p><p>Appositive - I would like to return to the outback, the vast open spaces, and the joyful experience of being beneath its grand blue skies.</p><p>Analysed sentences to identify exclamatory type, complex structure, appositive phrase and noun of direct address. &nbsp;Also discuss contraction ‘it will &gt; it’ll\' reflecting how we speak, and identify morphemes in selected words. &nbsp;Ask comprehension questions for selected words. &nbsp;</p>', NULL, NULL, '2022-08-19 07:49:05', '2022-08-19 09:36:52'),
(2988, '2022/08/19', '02:28 pm', '3', '4', 'Molly  Jackson', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Manipulate (delete or substitute) second phoneme in initial blend - Kilpatrick Level K', 'Neve Mitchell', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>&nbsp;Segment/count/blend: swim, twist, clip, basket, strange</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR: 50-70</td></tr><tr><td>WPR: ng ey er ck sh ai ea or dge ed ph&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Read R&amp;S: Current Ayres Column</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Rule review: 9 6&nbsp; 29 25 13</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD: fence-letters</td></tr><tr><td>Read R&amp;S</td></tr><tr><td>Explain/discuss the markings and meanings of analysed words.</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Rule Intro: NA</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Sentence Structure: Use Ayres words in sentences. ID structure/type and colour code necessary elements.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p>Notes</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Molly made a couple of phonological errors, some due to just uncertainty. Separating the consonant blends in our PA activity was tricky for her. She also made a couple of errors in spelling that showed she wasn\'t /really/ thinking, e.g. \"What\'s the Job of SFe here (3)\" MJ: \"Making the n say it\'s name?\"</td></tr><tr><td>Molly also made a couple of concerning comments: \"I\'m so dumb, I feel stupid,\" but completely brushed me off when I tried to talk about it. She would talk over me, \"Okay, okay, okay, let\'s just move on!!!\".&nbsp; I did speak to Ashley about bullying a week or two ago, and he says it\'s being taken care of -- I wonder if that\'s the source for Molly\'s uncertainty.</td></tr><tr><td>She also had trouble connecting the sound and symbol. I\'m stuck because everytime I try to talk about the sound and symbol connection she talks over me like above, and asking her to focus or get frustrated makes her so upset that it\'s impossible for her to then absorb information.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-08-19 14:28:31', '2022-08-19 16:01:29'),
