(3015, '2022/08/22', '03:36 pm', '3', '5', 'Elsa Clennet', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Delete final sound in word or final blend - Kilpatrick Level I', 'Neve Mitchell', 'Achieved', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>PA: Kilpatrick Level I</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR:&nbsp; 45-70</td></tr><tr><td>WPR: ar eigh ci ti ough ou ee ch ea</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Rule review: 4 2 5 6 14</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD: similar-steak</td></tr><tr><td>Read R&amp;S</td></tr><tr><td>Explain/discuss the markings and meanings of analysed words.</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Rule Intro: NA</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Sentence Structure: Use Ayres words in sentences.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Review Elsa\'s informative draft in her book -- curious to see if she picks up on some of her spelling errors and can correct them (a couple of rules I know she knows and can apply:e.g.&nbsp; 2, 24).</td></tr><tr><td>Edit Elsa\'s paragraph digitally/on my computer. Revise word choice where needed and discuss purpose of rewording sections/sentences -- ask questions such as, who is the audience? What type of text is this (Elsa was initially thinking of a BTN style bulletin -- does that change the language and formality of our tone?)</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p>Notes:</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Elsa did well today. A very standard lesson, she didn\'t pick up on many of her errors when reading back through her work, but was okay about correcting them when they were identified with Word\'s spell check function.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-08-22 15:36:57', '2022-08-22 17:46:05'),
(3016, '2022/08/22', '03:45 pm', '3', '5', 'Connor McLaren', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Substitute onset & rime - Kilpatrick Level G', 'Ellie Connor', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Connor (3:30pm – 4pm)</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td><strong>Phonological Awareness</strong></td><td>forty (2/4), population (4/9), judge (1/3), weather (2/4)</td><td>ü</td></tr><tr><td>Phonemic Awareness</td><td>Kilpatrick G2</td><td>ü</td></tr><tr><td>Morphemic Awareness</td><td>Donah #32</td><td>ü</td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Phonics:</strong>&nbsp;</p><p>OPR/WPR</p></td><td>ng gn kn n ea th or our er dge aw au</td><td>ü</td></tr><tr><td>Handwriting</td><td>Focus on baseline</td><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>High Frequency Vocab:</strong></p><p>Read for spelling &amp; reading</p></td><td><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Read for S&amp;R last week’s words (restrain – navy)&nbsp;</p></td><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Rule Review</td><td><p>Rules 6, 4, 14, 23</p><p>baby, nation, dodge</p></td><td>ü</td></tr><tr><td>Spelling Dictation</td><td><i>Sec O:&nbsp; forty, fourteen, fourth, four, population, proper, judge, weather, whether</i></td><td>ü</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p><strong>Connor:&nbsp;</strong>Latest MM (May 2022) placed CM at Section S</p><p>Connor arrived a little late today, so we only got around 15-20 minutes of individual time. Moved quickly through PA, MA and phonos, and started looking at cue words when Lachlan arrived. Connor was nicely settled today, staying in his seat and engaging in the lesson well, but did need some prompting to allow Lachlan a chance to respond (partly because Lachlan was quiet and reluctant).</p><p><strong>Connor &amp; Lachlan (4pm – 4:30pm)&nbsp;</strong></p><p>Together – Writing &amp; composition, mental actions and reading</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Writing:</strong>&nbsp;</p><p>Sentence Structures</p></td><td><p>Recap sentence structures (booklet)</p><p>Simple sentences:&nbsp;</p><p>Write me a simple declarative sentence using the word “judge” as a verb.</p><p>Mark the three levels of sentence structure on given sentences</p></td><td>ü</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p><strong>Connor &amp; Lachlan:&nbsp;</strong>Boys did well with SD words. Handwriting for both was dreadful, and we might need to go back to placing a stronger focus on letter formation during WPR and SD. Lachlan would rush his words, and just had no desire to go back and fix them. Connor wasn’t as bad once I asked him to focus on his handwriting, but the size of his letters can sometimes be far too big. Lachlan was working really slowly and seemed disengaged – wasn’t bothering to try and answer my questions, possibly because he knew Connor would answer quickly. Finished SD words and asked the boys to do a sentence writing task. Lachlan was resistant and needed lots of prompting. Connor was eager to get going but gave me a sentence using ‘judge’ as a noun to start with. He tweaked it slightly and was able to self-correct his error when he realised. I worked one-on-one with Lachlan to help him write his sentence as he was quite disengaged. Played a game of Uno before Connor left.</p>', '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week Five</td></tr><tr><td>Monday, 22 August 2022</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', '2022-08-22 15:45:06', '2022-09-17 16:07:37'),
(3017, '2022/08/22', '04:01 pm', '3', '4', 'Lachlan  Smith', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Substitute onset & rime - Kilpatrick Level G', 'Ellie Connor', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p><strong>Connor &amp; Lachlan (4pm – 4:30pm)&nbsp;</strong></p><p>Together – Writing &amp; composition, mental actions and reading</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Writing:</strong>&nbsp;</p><p>Sentence Structures</p></td><td>Recap sentence structures (booklet)</td><td>ü</td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Reading:</strong>&nbsp;</p><p>Mental actions &amp; comprehension</p></td><td><p>Recap mental actions &amp; text structures (boys to work together and sort magnets)&nbsp;</p><p>NM inference passage</p><ul><li>Discuss infer vs. imply</li><li>Read passage and work through mental actions<ul><li><strong>Monitor comprehension</strong></li><li><strong>Make connections</strong> – Narnia, playing hide and seek as a kid, fox fur at antique shop</li><li><strong>Predict</strong> – character</li><li><strong>Reformat</strong> – identify key words</li><li><strong>Mentally summarise</strong> – summarise passage in one sentence</li></ul></li></ul></td><td>&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p><strong>Connor &amp; Lachlan:&nbsp;</strong>Looked at the sentence structure workbook with both boys. Took us the whole half hour to get through the first page. Even though I’ve done sentence structure to death with both boys, neither were very confident or automatic with their responses. Lachlan hardly offered any input, and was fiddling with his pencil the whole time, or groaning about how bored he was. Confirmed that my decision to split the boys was the correct one.</p><p><strong>Lachlan (4:30pm – 5pm) – possibly assessments?</strong></p><p>Lachlan: needs to do SA spelling, Wadd reading and Wadd speling</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td><strong>Phonological Awareness</strong></td><td><i>restrain (2,7)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;royal (2,4)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;object (2,6)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; pleasure (2,6)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; navy (2,4)</i></td><td>ü</td></tr><tr><td>Phonemic Awareness</td><td>Kilpatrick G2</td><td>ü</td></tr><tr><td>Morphemic Awareness</td><td>Donah #32</td><td>ü</td></tr><tr><td>Challenge Word</td><td>Say, base word, syllables, prefixes/suffixes – population – state of being. Populate = to live/inhabit (VERB) therefore population = noun of those who live/inhabit</td><td>ü</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p><strong>Lachlan:&nbsp;</strong>Worked through same activities that Connor and I did: phonological then phonemic awareness, Donah and a different challenge word. Lachlan reluctant to give responses, needed a lot of prompting and scaffolding. Completed OPR 1-70 assessment, and Lachlan got all 70 oral phonograms correct! Then did WPR - Lachlan was definitely not very engaged in this task and it became clear that it was a lot more challenging for him. Need to work on: x, ou, er x5 (even though all correct), au/aw, dge, gn/kn, ey, ar</p>', '<p>Started half hour crossover this week - Connor from 3:30pm, Lachlan from 4pm</p>', '2022-08-22 16:01:04', '2022-09-17 15:51:16'),
(3018, '2022/08/22', '04:20 pm', '3', '5', 'Arki Young', 'English', 'Writing - Paragraph & Composition Construction', 'Paragraphs - Two or more sentences about a topic presented in a logical order of ideas with appropriate indentations and margins', 'Articulate the meaning of paragraph, list attributes & explain conventions', 'Neve Mitchell', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Arki\'s assignment from school required him to write some \"TEEL\" paragraphs, which Arki asked me to walk him through. Together we went through some slides on Canvas provided by Arki\'s teacher (from a lesson?) and we brainstormed some examples for each aspect of the paragraph.</td></tr><tr><td>We then talked through Arki\'s assignment and identified what he needed to do.</td></tr><tr><td>Created a plan on the whiteboard for Arki\'s first TEEL paragraph, which Arki said was helpful.</td></tr><tr><td>He then asked if we could create a plan for his second paragraph so that he had scaffolds to work off at home. The second paragraph required us to talk a little more about literary devices, as the question was about the setting reflecting an aspect of the novel. We talked a little about what this might mean and how we could talk about it in the paragraph.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-08-22 16:20:35', '2022-08-22 18:15:06'),
(3019, '2022/08/22', '04:32 pm', '3', '5', 'Arlo Clark', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Language Rules (Pronunciation/Spelling/Grammar)', 'Rule 4: vowels a, e, o, u say their second (long) sound at the end of a syllable', 'See Notes', 'Yina Peng', 'Achieved', 'Achieved', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Kilpatrick f</p><p>OPR/WPR:o, u, s, a, oo, g, d &nbsp; &nbsp;Arlo struggles with retainning of knowledge. He has been shaky at the sounds of the phonograms a, u, and oo. He cannot remember phonogram oo.He usually concentrate very well yet he absorb things slowly and need repeats.<br>Handwriting focus: clockface letter s. Arlo loves coloring and he is great at it.</p><p><br>rule review: rule 4. We did colour code activity(pink book page 1) to help him master this rule.&nbsp;<br>SD: &nbsp;not, us, am, good.&nbsp;<br>Sentences: Arlo was required to write a sentence with 2 of the SD words.&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-08-22 16:32:05', '2022-08-24 07:26:12'),
(3020, '2022/08/22', '04:33 pm', '3', '3', 'Angus Singleton', 'Mathematics', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Campbell Jepson', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-08-22 16:33:01', '2022-08-22 16:33:01'),
(3021, '2022/08/22', '05:29 pm', '3', '5', 'Lucy Crosswell', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms (include purpose - to connect speech sounds to their written symbol which helps with reading, writing and spelling)', 'Oral Phonogram Review (OPR) - Various Phonograms (see notes)', 'Neve Mitchell', 'Achieved', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>PA: Kilpatrick G1</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR: 1-8, 27-38</td></tr><tr><td>WPR: c a g ow ou th ee ai ay ar</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Rule 4 review by creating a rule card. Spelling dictate a few clue/reference words: baby open me emu</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Not completed:</td></tr><tr><td>SD: Rule Page 1: Vowel sounds/Rule 4 -- set up</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Use Ayres words in a sentence.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>I\'ve noticed I need to change my wording for Lucy a fair bit. E.g. \"last letter in a syllable, strongest sound (rather than second sound/name).\" She also responded better to clapping out syllable rather than the standard hand movement.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-08-22 17:29:33', '2022-08-22 18:45:10'),
(3022, '2022/08/22', '05:44 pm', '3', '5', 'Luna Shapiro', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Neve Mitchell', NULL, NULL, 'Rescheduled', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Rescheduled 30 Aug</td></tr><tr><td>PA: Kilpatrick G2 -- tricky for Luna, very hit or miss. I think it\'s the concept but I haven\'t found an explanation that works for her.</td></tr><tr><td>Word recognition: Fitzroy flashcards -- okay, a couple of errors and questions such as: which way do I read it? B/D mix ups.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR: 1-8,b h k m n p r sh th ee ow oo ch er ck ed</td></tr><tr><td>WPR: g o h n r p sh ch&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Luna asked \"Can I see the card please?\" for sh and ch</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Fitzroy #5</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Rule review: N/A</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD: hen pet&nbsp; vet&nbsp; fox had&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Read R&amp;S</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Oral Fluency: Fitzroy 5</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>SCORE</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>This was a morning session and Luna seemed much more focused with her energy! I think she could sustain an hour in the morning -- even Luna said so, although with the aim of wanting to keep colouring in.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-08-22 17:44:41', '2022-09-13 16:50:44'),
(3023, '2022/08/22', '06:07 pm', '3', '5', 'Callisto Pratten', 'Mathematics', 'Data Representation and Interpretation', 'Read, organise & represent data', 'Discussion & Practise (on board/in book)', 'Rosemary Beswick', 'Achieved', 'Achieved', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'Followup', '<p>Callisto\'s class started a new unit of work on Bivariate Data today when she was absent from class. We worked very quickly through Set 1 of the book which is a review of linear equations. We then moved on to having a look at Scatter Plots and drawing lines of best fit by eye and finding the equation to the line of best fit.</p>', NULL, NULL, '2022-08-22 18:08:25', '2022-08-22 18:15:29'),
(3024, '2022/08/23', '09:23 am', '3', '5', 'Henry  Badock', 'Mathematics', 'Number & Place Value', 'Mental Computation', 'Mad Minute Maths - Facts to 30', 'Laree Thorsby', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>T3W5</p><p>Henry began quite oppositional and took time to warm up. Eventually cooperated when reminded there would not be time for a game.&nbsp;</p><ol><li>Mental Computation using number facts to 30. encouraging recognising friends of ten.</li></ol><p>Henry can do so up to 20 but does not recognise these beyond that. he does not consistently use chunking to 10 to assist. Focussed on chunking to 10 with addition.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><ol><li>.Addition and subtraction worksheets from text. Henry happy to complete these. Now articulates and demonstrates he must start at the units column. It is noted he very explicitly said allowed whether the problem was an add or takeaway.&nbsp;</li></ol><p>&nbsp;</p><ol><li>Multiplication with manipulatives.&nbsp;</li></ol><p>Same activity as last week. Pegs and cups in various groups on table . Emphasis on no answers required.&nbsp;Read the task, demo the task, write the task in booklet.&nbsp;</p><p>Henry was focused on getting the answer. He could not focus on one task with other tasks set up beside him. Present one at a time and use a different format. – This week I asked Henry to demo the task himself using manipulatives. He engaged immediately and completed it all without an issue.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>4. Bucket toss using counters to represent a value of 5/10. Writing scores on board as multiplication.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-08-23 09:23:24', '2022-08-23 14:42:14'),
(3025, '2022/08/23', '02:43 pm', '3', '5', 'Esther Mclver', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Laree Thorsby', NULL, NULL, 'Cancelled - No Show', 'N/A', 'Cancelled', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Esther absent. no catch up.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-08-23 14:44:20', '2022-08-23 14:45:47');
INSERT INTO `attens` (`id`, `date_created`, `time`, `term`, `lesson`, `student_name`, `subject_name`, `concept_name`, `conceptDetail`, `learningActivity`, `tutor_name`, `tutor_evaluation`, `student_self`, `student_attendance`, `homework_completed`, `weekly_lesson`, `homework_assignment`, `email_school`, `comment`, `commentPrivate`, `notesAttendance`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(3026, '2022/08/23', '02:46 pm', '3', '4', 'Esther Mclver', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Language Rules (Pronunciation/Spelling/Grammar)', 'Rule 11: Drop the silent final \'e\' when adding a vowel ending/suffix', 'Spelling Notebook - Rule Page 4', 'Laree Thorsby', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Tardy', 'Not Returned', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>T3 W4&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>OPR&nbsp; vowels ch ck k sh ow ou ng ed ee ea</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>formally added 4th sound to O</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Rule Review:&nbsp; &amp; SD</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>establish Rule 11 and do rule page.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Writing:</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Complex sentences model with blocks –&nbsp;</p><p>Practice verbal sentences when given a DC</p><p>Practice verbally IC + DC</p><p>Practice reversing.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Essie picked this up very quickly.</p><p>Focus – language: subbie, IC, DC, POS.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Reading – OF 112 N 1 min 0 errors, 0 sc, 97/97 words</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>HW&nbsp; Sentences Complex&nbsp; - language of and examples.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-08-23 14:47:24', '2022-08-23 14:49:36'),
(3027, '2022/08/23', '02:51 pm', '3', '4', 'Andrew Allan', 'English', 'Writing - High Frequency Vocabulary + Sentence Construction', 'Elements of a compound sentence > Capital letter, two independent clauses joined by a coordinating conjunction (FANBOYS), ending punctuation', 'Recognise/Analyse/Model/Compose compound sentences that include subject nouns/pronouns and coordinating conjunctions for, and, nor, but, or, yet, so (FANBOYS)', 'Laree Thorsby', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'Not Returned', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>T3 W4&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>OPR&nbsp; vowels&nbsp;</p><p>WPR vowels au aw ti ci si ough gn gu o ew ui</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Sect H&nbsp; man men have run ran&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Writing:</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Simple sentences using work sheet and chart. Match subject with verb.&nbsp;</p><p>Compound sentences model with blocks</p><p>Join 2 simple sentences together using and.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Focus – language: subject noun, verb, object noun plus adjectives, capital. Full stop. FANBOYS – Andrew familiar with these.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Write one sentence in workbook following the model.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Reading 1000 animal facts&nbsp;</p><p>Rule practice: GAME&nbsp;</p><p>Rule 4 connect 4&nbsp; – Andrew can consistently articulate this rule.&nbsp;</p><p>HW&nbsp; Read about t-rex</p>', NULL, '2022-08-23 14:52:24', '2022-08-23 14:55:39'),
(3028, '2022/08/23', '03:31 pm', '3', '5', 'Brock Smith', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Language Rules (Pronunciation/Spelling/Grammar)', 'Rule 31: \'l\' may change the sound of \'a\' and \'o\'', 'See Notes', 'Yina Peng', 'Achieved', 'Achieved', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Brock has been asking to make the lessons more fun.He complains that he has been studying 6 hours at school and he wants our one hour to be more playful and fun. He enjoys doing the parts of speech games yet he does not want to do any more tasks. He shuts down when he feels any challenge these days. He does not have much passion to learn.&nbsp;</p><p>Kilpatrick H1<br>OPR/WPR: ai, r, ea, a, ch, e, ck, o, ear. He has no problems with these and we will need to reduce times for phonograms.<br><br>rule review rule 25,rule 32</p><p>SD: pair, pear, pare, check, prove, heard, hear<br>read for spelling<br>read for reading&nbsp;<br>write a sd compound sentence and color code pronoun. Brock struggles to make up sentences that make sense logically yet his compound sentence has the correct structure.&nbsp;<br>online pronoun game&nbsp;<br>Writing: publishing. He did not want anyone see his writing so we put it in his folder.&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-08-23 15:31:45', '2022-08-24 08:58:18'),
(3029, '2022/08/23', '03:31 pm', '3', '5', 'Sophie Mirowski', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms (include purpose - to connect speech sounds to their written symbol which helps with reading, writing and spelling)', 'Oral Phonogram Review (OPR) - Various Phonograms (see notes)', 'Neve Mitchell', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>PA: Kilpatrick H</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR: 50-70</td></tr><tr><td>WPR: er th ough or ea</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Rule review: 29 26 4 4</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD: himself-or</td></tr><tr><td>Read R&amp;S</td></tr><tr><td>Explain/discuss the markings and meanings of analysed words.</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Rule Intro: NA</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Sophie was very chatty today, perhaps because I haven\'t seen her in a couple of weeks? She just could NOT stop talking -- interrupting me and herself to jump onto her next story. When I could get her to focus she did well. I would still like us to be getting through more a lesson, and I\'m very conscious that I feel our hour isn\'t being used effectively/to its full potential.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-08-23 15:32:29', '2022-08-30 16:50:21'),
(3030, '2022/08/23', '04:28 pm', '3', '5', 'Callum Coulson', 'English', 'Writing - High Frequency Vocabulary + Parts of Speech', 'Verbs - doing, linking, helping', 'See Notes', 'Yina Peng', 'Achieved', 'Achieved', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>kilpatrick i<br>OPR/WPR: a, o, s, r, ough, i, ng, e, Callum is getting so much better at phonograms. He is not farmiliar with the written form of phonogram ough.&nbsp;<br><br>rule review4, 17, 21, 19, 31`<br>SD: all, al most, brought, bring, less, e vent, off, of<br>read for spelling and reading; &nbsp; &nbsp; understanding words and word class; He has mastered nound and verb. &nbsp;&nbsp;<br>write a compound sentence with sd words, find the adj. Callum was struggling with compound sentence writing. His sentence did not make sense logically. We need to write paragraghs and analyze sentence structures in there.&nbsp;</p><p><br>writing process step 1. Callum has being collecting background information for gis paragrgh writing.&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-08-23 16:28:20', '2022-08-24 09:12:25'),
