(3051, '2022/08/24', '05:34 pm', '3', '5', 'Finn McKenzie', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms (include purpose - to connect speech sounds to their written symbol which helps with reading, writing and spelling)', 'Oral Phonogram Review (OPR) - Various Phonograms (see notes)', 'Neve Mitchell', 'Achieved', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-08-24 17:34:37', '2022-08-24 18:29:55'),
(3052, '2022/08/25', '08:53 am', '3', '5', 'Lewis Prevost', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Delete syllable from three syllable word - Kilpatrick Level E', 'Ellie Connor', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week Five, Lesson Two</td></tr><tr><td>Thursday, 25 August 2022</td></tr><tr><td>NW relief</td></tr><tr><td>PA: red (1/3), of (1/2), be (1/2), but (1/3), this (1/3) (syllables / sounds)</td></tr><tr><td>PA: Kilpatrick E2 set 3</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR/WPR: e th s ou ar ch ed ow ea</td></tr><tr><td>Will likely need prompting for WPR, which is fine (delayed feedback). Focus is on handwriting (sitting on baseline and short letters half-sized, tall letters tall)</td></tr><tr><td>Recap of syllable types - Closed Syllables - red, prod, bent, vict, am, hit, trav, and Open Syllables so, tu, de, se, flu, fro, tri (reinforce Rule 4)</td></tr><tr><td>Rule 4</td></tr><tr><td>Dictate: red, of, be, but, this</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Home support pack</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Phonemic Awareness: red, of, be, but, this<br>&nbsp;<br>Phonological Awareness: Kilpatrick Level E2, Set 3. Lewis initially had difficulty deleting the /s/ as part of the first syllable in \'distraction\', but after breaking the word into distinct syllables with a corresponding fist scaffold, Lewis was able to delete this initial syllable accurately.<br>&nbsp;<br>Oral Phonogram Review: ea, s, ow, ou, th, ch, ar, e, ed - focused on clear pronunciation and racing through and blending sounds<br>&nbsp;<br>Written Phonogram Review: Base line focus.&nbsp; &nbsp;All phonograms listed above.&nbsp; &nbsp;Delayed feedback.&nbsp; I made some intentional errors after saying, \"Let\'s see if I get them right.\"&nbsp; Lewis needed prompting to notice my \'errors\'.<br>&nbsp;<br>Spelling Dictation: red, of, be, bee, but, this, is. Lewis initially noted that he and Ellie roll a dice to find out how many words will be dictated.&nbsp; I suggested we do the for words Ellie had left for us. Lewis rolled the dice and was more than happy for it to land on \'5\'. When writing \'be\', Lewis recorded \'bee\'.&nbsp; Prompting needed to record \'be\' as per scaffold (prompting needed to look at fingers and make connection with number of letters required), and then recorded \'bee\' and bracketed the two words.&nbsp; Talked about the bracket showing a relationship or connection.&nbsp; What is the connection?&nbsp; \"They have the same [letters] but one has the digraph.\"&nbsp;<br>Lewis also added the word \'is\' making a connection to \'this\' and initiated marking with a bracket.&nbsp; Discussed the marking of a letter not saying it’s usual sounds with a double underline, the marking for Rule 4, second sound of /th/, and second sound of /s/. Lewis was quick to make connections on several levels during this task, explaining that \"Ellie has already taught me that,\" and \"Lots of the things you\'re teaching me, Ellie has already told me.\"<br>&nbsp;<br>Read for spelling and read for reading.<br>&nbsp;<br>Syllables: Syllable Plus sorting activity – Lewis was unable to articulate the meaning of a closed or open syllable. Using the Syllable Plus magnet strip, I placed an asterisk above \'closed\' and \'open\' as the two types of syllables we would be focusing on today, and recorded the word consonant and vowel at the top of each as I explained that a closed syllable ends with a consonant sound and an open syllable ends with a vowel sound. Lewis sounded each given syllable, identified the final sound as consonant or vowel and then placed the magnet beneath the corresponding heading. Lewis picked this up very quickly and was easily able to identify these two syllable types by the end of the session.&nbsp; This was a good opportunity to notice vowels saying their second sound at the end of the syllable – Rule 4.&nbsp; We finished with reading for spelling.<br>&nbsp;<br>It was apparent today that Lewis relies on segmenting before being able to blend/read an unfamiliar syllable or word.<br>&nbsp;<br>Lewis began the lesson being quite active, interested in Marley and other items in the room.&nbsp; He appeared unable to remain seated or standing at the desk and would frequently move away and around the room in the middle of an oral activity or conversation. I encouraged Lewis to remain at the table during activities and that after each activity we could chat and he could leave the table. Only a couple of reminders were needed for him to settle which in turn supported his concentration.&nbsp; Lewis appeared eager to produce quality writing and articulately made many connections with concepts that he has been taught in the past.<br>&nbsp;<br>For Lewis’ next lesson, I would recommend repeating the Syllable Plus work today and perhaps adding in the c+le and the SFe syllable types.&nbsp; I notice he’s looked at SFe, so this might be another positive connection for him to make.&nbsp; I would also recommend returning to last lesson’s dictated words to identify syllable types.&nbsp; We didn’t get to do that but might be a useful segue from last lesson to next.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week Five, Lesson Two</td></tr><tr><td>Thursday, 25 August 2022</td></tr><tr><td>NW relief</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', '2022-08-25 08:53:03', '2022-09-17 16:24:25'),
