(3056, '2022/08/25', '03:34 pm', '3', '5', 'Lucy Fairbrother', 'Mathematics', 'Measurement', 'Solve problems involving the comparison of lengths and areas using appropriate units', 'Text book - Exercises, Questions, Activities', 'Naomi Wright', 'In Progress', NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', '<p>Worked on measurement problems from NSPM Level 3 p 123 and 124. &nbsp;Lucy had some difficulty with converting metres to centimetres in order to accurately solve worded problems. &nbsp;She was also unsure about the conversion of 3640m to km. &nbsp;Discussed that the question was asking for conversion to km and m, so she just needed to take the 3000m out of the total to make 3km and leave the rest as they were given in metres.&nbsp;</p><p>Key Math plotting points on a grid - review Cluster 1, Lesson 3, Level 2 and complete cluster 1, Lesson 3, Guided Practice. &nbsp;Lucy was completely independent with this task.</p><p>Moved on to Numeration Concept Cluster 1, Lesson 2, Activity 1, 2, &nbsp;in which Lucy was required to identify a number close to the given number. &nbsp;She had some hesitancy with this task initially, however, this grew to Lucy withdrawing and saying, “I don\'t know.” &nbsp;I talked her through the task of finding the value of the gap between the first two numbers in the number pattern 675, 700, 725 and to calculate the value of the next number in the pattern. &nbsp;I stepped this working right back to counting in groups of five to find the initial gap (Lucy\'s suggestion), however, she then couldn\'t work out the total number of groups she had counted and the value of those groups. &nbsp;See working on the back of the practice page. &nbsp;</p><p>Calculating the value of the next number was difficult for Lucy when attempting this in a horizontal equation. &nbsp;I recorded O T H above the digits to help her work out the value of each column (which she has done with numbers in the tens and one-hundreds, however, she was completely unable to do this today. There had been nothing remarkable about the lesson up to this point.</p><p>Lucy\'s mum mentioned that she is worried that dyscalculia will prevent Lucy from ever being able to develop the skills she needs to perform mental arithmetic at this level. &nbsp;It is interesting timing that this is a present concern for her and that it is the next skill to be covered in the Key Maths response to her assessment. &nbsp;When offered a chocolate on the way out the door, Lucy declined and walked quickly away from her mum and I clearly very upset. &nbsp;See text message to Lynette.</p><p>Lynette subsequently called and noted that Lucy cried all the way home and that she had hugs with Lynette and told her it was nothing Lynette had said that caused her to feel upset. Lucy has not identified what upset her. &nbsp;I wonder if the level of mental computation required for this task was too much at this time and past vulnerabilities were triggered. &nbsp;Given Lucy is doing so well in maths at school and at tutoring, this may have been a big disappointment for her.</p><p>Going forward, construct a lesson based on the Essentials Resource curriculum (see photos on phone) and integrate these skills in Lucy\'s workbook. &nbsp;Lynette encouraged me not to mention today, and I won\'t use the same resource that might trigger a response to this experience.</p>', NULL, '<p>Note that today\'s lesson is the 5th scheduled lesson. &nbsp;The lesson for Tuesday 23/08/2022 was a catch up for Week 3 when Lucy was away and unwell.</p>', '2022-08-25 15:34:46', '2022-08-25 19:15:38'),
