(3060, '2022/08/25', '04:33 pm', '3', '5', 'Chelsea Cooper', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Substitute onset & rime - Kilpatrick Level G', 'Ellie Connor', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week Five</td></tr><tr><td>Thursday, 25 August 2022</td></tr><tr><td>EC away - NW relief</td></tr><tr><td>PA: Kilpatrick</td></tr><tr><td>MA: Donah #30</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Challenge word: torrential - no problems with this except didn\'t connect r.14 even after HW review.&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Chelsea to break into syllables, sound each syllable while writing (try to get her to do this independently) and mark.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Rule Review: 13 (tells us what we can\'t use), 14 (three options), intro rule 15 (narrows it down)</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD: rule page 6 - si (1st sound) words</td></tr><tr><td>Read S&amp;R</td></tr><tr><td>Review HW activities: Read list words for spelling and reading, discuss rules on syllabified words, correct \'confidential\' from noun to adjective, spelling quiz in back of HW book.&nbsp; &nbsp;Chelsea made a strong connection for r.29 on the double consonant words.&nbsp; They aren\'t all technically this rule, but because she had made a connection and was thinking about it, I didn\'t correct it. We can chat about this.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Separate out compression, discussion and depression into prefixes, base words and suffixes - sion turns verb into noun.&nbsp; &nbsp;Record in HW book.</td></tr><tr><td>Record dictated sentences for discussion, compression and session (see HW book).&nbsp; I had a discussion with my teacher.&nbsp; The compression in the cabin was low.&nbsp; The tutoring session is over.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Practice writing out today\'s \'si\' words in syllables placing particular emphasis on the /s/ at the end of the second syllable.&nbsp; &nbsp;Record each word in a sentence.</td></tr><tr><td>This lesson was fifteen minutes late starting as my previous student had become upset in our lesson.&nbsp; &nbsp;Chelsea wasn\'t very conversational, so bad combination of new tutor and late start.&nbsp; She was so lovely about the prior upset though.&nbsp; She said, \"Was she doing maths?&nbsp; I get upset with maths too.\"&nbsp; I also couldn\'t find Chelsea\'s folder (Do I need new glasses?), so we did our work in her HW book.&nbsp; I\'m so sorry!&nbsp; I hope it doesn\'t matter.&nbsp; I was totally disarmed by my previous lesson, so this was not my finest hour, but we covered a fair bit (just not all of what was planned!)&nbsp; I noted that Chelsea had significant difficulty making connections between the HW words and recognising that they were all r.14.&nbsp; &nbsp;Even at the point of the last word, she still needed prompting to recognise this commonality.&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week Five</td></tr><tr><td>Thursday, 25 August 2022</td></tr><tr><td>EC away - NW relief</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', '2022-08-25 16:33:19', '2022-09-17 12:59:45'),
(3061, '2022/08/26', '07:47 am', '3', '5', 'Archie Lester', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - High Frequency Vocabulary', 'Analysis of word structure and application of learned concepts (sounds, phonograms, rules)', 'Challenge Word Analysis - Record and label syllables, markings and rules + discuss morphemes', 'Naomi Wright', 'In Progress', NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', '<p>Challenge Word: reversible. &nbsp;Identify base word (reverse) to support recognition of Rule 11. &nbsp;Syllables, markings, rules, morphemes + their meanings + derived word.</p><p>Spell Check: &nbsp;Last week\'s affix words - answer check for understanding questions re base words, affixes, prefixes, suffixes, derived words, rules of base, rules for adding vowel and consonant suffixes. &nbsp;Archie able to answer most questions with confident accuracy. &nbsp;Only error on quiz was ‘hopeless’ which we talked through at length.</p><p>Improving Morphemic Awareness: #15.</p><p>Vowel Suffix Intro: est (super adjective) &gt; upgliding hand to an capital A, er (verb &gt; noun) &gt; V fingers to N sign language, y (in the character or like the base &gt; action of a palm + a palm (like a mirror), clap). &nbsp;Taught noun, verb, adjective and adverb hand signals.</p><p>Rule Page - Vowel Suffixes with marking and rule analysis.</p><p>Assistive Technology: Sense Lang Touch Typing, iPad and Word voice to text and read aloud functions.</p><p>See HW email.</p>', NULL, NULL, '2022-08-26 07:47:48', '2022-08-26 09:40:20'),
(3062, '2022/08/26', '03:30 pm', '3', '5', 'Molly  Jackson', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Manipulate (delete or substitute) second phoneme in initial blend - Kilpatrick Level K', 'Neve Mitchell', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Rescheduled', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Rescheduled to 17 Sep</td></tr><tr><td>PA: Kilpatrick K1</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;Segment/count/blend: finish, strength, cast, drift</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Spell Check: MM List 2 1-10</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR: 27-51</td></tr><tr><td>WPR: 27-50</td></tr><tr><td>Errors: oy ur aw or&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Rule review: 20 17 4 29</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD: trust-provide</td></tr><tr><td>Read R&amp;S</td></tr><tr><td>Explain/discuss the markings and meanings of analysed words.</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Rule Intro: NA</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Sentence Structure: Use Ayres words in sentences. ID structure/type and colour code necessary elements.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>A point of focus (maybe for homework?): \"ild\" spelling pattern -- child wild mild&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Molly was pretty much her usual self during this morning lesson! Very bubbly and excitable. She fared a little better than usual in spelling and was quite onto it with her rules, but it was the same kind of focus that she can employ on an afternoon, so I don\'t think the timing played much of a role.&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-08-26 15:30:05', '2022-09-14 09:26:44'),
(3063, '2022/08/26', '03:36 pm', '3', '5', 'Connor Thompson ', 'Mathematics', 'Linear & Non-Linear Relationships', 'Linear & Non-linear equations', 'School-assigned worksheet/task', 'Neve Mitchell', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Maths -- Connor\'s \"Online Maths\"</td></tr><tr><td>Worked through the problems assigned by Connor\'s teacher again. This set were predominately focused on filling in values tables. This was relatively easy drill work for Connor. The only thing we had to discuss was&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Connor had had the swimming carnival today and was in an unusual mood. He was quite cheerful but not at all prepared to learn. He was quite entertaining and funny, although it was a little frustrating that it took so long considering the type of work that it was.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Connor also pointed out that we should be working on a set that he was having trouble with. These questions again required Pythagoras (which Connor can do) but weren\'t obviously pythagoras questions (such as, find the interval between two points on a graph, requiring him to spot the triangle and then make the connection with his other knowledge of Pythagoras).</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p>Notes:</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Connor was very chatty this lesson, telling me all about his welding class at school. I think it was probably the most I\'ve ever heard Connor speak in one lesson. He spun me a yarn about blowing up the school with the welding equipment.</td></tr><tr><td>Connor was also doing things like: putting in random, very long equations into his calculator and reading out the equations, continuously talking to himself in a silly/exaggerated way (e.g. Woah! That\'s! A! Five!), showing me \"magic\" tricks (throwing the pen over his shoulder and making it disappear), speaking in different accents, mucking about on the wobble stool, generally being very expressive and talkative. It was very unusual!&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-08-26 15:36:21', '2022-08-26 16:29:07'),
