(3137, '2022/09/01', '04:30 pm', '3', '12', 'Samuel Lamont', 'English', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Campbell Jepson', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-09-01 16:30:42', '2022-09-01 16:30:42'),
(3138, '2022/09/01', '04:33 pm', '3', '6', 'Chelsea Cooper', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Substitute onset & rime - Kilpatrick Level G', 'Ellie Connor', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week Six</td></tr><tr><td>Thursday, 1 September 2022</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>PA: Kilpatrick</td></tr><tr><td>MA: Donah #31</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Challenge word: tension</td></tr><tr><td>VD: talk about morphemes as well as phonograms and markings</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR/WPR: wr oa ay oe ey gn ie dge ei eigh ti ci si</td></tr><tr><td>Prompting with ey, eigh, dge, ie</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Rule Review: 13, 14, 15 (intro r.16)</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD: rule page 6 - si (1st sound) words into rule page</td></tr><tr><td>Read S&amp;R</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Read a book</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>No hwk</td></tr><tr><td>CC needed some thinking time with some PA activities, but was mostly accurate. Did well with MA (prompting to articulate what a morpheme is) and challenge word. Good convo about challenge word morphology vs spelling. Pretty good with phonos, but needed prompting with a few. Able to articulate knowledge of rules 13-15 with some coaching. Needed a little help with her handwriting in SD (i.e. \'s\' way too big), but otherwise fine with the words and content. Did 3 x ORF and then Chels read some of her story to me.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week Six</td></tr><tr><td>Thursday, 1 September 2022</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', '2022-09-01 16:33:46', '2022-09-17 13:01:09'),
(3139, '2022/09/01', '06:29 pm', '3', '4', 'Angus Singleton', 'Mathematics', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Campbell Jepson', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-09-01 18:29:48', '2022-09-01 18:29:48'),
(3140, '2022/09/02', '07:48 am', '3', '6', 'Archie Lester', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - High Frequency Vocabulary', 'Analysis of word structure and application of learned concepts (sounds, phonograms, rules)', 'Challenge Word Analysis - Record and label syllables, markings and rules + discuss morphemes', 'Naomi Wright', 'In Progress', NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', '<p>During PA awareness today, two additional skills were tested. &nbsp;1) Did not require Archie to say the word before manipulating its sounds. &nbsp;Eg: &nbsp;The word is him - change /i/ to /e/. &nbsp;2) Gave Archie two words and he identified how the sounds had been manipulated. &nbsp;Eg: &nbsp;The words are rain and chain. &nbsp;“Changed the /r/ to /ch/. &nbsp;The words are fleet and flee. &nbsp;”Deleted the /t/.\" &nbsp;Archie found fleet/flee difficult and required scaffolding and prompting to identify that the /t/ had been deleted. &nbsp;He was also relying on letter placement and name instead of sounds. &nbsp;Eg: &nbsp;\"Changed the ‘O’ to an ‘A’. &nbsp;Encouraged Archie to think about the sounds that had changed and not the spelling of the word.</p><p>Morphology - Donah Activity Sixteen.</p><p>Oral and Written Morpheme Reviews: &nbsp;-er, -ly, -est, -es, -y, -tion, -sion, -ness</p><p>Introduce and explain Rules 13, 14, 15, 16 with examples. &nbsp;Review a second time. &nbsp;Ask check for understanding questions. &nbsp;</p><p>Rule Page 6 - Set up, discuss format and dictate - nation, infection, discussion, depression, facial, spacious</p><p>Survey of Morphemes in dictated words - record the analysed word, its morphemes (base and affixes) and the meaning for each. &nbsp;nation &gt; base = nat (born), suffix = ion (noun), infection &gt; prefix = in (into), base = fect (put), suffix = ion (noun). &nbsp;discussion &gt; base = discuss (talk/investigate), suffix = ion. &nbsp;compression &gt; prefix = com (together), press (push), ion (noun).</p>', NULL, NULL, '2022-09-02 07:48:34', '2022-09-02 09:44:52'),
(3141, '2022/09/02', '03:28 pm', '3', '6', 'Connor Thompson ', 'Mathematics', 'Linear & Non-Linear Relationships', 'Linear & Non-linear equations', 'School-assigned worksheet/task', 'Neve Mitchell', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Maths -- Connor\'s \"Online Maths\"</td></tr><tr><td>More problems that required two-step solutions, though Connor\'s familiarity with the problems worked in his favour and he seemed to find the tasks relatively simple to complete when they were the same type of problems that he had seen previously.</td></tr><tr><td>Connor\'s second module was finding the circumference of a circle. We had some trouble here. I initially couldn\'t tell if Connor didn\'t understand the concept or was being deliberately disruptive. When I asked if he would like me to talk about the circumference of a circle and what it means he said yes, so I now assume the former. I told Connor again that he can ask for further clarification whenever and doesn\'t need to wait for me to ask, because he knows better than me what concepts he would like help with.</td></tr><tr><td>In explaining circumference, I started with some perimetre talk. After my initial explanation (the perimetre is the name we give to the distance it would be to go around a shape -- with diagram and demonstration), Connor requested a more detailed explanation. I enacted a practical scenario involving the desk -- we measured the width and length of the desk, then worked out how much tape we would need to put around the outside of the desk. Connor then asked if we could do his unit on perimetre, so we switched to that.</td></tr><tr><td>Connor needed some help. Questions that again required a two-step process (such as converting some measurements from cm to m) were tricky. Connor seemed better and more accurate when focusing on applying just his knowledge of perimetre.</td></tr><tr><td>Connor needed (calculator) assistance with basic number facts, including addition 1-20 and subtraction 1-10. He did not immediately recognise \'friend of ten\' number pairs.&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Connor had difficulty with visual logic questions (e.g. when given an irregular shape with missing sides, that required him to work out the missing sides before finding the perimetre).</td></tr><tr><td>We also had trouble with the question: \"A square has a perimetre of 62, what is the side length?\". Connor seemed to have trouble conceptualising how to solve this problem. There may have been some genuine confusion, but after I explained and instructed him I\'m fairly confident he was messing with me. He repeatedly tried to figure out the side lengths by putting four random numbers in his calculator to see if they equalled 62, despite repeated instruction that a square has four equal sides.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-09-02 15:28:01', '2022-09-02 16:59:19'),
(3142, '2022/09/02', '03:31 pm', '3', '4', 'Freya McIver', 'Study Skills', 'Research', 'See Notes', 'See Notes...', 'Ellie Connor', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week Six, Lesson Four</td></tr><tr><td>Friday, 2 September 2022</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Freya brought along a CAT for HASS today, which is apparently a fairly major assignment. We decided that the most productive use of time was to plan all 3 tasks so that Freya has a solid structure after she leaves, and is able to use it to write the assignments in her own time. We managed to get through all three plans, and had really good coversation about all of them. Freya needed some prompting to think a little deeper about some questions e.g. she would list objective facts and I would need to prompt, okay, but why would those things make him popular? Good lesson.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week Six, Lesson Four</td></tr><tr><td>Friday, 2 September 2022</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', '2022-09-02 15:31:07', '2022-09-16 16:20:19'),
(3143, '2022/09/02', '03:33 pm', '3', '2', 'Harlow Booy', 'Mathematics', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Wright', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-09-02 15:33:03', '2022-09-02 15:33:03'),
(3144, '2022/09/02', '04:28 pm', '3', '6', 'Nate Betros', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms (include purpose - to connect speech sounds to their written symbol which helps with reading, writing and spelling)', 'Oral Phonogram Review (OPR) - Various Phonograms (see notes)', 'Neve Mitchell', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR: 27-50</td></tr><tr><td>WPR: ay th ng ee ow ou ai ar ea ough ei ie ey</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>PROMPT CARDS ON BOARD</td></tr><tr><td>Read R&amp;S: Current Ayres Column</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Rule review: 21 20</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD: itself-young</td></tr><tr><td>Read R&amp;S</td></tr><tr><td>Explain/discuss the markings and meanings of analysed words.</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Rule Intro: NA</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Sentence Structure: Use Ayres words in a group of 3 related sentences.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Oral Fluency: 215 -- read aloud at the start of the lesson. Nate had only practised at home once (contrary to my instructions) and I could tell when listening to him that by about halfway through, reading aloud extensively was affecting him (his voice was wobbly and uncertain, although he said he wasn\'t nervous).</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p>Notes:</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Nate was really good today with spelling! At the beginning of the spelling portion I asked what I was expecting to see, he told me a few things (neat handwriting, pointed at the example) and I noted a few others: not pressing too hard with pencil, letters all the same size, sitting on the base line, legible. Nate followed through on all accounts. He also did not fuss when I asked \"is that your neatest handwriting?\" and actually erased his work and tried again without comment. Very promising.&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-09-02 16:28:50', '2022-09-02 17:36:16'),
(3145, '2022/09/02', '04:42 pm', '3', '6', 'Callisto Pratten', 'Mathematics', 'Data Representation and Interpretation', 'Read, organise & represent data', 'Discussion & Practise (on board/in book)', 'Rosemary Beswick', 'Achieved', 'Achieved', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', '<p>Callisto has an assignment on Bivariate Data due on MOnday. We therefore worked on this. She needed very little intervention from me and was able to work quite independently on most tasks. This is a real positive as it shows the value of her more regular attendance at class recently.</p>', NULL, NULL, '2022-09-02 16:44:21', '2022-09-02 16:47:19');
