(3146, '2022/09/02', '09:13 pm', '3', '6', 'Andrew Allan', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Language Rules (Pronunciation/Spelling/Grammar)', 'Rule 7: There are five jobs for a silent final \'e\' > Job 1 - The \'e\' on the end makes the vowel say it\'s second (long) sound with a consonant in between', 'See Notes', 'Laree Thorsby', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', NULL, '<p><strong>T3W6</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>OPR</strong>&nbsp; vowels ough l f s z kn gn ew ui&nbsp; &nbsp;ea or aw au ay</p><p><strong>WPR</strong> vowels + above&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Rule review</strong></p><p>Game j1.</p><p>Lit tle j4. r.29</p><p>smell r.17</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Spelling Dictation</strong></p><p>ate (job 1.) ap ple&nbsp;r.29 (job 4.) au thor bread (2) fill r.17</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Writing</strong></p><p>Rule 17 Worksheet to complete</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Compound sentences using work sheet.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Focus</strong> – language: subject noun, verb, object noun plus adjectives, capital. Full stop.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Write one compound sentence in either story book or or work book about T-Rex. &nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Reading</strong></p><p>OF Fitzroy 41+&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Game</strong></p><p>Rule 4 connect 4&nbsp;</p><p><strong>HW</strong>&nbsp;</p><p>Complete Rule 17 sheet.</p><p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-09-02 21:14:39', '2022-09-02 21:16:22'),
(3147, '2022/09/03', '09:00 am', '3', '7', 'Archie Lester', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - High Frequency Vocabulary', 'Analysis of word structure and application of learned concepts (sounds, phonograms, rules)', 'Challenge Word Analysis - Record and label syllables, markings and rules + discuss morphemes', 'Naomi Wright', 'In Progress', NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', '<p>Repeat of yesterdays lesson structure including PA approach.</p><p>Review of rules 13, 14, 15, 16. &nbsp;</p><p>Dictate Rule Page 6 words - collection, potential, depression, session, occasion, explosion, (finance) financial, (music) musician. &nbsp;Check for understanding questions re rules, markings, morphemes.</p><p>Analysing bases and affixes + meanings of each. &nbsp;See practice page.</p><p>Introduced interjections (PPT slides) with associated punctuation marks and examples. &nbsp;Dictated following sentences for Archie to record and punctuate. &nbsp;Check for understanding questions re # of punctuation marks, the purpose of each punctuation mark, contractions, clauses, subject nouns, verbs and interjections.</p><ul><li>Wow, you have an enormous collection of marbles.</li><li>Oh dear. Even though the vet used chest compressions, he couldn\'t save the dying goat.</li><li>Hey, this room is really spacious, so we\'ll be able to fit all of the participants in without any problems.</li></ul><p>Checked in with Archie re Sense Lang Touch Typing practice at home. &nbsp;See new HW email.</p><p>Game of Quick Math (Beginner Addition) as a brain break from literacy as lesson ran for over 1.5 hours. &nbsp;Archie loved this app and wanted to continue playing. &nbsp;He reduced his time form 1m 41s to 50+s.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, NULL, '2022-09-03 09:00:46', '2022-09-03 13:23:42'),
(3148, '2022/09/03', '11:32 am', '3', '3', 'Lottie Young', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Substitute onset & rime - Kilpatrick Level G', 'Naomi Wright', 'Achieved', NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', '<p>Decoding consonant blends (Reading Link cards). &nbsp;Lottie read consonant blends with relative fluency - definite improvement on past performance. &nbsp;</p><p>SCORE Book 3 words need further practice. &nbsp;She is reversing p/b sounds and also sometimes adding a /p/ sound at the end of a word that ends with ‘m’.</p><p>Words analysed: &nbsp;rock, speck, brick, truck, block, pluck</p><p>Compound sentence construction - used SBB to model three layers of sentence construction including parts of speech, clause and whole sentence. &nbsp;Model how to turn two simple sentences into a compound sentence including the job of the comma and FANBOYS. &nbsp;Lottie made a connection with the word FANBOYS, “Oh! &nbsp;I see why they\'re called FANBOYS!”</p><p>Dictated the model sentence: &nbsp;The truck crashed. &nbsp;The rock rolled. &nbsp;The truck crashed, and the rock &nbsp; rolled. &nbsp;Ask check for understanding questions about elements and structure (layers).</p><p>Lottie finished with composing a sentence for the words ‘speck’ and ‘pluck’. &nbsp;I plucked a feather, and there was a speck of dirt. &nbsp;Lottie did not make many connections with the spelling of the words she was using including ‘ed’ for past tense (used ‘t’) and ‘ck’ spelling. &nbsp;She was most attentive to sentence elements, however, and was able to identify clauses and answer all questions about punctuation.</p>', NULL, '<p>This Saturday lesson was a make up for when Naomi was unwell last term. &nbsp;Lottie has also missed the last three Friday lessons due to illness.</p>', '2022-09-03 11:32:45', '2022-09-03 13:39:01'),
