(3158, '2022/09/05', '03:32 pm', '3', '7', 'Mia Harvey', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Language Rules (Pronunciation/Spelling/Grammar)', 'Rule 5: i and y may say their second (long) sound at the end of a syllable', 'See Notes', 'Yina Peng', 'Achieved', 'Achieved', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Mia and Thomas got along very well this lesson and it can be beneficial for both of them to work on one project. They learn about team work.</p><p>Kilpattrick F &nbsp;with timer<br>OPR/WPR g, o, l, d, a, e, f, u. They both are &nbsp;a bit shaky for a, e, and u sounds.&nbsp;<br>morphology activity 6 for Mia. Tom-written focus g. Thomas still likes to write letters from bottom to top for line letters and he still can\'t write a or g without lifting his pencil.&nbsp;<br>rule 4, 5, 6, 17 with activity. Thomas has a great memory and understanding ability, yet Mia can retain knowledge longer than Thomas. They two make a great team for learning together.&nbsp;<br>SD: my, will, a go, bad, red, of, be<br>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-09-05 15:32:01', '2022-09-06 15:46:03'),
(3159, '2022/09/05', '03:32 pm', '3', '7', 'Connor McLaren', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Substitute onset & rime - Kilpatrick Level G', 'Ellie Connor', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week Seven</td></tr><tr><td>Monday, 5 September 2022</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>PA: Kilpatrick G2</td></tr><tr><td>MA: Donah #32</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR: oy aw u ai au ti th er sh ee ow ou oo ch ar</td></tr><tr><td>WPR: oy aw u ai au ti th er&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Rule review: 4, 14, 2, 6</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD: Sec. S - often, motion, theatre, improvement, improve, century, cent, total, mention</td></tr><tr><td>Read S&amp;R</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Connor did well with PA, MA and phonos. Prompting to stay on task and stop talking about unrelated things - he typically will respond fine to my instruction, though (without Lachlan present), even though it does sometimes require repetition. Lots of prompting with \'theatre\' in SD - CM really struggled with this one, especially with the final syllable. He repeatedly erased and then rewrote it incorrectly (\'ter\' and without a syllable break before), and just couldn\'t seem to compute what I was saying. Eventually I modelled on the board for him what I wanted him to write, and that helped. Just made it through the whole list for today, including reading for S&amp;R when Lachlan arrived.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p>PAIRED</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Recap sentence structures (booklet)<br>&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Continued sentence structure booklets. Boys are really bored with this task and don\'t seem to enjoy it! As a result, it\'s a bit of an effort to keep them engaged and make sure that this is a productive time. Regardless, we did get through a bit today and had good convos about sentence structure. Neither Connor nor Lachlan can confidently tell me about any sentence structures or parts of speech, but in application can actually demonstrate some knowledge. E.g. when marking the PoS in sentences, both boys were fine working independently. Connor was especially distracted today and kept trying to talk over me or to me - I had to get a bit snappy once or twice when they repeatedly ignored my instructions or weren\'t listening to what I was saying. Can be especially frustrating as I know we spent so long on sentences in the past.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week Seven</td></tr><tr><td>Monday, 5 September 2022</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', '2022-09-05 15:32:02', '2022-09-17 16:05:37'),
