(3161, '2022/09/05', '03:38 pm', '3', '7', 'Elsa Clennet', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms (include purpose - to connect speech sounds to their written symbol which helps with reading, writing and spelling)', 'Oral Phonogram Review (OPR) - Various Phonograms (see notes)', 'Neve Mitchell', 'Achieved', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>PA: Kilpatrick I</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR: 42-70</td></tr><tr><td>WPR: ph ough ed or ir gu ar ci er kn gn</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Rule review: 26 4 11 28&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD: United States-circle</td></tr><tr><td>Read R&amp;S</td></tr><tr><td>Explain/discuss the markings and meanings of analysed words.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Sentence Structure: Use Ayres words in sentences.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Writing Process: Chat to Elsa about how we\'re going to progress with her informative writing. Perhaps a 3 week writing project on a topic of her choice.&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p>Notes</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>A fun lesson from Elsa! We didn\'t get through quite as much as I wanted to, but Elsa was a little late and very tired from school. We also had an instance of her using a word incorrectly, but I\'ve postponed our chat about that to next week where she won\'t be in an observed lesson (as I think it made her a ltitle nervous!)</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-09-05 15:38:19', '2022-09-12 16:14:50'),
(3162, '2022/09/05', '03:48 pm', '3', '3', 'Seth Vanderlaan', 'English', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Campbell Jepson', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-09-05 15:48:42', '2022-09-05 15:48:42'),
(3163, '2022/09/05', '04:00 pm', '3', '5', 'Lachlan  Smith', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Substitute onset & rime - Kilpatrick Level G', 'Ellie Connor', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p><strong>Connor &amp; Lachlan (4pm – 4:30pm)&nbsp;</strong></p><p>Together – Writing &amp; composition, mental actions and reading</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Writing:</strong>&nbsp;</p><p>Sentence Structures</p></td><td><p>Recap sentence structures (booklet)</p><p>Simple sentences:&nbsp;</p><p>Write me a simple declarative sentence using the word “judge” as a verb.</p><p>Mark the three levels of sentence structure on given sentences</p></td><td>ü</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p><strong>Lachlan (4:30pm – 5pm) – possibly assessments?</strong></p><p>Lachlan: needs to do SA spelling, Wadd reading and Wadd speling</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td><strong>Phonological Awareness</strong></td><td><p>forty (2/4), population (4/9), judge (1/3), weather (2/4)</p><p>Struggled with ‘judge’</p></td><td>ü</td></tr><tr><td>Phonemic Awareness</td><td>Kilpatrick G2</td><td>ü</td></tr><tr><td>Morphemic Awareness</td><td>Donah #32</td><td>ü</td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Phonics:</strong>&nbsp;</p><p>OPR/WPR</p></td><td>ng gn kn n ea th or our er dge aw au</td><td>ü</td></tr><tr><td>Handwriting</td><td>Focus on baseline</td><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>High Frequency Vocab:</strong></p><p>Read for spelling &amp; reading</p></td><td><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Read for S&amp;R last week’s words (restrain – navy)&nbsp;</p></td><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Rule Review</td><td><p>Rules 6, 4, 14, 23</p><p>baby, nation, dodge</p></td><td>ü</td></tr><tr><td>Spelling Dictation</td><td><i>Sec O:&nbsp; forty, fourteen, fourth, four, population, proper, judge, weather, whether</i></td><td>ü</td></tr><tr><td>Syllabification</td><td>Check the syllable count on all list words</td><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Writing: &nbsp;</strong>Vocabulary</td><td>Use ‘weather’ and ‘whether’ in sentences to show an understanding of the different meanings. Revisit homophones.</td><td>ü</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p><strong>Connor &amp; Lachlan:&nbsp;</strong>Boys did well with SD words. Handwriting for both was dreadful, and we might need to go back to placing a stronger focus on letter formation during WPR and SD. Lachlan would rush his words, and just had no desire to go back and fix them. Connor wasn’t as bad once I asked him to focus on his handwriting, but the size of his letters can sometimes be far too big. Lachlan was working really slowly and seemed disengaged – wasn’t bothering to try and answer my questions, possibly because he knew Connor would answer quickly. Finished SD words and asked the boys to do a sentence writing task. Lachlan was resistant and needed lots of prompting. Connor was eager to get going but gave me a sentence using ‘judge’ as a noun to start with. He tweaked it slightly and was able to self-correct his error when he realised. I worked one-on-one with Lachlan to help him write his sentence as he was quite disengaged. Played a game of Uno before Connor left.</p><p><strong>Lachlan:&nbsp;</strong>Latest MM (May 2022) placed LS at Section P</p><p>Lachlan was really disengaged and resistant today. I actually asked him if he was okay and if there was anything bothering him, as he was constantly fiddling with his rubber and pencil, head down and cap over his eyes. He was very quiet and I had to really work to get him to respond to my questions or prompts. After Connor left, we did PA, MA and phonos. Lachlan really struggled with au and our but was otherwise okay (some prompting with cues e.g. gn and kn). Then talked about ‘weather’ and ‘whether’. Discussed homophones (Lachlan unable to tell me what the word meant straight away and needed prompts), then I asked Lachlan to use them both in sentences. He was fine with ‘weather’, although I did ask him to improve it by adding more information. He was a bit stumped on ‘whether’ though. It seems that he didn’t really understand the word, and it seemed to frustrate him. He kept saying that it was stupid because he was never going to use or read the word, and I ended up dictating a sentence for him to write, as he wasn’t going to come up with one himself.</p>', '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week Five</td></tr><tr><td>Monday, 22 August 2022</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p>Connor 3:30pm, Lachlan 4pm</p>', '2022-09-05 16:00:33', '2022-09-17 15:56:26'),
