(3189, '2022/09/08', '08:47 am', '3', '7', 'Lewis Prevost', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Delete syllable from three syllable word - Kilpatrick Level E', 'Ellie Connor', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week Seven, Lesson Two</td></tr><tr><td>Thursday, 8 September 2022</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>PA: out (1/2), time (1/3), may (1/2), into (2/4), him (1/3), today (2/4)</td></tr><tr><td>PA: Kilpatrick E2 set 6</td></tr><tr><td>PA: Donah #20</td></tr><tr><td>LP really good with part 3 because he enjoys making connections!</td></tr><tr><td>OPR: ou ay ai o our ir ur</td></tr><tr><td>WPR: ou ai ir o our ay ur</td></tr><tr><td>Recap of syllable types - can sort some of the little cards in Yellow Box. Will likely need lots of prompting (intro\'d last lesson)</td></tr><tr><td>Review rule 18&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Sec A-G, SD: out, time, may, into, him, today</td></tr><tr><td>Identify syllable types of spelling words (make connections with previous activity)</td></tr><tr><td>Use spelling words in sentences</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Game or book</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Home support pack</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>We had SUCH a great lesson today! All our work was integrated, and I could see the focus and determination on Lewis\' face as he thought through a lot of our activities. He was a little wobbly to start (literally - moving around a lot), but was still answering my questions and engaging with the content. Lewis was very excited today to tell me about the walrusapillar, so this took up some time at the start as I tried to redirect him back to the task. After I told him that we\'d revisit the walrusapillar later, he seemed to settle into his work a little more. Prompting with ir/ur cues and our, otherwise fine with OPR/WPR - even got through all written phonos&nbsp; He was alllll over the syllable types! I wa very impressed.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week Seven, Lesson Two</td></tr><tr><td>Thursday, 8 September 2022</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', '2022-09-08 08:47:28', '2022-09-17 16:28:50'),
(3190, '2022/09/08', '03:35 pm', '3', '6', 'Reuben Shelverton', 'English', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Juno Galang', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-09-08 15:35:24', '2022-09-08 15:35:24'),
(3191, '2022/09/08', '03:39 pm', '3', '7', 'Lucy Fairbrother', 'Mathematics', 'Number & Place Value', 'Mental Computation', 'Mad Minute Maths - Facts to 100', 'Naomi Wright', 'In Progress', NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', '<p>Lucy achieved highest score in division equations on MMM today.</p><p>Lucy required significant coaching when applying short multiplication and division to represent the workings needed when solving a word problem. &nbsp;She was confidently able to solve the problem mentally but was unable to show this in numerical form.</p><p>Completed Numeration Cluster 3 Lesson 1 Independent Practice - finding the difference between two numbers after identifying greater/less than. &nbsp;Lucy was engaged in the coaching process of finding the difference between 4920 and 5207 using steps to the nearest 100. &nbsp;From 4920 &gt; 80 to 5000 &gt; 200 &gt; 7 = a difference of 287. &nbsp;This process was most beneficial and will be repeated next lesson where Lucy can continue to consolidate the skill of partitioning numbers in this way (including bridging 100s and 1000s).</p><p>Lucy was amazing today voluntarily accepting the company of two new tutors who were in for observations and training. &nbsp;The lesson was a little quieter than usual, but Lucy was no less productive or engaged.</p>', NULL, '<p>Lucy was joined by Miah and Aimee as new tutor observers for today\'s.</p>', '2022-09-08 15:39:34', '2022-09-08 19:45:45'),
(3192, '2022/09/08', '04:34 pm', '3', '7', 'Callisto Pratten', 'Mathematics', 'Linear & Non-Linear Relationships', 'Linear relationships (Co-ordinates, Cartesian Plane)', 'Text book - Exercises, Questions, Activities', 'Rosemary Beswick', 'Achieved', 'Achieved', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'Followup', '<p>I had a lengthy discussion with Callisto about her goals for Maths for the remainder of the year and we agreed that she should aim to pass the subject and should do the exam. Stephen was happy with this decision. I have communicated this information to her teacher. We then spent time working on Set 3 from the bivariate data book. This is a very short set and did not pose any real problems, although the final question that Callisto did not get time to complete, needs to involve a discussion with her teacher.</p>', NULL, NULL, '2022-09-08 16:34:04', '2022-09-08 18:27:55'),
(3193, '2022/09/09', '09:05 am', '3', '8', 'Archie Lester', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - High Frequency Vocabulary', 'Analysis of word structure and application of learned concepts (sounds, phonograms, rules)', 'Challenge Word Analysis - Record and label syllables, markings and rules + discuss morphemes', 'Naomi Wright', 'In Progress', NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', '<p>Challenge Words: &nbsp;syncytial and species</p><p>PA - Kilpatrick J Mixed Level p194 (Archie was given two words and had to identify what had changed) and Set S9 196 (Archie was given the initial word + instruction and not required to say the initial word).</p><p>Sandra Donah - Activity 18. &nbsp;Record words on whiteboard and discuss parts of speech for each word in the compound words.</p><p>OMR - all prefixes and suffixes introduced to date. &nbsp;Step One - Read for spelling and reading. &nbsp;Step Two - state meaning for each.</p><p>WMR/Morpheme Dictation and analsyis - ion, tion, re, es, un, sion x2, out, ed - include rules and markings.</p><p>Spelling Dictation - patient and ambition. &nbsp;No rhythm was established in this lesson. &nbsp;Archie appeared not to have had his medication (according to Mum), so there was much distraction during each task with questions, observations, stories etc. &nbsp;Archie wrote patient as pationent. &nbsp;He was unable to encode this word independently even when sounding out.</p><p>Identifying Bases and Affixes - infectious, potential, musician, collection.</p><p>Analyse sentence recorded for HW - ID interjection, sentence structure, dependent and independent clauses, conjunctions and associated punctuation.</p><p>Introduced concept of prepositions and prepositional phrases - perfect segue as Archie had included a prepositional phrase in one of his sentences. &nbsp;Discussed that some prepositions may be part of a phrase or part of a clause. &nbsp;‘After the bushwalk’ is a clause because there is no verb for the subject noun.</p><p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, NULL, '2022-09-09 09:05:38', '2022-09-09 10:38:33'),
(3194, '2022/09/09', '09:06 am', '3', '4', 'Lottie Young', 'English', 'Reading - Fluency & Prosody', 'Read words aloud - accurately, automatically, with expression (words in isolation)', 'Word Decoding Flashcards - read for spelling and/or read for reading', 'Naomi Wright', 'In Progress', NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', '<p>Read Reading Links consonant blend cards and discuss the ‘l’ making the /a/ say /ar/ and making the /o/ say /oh/, the i and o saying their second sound when followed by two consonants.</p><p>PA - Kilpatrick G2 Set 13 (Lottie was given the initial word and the instruction - she was not required to say the word to begin). &nbsp;She was very stuck on won &gt; wig and pat &gt; pop. &nbsp;Nil other errors.</p><p>SCORE - Book 3 Page 125 - all columns. &nbsp;Lottie having difficulty with reversing b/p and substituting end sounds. &nbsp;On the fourth column, she self correct all five errors made. &nbsp;</p><p>Sandra Donah Morphology - Activity Fifteen. &nbsp;Record words on whiteboard. &nbsp;Discuss markings, part of speech, and meaning.</p><p>Spelling Dictation of Sandra Donah words - sound and write with markings, rules and word analysis explanations after reading for reading.</p><p>Use dictated words in a dictated sentence: The mailman packed his footbath, raincoat, mailbox and pepperspread in his backpack as he and his watchdog set off set off in their spaceship away from the rainstorm.</p><p>Lottie was very distracted today and passively resistant to persevering with set tasks. &nbsp;Behaviours included throwing her hairband away under her table, hiding her ruler in her clothes and pretending to look around the room for it (this went for a few minutes), standing up to do her work, jigging and frequently laughing in exasperation asking ‘how many more’. &nbsp;It was important that we persevere with the tasks set as Lottie has had an extended absence and we need to be bringing together lots of knowledge that she already has. &nbsp;She also needs to be developing neural capacity to attend for increasing periods of time. &nbsp;We completed all task, but we were fifteen minutes late finishing.</p>', NULL, NULL, '2022-09-09 09:06:36', '2022-09-09 10:47:30'),
