(3210, '2022/09/12', '03:34 pm', '3', '8', 'Elsa Clennet', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Substitute vowel phoneme - Kilpatrick Level J', 'Neve Mitchell', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>PA: Kilpatrick J</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR: 27-70</td></tr><tr><td>WPR: gu or ci ti er au ou si ough&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Rule review: 4 14 29 11</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD: argue-office</td></tr><tr><td>Read R&amp;S</td></tr><tr><td>Explain/discuss the markings and meanings of analysed words.</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Rule Intro: NA</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Sentence Structure: Use Ayres words in a very short creative piece. Write 2-3 sentences that incorporate dialogue and first person.</td></tr><tr><td>Writing Process: Start planning Elsa\'s piece of informative writing.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Elsa was incredibly tired today and also had hurt her back, so she was not in the best headspace for tutoring. I was impressed with her perseverance here. She had most of her work down like clockwork (yay!) but her articulation suffered. Her planning activity was quickly and easily completed.&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-09-12 15:34:38', '2022-09-12 17:56:30'),
(3211, '2022/09/12', '03:35 pm', '3', '8', 'Connor McLaren', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Substitute onset & rime - Kilpatrick Level G', 'Ellie Connor', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week Eight</td></tr><tr><td>Monday, 12 September 2022</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Continue sentence structure booklet - analysing parts of speech of simple sentences</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>The boys aren\'t enjoying the sentence structure booklet! Neither of them were able to articulate their knowledge of simple sentence structures and parts of speech, despite how often we\'ve talked about it. I had to model a simple sentence for them. Need to recap parts of speech.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>PA: Kilpatrick G2</td></tr><tr><td>MA: Donah #34</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR/WPR: er ti ar ai ou oa ea u igh ng</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Rule review: 4, 6, 11, 22, 24</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD: Sec. P - beautiful, beauty, flight, travel, rapid, repair, troubling, trouble</td></tr><tr><td>Read S&amp;R</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>LS came in with a lot of attitude during our shared lesson, and was constantly fidgeting, but sharpened his focus after Connor left. I said to Lachlan on his way out: \"I\'m really impressed with you today. Not because you got every word right first go - because you didn\'t! - but because you persisted and tried again until you did&nbsp;get it right, and that\'s the most important thing\". Lachlan struggled with reading for spelling \'beautiful\', \'beauty\', and \'troubling\' - really wanted to add a syllable. Even though it was difficult for him, he continued trying and didn\'t get frustrated and give up. Otherwise fine with PA, MA, phonos.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week Eight</td></tr><tr><td>Monday, 12 September 2022</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', '2022-09-12 15:35:25', '2022-09-17 16:03:40'),
(3212, '2022/09/12', '04:00 pm', '3', '8', 'Lachlan  Smith', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Substitute onset & rime - Kilpatrick Level G', 'Ellie Connor', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week Eight</td></tr><tr><td>Monday, 12 September 2022</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p>TOGETHER</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Continue sentence structure booklet - analysing parts of speech of simple sentences</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>The boys aren\'t enjoying the sentence structure booklet! Neither of them were able to articulate their knowledge of simple sentence structures and parts of speech, despite how often we\'ve talked about it. I had to model a simple sentence for them. Need to recap parts of speech.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p>LS INDIV</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>PA: Kilpatrick G2</td></tr><tr><td>MA: Donah #34</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR/WPR: er ti ar ai ou oa ea u igh ng</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Rule review: 4, 6, 11, 22, 24</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD: Sec. P - beautiful, beauty, flight, travel, rapid, repair, troubling, trouble</td></tr><tr><td>Read S&amp;R</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>LS came in with a lot of attitude during our shared lesson, and was constantly fidgeting, but sharpened his focus after Connor left. I said to Lachlan on his way out: \"I\'m really impressed with you today. Not because you got every word right first go - because you didn\'t! - but because you persisted and tried again until you did&nbsp;get it right, and that\'s the most important thing\". Lachlan struggled with reading for spelling \'beautiful\', \'beauty\', and \'troubling\' - really wanted to add a syllable. Even though it was difficult for him, he continued trying and didn\'t get frustrated and give up. Otherwise fine with PA, MA, phonos.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p>&nbsp;</p>', '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week Eight</td></tr><tr><td>Monday, 12 September 2022</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', '2022-09-12 16:00:19', '2022-09-17 16:00:30'),
(3213, '2022/09/12', '04:33 pm', '3', '8', 'Arlo Clark', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms (include purpose - to connect speech sounds to their written symbol which helps with reading, writing and spelling)', 'Oral Phongram Review (OPR) - Cards 31 > 45', 'Yina Peng', 'Achieved', 'Achieved', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Kilpattrick &nbsp;F1<br>OPR/WPR:w, i, a, ou, y. &nbsp;Arlo sometimes struggles with the retaining of things we have learned. He needs reminds. He is shaky at the sounds of y and i. He usually needs a bit of help with the sounds of ou yet he also needs help with the writing format for it.&nbsp;</p><p>morphology activity 3<br>rule review: 17.&nbsp;<br>SD: &nbsp;will, all, your, you<br>SD words sentence. Arlo spelt frend for friend.&nbsp;<br>reading. Hot dog Bob. Arlo cannot read natually and he tends to sound out words and strugle with blending them together.&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-09-12 16:33:34', '2022-09-13 16:18:16'),
(3214, '2022/09/12', '04:34 pm', '3', '7', 'Arki Young', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms (include purpose - to connect speech sounds to their written symbol which helps with reading, writing and spelling)', 'Oral Phonogram Review (OPR) - Various Phonograms (see notes)', 'Neve Mitchell', 'Achieved', 'N/A', 'Rescheduled', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Rescheduled to 15 Sep</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR: 44-70</td></tr><tr><td>WPR: ea ough oy ti or dge wh our</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Rule review: 4 6 14</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD: royal-four</td></tr><tr><td>Read R&amp;S</td></tr><tr><td>Explain/discuss the markings and meanings of analysed words.</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Rule Intro: NA</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p>Notes</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>A very short lesson with Arki today due to a mix up on Claire\'s part where she thought the catch up was scheduled from 4:30-5:30 rather than 3:30-4:30.</td></tr><tr><td>Despite this we got through an impressive amount, and managed the whole of the spelling portion. Arki is completely on the ball as per usual and perfect with his articulation and dictation. He also wrote a fun sentence using his spelling words: \"It gave me great pleasure to measure the amount of treasure.\"</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-09-12 16:35:15', '2022-09-15 16:40:43'),
(3215, '2022/09/12', '04:35 pm', '3', '8', 'Arki Young', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms (include purpose - to connect speech sounds to their written symbol which helps with reading, writing and spelling)', 'Oral Phonogram Review (OPR) - Various Phonograms (see notes)', 'Neve Mitchell', 'Achieved', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR: 50-70 shuffled</td></tr><tr><td>WPR: th er or ti oa ai sh oy</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Rule review: 4 13 14</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD: rather-restrain</td></tr><tr><td>Read R&amp;S</td></tr><tr><td>Explain/discuss the markings and meanings of analysed words.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Sentence Structure: Use Ayres words in sentences and identify type. A good and in-depth conversation about one of Arki\'s sentences. We explored various parts of speech (including the word \'rather\') and had a recap of some parts of speech. Arki also provided his own definitions/reasoning/explorations into the parts of speech and how words might be classified. I really liked his connection with prepositions showing \"location\" in time and space -- can\'t believe I haven\'t thought to use that word before.&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Our spelling lesson took a long time today because Arki and I had many conversations about spelling conventions, pronunciation differences, rule application, minims, etc. It was good to get back in the swing of a literacy lesson, as we haven\'t done one for about three weeks now.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-09-12 16:35:43', '2022-09-12 17:53:32'),
(3216, '2022/09/13', '08:45 am', '3', '4', 'Max Shapiro', 'English', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Campbell Jepson', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-09-13 08:45:42', '2022-09-13 08:45:42'),
(3217, '2022/09/13', '08:45 am', '3', '8', 'Luna Shapiro', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms (include purpose - to connect speech sounds to their written symbol which helps with reading, writing and spelling)', 'Oral Phonogram Review (OPR) - Various Phonograms (see notes)', 'Neve Mitchell', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>PA: Kilpatrick G2</td></tr><tr><td>Word recognition: Fitzroy flashcards</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR:&nbsp; 1-8,b h k m n p r sh th ee ow oo ch ay ar er ckkii</td></tr><tr><td>WPR: p m n r h b a g d sh ck</td></tr><tr><td>b/d mix ups. Luna was determined to connect all her letters together today and would not stop linking them despite when she was asked to stop.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>SD: man ran hen pen men big god dog gap</td></tr><tr><td>Mixing 2 o\'clock and jumping letters was NOT a good idea as she got muddled. I could prompt her and she could fix it up, but I noticed errors (e.g. after I prompted that g was a 2 o\'clock letter, she applied that to p).</td></tr><tr><td>An observation is that she still needs practice for her g formation in spelling/writing contexts.&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Colouring time (about 5 mins)</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Use spelling words in oral sentences:&nbsp; I can see a man. I ran a mile. I see a big hen. I can see a man writing with a pen.&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Write 1 of Luna\'s oral sentences Of note:.g and s in writing context. Finger spacing between words.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Fitzroy #5: Read a few sentences aloud. Was/went mix up again.</td></tr><tr><td>SCORE fan as fish</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p>Notes</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Luna was a little tired this morning due to a poor night\'s sleep, but even then we still got through an impressive amount of activities (that we wouldn\'t have had she been tired in the afternoon). I\'m really pleased with how she\'s going in these morning lessons. See above for other notes.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-09-13 08:45:58', '2022-09-13 16:41:40'),
(3219, '2022/09/13', '03:56 pm', '3', '3', 'Aylah Harrex', 'Mathematics', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Kieran Oates', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-09-13 15:56:49', '2022-09-13 15:56:49'),
(3220, '2022/09/13', '04:19 pm', '3', '8', 'Brock Smith', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Yina Peng', NULL, NULL, 'Cancelled - No Show', 'N/A', 'Cancelled', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-09-13 16:19:52', '2022-09-13 16:19:52'),
(3221, '2022/09/13', '04:30 pm', '3', '8', 'Callum Coulson', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms (include purpose - to connect speech sounds to their written symbol which helps with reading, writing and spelling)', 'Oral Phongram Review (OPR) - Cards 1 > 70', 'Yina Peng', 'Achieved', 'Achieved', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>kilpatrick i<br>OPR/WPR: 1-70. Callum has surprised me with all the 70 common phonograms. He could barely remeber them at the very begaining but today he could say all sounds out loud fluently with a few exceptions.&nbsp;<br>parts of speech review: Callum sometimes understands parts of speech in sentences yet he cannont articulate the concept of them.&nbsp;<br>writing process: Callum wrote 2 compound sentences and 1 complex sentence in his paragragh writing. He is capable to do more complex sentences yet he can be careless for his spelling and capital letters sometimes. His sentences tend to be less expressive as he does not use many adjectives or adverbs.&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-09-13 16:30:09', '2022-09-14 08:56:13'),
(3222, '2022/09/13', '04:32 pm', '3', '7', 'Andrew Allan', 'English', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Laree Thorsby', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-09-13 16:32:23', '2022-09-13 16:32:23'),
(3224, '2022/09/13', '04:33 pm', '3', '8', 'Shay Douglas', 'Academic Coaching', 'Independent Study', 'School Assigned Worksheet or Assignment', 'See Notes', 'Neve Mitchell', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Subject: Chemistry</td></tr><tr><td>Focus: Shay\'s Chemistry Report</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Shay requested independent study time to work on writing his chemistry report. He had completed a practical experiment at school that he needed to write a report on using the given template from his teacher. This task was very similar to other tasks Shay has completed for his science class, and although I offered him my assistance, he told me he felt confident and would ask for help if he needed it.&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-09-13 16:33:32', '2022-09-13 17:10:55'),
(3225, '2022/09/13', '04:35 pm', '3', '8', 'Sophie Mirowski', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms (include purpose - to connect speech sounds to their written symbol which helps with reading, writing and spelling)', 'Oral Phonogram Review (OPR) - Various Phonograms (see notes)', 'Neve Mitchell', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'Rescheduled', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Cancelled - Soph unwell. Rescheduled to: 29 Sep</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR: 50-70</td></tr><tr><td>WPR: ea th au er ough ti si ci</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Read R&amp;S: Current Ayres Column</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Rule review:20 4 14 15</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD: leather-steal</td></tr><tr><td>Read R&amp;S</td></tr><tr><td>Explain/discuss the markings and meanings of analysed words.</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Rule Intro: NA</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Sentences: Use Ayres words in oral sentences.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p>Notes</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Sophie was a DREAM today. She was so focused and aware of herself. Her articulation during spelling was a huge improvement on usual. She still made a couple of errors/guesses, but overall much more articulate. I shared how impressed I was with her and she agreed that she felt much more \"awake\" and \"excitable\" today (but, notably, excited for learning rather than to hang out with me).&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-09-13 16:36:19', '2022-09-29 16:42:32'),
