(3245, '2022/09/14', '06:34 pm', '3', '8', 'Finn McKenzie', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Neve Mitchell', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Tardy', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-09-14 18:34:55', '2022-09-14 18:34:55'),
(3246, '2022/09/15', '10:18 am', '3', '8', 'Lewis Prevost', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Delete syllable from three syllable word - Kilpatrick Level E', 'Ellie Connor', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week Eight, Lesson Two</td></tr><tr><td>Thursday, 15 September 2022</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>PA: Kilpatrick E2 set 7</td></tr><tr><td>MA: Donah #21</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR: oo oy oi dge igh ir&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>WPR: oo dge oi ir igh oy</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>SD: Sec. A-G: look, did, like, six, boy, book</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Use spelling words in sentences</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Home support pack</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Lewis really wobbly today at the start of our lesson. We were in T1 which was different to normal, he\'d just recovered from being sick, and he\'d had his meds later than usual - all of these things contributed, I think. As a result, I definitely needed to give him more prompts to sit down, listen or focus, but we still got through everything I wanted to. Wandered around during PA and MA, but still got everything right. Needed some coaching with manipulating words in Donah part 1, but probably due to lack of focus. I was so impressed with Lewis\' handwriting in particular today. It seemed to be happening for him without requiring too much concentration on his end - more of a habit for him now. I corrected his formation of \'y\' once (wrote it as it\'s typed), and he continued to write it correctly for the rest of the lesson without my prompt. Got through PA, MA, phonos in 15mins! No issue IDing markings in SD words, and we got through them pretty efficiently. Pretty much finished spelling by 9:05 (20mins). Lewis had a two minute drawing break, and as soon as I told him time was up, he put it to the side with no complaint. We spent the last portion of our lesson building a sentence using Lewis\' spelling words. Verbally, he came up with \"The boy looked at books\", and I suggested adding the spelling word \'six\'. I wrote on the board: \"The boy looked at six books\", and then progressively asked Lewis to add a word to describe the boy, to describe the books, and then to describe how he looked (i.e adjectives &amp; adverb). Final sentence: \"The speedy boy looked happily at six dragon-tail books\". Lewis wrote this into his book with great care and precision (beautiful handwriting), then underlined his spelling words. To finish, I analysed the sentence with Lewis, asking him to ID the subject (\"who the sentence is about\") and the verb first, then looking at the various describing words. Lewis has been doing this at school, even using the language of noun and verb, but he wasn\'t able to articulate this knowledge with me. Will continue this sentence work next week - also want to look at the morphology of \'looked\' and \'books\'.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week Eight, Lesson Two</td></tr><tr><td>Thursday, 15 September 2022</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', '2022-09-15 10:25:58', '2022-09-15 10:27:58'),
(3247, '2022/09/15', '02:32 pm', '3', '7', 'Mia Harvey', 'Mathematics', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Campbell Jepson', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-09-15 14:32:00', '2022-09-15 14:32:00'),
(3248, '2022/09/15', '03:29 pm', '3', '8', 'James  Coleman', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Substitute onset & rime - Kilpatrick Level G', 'Ellie Connor', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week Eight</td></tr><tr><td>Thursday, 15 September 2022</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>PA: Kilpatrick</td></tr><tr><td>MA: Donah #33</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Challenge word: amphibian</td></tr><tr><td>VD: talk about etymology</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR/WPR: ng ch ai ea gu ui th oa wh ear ew er</td></tr><tr><td>Prompting/hesitation with \'ear\' cue</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Rule Review: 2, 9, 29, 6</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD: Sec. N: centre, front, running, run, rule, carry, chain, death, learn, wonder</td></tr><tr><td>Read S&amp;R</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Use spelling words in sentences - include a compound and interrogative, integrate parts of speech ideas</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Looked at homework first, but James hadn\'t done his sentence writing. He wrote two sentences using four spelling words. Very tired and slow today, fiddling with everything in his hands and making a mess of his pencil lead. Very droopy, spent a while with his head on the desk. Fine with PA and MA, no issues syllabifying challenge word. Good connections and convo about the challenge word, but JC obviously wasn\'t into it! Able to articulate rules when reviewing, and no issues applying knowledge in SD. Found \'carry\' marking difficult, and spent a really long time trying to work it out (couldn\'t hear that \'a\' was making its first sound), but we got there in the end. Finished by using some spelling words in sentences (focus on structure, types and parts of speech).</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week Eight</td></tr><tr><td>Thursday, 15 September 2022</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', '2022-09-15 15:29:36', '2022-09-17 12:46:43'),
(3249, '2022/09/15', '03:29 pm', '3', '2', 'Stella Bowerman', 'Mathematics', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Campbell Jepson', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-09-15 15:29:52', '2022-09-15 15:29:52'),
(3250, '2022/09/15', '03:31 pm', '3', '7', 'Reuben Shelverton', 'English', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Juno Galang', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-09-15 15:31:52', '2022-09-15 15:31:52'),
(3251, '2022/09/15', '03:32 pm', '3', '8', 'Lucy Fairbrother', 'Mathematics', 'Number & Place Value', 'Mental Computation', 'Mad Minute Maths - Facts to 100', 'Naomi Wright', 'In Progress', NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', '<p>We reviewed last week\'s lesson comparing two given numbers as being greater or less than. &nbsp;Lucy was immediately able to articulate the subtraction equation that she would use to calculate the difference, and indeed, Lucy had been doing so in our previous problem solving task seamlessly. &nbsp;Lucy was subsequently coached through how to calculate the difference between the given numbers using mental arithmetic.&nbsp;</p><p>This task was daunting for her initially as she was reluctant to contribute to the working out and stated, “I don\'t know,” when asked prompt questions. &nbsp;I used a number line on which I placed the two given numbers and worked through with Lucy how to identify the nearest 5, nearest 10, nearest 100 etc. &nbsp;We calculated the difference between the given and the nearest, the next easily manipulated number and so one until we reached the second given number. &nbsp;I draw an arc over each gap with the corresponding difference, before finally calculating the total difference. &nbsp; Lucy recorded these workings in her exercise book and was able to solve the final problem independently and with no number line.</p><p>This was a most fruitful exercise and one that we will review next lesson.</p><p>Lucy\'s mum will also give her some practice number pairs to complete at home. &nbsp;</p><p>Lucy will also continue working on the NSPM workbook. &nbsp;It is valuable to note that Lucy is confidently solving worded problems with various types of modelling, workings and labels and is articulate about this problem solving process.</p>', NULL, NULL, '2022-09-15 15:32:42', '2022-09-15 18:32:09'),
