(3260, '2022/09/15', '04:33 pm', '3', '8', 'Chelsea Cooper', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Substitute onset & rime - Kilpatrick Level G', 'Ellie Connor', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week Eight</td></tr><tr><td>Thursday, 15 September 2022</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>PA: Kilpatrick</td></tr><tr><td>MA: Donah #33</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Challenge word: amphibian</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR/WPR: ng ch ai ea gu ui th oa wh ear ew er</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Rule Review: 2, 9, 29, 6</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD: Sec. N: centre, front, running, run, rule, carry, chain, death, learn, wonder</td></tr><tr><td>Read S&amp;R</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Look at HW sentences and last week\'s words</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Spelling words in sentences</td></tr><tr><td>Chelsea did really well today. She was engaging in discussion with each of our tasks, and made a particular effort to keep her handwriting neat today.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week Eight</td></tr><tr><td>Thursday, 15 September 2022</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', '2022-09-15 16:33:23', '2022-09-17 13:03:38'),
(3261, '2022/09/16', '07:45 am', '3', '9', 'Archie Lester', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - High Frequency Vocabulary', 'Analysis of word structure and application of learned concepts (sounds, phonograms, rules)', 'Challenge Word Analysis - Record and label syllables, markings and rules + discuss morphemes', 'Naomi Wright', 'In Progress', NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', '<p>Challenge Words: &nbsp;accession r. 2, 15 and procession r.4, 2, 15 - discussion Charles accession to the throne, and morphemes.</p><p>PA - Gave word + instruction for Archie\'s response. &nbsp;He was not asked to say the word to begin. &nbsp;Archie had nil difficulties nor hesitations with this task today.</p><p>Phonogram reviews: ci, si, ti, kn, gn, ie, eigh, igh, dge, au. &nbsp;Handwriting focus: &nbsp;Tall letters.</p><p>Morphology completed on mini-whiteboard with x2 ‘base word’ headings. &nbsp;Identify noun and adjective. &nbsp;Make connections with other compound words that have the same noun.</p><p>Analyse morphemes for derived words explosion, financial, vision.</p><p>Assessed Archie\'s spelling progress on Morrison McCall List 2 - Archie continues to make steady progress with 11 months improvement in the last 9 months. &nbsp;He has closed the gap by 2 months and is now spelling just 2 months beneath his chronological age. &nbsp;The aim is to now increase Archie beyond expectations for a student of his age giving him access to a written vocabulary commensurate with his oral vocabulary.</p><p>Archie read Comprehension Passage Level 4, #4 and identified remaining key words. &nbsp;He reformatted the passage by listing the key words in his book. &nbsp;Using key words, he dictated a summary of the passage as I typed. &nbsp;Archie initially reduced the passage from approximately 137 words to 89 words. &nbsp;When asked what the main message of the author was, Archie replied, “Owen thought everything in the world in the olden days was black and white because all the movies in the olden days were black and white.”</p>', NULL, NULL, '2022-09-16 07:45:49', '2022-09-16 12:10:22'),
(3262, '2022/09/16', '08:57 am', '3', '5', 'Lottie Young', 'English', 'Reading - Fluency & Prosody', 'Read words aloud - accurately, automatically, with expression (words in isolation)', 'Success Controlled Optimal Reading Experience (SCORE) - Book 3', 'Naomi Wright', 'In Progress', NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', '<p>Lottie practiced her SCORE page at home this week which is great news. &nbsp;She continued to stumble on words reversing b/d and b/p and not always reading accurately the final sound in words. &nbsp;eg plug as plum, plot as plob. &nbsp;When using her guiding finger, the rate of accuracy notably improved.</p><p>These same words were then used in spelling dictation - club, clam, plot, flag, flap, slip, class, blip, slap, blab, plum, blob, clap, blot, plug, glass, sled, plop, slam, glad, fluff. &nbsp;The aim here was to take the writing road to reading in an effort to strengthen Lottie\'s decoding skills with these read-aloud words.</p><p>When dicating words, Lottie needed repeated instruction to slow down and dictate one sound for one symbol at a time in order to ensure a strong neural connection was being made between each sound and its corresponding letter.</p><p>Words used in sentences that were subsequently dictated, assessed and labelled for ‘type’.</p><ul><li>The flag outside my classroom flaps in the wind. (declarative)</li><li>Did the boys plot to throw plums at the glass sled? (interrogative)</li><li>Blot out the blob of ink on the page. (imperative)</li><li>If you go too fast, you will slam into the plug! (exclamatory)</li></ul><p>Working toward strengthening retention, Lottie was asked to repeat and recall the sentence as she wrote without prompting by Naomi as much as possible. &nbsp;</p><p>Discussed which punctuation mark would be used based on oral expression. &nbsp;Lottie made strong connections with the information provided outlining sentence types, helping her to label each one.</p><p>Visual the text - what does your imagination see? &nbsp;\'Drac, the Warrior Queen of Tirnol Two, is in terrible danger. &nbsp;She is fearless, as fast as the whirlwind, as wise as the White Wizard…</p><p>Lottie found creating and describing imagined images to go with the words quite difficult. &nbsp;She attempted to angle herself so as to see the book being read. Visualisation practice to be incorporated into each lesson.</p>', NULL, NULL, '2022-09-16 08:57:05', '2022-09-16 11:42:32'),
(3263, '2022/09/16', '02:24 pm', '3', '8', 'Molly  Jackson', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Manipulate (delete or substitute) second phoneme in initial blend - Kilpatrick Level K', 'Neve Mitchell', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>PA: Kilpatrick K1</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR: 45-70</td></tr><tr><td>WPR: 51-70 or aw au ck</td></tr><tr><td>Errors: gu kn&nbsp; aw au</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Read R&amp;S: Current Ayres Column</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Rule review: 4 6 17 28</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD: sight-army</td></tr><tr><td>Read R&amp;S</td></tr><tr><td>Explain/discuss the markings and meanings of analysed words.</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Rule Intro: NA</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Use an Ayres word and MM word in a sentence:</td></tr><tr><td>Use glad and fixed in a sentence.</td></tr><tr><td>Use same and born in a sentence.</td></tr><tr><td>Use night and sight in a sentence. Use cent in a sentence. Use within and stood in a sentence.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Oral Fluency: ORF 318</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Molly was in an odd mood today. She came up to the room five minutes early and started throwing a mock tantrum. She threw some things on the floor when she realised there were no chocolates. She was giggling and thought it was very funny. I was unimpressed but not cross because she wasn\'t being malicious. At the end of the lesson I asked her to please not throw my things on the floor next time. Molly became so apologetic that I felt terrible for asking. She also said \"please don\'t tell my parents\" and I assured her I wouldn\'t. I think this likely just comes from her general worry about upsetting people/doing things wrong, not something to be concerned about (with her parents)</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Had trouble with coins and fight (written as fix).&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>glad = sounded out g/a/l/d, wrote gald, said \"that doesn\'t look right\", then sounded gad and wrote gad</td></tr><tr><td>Same and night -- correct.</td></tr><tr><td>cent = cet, sounded a couple of times and didn\'t spot her error, although she apparently knew it was wrong because I \"gave her a funny look.\"</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-09-16 14:24:07', '2022-09-16 16:07:56'),
(3264, '2022/09/16', '03:26 pm', '3', '3', 'Harlow Booy', 'Mathematics', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Wright', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-09-16 15:26:28', '2022-09-16 15:26:28'),
(3265, '2022/09/16', '03:30 pm', '3', '8', 'Connor Thompson ', 'Mathematics', 'Shape', '2D', 'Text book - Exercises, Questions, Activities', 'Neve Mitchell', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Maths -- Connor\'s \"Online Maths\"</td></tr><tr><td>Finding area of composite shapes. Before we could get started we had to talk briefly about area as a concept as Connor was still thinking about perimeter. I used a 100 block to demonstrate the difference between the two and show Connor area. We also needed to discuss composite shapes.</td></tr><tr><td>Connor did okay with these. I told him he could fly through them if he chose to, and Connor responded \"If I was doing this at home it would take me 2 hours, not joking\". I said I imagined that is because he doesn\'t have someone keeping him on track. I pointed out that, as has been the case in all our lessons on this, Connor is perfectly capable at completing the questions once he gets into the rhythm.</td></tr><tr><td>Connor frequently made errors such as: using the triangle are formula to find the area of a rectangle, multiplying instead of adding two areas to find the total.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-09-16 15:30:49', '2022-09-16 16:41:20'),
(3266, '2022/09/16', '03:32 pm', '3', '5', 'Freya McIver', 'Academic Coaching', 'Independent Study', 'School Assigned Worksheet or Assignment', 'See Notes', 'Ellie Connor', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week Eight, Lesson Five</td></tr><tr><td>Friday, 26 August 2022</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Recap of WP, text structures and sentence structures - crash course session!</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Freya didn\'t bring any work today, so we did a little crash course session on sentence types, structures, paragraphs and the writing process. We worked&nbsp; through the sentence type &amp; structure assessment together. Freya has a good understanding of these concepts, but struggles to articulate it using the appropriate language. E.g. she can write a compound sentence with no issue but struggles to articulate the structure and why it\'s accurate. Good convo recapping clauses, connection between FANBOYS being coordinating conjunctions and subbies as subordinating conjunctions etc.&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', '<p>Lesson five, week 8</p><p>16/9/22</p>', '2022-09-16 15:32:18', '2022-09-16 16:45:03');
