(3286, '2022/09/19', '03:26 pm', '3', '9', 'Connor McLaren', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Manipulate (delete or substitute) initial phoneme in initial blend - Kilpatrick Level H', 'Ellie Connor', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week Nine</td></tr><tr><td>Monday, 19 September 2022</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>PA: Kilpatrick</td></tr><tr><td>MA: Donah #35</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Challenge word: amphibian</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR/WPR: ng ch ai ea gu ui th oa wh ear ew er</td></tr><tr><td>Struggled with \'ear\' in OPR</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Rule review: 12, 4, 29, 24, 6, 14</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD: Sec. S - examination, examine</td></tr><tr><td>Read S&amp;R</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Well settled and calm, understood when it was time to settle into doing work. Great convo about challenge word.&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Recap mental actions &amp; text structures (boys to work together and sort magnets)&nbsp;<br>NM inference passage<br>- Discuss infer vs. imply<br>- Read passage and work through mental actions<br>o Monitor comprehension<br>o Make connections – Narnia, playing hide and seek as a kid, fox fur at antique shop<br>o Predict – character<br>o Reformat – identify key words<br>o Mentally summarise – summarise passage in one sentence</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Boys not into the activity. Neither able to articualte text types knowledge and needed lots of prompting. LS especially very uncooperative and questioning the point</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p>&nbsp;</p>', '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week Nine</td></tr><tr><td>Monday, 19 September 2022</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', '2022-09-19 15:26:27', '2022-09-26 17:13:09'),
(3287, '2022/09/19', '03:29 pm', '3', '9', 'Thomas Johnson', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Language Rules (Pronunciation/Spelling/Grammar)', 'Rule 19: i may say /I/ and o may say /O/ when followed by two consonants', 'See Notes', 'Yina Peng', 'Achieved', 'Achieved', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Thomas was quite hypoactive today and he told me that it was becasue he did not get to do any physical activity at school because of the rain., so we did some ball game and he was still quite high energy afterwards. This can be a bit distractive to Mia sometiems so I have decided to have some individual times with Thomas and Mia and meantime have 30 minutes crossover for group activities.&nbsp;</p><p>Kilpattrick F &nbsp;with timer<br>OPR/WPR o, i, ay, oo, d. They both was not very fluent on o and oo. Mia tends to rememeber things slowly yet she retains knowledge. However, Thomas tends to remember things faster but he usually forgets quickly and he understands things faster.&nbsp;<br>Mia: hi Jack. Thomas: handwriting&nbsp;<br>rule 18, 19 with activity will<br>SD: old, time, may, in to, him, to day, look, did<br>&nbsp;compose sentences using SD words.</p><p>reading hey Jack, blue. Mia can read paragrghs naturally with a few words that she needs to sound out yet Thomas needs a lot of practice for his oral fluency. He will need something more decodable to read.&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-09-19 15:29:36', '2022-09-21 12:46:13'),
(3288, '2022/09/19', '03:30 pm', '3', '9', 'Mia Harvey', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - High Frequency Vocabulary', 'Analysis of word structure and application of learned concepts (sounds, phonograms, rules)', 'Spelling Dictation - Precisely say, write and read words in Section A-G', 'Yina Peng', 'Achieved', 'Achieved', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Mia has shown that she can rememeber phonograms betetr and she usually can remember things from the past weeks. Thomas was quite hypoactive today and he told me that it was becasue he did not get to do any physical activity at school because of the rain., so we did some ball game and he was still quite high energy afterwards. This can be a bit distractive to Mia sometiems so I have decided to have some individual times with Thomas and Mia and meantime have 30 minutes crossover for group activities.&nbsp;</p><p>Kilpattrick F &nbsp;with timer<br>OPR/WPR o, i, ay, oo, d. They both was not very fluent on o and oo. Mia tends to rememeber things slowly yet she retains knowledge. However, Thomas tends to remember things faster but he usually forgets quickly and he understands things faster.&nbsp;<br>Mia: hi Jack. Thomas: handwriting&nbsp;<br>rule 18, 19 with activity will<br>SD: old, time, may, in to, him, to day, look, did<br>&nbsp;compose sentences using SD words.</p><p>reading hey Jack, blue. Mia can read paragrghs naturally with a few words that she needs to sound out yet Thomas needs a lot of practice for his oral fluency. He will need something more decodable to read.&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-09-19 15:30:23', '2022-09-21 12:49:26'),
(3289, '2022/09/19', '03:32 pm', '3', '5', 'Seth Vanderlaan', 'English', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Campbell Jepson', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-09-19 15:32:14', '2022-09-19 15:32:14'),
(3290, '2022/09/19', '03:39 pm', '3', '9', 'Elsa Clennet', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Substitute vowel phoneme - Kilpatrick Level J', 'Neve Mitchell', 'Achieved', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>PA: Kilpatrick J</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR: 27-70</td></tr><tr><td>WPR Assessment: 27-50</td></tr><tr><td>Errors: aw (wrote or, self corrected to aw when or ordinary came up later).</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Rule review: 4 11 14</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD: victim-concern</td></tr><tr><td>Read R&amp;S</td></tr><tr><td>Explain/discuss the markings and meanings of analysed words.</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Rule Intro: NA</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Use Ayres words in narrative sentences.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Elsa and I were a bit slow this lesson -- she was running fairly late (about ten mins) and then the OPR and WPR seemed to eat up our time slightly. Spelling also took longer than usual, which is on me. We were quite chatty and I didn\'t keep her as on track as I should have.</td></tr><tr><td>She was generally great. We had a chat about her sentences making grammatical sense (\"an invite to the invitation\"). Elsa heard and understood what I was saying about invite being a verb/noun and invitation a thing rather than a place you can go to, and had a cheeky response/solution, which was to change it to \"invitation night\" -- a special night that you are invited to to receive even more invitations!</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-09-19 15:39:56', '2022-09-19 16:33:32'),
(3291, '2022/09/19', '04:00 pm', '3', '9', 'Lachlan  Smith', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Substitute onset & rime - Kilpatrick Level G', 'Ellie Connor', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week Nine</td></tr><tr><td>Monday, 19 September 2022</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Recap mental actions &amp; text structures (boys to work together and sort magnets)&nbsp;<br>NM inference passage<br>- Discuss infer vs. imply<br>- Read passage and work through mental actions<br>o Monitor comprehension<br>o Make connections – Narnia, playing hide and seek as a kid, fox fur at antique shop<br>o Predict – character<br>o Reformat – identify key words<br>o Mentally summarise – summarise passage in one sentence</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Boys not into the activity. Neither able to articualte text types knowledge and needed lots of prompting. LS especially very uncooperative and questioning the point</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>PA: Kilpatrick</td></tr><tr><td>MA: Donah #35</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR/WPR: ng ch ai ea gu ui th oa wh ear ew er</td></tr><tr><td>Struggled with ui until prompt, ear&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Rule review: 24, 28 (tried)</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD: Sec. P - entrance, importance, important, carried, carry</td></tr><tr><td>Read S&amp;R</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Grumpy and unmotivated. Kept questioning work - esp with MA sctivity</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week Nine</td></tr><tr><td>Monday, 19 September 2022</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', '2022-09-19 16:00:40', '2022-09-26 17:17:07'),
(3292, '2022/09/19', '04:30 pm', '3', '9', 'Arlo Clark', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Language Rules (Pronunciation/Spelling/Grammar)', 'Rule 18: English words don\'t end with \'a\' alone - use ay', 'See Notes', 'Yina Peng', 'Achieved', NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Arlo is usually very dedicated to his learning and he especially likes writing. Yet he complained a lot today that he was tired and did not want to do any work. He usually likes to play physical games a lot such as card games and ball throwing.&nbsp;</p><p>Kilpattrick &nbsp;F1<br>OPR/WPR:ou, oo, ay, i, o, l, ai, oi, oy. We have learned new phonograms today including oo, ai, ay, oi, oy.&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;handwriting focus: we focused on e today and Arlo is usually pretty good at this and enjoys handwriting.&nbsp;<br>rule review: 18. We learned a new rule rule 18 today and Arlo could understand this rule quickly.&nbsp;<br>SD: &nbsp;out, may, in to, him, to day, look, did<br>SD words sentence.&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-09-19 16:30:41', '2022-09-21 12:05:35'),
(3293, '2022/09/19', '04:32 pm', '3', '9', 'Arki Young', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms (include purpose - to connect speech sounds to their written symbol which helps with reading, writing and spelling)', 'Oral Phonogram Review (OPR) - Various Phonograms (see notes)', 'Neve Mitchell', 'Achieved', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR: 45-70</td></tr><tr><td>WPR: ti er dge ea th wh wor ai ough ie</td></tr><tr><td>To look at further: ough ey ie dge</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Read R&amp;S: Current Ayres Column</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Rule review: 4 14 23 8</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD: population-figure</td></tr><tr><td>Read R&amp;S</td></tr><tr><td>Explain/discuss the markings and meanings of analysed words.</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Rule Intro: NA</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Use homophone pair in two different sentences to show meaning.</td></tr><tr><td>Talked about \'whether\' as a conjunction and modelled on the blocks. Arki initially wrote \"whether I should do my homework or play outside\", which was missing something at the start to add context. We discussed how even though there was a SN and V, \"whether\" was a conjunction and therefore needed to be joining two things together.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p>Notes</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>A good lesson with Arki! He had a very articulate and knowledgeable conversation with me about homophones, homographs and homonyms, and also asked some great questions about the rules we used today.</td></tr><tr><td>It was also great to see Arki reviewing and editing his work. His initial sentence included \"sunny with a bit cloudy\" but when he reviewed his sentence (independently!) he spoke aloud about how he might be able to change it to make more sense, before enacting one of these thought processes.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-09-19 16:32:00', '2022-09-19 17:38:12'),
(3294, '2022/09/19', '04:34 pm', '3', '6', 'Angus Singleton', 'Mathematics', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Campbell Jepson', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-09-19 16:34:14', '2022-09-19 16:34:14'),
(3295, '2022/09/20', '07:34 am', '3', '1', 'Lachlan Kratz', 'English', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Campbell Jepson', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-09-20 07:34:35', '2022-09-20 07:34:35'),
(3296, '2022/09/20', '07:48 am', '3', '1', 'Millicent Fyshe', 'Mathematical Assessment', 'Waddington Module', 'Module 1 - 15', 'Module 1 - 15', 'Sang Nguyen', 'In Progress', 'In Progress', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Focus on Millie Maths lessons:</p><ol><li>Part-part whole knowledge (friends of ten using tens frames, concrete materials to model etc)</li><li>Make, name and recording numbers using concrete materials</li><li>Partitioning two- and 3-digit numbers into their place value parts</li><li>Fluency with “ten ones is 1 ten, ten tens is 100” etc</li><li>rearranging and renaming two- and 3-digit numbers (example: 21 is 2 tens and 1 one, 1 ten and 11 ones, 21 ones)</li><li>Using efficient counting strategies (skip counting in 2s to make groups of ten)</li><li>Patterns on the 100s chart (ten more ten less etc.)</li><li>Counting backwards and forwards (ten more, ten less, 1 more, 1 less)</li></ol>', NULL, '2022-09-20 07:48:47', '2022-09-20 09:11:10'),
(3297, '2022/09/20', '08:48 am', '3', '5', 'Max Shapiro', 'English', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Campbell Jepson', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-09-20 08:48:25', '2022-09-20 08:48:25'),
(3298, '2022/09/20', '08:48 am', '3', '9', 'Luna Shapiro', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms (include purpose - to connect speech sounds to their written symbol which helps with reading, writing and spelling)', 'Oral Phonogram Review (OPR) - Various Phonograms (see notes)', 'Neve Mitchell', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>PA: Kilpatrick G2 -- Luna had a lot of difficulty with these today!</td></tr><tr><td>Word recognition: Fitzroy flashcards</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR:&nbsp; 1-8,b h k m n p r sh th ee ow oo&nbsp; ch ay ai ar oy oi er ck</td></tr><tr><td>WPR: Same as above</td></tr><tr><td>Luna wanted to combine her OPR and WPR today, which I allowed. So, she saw the symbol and then immediately wrote the symbol. She willingly wrote all her phonograms with this method. s reversal, ck reversal</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>SD: bat ban big dog dot&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Read R&amp;S</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Write and illustrate a story. Luna sounded and wrote words she would need for her story on the whiteboard (vet, dog, sick).</td></tr><tr><td>She was very dedicated and quiet during this activity. A good one to repeat in future. She was so careful and precise with her handwriting and finger spacing.&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Luna wasn\'t feeling well today, and you could tell. Her attitude was very similar to how she would behave in the afternoon lessons. She struggled to stay focused and made some errors that she hasn\'t been making recently (such as writing n backwards in her name). She also wanted plenty of drawing time. At one point she exclaimed: \"I don\'t want to do this, I want to be at home in my bed!\"</td></tr><tr><td>Sent home my homework Fitzroy Pack 1-6.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-09-20 08:48:46', '2022-09-20 10:00:28'),
(3299, '2022/09/20', '03:29 pm', '3', '8', 'Sophie Mirowski', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Manipulate (delete or substitute) initial phoneme in initial blend - Kilpatrick Level H', 'Neve Mitchell', 'Achieved', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>PA: Kilpatrick H</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR: 27-70</td></tr><tr><td>WPR: er ea th ng ow ch ee ough ci</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Read R&amp;S: Current Ayres Column</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Rule review: 26 4 11</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD: number-cheerful</td></tr><tr><td>Read R&amp;S</td></tr><tr><td>Explain/discuss the markings and meanings of analysed words.</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Rule Intro: NA</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Sentences: Use Ayres words in oral sentences.</td></tr><tr><td>Sentences: Compose written sentence using Ayres words and sort each sentence into sentence types.&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p>Notes</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>We had Rhianna sitting in on Soph\'s lesson today, and the difference was phenomenal. I don\'t know if it was just because there was someone new who she was wary of, or if she has simply become too comfortable with me, but we got through so much work! We finished spelling at 4:10, which left us with nearly double the amount of time we usually have for sentences. She wrote multiple sentences and then we were able to model them on the blocks and discuss structure and type elements.</td></tr><tr><td>What I\'ll try in the first instance is speaking to Sophie next week about mimicking our lesson today -- perhaps by pointing out that our speed/focus today allowed us time for a game that we don\'t usually have. It\'s worth pointing out that Sophie did say herself that she is usually very tired on Tuesday afternoons, but had had a really good day today and didn\'t feel tired. In which case, maybe we should see about getting her to a morning lesson? Perhaps if I could move her up to a Tuesday 7:45...</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-09-20 15:29:29', '2022-09-20 16:47:05'),
(3300, '2022/09/20', '04:28 pm', '3', '8', 'Andrew Allan', 'English', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Laree Thorsby', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-09-20 16:28:47', '2022-09-20 16:28:47'),
(3301, '2022/09/20', '04:31 pm', '3', '9', 'Callum Coulson', 'English', 'Writing - High Frequency Vocabulary + Sentence Construction', 'Elements of a complex sentence > Capital letter, one independent clause, one dependent clause containing a subordinate conjunction, ending punctuation', 'Articulate/Explain the elements of a complex sentence (include use of manipulatives)', 'Yina Peng', 'Achieved', 'Achieved', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Callum is very dedicated to his tutoring here and he really enjoys learning with us. He has graspped all phonograms and concepts of sentence structures and parts of speech, yet he will need a lot of practice in his spelling and writing. He is quite behind for his spelling skills as he is not flexible at using different phonograms.&nbsp;</p><p>kilpatrick i<br><br>rule review:31, 21, 4, 29<br>SD: charge, mem ber, case, while, al so, re turn, of fice &nbsp;He was confused with the word office-ofise<br>read for spelling and reading and understanding words and word class; &nbsp;</p><p>add suffix/prefix. show+case, member+ship</p><p>sentence structures. Callum is a bit confused with complex sentence and compound sentence.&nbsp;<br>text types. We talked about narrative, informative, and narrative-informative text structures. Callum understands the concepts very well.&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-09-20 16:31:27', '2022-09-21 12:30:47'),
(3302, '2022/09/20', '04:34 pm', '3', '9', 'Shay Douglas', 'Academic Coaching', 'Independent Study', 'School Assigned Worksheet or Assignment', 'See Notes', 'Neve Mitchell', 'Achieved', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Subject: Chemistry</td></tr><tr><td>Focus: Shay\'s Chemistry Report</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Shay again requested to work independently on his chemistry report. I offered to proof read what he had so far but he declined. I also asked if he had any other work that he would like me to look over during the hour, but he also said no to this offer. I feel as though my presence is becoming a little redundant! But if Meg/Shay are happy to continue with this arrangement, then I still think that Shay gets a benefit out of the set hour a week.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-09-20 16:34:26', '2022-09-27 15:22:47'),
(3303, '2022/09/20', '04:45 pm', '3', '5', 'Esther Mclver', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Language Rules (Pronunciation/Spelling/Grammar)', 'Rule 7: There are five jobs for a silent final \'e\'', 'See Notes', 'Laree Thorsby', 'Achieved', NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', '<p>Jobs of Silent Final ‘e’:</p><ul><li>Oral review of all five jobs (Essie was able to recall Jobs 1, 2 and 5, but needed some prompting for 3 and 4)</li><li>Apply knowledge of Jobs SF ‘e’ to given multi-syllable words in a word-sort on the stairs.</li><li>Dictate x5 sorted words for analysis (athlete, expensive, balance, circle, medicine)</li></ul><p>Morphology:</p><ul><li>Introduce language - phon eme (smallest unit of sound), graph eme (smallest unit of writing), morpheme (smallest unit of meaning), derived word.</li><li>Introduce morphemes: &nbsp;Prefixes - un, re, over, under, up-, out- &nbsp;and suffixes -ful, -less, -s, -ed, -ing.</li><li>Oral morpheme review (OMR) with actions.&nbsp;</li><li>Written morpheme review (WMR) with base hyphen.</li><li>Record derived words on mini-whiteboard with magnet headings for each morpheme. (un-happy, over-heat-ed, over-heat-ing, under-cook-ed)</li></ul><p>Composition:</p><ul><li>Introduce parts of speech - injections (see PPT presentation)</li><li>Identify interjection and main sentence in given examples on powerpoint.</li><li>Note how interjections are punctuated.</li><li>Identify the emotions being communicated by each one.</li><li>Use given interjections in oral sentences using dictated spelling words.</li></ul><p>Oral Reading Fluency:</p><ul><li>Passage 113N - read by Essie in 40 seconds. &nbsp;She notes that she thinks she was given the wrong passage as it is one that she has read before and her current level is higher than this one. &nbsp;(This would be a misunderstanding in the relief teaching arrangements.</li></ul>', NULL, '<p>Essie and her family are going on holiday from Thursday 22/9/2022. &nbsp;A catch up will be needed for next week\'s missed lesson.</p>', '2022-09-20 16:45:07', '2022-09-20 17:37:19'),
(3304, '2022/09/20', '05:11 pm', '3', '1', 'James Oettle', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms (include purpose - to connect speech sounds to their written symbol which helps with reading, writing and spelling)', 'Oral Phonogram Review (OPR) - Various Phonograms (see notes)', 'Neve Mitchell', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p><strong>Monday 12 Sep&nbsp;– Lesson 1 (with me)</strong></p><p>Don’t Be Greedy</p><p>Continue PAST Assessment&nbsp;</p><p>Non-Word Assessment (see if James’ reading ability is tied to decoding or perhaps just visual memory)</p><ul><li>Definitely memory based on how advanced James’ teacher says he is and what he’s reading. Dad told me they asked her to do another assessment which put him at level 20 – but he’s definitely using visual memory, since he was&nbsp;</li></ul><p>Deliver a pared-back version of the spiel (we use reading and writing to communicate, we use letters to write words, letters make sounds in words): communicate = “you make animal sounds to communicate with animals” (observation from James – OzPhonics link?)</p><p>Introduce to phonograms 1-8. James may know letter names/first sounds. Introduce to first sounds of all.</p><p><strong>Writing</strong></p><ul><li>Explain that we are going to learn to write these letters. Explain that we are going to learn to write these letters as a group because they all begin at the same point.&nbsp;</li><li>Show James a clock. Find 2 o’clock on the clock. Practice drawing anti-clockwise circles around the clock, starting at 2 o’clock. Use a marker. Then have a go with a, d, g, o. (only did a and d)</li><li>Praise James for his use of ducky grip. When writing the letters, talk to pencil to provide instruction.</li><li>Continue practicing a, d, g, o with a 2 o’clock worksheet/scaffold, on paper with pen (whiteboard marker? Chunky).</li><li>Depending on how James is going – introduce to the 2x2 boxes for practice.</li></ul><p>Short Break – a colouring in activity of James’ choice (top to bottom, left to right line practice).</p><p><strong>NOT COMPLETED:</strong></p><p><strong>Writing</strong></p><ul><li>Now we are going to use those letters in words (some real/fake): dog, dag, gad, god</li><li>May use magnet letters or handwrite on whiteboard/in book.&nbsp;</li><li>Read for reading and spelling.</li><li>Make up an oral sentence using the word dog:</li></ul><p>Fitzroy #5x</p><p>SCORE Book 1</p><p>Notes</p><p>James had some difficulty with the past test, particularly in regards to identifying initial and last sounds in words. He was giving me the letter name for all of them. When prompted, he could provide the sound for most words, except for words beginning with two letter phonograms (sh). Here he became confused and tried to give me the letter H. James\' dad did make a comment about asking James\' teacher to reassess him with his reading, and said that James had been placed on level 20. However, based on his non-word test that I did today, he\'s relying heavily on his visual memory and not on decoding skills. We really want to get onto that now by stressing the sound simple connection, which should be fairly easy to do through our foray into various symbols.&nbsp;</p><p>James was very pleasant and agreeable, but excited and a little bit resistant to writing. Dad did warn that that might be an issue. At-home work is going to be really important here, so if I can find a more interesting and exciting way of practising formation other than handwriting sheets, that would be really helpful. Perhaps if I could find or create more colouring work, or some join the dots pictures might also work really well. It was difficult to explain the spiel to James, and asking him to listen for the sounds in words was like a foreign concept to him. I\'m unsure how to pair the spiel back enough for him to get it and then utilise it. I feel positive though about where we\'re at and what we\'re doing.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-09-20 17:12:00', '2022-09-20 17:15:36');
INSERT INTO `attens` (`id`, `date_created`, `time`, `term`, `lesson`, `student_name`, `subject_name`, `concept_name`, `conceptDetail`, `learningActivity`, `tutor_name`, `tutor_evaluation`, `student_self`, `student_attendance`, `homework_completed`, `weekly_lesson`, `homework_assignment`, `email_school`, `comment`, `commentPrivate`, `notesAttendance`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(3305, '2022/09/20', '05:12 pm', '3', '2', 'James Oettle', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms (include purpose - to connect speech sounds to their written symbol which helps with reading, writing and spelling)', 'Oral Phonogram Review (OPR) - Various Phonograms (see notes)', 'Neve Mitchell', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p><strong>Monday 19 Sep – Lesson 2 (with me)</strong></p><p>JOBS/GAMES on board.</p><p>Continue PAST Assessment&nbsp;</p><p>Syllable/sound segmentation with counters – JO not listening to instructions.</p><p>Deliver a pared-back version of the spiel (we use reading and writing to communicate, we use letters to write words, letters make sounds in words): communicate</p><p>OPR phonograms 1-8, first sounds. Help us with our reading, writing, spelling.</p><p><strong>Writing -- Repeat last lesson</strong></p><ul><li>Explain that we are going to learn to write these letters. Explain that we are going to learn to write these letters as a group because they all begin at the same point.&nbsp;</li><li>Show James a clock. Find 2 o’clock on the clock. Practice drawing anti-clockwise circles around the clock, starting at 2 o’clock. Use a marker. Then have a go with a, c, d, g. Good – James behaviour/excitement made it tricky to get through this in good time. Need to also practice keeping pen on paper for d and g</li><li>Praise James for his use of ducky grip. When writing the letters, talk to pencil to provide instruction + keeping pencil on page.</li><li>Continue practising a, d, g, c with a 2 o’clock 2x2 boxes. James did not carry 2 o’clock over.</li></ul><p><strong>Writing – NOT COMPLETED</strong></p><ul><li>Now we are going to use those letters in words (some real/fake): dog, dag, gad, god</li><li>May use magnet letters or handwrite on whiteboard/in book.&nbsp;</li><li>Read for reading and spelling.</li><li>Make up an oral sentence using the word dog:</li></ul><p>Fitzroy #5x</p><p><strong>Notes:</strong></p><p>James was absolutely bouncing off the walls this lesson. It was difficult to keep him on task, however when he did so he very quickly picked up the concept of “2 o’clock” and instructing his pencil. I was impressed by his ability and so tried to move him away from the scaffold to the 2x2 boxes, but although he retained the 2 o’clock start when tracing the letter, he abandoned it immediately when copying.&nbsp;</p><p>At the end of the lesson I spoke with Anne about how James had gone. She seemed keen on the clockface letters (“Great, great, I’m an early childhood educator so I understand what you’re saying”), and then asked how James was going with his name. It was here that she started to get aggressive. In summary, she said:</p><ul><li>James can’t write his name.</li><li>She wants him to be able to write his name. This was “the one thing [she] asked for” in regard to tutoring.</li><li>Writing his own name is a milestone measured at school. He needs to be able to write his name (she was very insistent on this point).</li><li>She thought after 8-9 weeks of tutoring he would have improved, but he hasn’t got any better. She re-iterated this point a lot as well.</li><li>I explained my mentality on teaching the letters in groups. I briefly explained that I would rather teach them in formation based groups rather than in the context of his name, and then once he can write all the letters he’ll obviously be able to write his own name, as one skill follows the other. James knows which letters go in his name and which order they go in. Anne said she didn’t understand what I was saying here.</li><li>The conversation was a difficult one also because James was yelling at both of us in excitement.</li></ul><p>Below email to Mum sent 20.9.20 in response to conversation:</p><p>Dear Anne,</p><p>I hope you’ve had a wonderful rest of your day. I just wanted to follow on from our conversation this morning, as I feel like my ‘off the top of my head’ explanation of what I’m hoping to achieve with James could have been worded much more effectively!</p><p>Essentially, I want to consolidate James’ knowledge of letters and letter writing by looking at them in groups based on handwriting formation (such as a, c, d, g, o, s, and q, which all begin at the same point). Doing so helps to reinforce the neural pathways required to write those letters, and forms mental connections that don’t necessarily occur when learning to write letters in an individual, isolated context. Alongside being best practice teaching, I feel that this will be especially helpful for James given that his fine motor skills are still developing. If you’re interested, I’ve attached an excerpt from the Independent Kids Handwriting Program to illustrate what I mean by handwriting formation groups! We use a slightly modified version here, but the principle is the same.</p><p>I’m also using explicit instruction during handwriting and having James articulate his understanding back to me. We’re doing lots of ‘talking to our pencil’, and will be recognising short/tall letters, letters that extend below the base line (I like to call them monkey letters, because they have a monkey tail ), as well as other handwriting features such as the base line, midpoint, and top line. I feel really strongly about getting these concepts down early, since they’re so foundational and will be built on when spelling/writing words and sentences becomes a focus.&nbsp;</p><p>In terms of writing his name, James did write it independently on the board this morning! I’ve attached a photo for you. As you can see, his formation for ‘a’ and ‘m’ needs development – we’ve been working on ‘a’ (as part of the clockface letters) for the last two weeks, but as I mentioned to you this morning, James isn’t quite ready to apply the correct formation without a scaffold just yet. If you imagine the ‘a’ as being written over a clock, James currently starts writing the letter at 10 o’clock, which means his pencil isn’t in the right position to draw the line down the side. Another general formation element to keep an eye on will be him lifting his pencil from the paper, and a good one to keep reinforcing at home as well. It’s also great that I’m not seeing any reversals in his writing, and although his ‘e’ could be written more accurately, that it begins and ends in the correct place is a sound start.</p><p>It sounds as though you’re already working with James at home. Would you be open to me sending home some activities and scaffolds to use, so that James is receiving consistent instruction and hearing the same language? I’ve got a great name writing activity to do with James next week, and I’m happy to provide you with a copy to do at home as well if that’s of interest to you!</p><p>Please let me know if you’d like to chat further about anything I’ve mentioned here, and please feel welcome to share your thoughts.</p><p>Best wishes,</p><p>Neve.</p>', NULL, '2022-09-20 17:12:21', '2022-09-20 17:18:14'),
