(3330, '2022/09/22', '04:30 pm', '3', '19', 'Samuel Lamont', 'English', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Campbell Jepson', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-09-22 16:30:07', '2022-09-22 16:30:07'),
(3331, '2022/09/22', '05:42 pm', '3', '8', 'Finn Mackey', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms (include purpose - to connect speech sounds to their written symbol which helps with reading, writing and spelling)', 'Oral Phonogram Review (OPR) - Various Phonograms (see notes)', 'Laree Thorsby', 'In Progress', NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', '<p>Based on observations during last week\'s lesson in which he often said, “I know it! &nbsp;I just can\'t remember it!\" I began today with a review of phonograms sh, ti, si, ci and encouraged Finn to articulate the cues that were given for each phonogram.&nbsp;</p><p>These same phonograms were then used in the words nation, infection, compression, discussion, vision, explosion, (face) facial, (space) spacious. &nbsp;</p><p>We identified the base (word root or base word), prefixes and suffixes. &nbsp;We discussed that the original word usually tells us which /sh/ phonogram to use (and when it doesn\'t seem logical, like in admit &gt; admission, it may be connected to the etymology of the word…Latin &gt; admisio.</p><p>We discussed how the final letter of the base connects with the ‘i’ of the suffix ‘ion’ to be pronounced as /sh/. &nbsp;Finn was very articulate about these concepts when asked check for understanding questions.</p><p>We then looked at the meaning of each word and its part of speech, labeling each word on the board - recognising that ‘ion’ shows a noun, and ‘ial’ shows an adjective (His facial hair was black.) &nbsp;Sentences were provided in which Finn had to aurally listen for and state the job the given word was doing. &nbsp;(Noted ‘facial’ could also be a noun. &nbsp;The facial given by the beautician was relaxing.)</p><p>Finn was then asked to write a simple sentence using the word ‘infection’. &nbsp;The sentence was then modelled using SBBs and the precision of the language choices were ‘revised’ one word at a time. &nbsp;Each word was connected to a block on the model, and as the sentence became more descriptive, more blocks were added to the model.</p><ul><li>He got an infection.</li><li>Fred got an infection.</li></ul><p>Discussed the need for ‘got’ to have an object noun (transitive verb) compared to other verbs that don\'t need a noun - He jumped. She sang. &nbsp;They read.</p><p>Looked up the thesaurus for a more precise version of the word ‘got’. &nbsp;Fun discussion trialing options.</p><ul><li>Fred developed an infection.</li><li>Fred developed a brutal infection.</li></ul><p>Finn was unable to state the difference between when to use ‘a’ and when to use ‘an’. &nbsp;Lesson ensued in same. &nbsp;Eg: &nbsp;a book, a brutal, a car, a fabulous, a dodgy, a game. &nbsp;an egg, an apple, an infection, an interesting, an unusual, an igloo. &nbsp;Also discussed the difference between ‘an/a’ and ‘the’. &nbsp;“The is specific.” &nbsp;(FM)</p><p>I then introduced the word ‘preposition’ - Finn was asked to identify the prefix and base word (pre + position). &nbsp;I explained that the job of a preposition is to tell the position of something in time or space, and that prepositions are always part of a phrase (Finn was able to articulate the difference between a phrase and a clause without prompting), and that the phrase begins with the preposition and ends with an object noun. &nbsp;Added a prepositional phrase to the sentence:</p><ul><li>Fred developed a brutal infection on Mars.</li></ul><p>Finally introduced interjections - inter = between, ject = throw, ion = noun. &nbsp;It\'s when an author throws sudden emotion into their writing. &nbsp;It is not part of the main sentence structure. &nbsp;Finn then added an interjection to his sentence. &nbsp;</p><p>He was also asked to add a related sentence. &nbsp;Finn did not know what a related sentence was, but after a couple of examples and non-examples, he composed the following:</p><ul><li>Wow! &nbsp;Fred developed a brutal infection on Mars. “That\'s so cool!”</li></ul><p>We\'ll chat about quotation marks next lesson ;-)</p><p>Once the lesson was underway and I had been casually clear about my expectations, Finn really paid attention to his handwriting and remained engaged in the lesson until 10 minutes after finishing time. &nbsp;This was a most fruitful and extensive session. &nbsp;I\'ll review the same process next week.</p>', NULL, '<p>This lesson was conducted as a relief lesson by NW as LT was absent due to illness.</p>', '2022-09-22 17:42:51', '2022-09-22 19:11:22'),
(3332, '2022/09/23', '08:52 am', '3', '6', 'Lottie Young', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Manipulate (delete or substitute) initial phoneme in initial blend - Kilpatrick Level H', 'Naomi Wright', 'Not Yet', NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', '<p>Phonological Awareness - Lottie was unable to delete the first of the consonant blend sounds. &nbsp;She was given finger scaffolding for most of the words in Set 1 bar the final one which she was able to do without support.</p><p>Sandra Donah - review of compound words, the noun and adjective needed. &nbsp;Lots of check for understanding questions, both knowledge and application.</p><p>Score - Book 3 page 125, Test 129 - seamless, Test 134, page 130</p><p>Fitzroy Reader assess - Books 1 - 4 (see record page)</p><p>Words dictated: trim, brag, drum, brig, drip, trap, drop, brat, brim, drat, dress, brass (wiht markings and rules).</p><p>Introduce interjections - inter = between, ject = throw, ion = noun/thing. &nbsp;Review emotions - what emotions can be interjected in to composed sentence using the words brat, dress, trap? &nbsp;“Angry.” &nbsp;Reviewed options on given reference page.</p><p>Man! A brat trapped me while I was wearing a dress. &nbsp;&nbsp;</p>', NULL, NULL, '2022-09-23 08:52:06', '2022-09-23 10:07:38'),
(3333, '2022/09/23', '02:22 pm', '3', '9', 'Molly  Jackson', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Manipulate (delete or substitute) second phoneme in initial blend - Kilpatrick Level K', 'Neve Mitchell', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>PA: Kilpatrick K1</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR:27-70</td></tr><tr><td>WPR: gu kn or au aw ea ur oa ir&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Spell Check: coin join noise oink void&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>MM Raw Score: 15</td></tr><tr><td>Up 2 points (4 months) with a spelling age of 8.2</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Sentence writing: create 2x 3 sentence stories.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>oi phonogram practice -- urgent. Tried to give Molly a spell check on oi words but she struggled immediately and became visibly distressed.&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>I need to do way more sound/symbol and phonemic/phonological awareness activities with Molly. I do not know how to get over the hurdle she\'s facing of relying on her memory or being unable/unwilling to encode based solely on what she hears.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-09-23 14:22:56', '2022-09-23 16:12:26'),
(3334, '2022/09/23', '04:28 pm', '3', '1', 'Nate Betros', 'Mathematics', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Ivan Botero', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-09-23 16:28:59', '2022-09-23 16:28:59'),
(3335, '2022/09/23', '04:29 pm', '3', '9', 'Nate Betros', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms (include purpose - to connect speech sounds to their written symbol which helps with reading, writing and spelling)', 'Oral Phonogram Review (OPR) - Various Phonograms (see notes)', 'Neve Mitchell', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR: 27-70</td></tr><tr><td>WPR: 51-70</td></tr><tr><td>Errors: kn and gn confusion, gn as ng --&gt; Homework drills?</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Read R&amp;S: Current Ayres Column</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Rule review: 26 29 4 6</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD: himself-vote</td></tr><tr><td>Read R&amp;S</td></tr><tr><td>Explain/discuss the markings and meanings of analysed words.</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Rule Intro: NA</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Orally plan story: characters = 2 Uno cards + John and his friend, plot = John and his friend play Uno and receive a stack of letters from the Uno cards (aka the same plot as The Day the Crayons Quit).</td></tr><tr><td>Begin composing narrative.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p>Notes</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Nate was under the weather this lesson but persevered and did well. He has become quite agreeable to writing stories, especially when it coincides with his interests. Spelling and rules wise he could have been a little bit more on the ball, but I think it was to do with feeling unwell.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-09-23 16:29:09', '2022-09-23 17:26:49'),
(3336, '2022/09/26', '08:44 am', '3', '10', 'Lewis Prevost', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Delete syllable from three syllable word - Kilpatrick Level E', 'Ellie Connor', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week Ten, Lesson One</td></tr><tr><td>Monday, 26 September 2022</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>PA: quack, smack, rocket, playing</td></tr><tr><td>PA: Kilpatrick E2 set 10</td></tr><tr><td>MA: Donah #24</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR/WPR: qu ck ey igh ur ph ay ng</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Rule review: intro rule 25</td></tr><tr><td>SD: P&amp;T words: quack, black, smack, hammock, rocket, o\'clock, playing</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Read Pip &amp; Tim \"Quack!\"</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>CVC game</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Home support pack</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Lewis was so so tired today! As a result, he settled in really quickly, but was definitely droopy. No issues with PA and MA (making better connections with MA and improving his ability to ID syllables faster). Did well with his phonos and SD despite the tiredness. Not fluently articulating rule 25 / cue for \'ck\', but I think he understands and can apply it. After SD using Pip and Tim words, I was SO impressed with how Lewis started reading really fluently. He did the first page or two only sounding out a couple of words aloud. As he fatigued, I think he reverted back to sounding aloud before blending, but he was recalling words he\'d previously decoded (e.g. sundeck). Finished with a CVC game, and sent home some jobs for him to complete.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p>Homework:</p><p>Here are some jobs that he can complete at home.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><ul><li>Practice phonograms: ck, ey, igh, dge, ay, ur, ng, ph (we did these today)</li><li>Practice writing these spelling words, and marking the two-letter phonograms.<ul><li>bucket</li><li>sundeck</li><li>smack</li><li>truck</li><li>hammock</li><li>luck</li><li>jacket</li><li>black</li></ul></li></ul><p>*Remember that ‘ck’ can only be used following a vowel saying its first sound</p><ul><li>Use your spelling words in sentences (either dictated for Mum to write, or handwritten independently)</li><li>Find and circle/underline/highlight the subject noun (who the sentence is about) and the action verb (what the subject is doing) in these sentences:<ul><li>I live on a long street.</li><li>She put the shiny ring on her little hand.</li><li>My teacher will quickly ring Mum to say hello.</li><li>We watched a live stream of the game.</li><li>Lewis will come to the sunny beach at 2 o’clock today.</li><li>The happy boy swung in his hammock.</li><li>The black truck drove quickly, but the lucky duck ran faster.</li></ul></li></ul>', '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week Ten, Lesson One</td></tr><tr><td>Monday, 26 September 2022</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', '2022-09-26 08:44:09', '2022-09-26 10:24:17'),
