(3341, '2022/09/26', '03:38 pm', '3', '10', 'Elsa Clennet', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms (include purpose - to connect speech sounds to their written symbol which helps with reading, writing and spelling)', 'Oral Phonogram Review (OPR) - Various Phonograms (see notes)', 'Neve Mitchell', 'Achieved', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR: 50-70</td></tr><tr><td>WPR: ch ph or oi er ck ea</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Spelling: Morrison McCall. 35/SA 11.10 -- 8 months improvement.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Write a short narrative piece in the last 15 minutes.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Elsa\'s spelling test was interesting. I\'m glad she\'s gone up! We had a \'chill\' spelling test where we took some time to get set up and made a cuppa, all trying to put her at ease. She didn\'t seem too tired from school which was also great conditions for the test.&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>She wrote and self-corrected a few words (cities, piece). I tried to get her to explain why she knew cities was spelled cities not citeis (thinking about r.24) and her explanation was \"I before e except after c,\" which was technically true here. This came up again with \"piece\". First she wrote peace, then identified her error, then changed it to peice, then said \"Wait, that\'s not right, it\'s i before e\" but didn\'t change her answer. She changed her answer when I prompted her to look back at her words after she had completed the test.</td></tr><tr><td>I marked four words with stars as they were only one letter away from being correct. This would have bumped her up to 39/S.A. 12.9, which is an exciting look ahead for where she\'s going.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-09-26 15:38:38', '2022-09-26 17:13:56'),
