(3351, '2022/09/27', '03:29 pm', '3', '10', 'Sophie Mirowski', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms (include purpose - to connect speech sounds to their written symbol which helps with reading, writing and spelling)', 'Oral Phonogram Review (OPR) - Various Phonograms (see notes)', 'Neve Mitchell', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>PA: Kilpatrick H</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR: 27-50</td></tr><tr><td>WPR: ch ck ng ai ea th er kn</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Read R&amp;S: Current Ayres Column</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Rule review: 11 4 6 25</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD: chicken-knock</td></tr><tr><td>Read R&amp;S</td></tr><tr><td>Explain/discuss the markings and meanings of analysed words.</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Rule Intro: NA</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Break: Jenga</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Sentences: Compose written sentence using Ayres words and sort each sentence into sentence types.&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>NOT COMPLETED:</td></tr><tr><td>Text Types: Introduce to concept of text types (N and I), and complete the text types sorter on the whiteboard.</td></tr><tr><td>Writing Process: Show poster. Plan a short narrative, using the elements from the board and perhaps a mind map structure? If necessary, use the story cubes for inspiration.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Sophie was a little easier to keep on track this week! She got incredibly muddled during the rule review, saying: \"I\'m so confused! Aaa! I don\'t know!\" and then \"I was focusing on something completely different. I was thinking about how at Halloween all the shops have scary Halloween things in them.\"</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-09-27 15:29:23', '2022-09-27 16:57:00'),
(3352, '2022/09/27', '03:59 pm', '3', '4', 'Aylah Harrex', 'Mathematics', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Kieran Oates', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Started off the lesson very poorly and inattentive. She forgot her homework so we started a unit on fractions.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-09-27 15:59:41', '2022-09-27 17:04:14'),
(3353, '2022/09/27', '04:24 pm', '3', '8', 'Lachlan Prior', 'English', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Campbell Jepson', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-09-27 16:24:28', '2022-09-27 16:24:28'),
(3354, '2022/09/27', '04:27 pm', '3', '10', 'Callum Coulson', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms (include purpose - to connect speech sounds to their written symbol which helps with reading, writing and spelling)', 'Oral Phongram Review (OPR) - Cards 1 > 70', 'Yina Peng', 'Achieved', 'Achieved', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<p>Today is the last day for Calllum\'s tutoring and we did a summary assessment in oral phonograms review, written phonogram review, spelling and reading.&nbsp;</p><p>He was a bit nervous hence he did not do very well for phonograms.I will write a short result report next term and forward it here.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, '2022-09-27 16:27:32', '2022-09-28 11:53:32'),
(3355, '2022/09/27', '04:34 pm', '3', '10', 'Shay Douglas', 'Study Skills', 'Research', 'See Notes', 'See Notes...', 'Neve Mitchell', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Discipline: History/English</td></tr><tr><td>Focus Areas: Source analysis skills, general analysis skills, making connections, contextualising sources.</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Activity: Introduce student to Trove, the database we\'ll be working with. Can discuss databases if needed. May like to point out that this is looking ahead a little at University work, where search databases will play a stronger focus than in school/college</td></tr><tr><td>Decide on a topic (suggestions: family, your hometown/street, advertisments) and explore the different sources provided on Trove. Select \"Images\". From selection, can discuss refining searches if desired, or simply choose an image for closer analysis.&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Analyse the image using a source analysis organiser or context questions (note -- will probably need to have covered source analysis in a previous lesson). After the image has been analysed, find two related sources to contextualise the image. These can be images, newspaper articles, anything available on Trove. Compile the three sources into a Word document and (in two or so sentences) explain how the two supplementary sources relate to the first image.</td></tr><tr><td>Now, create a short paragraph that combines all these features. It should: introduce a topic (e.g. Tasmanian families in the 1950s), introduce the first image source, explain how the source relates to the topic, make one insightful comment on what the source can teach us about the topic, state the relevance of the other two sources, and end with a short concluding statement.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', NULL, '2022-09-27 16:34:53', '2022-09-27 17:23:14'),
