(3368, '2022/09/28', '05:32 pm', '3', '4', 'Finn McKenzie', 'English', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Neve Mitchell', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-09-28 17:32:54', '2022-09-28 17:32:54'),
(3369, '2022/09/29', '08:25 am', '3', '5', 'Angel King', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Delete final sound in word or final blend - Kilpatrick Level I', 'Laree Thorsby', 'In Progress', NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', '<p>PA - practiced concepts bread without the b, grape - change g to d, rhyme - change r to t.</p><p>Spoke about different reading skills - decoding (tricky for dyslexic brains), fluency (not reading like a robot), comprehension (understanding).</p><p>WPR (handwriting focus - midpoint): er, ea, ck (used after a vowel saying its first sound), oa as in boat, au (not allowed at the end of an English word), qu, y, e, o</p><p>Initially unable to recall qu in spite of heavy focus on this over the past two weeks both at school and in tutoring. &nbsp;Laboured to remember independently.</p><p>Introduced Angel to the Spalding phonogram app. &nbsp;Completed OPR - Lesson 1-26. &nbsp;Introduced to WPR. &nbsp;Will request this app be used at home on as close to daily basis as possible to aid retention and recall.</p><p>Spelling dictation using words with phonograms qu, x and ck. &nbsp;Review when to use ‘ck’ before starting. &nbsp;</p><p>queen, quick r.1, 25, duck, six r.20, Jax r.26, 20, truck r.25, quack r.1, 25.</p><p>Check for understanding questions re rules on dictated words.</p><p>Angel made an articulate connection today between rule 25, the phonogram \'ck, vowel sounds and the application of this rule in given words.</p><p>Discuss ‘sixth’ as came up in PA lesson and was difficult to pronounce and manipulate. &nbsp;Listed ordinal numbers with words and numeral version to show connection. &nbsp;1st - first, 2nd - second, 6th - sixth etc</p><p>Words in sentences (oral):</p><ul><li>The queen saw a duck. &nbsp;She quickly ran because the duck was very quiet but very quick.</li><li>Jax saw a trashcan and wanted to find a burger in it. &nbsp;He got stuck in the trashcan and a truck had to pull him out.</li><li>Jax saw a truck, and he wanted to go in. &nbsp;He locked himself in and he had to find an axe and budge himself out.</li></ul><p>Angel finds it extremely difficult to recall information discussed and reviewed in the same lesson. &nbsp;After reviewing several times with check for understanding questions and repeated articulation, it is easy to see the pathway connect. &nbsp;Further prompting is needed when Angel is asked to articulate her understanding, again at the end of the lesson.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, NULL, '2022-09-29 08:25:44', '2022-09-29 09:17:38'),
(3370, '2022/09/29', '08:48 am', '3', '17', 'Lewis Prevost', 'English', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Ellie Connor', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-09-29 08:48:38', '2022-09-29 08:48:38'),
(3371, '2022/09/29', '02:29 pm', '3', '8', 'Mia Harvey', 'Mathematics', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Campbell Jepson', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-09-29 14:29:59', '2022-09-29 14:29:59'),
(3372, '2022/09/29', '03:32 pm', '3', '9', 'Reuben Shelverton', 'English', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Juno Galang', NULL, NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-09-29 15:32:42', '2022-09-29 15:32:42'),
(3373, '2022/09/29', '03:40 pm', '3', '10', 'Lucy Fairbrother', 'Mathematics', 'Number & Place Value', 'Mental Computation', 'Mad Minute Maths - Facts to 100', 'Naomi Wright', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'Completed', 'Assigned', 'N/A', '<p>NSPM - Lucy talk Naomi through recording a model for problem (d) on page 146 and then completed her own model for problem (e). &nbsp;Lucy was articulate about the model, labels, values and workings for both of these problems.</p><p>Lucy then identified the type of model she would use to represent her workings for question (6) and recorded a model for question (7a).</p><p>Articulate meaning of simplifying and expanding fractions. &nbsp;What operation is used to expand/simplify a fraction? &nbsp;What is the highest common factor? What is an im/proper fractions? &nbsp;What do the numerator/denominators tell us? &nbsp;(proper = as it\'s meant to be, &nbsp;fraction = part, im = not). &nbsp;Practicing identifying proper and improper fractions and articulating why/how we know.</p><p>Complete Concept Cluster 4. &nbsp;Lesson 2, Level II. Review concepts to begin next lesson.</p>', NULL, NULL, '2022-09-29 15:40:33', '2022-09-29 16:40:55'),
(3374, '2022/09/29', '04:26 pm', '3', '9', 'Finn Mackey', 'English', 'Systematic Phonics - Sounds/Symbols (phonograms)', 'Precisely say and write common phonograms (include purpose - to connect speech sounds to their written symbol which helps with reading, writing and spelling)', 'Oral Phonogram Review (OPR) - Various Phonograms (see notes)', 'Laree Thorsby', 'Achieved', NULL, 'Attended Ontime', 'No', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', '<p>Read for spelling and reading Rule Page 6 words from last lesson.</p><p>Spelling Dictation: &nbsp;potential, collection, depression, admission (admissio), occasion, division, (finance) financial, (electric) electrician.</p><p>Record a simple sentence using the word collection. &nbsp;“I have a collection of Lego.”</p><p>Turn this simple sentence into a compound sentence. &nbsp;Model using SBB. &nbsp;Needed to talk through this task, but once the structure was clear on the model, Finn was able to construct a compound sentence.</p><p>Write a simple sentence for the word potential.</p><p>Add a dependent clause to create a complex sentence.</p><p>Email Kiim re catch up lesson in the second week of the holidays: <a href=\"mailto:kimcressman@hotmail.com\">kimcressman@hotmail.com</a>.</p>', NULL, NULL, '2022-09-29 16:26:08', '2022-09-29 18:44:09'),
(3375, '2022/09/29', '04:32 pm', '3', '10', 'Chelsea Cooper', 'English', 'Phonological & Phonemic Awareness', 'Understand that spoken words consist of sequences of sounds called phonemes', 'Substitute onset & rime - Kilpatrick Level G', 'Ellie Connor', 'In Progress', 'N/A', 'Attended Ontime', 'Yes', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', NULL, '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week Ten</td></tr><tr><td>Thursday, 29 September 2022</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>PA: Kilpatrick</td></tr><tr><td>MA: Donah #35</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>OPR/WPR: gu ai ui ch ough ck ey kn ear gn ea&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Rule Review: 25</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SD: pair, pear, pare, check, prove, heard, hear, inspect, itself</td></tr><tr><td>Read S&amp;R</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Use \'hear\' and \'heard\' in sentences to demonstrate meaning</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Chelsea did well today. She was very patient and seemed totally unfazed having Rhianna sitting in on the lesson. She was very excited to tell me all about camp when she arrived, so this took up a good 5 minutes at the start of our session. Did well with PA although needed some thinking time, no issues with MA. Good with phonos but does still need prompting for initial sounds of ea and ough before she can get going. Chels did really well with SD words, although I did notice that she struggled to read pair/pear/pare for spelling with the slightly altered sounds. Also confusion between ear and /ea//r/. Chelsea is good at composing sentences, but for some reason today she needed lots of prompting to make her sentence more interesting. Chelsea told us a little more about her camp, then we worked through her homework from last week before she headed off.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', '<figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Week Ten</td></tr><tr><td>Thursday, 29 September 2022</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', '2022-09-29 16:32:01', '2022-09-30 17:17:16'),
(3376, '2022/09/29', '04:49 pm', '3', '10', 'Callisto Pratten', 'Mathematics', 'General Mathematics', 'Networks and decision mathematics.', 'Project planning and scheduling using critical path analysis (CPA)', 'Rosemary Beswick', 'In Progress', 'In Progress', 'Attended Ontime', 'N/A', 'Completed', 'N/A', 'N/A', '<p>Callisto had started the Networks unit in class and had done some work from Set 3. We therefore started at this point with the lesson. The topic was critical path analysis. We both found it quite tricky but are on the way to mastering it.</p>', NULL, NULL, '2022-09-29 16:49:13', '2022-09-29 18:26:20'),
